 MONEY-SUB-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: NEW THROUGHOUT, UPDATING with Texas Legislature reaching a
compromise on school funds
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONFEREES REACH 11TH-HOUR DEAL ON SCHOOL FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   By KATHY WALT &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ House and Senate negotiators salvaged a $3.8
billion school finance plan at the 11th hour Saturday, after they
found an extra $100 million in funding.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reached around 10 p.m. grants $3,000 annual pay raises
to teachers and $300 million for kindergarten and pre-kindergarten
programs. It also grants $1.2 billion in school property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Agreement came after days of mostly private negotiations between
leaders of the Republican-dominated Senate and the
Democrat-controlled House, who earlier Saturday appeared to have
hit a brick wall in their talks.
</P>
<P>
   They were fighting over a difference of about $47 million,
minuscule compared to the spending plan, but one that represented a
huge philosophical chasm.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the agreement, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry compared the
negotiations to Aggie football _ ``you play until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty million dollars of the extra money came from a new lottery
revenue projection from Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander after a
lottery bill that was approved Friday changed the outlook for
income from the games.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Senate that did most of the compromising, with the
new version of Senate Bill 4 taking on all the features House
members had demanded, except for the Senate's idea of creating a
new funding level to help mostly fast-growing school districts
retire debt.
</P>
<P>
   The upper chamber agreed to a House proposal to give all
teachers and librarians a $3,000 annual pay raise, the largest
state-funded pay hike for public school teachers in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also yielded to House plans on how much to increase
per-student funding and even the $300 million the House wanted to
put into early childhood programs and ninth-grade dropout
prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   Those educational programs had been the sticking point in
earlier negotiations, but Perry said chief House negotiator Paul
Sadler, D-Henderson, had been ``very persuasive'' in persuading the
Senate to fund such programs. Those concessions were made even
though senators were aware they meant it would be impossible to
achieve a goal of $2 billion in taxpayer relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bill is better now than when it left the House.
Things that were important to House members are still in there,''
said Rep. Scott Hochberg, D-Houston. School districts will fare a
little better because they will have a bit more discretionary money
than the House plan had called for.
</P>
<P>
   The bill still faces a race to passage before the legislative
session ends at midnight Monday. A 24-hour waiting period is
required from the time the final version of the bill is placed on
members' desks, and there must be time for printing up the new
version.
</P>
<P>
   If approval cannot be given in time, the Legislature faces a
likely special session to handle the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush ``made an impassioned plea'' to Sadler,
the House Public Education Committee chairman, and to senators
negotiating the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Saturday night, after making a commencement speech to
Brazosport High School, the Republican governor had said, ``The
general consensus is we'd like to avoid a special session, but if
there has to be one, there has to be one. And a legitimate reason,
of course, would be for schools.''
</P>
<P>
   If the bill is not passed this session, both Bush and Perry
would lose _ at least temporarily _ some of their major campaign
promises.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, his goal of seeking $2.6 billion in tax cuts already
is impossible. But his plan to ban social promotion, also included
in Senate Bill 4, will survive. Also salvaged Saturday night was
Perry's call for ``master reading teachers,'' who would be paid
bonuses for their special skills in helping to teach students to
read.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Steve Olafson contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
