<HEADLINE>
HUSON WORKS HIS WAY AROUND ANGELS INFIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Andy Sheets, acquired after shortstop Gary DiSarcina
broke his left hand in spring training, was benched Saturday night
after going hitless in his last 18 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets, replaced by Jeff Huson, wasn't expected to provide much
offense. But after he committed his first error in his last 25
games Friday, manager Terry Collins gave him the night off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just seemed like a good time,'' Collins said. ``He has given
us more than we could have expected on defense. A rest here and
there isn't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheets, acquired March 29 as part of a deal that sent Phil Nevin
to San Diego, has never played more than 88 games in a season. That
was last year when he split time at short with Chris Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   Huson started at first base Thursday against Baltimore and moved
to third Friday to give slumping Troy Glaus a breather. Glaus, who
entered the game with just three hits in his last 43 at-bats,
returned to the lineup and hit a two-run home run in the sixth
inning, his sixth of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Huson came in batting .375 (3 for 8) on the homestand and
singled, stole a base and scored the Angels' second run in the
fourth inning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Draft update: The Angels do not have a pick in Wednesday's 1999
amateur draft until 68th, one ahead of the Dodgers' first
selection. Their first pick (No. 17) went to Boston as compensation
for signing Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 10 (including DH) projected opening-day starters
are products of the Angels farm system, including former No. 1s
Chuck Finley (Jan. 1985), Darin Erstad (June 1995) and Glaus (June
1997).
</P>
<P>
   After losing Jose Offerman, Dean Palmer and Tim Belcher to free
agency, the Royals will have six of the top 58 selections. They
already had the seventh pick overall and added No. 25 and 32 as
compensation for Offerman, who signed with Boston. They received
No. 43 and 54 for Palmer, who went to Detroit. The Royals did not
offer arbitration to Belcher, who signed a two-year, $10.2 million
deal with the Angels, and received no compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Local honors: Before tonight's game, Kansas City pitcher Kevin
Appier will be honored by the Lancaster Pony League for his
contributions to youth baseball in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Appier, who was struck above the left ankle by a line drive
Friday, received treatment before Saturday's game and reported the
injury was much improved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
