<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ WINS 10TH FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ When Pedro Martinez showed up Friday at Jacobs Field
with the mistaken notion it was his turn to pitch, Nomar
Garciaparra shook his head and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Pedro,'' the Red Sox shortstop said. ``That doesn't
surprise me a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, after Garciaparra helped make Martinez the
majors' first 10-game winner with a tiebreaking, three-run home run
in the Red Sox come-from-behind, 4-2 win over the Cleveland
Indians, he was reminded of Martinez's confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing he didn't think it was a 7 o'clock game,''
Garciaparra said. ``He'd probably just be getting up now.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a shame for anyone to sleep through this one,
an exquisitely played exercise that Martinez, for all his
magnificence (nine strikeouts and no walks in eight innings), stood
to lose until the Sox rallied in the eighth for four runs against
the Indians' own Dominican dandy, Bartolo Colon, and two relievers.
</P>
<P>
   And Garciaparra hardly looked the part of the hero against
Indians reliever Paul Shuey, when he was called for two check-swing
strikes and fouled back Shuey's potential punchout pitch. But then
Shuey left a split-fingered fastball at Garciaparra's waist, and
the Sox shortstop drove it 409 feet into the left-field seats, his
third home run in two games at Jacobs Field, his fourth in four
games, and ninth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those moments that had Sox manager Jimy Williams
sounding like Shirley MacLaine again, except Ms. MacLaine, for all
her past-life experiences, has not been introduced to Ty Cobb yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's those guys he used to play with,'' Williams said,
when asked to explain Garciaparra's knack for the grand gesture.
``I don't know. Some guys do it. They're just special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians threatened to upstage the Sox in the ninth, when
Martinez, his right hip aching, was lifted by Williams after giving
up a broken-bat single to Kenny Lofton to open the inning. Lofton,
the Indians' leadoff man, had three of the team's five hits off
Martinez, all singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hit was just like the one Lofton had in the eighth inning
last fall,'' Williams said, alluding to Lofton's rally-starter in
the playoff game that ended the Sox' season last October.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Tom Gordon walked the first two batters he faced, loading
the bases with nobody out for Manny Ramirez, who leads the planet
in runs batted in (60 in 47 games). But Gordon induced Ramirez to
ground to John Valentin, who stepped on third and threw across the
diamond for a double play as Lofton scored. After a walk to Jim
Thome, Gordon dropped a third-strike curveball on a mesmerized
Travis Fryman to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Watching those last three outs should have been as
nerve-wracking to Martinez as anything he faced through the first
eight innings. After giving up a run on two singles and a sacrifice
fly by Roberto Alomar in the first, Martinez didn't allow another
runner past first, retiring 23 of 25 batters until the ninth.
Martinez threw just 98 pitches, 72 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   While there may have been an epidemic of migraines among those
watching at home, Martinez claimed he never entertained a single
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get nervous,'' he said. ``The worst that can happen is
we lose the game. I know I have one of the best, if not the best
closer, in the last two years. I trust that man. I don't care if he
gives it up. Hopefully, he'll keep it all together, but I don't
care about the fact that the game is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust him. I trust everybody on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Martinez feels trust, the Indians should have fear. Six
times they have faced Martinez, including the playoff opener last
fall, and have lost to him five times. He has held them to just 33
hits and nine earned runs in 49 innings (1.65 ERA), while striking
out 51.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is doing it to everybody, of course _ his eighth
straight win improved his record to 10-1, with a 2.01 ERA _ but the
Indians, who still have the majors' best record (32-15) despite
losing two straight to the Sox, can't be relishing the thought of
seeing him again come October.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws all his pitches and he throws them for strikes,''
Indians manager Mike Hargrove said. ``On Manny Ramirez's first
at-bat, he threw a curveball and he got him out. (David) Justice
came up, and he's throwing 2-and-1, 2-and-2 changeups for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't throw a straight pitch. If it's up around the
waist, it's there for a purpose. If he's not the best pitcher in
the game, he's one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anyone else better right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
