</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MASS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHRENS CAPTURES MASSCAP 
</HEADLINE>
 CAP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The wrong horse got all the publicity. While
high-profile trainer Bob Baffert was making the grand tour of
Boston on behalf of his charge, 1997 Kentucky Derby-winner Real
Quiet, Jim Bond was up at Saratoga, quietly preparing Behrens for
Saturday's running of the $600,000 Massachusetts Handicap at
Suffolk Downs. This time, the silent treatment worked, as Behrens
wore down English invader Running Stag in the final yards to
prevail, while Real Quiet tired badly turning for home, and
finished a well-beaten third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in Saratoga nobody knows my phone number or my
address,'' said Bond, who did not bring Behrens to Suffolk until 7
a.m. Saturday. ``If he had been beaten, I'd have been a bum and
been thrown out of Boston. But Behrens likes his own environment.
He likes it up at Saratoga. If we ship him, sometimes he goes off
his feed. I don't like to ship him around. He ate breakfast just an
hour early at home and we put him on the van at 2:45 a.m. I thought
we had a good shot this way. This horse just gets better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   When the gate opened, Running Stag, who has shown very little
speed in his four previous races in the United States, sprang to
the front under Shane Sellers, sending a ripple through the crowd
of 17,174 with the unexpected move. Running Stag was closely
followed by Real Quiet, handled by Gary Stevens in his last ride in
the United States before switching his tack to England, and
Behrens, ridden by Jorge Chavez. Chavez was intent on stalking
Stevens, and the three raced in close contention, Running Stag on
the inside and Real Quiet in the middle, to the quarter pole. But
when the real running began, Real Quiet dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was three-wide, but that was the best part of the track,''
said Chavez, who had a great day overall, with three wins in four
rides on the card. ``Stevens tries to keep me out there, but I
didn't mind because it was the better going. When the other horse
(Running Stag) went to the lead. I didn't change anything in my
mind. I have a lot of confidence in Behrens, very, very much so.
So, I knew he could finish well. I was keeping my eyes on Real
Quiet, I wasn't really concerned with the other horse. At the
quarter pole, I realized I had more horse than Gary. I said to
myself: `This is my race.' But the other horse kept going. Then I
said: `Oops!' I have to go to work. I always thought I'd catch him,
but he kept going. Finally, I got him at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin was just a half-length, a measure that prevented a
daylight heist by an 8-1 shot. Real Quiet was sent off a favorite
at 4-5, while Behrens was 9-10 ($3.80 to win). The time for the
mile and one-eighth was 1:49, and Behrens needed nearly every inch
of that distance to gain the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when Running Stag went to the lead,'' said Bond.
``I was hoping there'd be a rabbit in the race, but I didn't expect
it to be him. And, I was surprised we were three-wide. Our game
plan was just to stay close to Real Quiet. I've been riding Jorge
for so long, that I know when he's in trouble and when he's not.
When he got to the turn, I knew he had a great shot. On paper it
didn't look like anybody wanted the lead. But things change very
rapidly when you get in these big races and Jorge made a great
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, a 5-year-old son of Pleasant Colony, was already the
leader in the National Thoroughbred Racing Association's Champions
series, and he picked up six more points for his MassCap victory,
for a total of 28. Owned by William Clifton of Waco, Texas, and Ann
and Donald Rudder of Avon, Conn., Behrens, who also has won the
Gulfstream Park and Oaklawn handicaps, has a chance to become the
Handicap Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed in what kind of horse he is, but I wanted to show
the world,'' said Bond. ``He has not gotten much respect for an
NTRA standing leader. In fact, I hardly ever hear his name
mentioned. Basically, he's matured. He knows who he is. He has the
will to win. He's got it down, got it down pat. It's going to take
a good horse to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond isn't sure what's next for Behrens, but the Breeders' Cup
(At Gulfstream Nov. 6) is the ultimate goal. For now, the horse and
horseman will return to their humble ways at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to bragging, you get in trouble,'' said Bond. ``I
want to keep my big mouth shut and let the horse do the talking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
