<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NY IS STILL ENTERTAINMENT CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thank God for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   New York's dysfunctional family has given us more than our share
of intrigue and entertainment in the last month. It has also given
us something in all too short supply: a rivalry. Or, shall we say,
as much of a rivalry as can exist in this era.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Knicks meet an Indiana Pacers team that literally
cut its playoff teeth against New York. Earlier, the Knicks went
down to the last shot to eliminate the Miami Heat, another
crypto-rival.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps best of all, the Knicks spared us the indignity of
having to watch an Atlanta-Indiana conference final.
</P>
<P>
   We won't even begin to contemplate the corporate intrigue from
the last month. It's ongoing. Peter Vecsey of the New York Post
called for coach Jeff Van Gundy's head on Friday while, in the same
space, pronouncing that Garden boss Dave Checketts is the Mormon
Tabernacle Liar.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, we think, we'll get back to basketball Sunday.
Reggie Miller has been salivating for New York ever since the
Pacers dispatched Philadelphia in four games. Small wonder. He has
scored 30 or more points seven times in 23 playoff games against
the Knicks. Only Michael Jordan (15 times) has done that more often
to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the fourth time in six years that the teams have
met, and each series has had its share of Miller Moments.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5, Eastern Conference finals, 1994: Miller scored 25 of his
39 points in the fourth quarter, including 19 in less than six
minutes, to rally Indiana from a 12-point deficit to a 93-86
victory and a 3-2 lead in the series. He had five 3-pointers and
one choke hold directed at Spike Lee. Alas, the Knicks won the
series in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Game 1, Eastern Conference semifinals, 1995: Miller scored 10
points in the final minute to give Indiana an utterly improbable
107-105 victory. The Pacers trailed, 105-99, with 18.7 seconds to
play, but then scored 8 unanswered points, all by you-know-who.
Miller tied the game on two treys in a space of 3.1 seconds. Then
he made two free throws with 7.5 seconds left to win the game.
Miller also had 29 in the seventh game as Indiana won the series.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4, Eastern Conference semifinals, 1998: New York was a
rebound away from tying the series, 2-2. But a loose ball ended up
in Miller's hands as time was winding down and he drained a
wide-open trey to send the game into overtime. He went on to score
a playoff-best 38 _ including 7 in overtime _ as the Pacers won,
118-107. They then closed out the Knicks at home to win the series
in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff time is Miller time. Since the Pacers became a serious
playoff regular (1993-94, starting with the Larry Brown era),
Miller has increased his scoring average in the postseason and has
a flair for big moments. New York, it seems, gets to see most of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers-Knicks series has all kinds of subplots. There's the
emergence of the new Knicks, who like to run and don't seem to need
Patrick Ewing. There's Van Gundy's creaky status. Chris Mullin, Sam
Perkins, and Mark Jackson, all are native New Yorkers. Indy
president Donnie Walsh is as well, and he secretly admitted he was
pulling for the Knicks when it became apparent Atlanta was going to
go down without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I only have sentimentality if we win,'' Walsh says.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are playing well. They haven't lost yet in the
postseason. But they also have beaten two teams (Milwaukee,
Philadelphia) who were your basic happy-to-be-there clubs, neither
having been in the postseason since 1991. The Knicks outlasted
Miami and then got Atlanta on a platter. The Hawks may well have
been the most offensively challenged team to participate in the
postseason since the introduction of the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the way we're playing,'' Walsh said. ``We
lost our way somewhere during the season. But then Larry Bird made
some adjustments and we got it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird ended the Pacers' dancing introductions. More important, he
stopped his two-platoon system and started going with his starters,
including Jackson, down the stretch. He also incorporated Derrick
McKey into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all Bird has left is to figure out which Rik Smits is going
to show up and he'll have all his bases covered. And by the way,
Donnie, what about those God-awful black socks everyone's wearing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year our team votes to do something together for the
playoffs and each year they always forget Rik is on the team,''
Walsh said. ``Last year, it was the shaved head. Rik looked awful.
This year, it's the black socks. It wouldn't look so bad if he
didn't wear them so high. But that's how he likes them.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearances notwithstanding, the Pacers are ready. They'd just
as soon have started Saturday to avoid a conflict with Sunday's
Indy 500, but NBC made the decision for them. Walsh said a lot of
people in town are upset over what they see as a totally
unnecessary conflict. But the game will go on and time will tell if
Miller writes another chapter in his book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain tried, honest he did, not to trash Shaquille
O'Neal. But, well, Shaq is such an easy (and legitimate) target
that Chamberlain couldn't restrain himself. ``It's a game of
skills,'' he said, pronouncing skills as if it were spelled
``skeels''. ``Not Shaquille.'' O'Neal, if possible, further lowered
himself after the Lakers were humiliated by the Spurs. First, he
again blew off the team meeting for the second straight season.
Then, he took a shot at Penny Hardaway, going so far as to say,
``As soon as I left, all the pressure was on him and he couldn't
handle it. He got his wish for back-dooring Superman.'' This is the
same ``Superman'' whose teams now have been swept out of the
playoffs in four of the last five years. This is the same
``Superman'' who, in the fourth quarters against the Spurs, took 15
shots and made seven. This is the same ``Superman'' who, in those
same fourth quarters, managed two blocks and four rebounds. This is
the same ``Superman'' whose teammates were terrified to give him
the ball down the stretch because they knew he'd be fouled and,
well, how does 2 for 10 sound in a close game? This is the same
``Superman'' who graced the cover of Sports Illustrated wearing a
white tux in a story about players who want to be singer/stars and
vice versa. The Lakers were eliminated a few days later.
Chamberlain referenced a poll in one LA-area paper in which 95
percent of the nearly 1,700 respondents said that Shaq should be
traded. ``He's not doing something right,'' Chamberlain said of
Shaq. ``There's something he's doing wrong and I don't even think
he himself knows what it is. But it's not just Shaq. The whole
Laker organization is in turmoil _ total turmoil.'' Meanwhile, Shaq
has a new motto: ``I've won everywhere but college, the pros, the
Pacific Division, and the Western Conference.'' . . . Former
Georgetown coach John Thompson said there wasn't any truth to
reports that he was being romanced by the Nets. But, he added, that
should not be construed to mean that he's not interested in the
job, or in any NBA job. Au contraire. ``I want to do this,'' he
said. He said his name may have come up in a general discussion
with the Nets a while back, but not in any serious way . . . The
Vancouver Grizzlies are shopping their No. 2 pick for a veteran
power forward. They believe they have enough young pups and don't
believe Elton Brand, whom some scouts believe will measure 6 feet 6
inches or 6-6 1/2 in Chicago, is the guy . . . Several general
managers say the Celtics aren't just shopping Ron Mercer, they're
all but putting him up for auction . . . Jalen Rose on Bird in this
week's Sporting News: ``He doesn't walk around with his 1989 press
clippings in his pocket.'' No, he doesn't. He played six games that
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle GM Wally Walker flew in for the Bill Russell tribute and
said he's confident Vin Baker will be back to All-Star form next
season. Walker had better be right. Baker dropped like a stone this
year, reporting out of shape and then getting hurt. He was a
monstrous disappointment. ``He'll be back, playing at the level he
was before,'' Walker said, saying Baker will stay in shape by
playing in the US Olympic qualifier in July. Baker is expected to
opt out next month and then the fun should really begin. As for the
Sonics, Walker said, ``We're not going to overreact to a 50-game
season. We felt we had a real solid team. We just have to shore up
our weaknesses.'' . . . Rick Pitino went on WEEI this past week and
said the state of college basketball was abysmal. He's right. The
NBA and its union blew a golden chance to improve two games _ the
college and the pro _ by failing to enact punitive salary scales
for kids leaving school early. There's only one reason why the
exodus continues _ money. If the union and league had adopted
scales based on years of school, and made the money a severe
deterrent rather than a panacea, the kids might stay in school,
grow up, play college ball and actually be ready for the NBA . . .
The Sixers' Theo Ratliff sat out Game 4 of the team's series with
Indiana because of a strained calf and took some heat _ anonymously
_ from teammates. He was not happy about it. ``I know myself,'' he
told reporters last week. ``If I was able to get out there, I would
have. That's all that matters, if I know in my heart that I would
never do anything to get out of it.'' Ratliff finished third in the
league in blocked shots in the first year of a seven-year, $62
million deal. His agent, Joel Bell, said Ratliff should have come
out long before then. ``He played the last part of last season on a
knee that was so bad, the doctor said stop and have the surgery
right now,'' Bell said. ``He did have the surgery after the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city of Charlotte launched a trial balloon this past week
and the Hornets promptly shot it down. The question: What if the
city offered to pay 30 percent of a new arena? The answer? Not
enough. The next two arenas, Miami and Indiana, are roughly 50/50
partnerships and that's what the Hornets are looking for. But as
long as the hated George Shinn is in charge _ he already drove off
Michael Jordan _ there will be little interest in helping the
Hornets . . . The Utah Jazz face an interesting future. They have
seven free agents, among them Karl Malone, Jeff Hornacek, and John
Stockton. Malone picked a bad time to deliver the worst scoring
game of his playoff career _ 8 points on 3-of-16 shooting _ in
Portland's clinching victory Thursday night. ``I'll get over it,''
Malone said. ``I just couldn't get anything going and I'll be
enough of a man to say that.'' If, as expected, Malone wins his
second Most Valuable Player Award, it'll be the first time since
1988 that the winner's team didn't at least get to the conference
finals. Jordan won the first of his five that season and the Bulls
lost in the conference semis to the Pistons. How much money do you
think you'd have made had you bet in January that the Lakers, Jazz,
or Rockets would not make it to the conference finals?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
