<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FIND SCORING TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Revolution discovered an effective
midfield attack and broke their scoring slump Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. But
their trademark, defense-first approach suffered as they played to
a 3-3 tie with the MetroStars, then won the postmatch shootout.
</P>
<P>
   During the first two-thirds of the game, the Revolution
displayed some of their best offense of the season in snapping a
360-minute scoreless streak. Giovanni Savarese scored twice in his
return to Giants Stadium after three seasons with the MetroStars.
But the Revolution twice squandered the lead in a wide-open, sloppy
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept the ball a lot and showed we have the ability to play
some football,'' said midfielder Ivan McKinley, whose 21st-minute
goal was the Revolution's first since May 1. ``But this season, we
never got down, not for one minute. If you look at our losses, only
three have been in regulation time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, who host Chicago Saturday, moved into a tie with
the MetroStars for fourth place in the Eastern Conference with
eight points in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time this season the Revolution have shown
the resourcefulness to rally after trailing. Eduardo Hurtado's
sixth-minute goal was the fourth this season the Revolution have
surrendered in the first 10 minutes of a game.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley tied the score by placing a header off the inside of
the left post in the 21st minute. Defender Dan Calichman started
the sequence by moving into attack, then Savarese found John
Harkes, who chipped to McKinley about 15 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution then took command of the midfield. Jair moved to
central midfield as Harkes went to the right side, Kris Kelderman
retained his supporting role, and McKinley took the left side.
</P>
<P>
   In the 34th minute, Savarese's first goal gave the Revolution
their first advantage since a 3-1 win over D.C. United April 24.
Kelderman drove a pass from the center circle to Harkes, who
penetrated to the end line and scrambled a pass to Joe-Max Moore,
who then found Savarese unmarked 12 yards from goal. Savarese sent
a low shot off MetroStars keeper Mike Ammann's left hand for a 2-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese scored his fourth goal of the season and 45th of his
MLS career early in the second half after an Arley Palacios free
kick had tied the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars capitalized on controversial decisions by referee
Ali Mohammed Bujsaim of the United Arab Emirates. Calichman was
called for a foul on Hurtado, then Mohammed Bujsaim cautioned
Savarese as the Revolution defensive wall was forced back even
beyond the 10-yard norm. Palacios's curving free kick into the
upper left corner of the net left goalkeeper-coach Walter Zenga no
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it wasn't a foul, then he moved the wall back 12
to 15 yards, so we might as well not have had a wall,'' Calichman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearing to be offside, Savarese quickly finished with
a left-footed drive for a 3-2 lead in the 54th minute. But the
MetroStars launched themselves into attack and Hurtado and Petter
Villegas set up Brian Kelly for the tying goal in the 58th minute
as the game accelerated into a frenetic pace.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minute, Revolution substitute Jamar Beasley bumped
Ammann and the ball into the net, but the goal was rightfully
disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes scored the lone shootout goal for the Revolution. Backup
goalie Jeff Causey replaced Zenga with two minutes to play and made
one save in the shootout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
