<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      05-30 2053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SABRES MOVE ON, JUNEAU FUTURE UP IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ He has heard the rumors, but the sound of Ottawa
doesn't ring quite right to Joe Juneau's ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep hearing that, too,'' said Juneau, the former Bruin who
will be an unrestricted free agent as of July 1. ``But Ottawa
doesn't make sense, because everything I read, they'll have trouble
paying the players they already have. So I doubt I'm going there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Juneau carries on here with the Sabres, now
with a chance of playing in the Stanley Cup finals for the second
year in a row. Washington's top scorer in last year's playoffs, he
was dealt to the Sabres at the March 23 trade deadline, Buffalo
hoping that he could add some touch to the power play. He popped in
his third postseason goal Thursday night against the Maple Leafs,
finishing off a shorthanded strike and his 10th point in 12 playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   But where will Juneau be when the season ends?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right here _ I hope they make me an offer,'' he said, before
the Sabres beat the Leafs, 5-2, Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in Game 4 of the
Eastern Conference finals. ``I like it here, and if they sign me, I
won't feel so much like a rent-a-player.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone going forward with Juneau, the rent these days is
high, which probably does exclude the small-market Senators from
getting into the bidding. Following his successful '98 playoffs
when he collected 17 points in 21 games, Juneau signed a one-year
contract extension with the Caps that brought him $2.2 million. The
Sabres ended up paying about $350,000 of that to bring him in for
the stretch drive. The market changes hour to hour in the NHL, but
it's conceivable Juneau's next deal could be worth $8 million to
$10 million over the next three or four years _ even if his
offensive productivity has diminished the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner (John Rigas) has talked to me a couple of times and
he's told me, `We're going to do what we can to keep you,' '' said
Juneau, who, like Rigas, is an RPI alum. ``So that's nice. It's
more than I ever heard from Harry (Sinden, the Bruins' president
and general manager).''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres also have their budget restraints, and despite what
Rigas may be saying, it likely would be a stretch for Juneau to be
back here in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens, now that they've ditched the likes of Mark Recchi
and Vincent Damphousse, could be enticed by Juneau. He's a Quebec
kid, and at, say, $3 million a year, he'd be making less than what
Recchi and Damphousse made last season. The Rangers could come
calling, too, especially if they begin striking out with their
lengthy wish list, which is believed to contain Theo Fleury and
Damphousse, among others. If the price were right, Juneau also
could be an interesting pickup for St. Louis, where a partnership
with Pierre Turgeon would have the potential of boosting both their
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word around Ottawa is that former Sabres forward and coach Rick
Dudley, the Senators general manager last season, soon will hitch
on with Tampa Bay as the Bolts' new president. Dudley actually had
the GM job in Tampa last year, but was detoured to Ottawa when Art
Williams cut in line and bought the team before Bill Davidson could
finalize his own offer. A year later, Williams has sold to the
76-year-old Davidson, Dudley's former employer with the Detroit
Vipers (IHL). A possible deterrent to Dudley signing on with the
Bolts: the Senators' wish for compensation; one report had them
seeking Rob Zamuner from the Bolts. A couple of names that have
popped up as Dudley's potential successor: Pierre Page and John
Muckler. Page is still looking for work after being let go a year
ago as the Ducks' coach. Muckler makes $1 million a year as the
Rangers' coach. Unless the Blueshirts were to bump him out from
behind the bench, he wouldn't be headed to the Senators . . . The
Rangers also have former Bruin Stephane Quintal on their free-agent
shopping list. The ``Q'' wanted a new deal in Montreal last summer,
but the Habs balked. They finally came up with a four-year offer,
worth about $8.4 million, around the All-Star break, but Quintal
didn't bite . . . How costly is the waiting game? The Rangers just
committed $34 million to Brian Leetch for the next four years (at
$6.5 million next year he'll make $500,000 more than Ray Bourque).
Had the Blueshirts done the deal last year, the four-year extension
likely would have been in the $25 million to $28 million range. But
when the Avalanche cut Peter Forsberg's new deal at $10 million per
season, the ante went up for everyone _ one more time . . . Toronto
coach Pat Quinn has seen enough of Dominik Hasek dropping his stick
in the crease, a move the Czech goalie has perfected, almost every
time he gets in trouble around the cage. ``To me,'' said Quinn,
``that's a penalty. A forward can't do it, so why should a goalie
be allowed?'' Perhaps Quinn is right, but Hasek was victimized by
the antic in Game 3 of the Toronto series. He was still without his
paddle when an Alexander Karpovtsev slapper whistled past him after
deflecting off Alexei Zhitnik's boot. Zhitnik had just finished
turning back to the play after pushing Hasek's stick back into the
crease. It's usually a successful prank, but that time the prank
was on Hasek . . . I'm not sure what this means, but Minnesota has
12,000 girls playing ice hockey . . . Meanwhile, a favorite
Minnesota son, Lance Pitlick, should cash in big this summer. The
Senators' character defenseman, who spent about six years in the
minors before making it to the big time, recently was declared an
unrestricted free agent . . . A recent survey showed that 29 of the
top 52 draft picks in '97 _ including Calgary first-rounder Daniel
Tkaczuk, the sixth pick _ remained unsigned. Clubs have until
Tuesday to get those picks under contract or they will be placed
back into this year's draft. The Bruins last week had yet to come
to terms with '97 picks Jim Baxter (180) or Eric Van Acker (218).
Ben Clymer (27) is looking to be declared a free agent, but his
case is headed to arbitration . . . WBZ Radio's Bob Beers, who
doubles as a Providence Bruins blue-liner, would have some trouble
holding the microphone these days. Slashed in Game 3 of the
Providence-Fredericton playoff series last week, his left middle
finger was fractured in six places.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ted Leonsis, the AOL executive who awaits league approval as new
majority owner of the Capitals, flew unannounced to Boston for one
of the Bruins-Sabres playoff games and watched from the stands.
``It was great stuff, a lot of fun,'' Leonsis told the Washington
Post. ``I got there early and walked around every floor of the
building. We could learn a lot from them.'' Prior to convincing Abe
Pollin to sell him the Capitals, Leonsis failed in earlier bids to
buy the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers . . . The Wings
announced Friday that Scotty Bowman will be back to coach next
season. ``I looked at the alternatives,'' Bowman said, ``and they
weren't all that attractive.'' In other words, he didn't want to
retire or move into scouting. He also knows, at age 65, that his
working years are growing short. ``When I was in Pittsburgh, and
the late Bob Johnson was coaching _ he took the job, I guess, in
his late 50s _ he would always relate everything to golf,''
recalled Bowman. ``He said then that he was on the back nine.
That's how I feel, too. I don't know what hole I'm on, but I'm on
the back nine.'' . . . Two of Bowman's top aides in Detroit, Dave
Lewis and Barry Smith, could be on some clubs' short lists for a
head coaching job. The Kings could have an eye on Lewis, who played
for them between stops on Long Island and in New Jersey. Smith was
runner-up to Jim Schoenfeld two years ago in Phoenix. GM Bobby
Smith dismissed Schoenfeld last week, just about a week after
voters resoundingly accepted the formation of a stadium district
aimed at building the Coyotes a new 18,000-seat arena at what is
now a dying shopping mall (Los Arcos) on the Phoenix/Scottsdale
border . . . Less than a month to go before the expansion draft and
the Atlanta Thrashers still haven't named a coach. GM Don Waddell
said last week that he expects to bring a handful of candidates to
Atlanta next month for final interviews . . . The Minnesota Wild
expect to have a GM named around July 4. Some of the reported
candidates include: Les Jackson, Dave McNab, Mike Smith, Paul
Holmgren, Herb Brooks, and Page.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether the Penguins will exist next season. Mario
Lemieux reworked his proposal last week for presentation to
bankruptcy judge Bernard Markovitz, which leaves the whole process
only one step from being offered on E-Bay. The league even has
talked publicly about the franchise being dissolved, which would
mean the likes of Jaromir Jagr would be up for grabs in some form
of dispersal/purchase draft. Remember, Markovitz has to protect the
creditors (some 200 of whom are owed approximately $125 million),
which means selling off the players and going out of biz really
isn't an option . . . Last week's tribute to Celtics great Bill
Russell has me thinking. May 10, 2000 will be the 30th anniversary
of Bobby Orr's overtime goal that clinched the 1970 Stanley Cup for
the Bruins. Imagine the crowd inside the Vault if Orr and pals were
brought together again on that date. Imagine the charity money it
would generate . . . There's a lot to like about Buffalo _ contrary
to what my pal Dan Shaughnessy writes _ but Sabres fans should feel
ashamed over the derisive chants they fired Bourque's way at Marine
Midland Arena during the Boston-Buffalo series. Foolish. What would
they have thought if Gil Perreault had received the same treatment?
Now, as for the city, without doubt Buffalo is in sad decay. But
there are a lot of bad cities in America. The shame of Buffalo is
not what it is, but that it refuses to play to its strengths (i.e.
waterfront, large surrounding population base, superb highway
infrastructure leading to Toronto, Boston, Manhattan, Cleveland,
and Pittsburgh). It could be one of the Northeast's great cities,
yet it just sits there with a dunce cap pulled over its eyes _ very
similar to what Boston had become by the mid-'60s . . . I'll listen
to sports radio again when someone approaches the art that David
Brudnoy displays nightly on WBZ. The media industry is a copycat
commerce. Why can't someone in sports take the Brudnoy schematic,
raise the standard (if there is one), and see what comes out of the
box? . . . It's not a fait accompli that Brian Sutter is back as
Flames coach next season. Management has picked up the option on
his contract, but the former Bruins coach would like a bump in pay
(he made less than $300,000 in US dollars last season) and a
contract extension. Coaches on one-year deals find it hard to
command respect from players, who figure the guy behind the bench
is a lame-duck boss . . . The big winner in the bounce of the
Ping-Pong balls in the NHL lottery drawing was Chicago. The
Blackhawks would have picked No. 8 overall but, with only a 3.7
percent chance of having their ball picked first, got bumped up to
No. 4. It's their best position since 1984, when they claimed Ed
Olczyk at No. 3. The Hawks also have the No. 23 pick. Perhaps they
could package the No. 23 with Alexei Zhamnov and land another prime
pick . . . The Cleveland Lumberjacks will be Chicago's IHL
affiliate next season, after Tampa Bay, under new ownership,
switched to the Detroit Vipers. Cleveland will have no fewer than
three coaches: Phil Russell, Blair MacDonald, and Perry Ganchar,
one of whom will get the No. 1 job. MacDonald, Wayne Gretzky's
first right wing in Edmonton, scored 46 goals in the Great One's
sidecar, prompting Oilers boss Glen Sather to say, ``A fire hydrant
could score 40 goals playing with Gretzky.'' . . . Speaking of
Gretzky, he was in the Madison Square Garden audience last Friday
night for the Daytime Emmy Awards, sitting with wife Janet Jones
and the cast of ``One Life to Live.'' During his playing days,
Gretzky appeared on ``The Young and the Restless,'' playing a thug
(``I'm Wayne from the Edmonton operation'').
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
