<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' PEREZ GETS SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Carlos Perez has had discussions with Dodgers ace and
Mr. Work Ethic, Kevin Brown, the past few days. And manager Davey
Johnson wanted to get Perez out of Saturday's game with only
positive thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Dodgers were looking out for the puzzling
left-hander, but the biggest difference might be that Perez was
looking out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to play around a lot before the game, but he was
acting like this was more of a championship game,'' Dodgers catcher
Angel Pena said. ``He concentrated. He was different when he came
in (the clubhouse).''
</P>
<P>
   He was different on the mound, too.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed two hits in five shutout innings and got help from
four relievers as the Dodgers beat the Atlanta Braves 2-1 in front
of a season-high 49,258 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's first win since April 30 also marked the first time in
four starts he's allowed less than four runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Kevin Brown was saying, `One pitch at a time, one
out at a time,''' said Perez, who improved to 2-6 and lowered his
ERA to 5.73. ``I really prepared myself. I never beat Atlanta (at
Turner Field). I just changed things a little bit. I used a lot of
fastballs inside. My velocity was a little better, especially when
you have an idea of what you're doing and you know where (the ball)
is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves lefty Tom Glavine (3-6) allowed six hits in seven
innings, but his downfall was an uncharacteristic four walks, three
in succession in the fifth inning. Though the Dodgers went 0 for 15
with runners in scoring position, Glavine issued bases-loaded walks
to Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi to give the Dodgers a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wanted a lead for Perez in the middle of the game and
got it. Though Perez threw only 71 pitches, after he hit Bret Boone
with a pitch and Chipper Jones reached on an error in the sixth,
Johnson went to his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Jamie Arnold got a pair of ground balls, the second
resulting in a double play to end the sixth. Jones homered off Alan
Mills in the eighth, but closer Jeff Shaw pitched the ninth for his
11th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if I got a chance to give him a win after five innings,
I'll do whatever I have to,'' Johnson said. ``If I had to use Shaw
in the eighth, I would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   As adamant as Johnson was about getting Perez out of the game
feeling good, Perez and Pena were equally insistent about pitching
inside. Pena said that's why Perez hit two batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the one that gets him over the hump,'' Johnson
said. ``I think a game like this can help ease the pressure. He
wasn't going to lose it. I wasn't going to let it happen. I needed
something positive for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez admitted he's been feeling the weight of signing a
three-year, $15 million contract during the offseason, especially
since he hasn't performed nearly the way he did last season when he
went 4-4 with a 3.24 ERA in 11 starts with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's velocity dipped to the low 80s on his fastball a few
starts ago, but it was back to the mid-80s against the Braves.
Things were going so poorly for Perez that five innings and no runs
qualifies as a windfall pitching performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really needed a win, and for it to keep going,'' Perez said.
``This year, I'm not going too good. I make good money, the team
takes care of me. I hope everything changes beginning with
tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
