<HEADER>
A6494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-AUTORACINGNOTEBOO     05-30 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUITS STILL NEED BETTER CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ So the parties in this split between the Indy
Racing League and Championship Auto Racing Teams are talking.
Actually, they have been talking for quite some time. The fact that
there is even a dialogue is a positive development, but,
unfortunately, it is the only one in the ongoing discussions
between Tony George, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway president and
IRL founder, and Andrew Craig, CART chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   According to published reports, the talks were joined last week
by NASCAR president Bill France and CART board member and car owner
Roger Penske, both of whom have a vested interest in bringing about
a reconciliation between the warring open-wheel series after their
two companies _ International Speedway Corporation and Penske
Motorsports _ merged earlier this month into a mega-motorsports
enterprise that will control 10 tracks throughout the country, with
four more on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to published reports that the IRL and CART were on
the verge of a merger, George confirmed there indeed had been a
meeting last Thursday in Indy between the principals, but he denied
that the sides had reached any kind of accord. He even went so far
as to suggest the story was planted by CART operatives ``in order
to manipulate their stock price,'' and to ``distract from this
race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no indication, from what I've picked up on, that
we're any closer in philosophy,'' George said. ``Talking may lead
to something, but as we talk today there's nothing that leads me to
believe we're closer (to a reconciliation).''
</P>
<P>
   All this, of course, should come as disheartening news to
open-wheel racing fans who would like nothing more than to see the
IRL and CART patch up their differences, reunite in a new series _
which could be called, quite simply, Indy Car _ and regain whatever
losses they have suffered in this costly and fractious dispute.
</P>
<P>
   It only seemed to get worse Thursday when Leo Mehl, the IRL's
executive director, openly groused that the only way a
reconciliation could be reached was if there was a compromise on
the engine rules, which appears to be the biggest stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the IRL is concerned, there is no room for
compromise,'' said Mehl, who launched into a harangue against CART
when asked about reports of a merger. ``I don't know anything about
that, but let me tell you my take on it. Just call it the May
Whine. The CART guys get the May Whine. They sit around in their
wine cellars and they see 50 hours of Indy on TV. There's a lot of
pressure from their sponsors; some of their sponsors are upset that
they don't have the right equipment. It's worse this year than I've
ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   CART officials have refused to engage the IRL in a war of
rhetoric. Ron Richards, CART's vice president of communications,
indicated that it was CART's intent to continue to work toward a
mutually beneficial reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I was disappointed in that comment,'' Penske said,
referring to George's remark about the series still being far apart
in philosophies. ``Because I think that the conversations that have
taken place, and I'm sure there have been many, they're genuine and
they're positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that was really what Tony was thinking,'' he
added. ``I know that Leo had some real sharp comments, but, really,
when you're trying to bring something together, comments by people
who are key really should be guarded so you work towards a solution
and not to drive the process further apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what encouraging developments the talks had produced,
George said, ``I can't say that we're encouraged about anything. I
think the media, in this case, jumped to conclusions. I can tell
you that we're going about our business and I'm sure they are doing
the same thing. All I can say is that anybody (from CART) who
chooses to run here is going to have to do so under the rules that
we have in place, and it's going to have to be for the series.
They're all welcome to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   But not until, it seems, CART first returns on its knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of the fun times I had in the week or two we'd
spend at Indy, going to St. Elmo's and a lot of the stuff we'd used
to do, we miss that,'' Penske said. ``And certainly, we'd like to
see that come back, but we need to think positively and there's no
question, in my mind, that we can pull this back together. But one
man's got to make that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our group is poised and ready to sit down and put it
together,'' he added. ``And I think they're prepared to put
something on the table that would be rational and easy to do and
everybody would win, but we'll see where this takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After finishing runner-up to Jeff Gordon in the last two
Coca-Cola 600s, Rusty Wallace, driver of the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford
Taurus, hopes the third time will be the charm in Sunday night's
NASCAR Winston Cup race at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte, N.C.
``Two years ago we led the 600 right until the end and got beat by
another team taking only two tires while we got four,'' Wallace
said. ``Then last year we led the thing until the very end and got
beat by a team taking on four tires when we got two. The thing is
that we lost them both to the same team and driver.''
Coincidentally, Gordon made a daring late-race move against Wallace
that, for all intents and purposes, wrested the lead and the
victory away from him in the 1999 Daytona 500. ``It really gets
frustrating to see the big wins like those just slip right through
your fingers when you're so close to winning them,'' Wallace said.
``It's doubly frustrating when it seems like it's the same guys
always taking away your big paycheck.'' . . . Dale Earnhardt Jr.,
the 24-year-old son of the seven-time Winston Cup champion, will
make his debut in Sunday night's Coca-Cola 600 after an impressive
qualifying effort Wednesday night in his Budweiser-sponsored
Chevrolet Monte Carlo (184.407 m.p.h.) that even outdid his old
man, who qualified 15th fastest (183.692 m.p.h.). It was the
culmination of Earnhardt's much-anticipated debut after Budweiser
announced a record $50 million-plus sponsorship deal with the
reigning Busch Grand National champion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr. said he was ``running on 8 to 8 1/2 cylinders''
after getting back behind the wheel of his car after suffering a
broken right ankle on the first turn of the season opener at
Homestead, Fla. ``I'm better, much better,'' he said . . .
Indianapolis Motor Speedway will honor the nation's 116 living
Congressional Medal of Honor winners at Sunday's race, including
three from Massachusetts: Thomas G. Kelley, a 60-year-old Vietnam
veteran from Boston; Thomas J. Hudner, a 74-year-old Korean War vet
from Concord; and Charles A. MacGillivray, an 82-year-old World War
II vet from Braintree . . . Arie Luyendyk, the pole sitter who is
retiring from open-wheel racing after Sunday's Indy 500, was
selected as an overwhelming favorite in an informal poll of 24
national media members, garnering 11 votes. Greg Ray and Scott
Goodyear tied for second with 4 votes apiece, while Robby Gordon
had 3 and Billy Boat and Kenny Brack each garned 1 vote . . . The
Globe's prediction: We're going with Ray. Last year's dark horse
has blossomed into a thoroughbred. Giddyap, Greg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
