<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-GROWTH-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP'S RISE MIRRORS REGION'S GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In 1949, the San Fernando Valley was nothing like
the sprawling, economically vital and diverse center of commerce it
is today.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, everything west of Sepulveda Boulevard
consisted of ranches and farms and orchards, with a few small
communities such as Chatsworth, Northridge and Canoga Park mere
dots in the otherwise rural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Los Angeles County was the largest farm crop producer
in the nation, and the Valley was a key part of that.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of local industrial leaders had a different vision
of the Valley. They saw it as a place where people could both live
and work. They wanted to create not just housing, but businesses
where the people who lived in those houses could work.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they wanted to help spur growth by creating a balance
between the houses built and the jobs available.
</P>
<P>
   So they founded the Industrial Association of the San Fernando
Valley, a group dedicated to development, land use and
transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   It is the group that in 1981 became known as the Valley Industry
and Commerce Association. And it is a group that celebrates its
50th anniversary with a gala dinner Saturday at the Sheraton
Universal Hotel in Universal City.
</P>
<P>
   Has the nonprofit VICA succeeded in its mission? According to
former chairman David Fleming, the answer is a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of VICA is found in the fact that the majority of
people that now live in the San Fernando Valley have jobs in the
San Fernando Valley,'' said Fleming, who attended his first meeting
of the group in 1959. ``That, in effect, is the `A' on VICA's
report card. That never would have happened without VICA.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Valley has grown, so has VICA. Starting out as an
advocacy group focused on development, land use and transportation
issues, VICA's reach has extended beyond that to embrace education,
immigration, welfare and other social and political issues that
members say are crucial for a healthy business and economic
environment.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, VICA focused on the San Fernando Valley and worked
with local officials to accomplish its goals. Now, it also
represents the neighboring Santa Clarita, Antelope, Conejo and Simi
valleys, and members are no strangers to Sacramento or Washington,
D.C., where they lobby hard on behalf of local interests.
</P>
<P>
   And from a purely volunteer-driven organization, it now has a
professional staff of 20 that helps further the organization's
causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key point is the changes in VICA just reflect the
changes in the Valley, the changes in the economy, the changes in
the needs of Valley businesses,'' said Ross Hopkins, who served as
VICA's president in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   According to VICA officials, the association took the lead in
establishing the Tillman Water Reclamation Plant in the Sepulveda
Basin, expansion of the freeway system through the Valley, and
zoning that encouraged industrial development in the Northwest
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It also influenced the development of Warner Center in Woodland
Hills, Porter Ranch in Northridge, Universal City and Fashion
Square Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   VICA is filled with longtime members such as Sanford Paris, who
runs Encino-based Paris Industrial Parks. He joined VICA in 1968
and is a past chairman of the association.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, the now 61-year-old was developing properties in
Pacoima. He was brought into the VICA fold by Walter Burke, a
longtime industrial real estate broker who had chaired the
association's water committee ``and used to regale the board with
the future problems of water for Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, joining the association seemed the natural thing to
do, Paris said. Plus, he was impressed with the membership, which
included top people from the various utilities, banks and the
Southern Pacific Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the movers and shakers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, he witnessed VICA's dramatic growth and its
increasing influence both in and out of the Valley. For example,
VICA members in the early 1970s traveled to Sacramento to help
resolve the controversial issue of where to locate a liquid natural
gas depot.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was to locate it somewhere along the coast. But the
demand for liquid natural gas fell and the facility was never
built.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the association during those years became more inclusive,
drawing in other types of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the name was changed: It's now Valley Industry
!ital!and!off! Commerce,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The changing face of the Valley's business environment also is
reflected in the way its membership has changed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more women, there are more smaller businesses and I
would say the membership is probably younger on balance, despite
all us old people,'' Paris said.
</P>
<P>
   Many past chairpersons left a profound mark on the association.
During Fleming's tenure in 1989 and 1990, for example, VICA
developed its political clout, lobbying to an unprecedented degree
at the state and federal levels on behalf of local business
interests.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   It also began inviting nationally and internationally known
figures such as Henry Kissinger to its annual dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has helped elevate the state of VICA,'' said Fleming, now
chairman of the Economic Alliance of the San Fernando Valley. ``We
now do outreach programs to Sacramento and Washington that had
never been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   In the more political and social arena, VICA has actively
supported local bond measures; worked with the city on business tax
reform; supported the Valley's right to study secession and
distributed petitions; supported the North American Free Trade
Agreement; advocated education and welfare reform; and is now
involved in reforming immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   It's all an impressive set of accomplishments, says Stuart
Solomon, a member since 1970 who helped create VICA's education
committee in the middle of that decade. Yet most people simply are
not aware of the crucial role that VICA played in bringing them the
things that they now take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   But it's this track record that keeps Solomon a happy VICA
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of this organization, as you would hear from
the people who've been involved over the years,'' Solomon said.
``It's really done a lot for the Valley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
