<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-VICA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICA TO TARGET TRANSIT, PUBLIC SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Over its 50-year life, the Valley Industry and
Commerce Association has grown into one of the most influential
bodies in Los Angeles, extending its interests from business to
encompass educational, social and quality-of-life issues.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the association has reached the half-century mark, what
do current members and officers foresee from VICA in the next 50
years? More of the same, they say, given the association's track
record.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond laboring for a better business environment, the
association will take a more active role in improving
transportation and public safety, said Steve Lew, chairman of the
VICA board and a consultant in civic affairs at Universal Studios
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Also needed is some unity between state and federal immigration
laws, now a confusing mish-mash that cause problems for employer
and employee alike, he said. It's an issue that VICA is already
dealing with at the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are issues that will be with us well into the 21st
century as they have been in the 20th,'' Lew said. ``So for those
reasons, VICA's future is very bright.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Lew and other members, VICA's focus on such issues
is essential to maintaining and strengthening the region's economy.
And given the region's economic importance, what's good for the
Valley will be good for the state as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality-of-life issues will always be a major focus, not
only for businesses but residents in the greater San Fernando
Valley region,'' Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that VICA will stop looking out for business
interests. On the contrary, association President Bonny L. Herman
expects VICA to expand its role in the business advocacy arena _ in
the Valley and perhaps the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business issues now have no geographic boundaries and,
therefore, VICA can become a Southern California if not a statewide
advocacy brand name,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Hill, an association vice chairman, has seen VICA's role
evolve dramatically in the 10 years he's been a member.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined, the association focused primarily _ though not
exclusively _ on business issues. Over the years, he saw its
influence extend into social areas that only seem to take VICA far
afield from its original intent.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Hill and other members, these issues are
crucial to preserving the region's economy. Simply stated, better
transportation, improved public safety and the like make the Valley
_ and the state _ a better place to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state becomes economically healthy it becomes
attractive to businesses ... from around the world,'' said Hill,
vice president of corporate relations at 20th Century Industries
based in suburban Woodland Hills. ``And the reverse is true: The
ability to market California products and California services to
the rest of the world is enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he sees VICA's influence expanding over the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see that VICA will play a major role in the promotion and
preservation of the economic vitality of the state of California,
and that VICA will have an increasing role at the national level,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herman's one disappointment is that VICA's membership isn't
growing fast enough for her satisfaction. VICA now has 330 members,
about half of them small businesses of 20 or fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   It's a problem that VICA shares with other business groups such
as the Valley's various chambers of commerce. Collectively, she
said, VICA and the chambers have some 7,000 members, yet there are
60,000 businesses in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Her wish for the coming years is to find ``the magic solution''
that will result in more businesses supporting their chambers and
VICA, thus taking ``a more active role in protecting their own
turf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The collective voices of many are more powerful than a few,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
