<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-PINEDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD RETAINS IBF CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ Felix Trinidad was an advertisement for himself
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The IBF welterweight champion not only crushed the hopes and
several vital organs of Hugo Pineda when he knocked him senseless
with a left hook to the solar plexus in the fourth round but also
made a persuasive argument that he is the best welterweight in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   This may not prove to be the case, because Oscar De La Hoya will
have something to say about that if the two meet as scheduled Sept.
18, but until such time as they do _ and there is not yet an
agreement between Trinidad and promoter Don King to make the match
_ Trinidad cannot make his case any more emphatically than he did
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Roberto Clemente Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Trinidad takes his opponents out with withering shots
to the head that temporarily render a man unconscious, but this
time the damage was done by a string of body shots that left Pineda
gasping for air after three rounds and on the floor and out of both
air and the fight by the end of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me to the body so hard and so much it knocked the air
out of me,'' Pineda (36-2-1) said. ``I was in good condition and
that let me go an extra round. But he punches very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It was evident almost immediately that Trinidad's hand speed was
vastly superior to Pineda's and the challenger realized it as well.
He made few bombing runs in the first two rounds and when he did,
he failed to deliver the payload that had brought him 27 of his 36
victories by knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Pineda would throw occasionally, but Trinidad either eluded his
punches or countered with a quicker return that scored, which is
why the challenger connected on only nine percent of his punches
(23 of 245).
</P>
<P>
   By the third round, the champion had turned into a stalker,
walking ever closer to Pineda in search of the opening he knew he
would find. Once he rocked Pineda in Round 3 and the partisan crowd
of 8,156 bellowed Trinidad's name, but Pineda stayed composed and
no further damage was inflicted beyond his growing reluctance to
move his fists too far away from his own ears as the air slowly
escaped from his belly.
</P>
<P>
   This obviously complicated Pineda's offensive efforts, but in
the very next round Trinidad closed the distance and the show with
two short right hands to the head and a crushing left hook to the
belly that dropped Pineda to the canvas in a crumpled heap.
</P>
<P>
   One hand clung to the bottom rope for a moment as if he might
use it to pull himself upright, but Pineda made no real effort to
move as the champion ran across the ring and climbed up on the
turnbuckle, his arms thrust toward the sky while the referee began
his count.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad remained atop those ropes with his back to Pineda,
supremely sure of his victory until he sullenly glanced over his
shoulder as referee Roberto Ramirez finished his count at 2:53 of
the round.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad not only landed 50 percent of his 151 punches, but in
the final round closed the show like a champion, connecting on 32
of the final 52 he threw.
</P>
<P>
   That Trinidad (35-0, 29 KO) can fight was obvious long before
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, but there remains scant evidence yet that he can
sell, which is what the fight game at his level is all about.
Although his performance Saturday night elevated him further in the
eyes of boxing purists, the IBF champion did nothing to help his
argument for a larger purse than the $8 million guarantee he
already has been offered to face De La Hoya because nearly 4,000
seats were left empty at Clemente Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a matter of boxing business. What Felix Trinidad did
Saturday night to Hugo Pineda was about the fighting business and
on this night, at least, Trinidad was king of that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WBA flyweight champion Leo Gamez (32-6-1, 24 KO) stopped game
but outclassed Josue Dickie Camacho (16-7, 6 KO) at 2:06 of the
eighth round after beating him consistently from first bell to
final punch . . . Former WBA featherweight champion Fred Norwood
(34-0-1, 20 KO) reclaimed the title from the man he first took it
from, winning a boring and foul-marred split decision from Antonio
Cermeno (35-3).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
