A6511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      05-30 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS BRASS PUTS THINKING CAP ON 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Tuesday is the day NFL teams start clearing
out veterans to make salary cap room for their rookies. It's the
day a team can cut a player and be able to spread out the remainder
of his signing bonus over several years, rather than absorbing it
all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Teams like the Patriots, who once plucked defensive lineman
Henry Thomas in a post June 1 move, likely will be active.
</P>
<P>
   According to the team's salary cap guru, vice president Andy
Wasynczuk, and coach Pete Carroll, the Patriots aren't likely to
wield the ax Tuesday, but wait until they get closer to signing
Damien Woody, Andy Katzenmoyer, and Kevin Faulk, their top three
draft picks, who are in line for decent salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing what needs to be done to prepare for things we
have to do in the next few weeks,'' said Carroll. ``We're making
sure we go through all of our options before we do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Their current plight is rather ominous. They are just $35,000
under budget, just enough to pay Zefross Moss's takeout bill but
not enough to sign their rookies, add a veteran defensive tackle or
running back, and continue contract extension talks with Ty Law and
Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk points out that restructuring existing contracts _
namely those of Bruce Armstrong and Ben Coates _ are two obvious
avenues available to them, or they could release players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure somebody will be cut at some point during the
summer,'' said Wasynczuk. ``It's not something we're going to do
right away or something we have to do right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' prime candidate for release is offensive tackle
Moss, a player some would argue was the team's most consistent
lineman last year. But he also has a contract that would save the
Patriots a good chunk of money at a position where they have
maneuverability and the need to introduce some youth into the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Moss's 1999 salary is $1.1 million and his pro-rated signing
bonus is $450,000, which the Patriots would have to absorb against
their cap for the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the possibility, much less likely, that if it was
decided that second-year man Tebucky Jones was going to start at
right cornerback, that Steve Israel, in the final year of his
contract, could be cut, providing a savings of $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   If Todd Rucci was the choice, the team would save his $1.085
million salary, but his pro-rated $560,000 bonus would count
against the cap through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been told anything, and I don't see it,'' said
Rucci's agent, Jack Bechta.
</P>
<P>
   Other less likely possibilities for release include Shawn
Jefferson, who will earn $1.3 million, with the team responsible
for the $518,500 against the cap. Jefferson already has received a
$350,000 roster bonus, which leads one to believe he is safe. Max
Lane, who will be paid $1 million this year, already has been paid
a $100,000 roster bonus. Safety Willie Clay will earn $1.5 million,
but it appears the Patriots want to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carroll says Jones has made so much progress he is a legitimate
candidate to start at the right corner spot. ``We can't wait to get
him out there,'' said Carroll. ``He's shown in some of our drills
the ability to stay with his man. We're very excited about him at
this point. We'll wait and see how he performs in training camp and
in the preseason games, but our inclination right now is to give
him a great chance to win a job.'' . . . Clay, a former teammate of
Barry Sanders, was taken back by the future Hall of Fame running
back's handling of his squabbleswith the Lions, which included
major criticism of the organization from Sanders's father. ``I'm a
little disappointed in Barry,'' said Clay. ``I know it's his
father, but Barry has to step in there and not let those things be
said. It puts the entire organization in an uproar. It puts (coach)
Bobby Ross and the organization in a tough position. Barry is the
best player in the NFL, but I don't know what's wrong with showing
up at least one day for a minicamp just to show his teammates that
he's a part of the team.'' . . . Clay spent last weekend overseeing
his camp in Pittsburgh, which attracted 650 youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' minicamp was swimming with former Patriots last week.
Ray Lucas, who suddenly finds himself the fourth quarterback behind
Scott Zolak and Tom Tupa, may see more duty as a receiver. The Jets
still covet his special teams ability. Keith Byars, meanwhile, was
not in attendance. He has said he'd like to return to the Jets for
another year, but Parcells is looking at his younger players at the
moment . . . Quite a sight at the Jets' camp at Hofstra is Richmond
rookie defensive tackle Marc Megna of Fall River, who likes to work
out after the workout . . . University of New Hampshire running
back Jerry Azumah, drafted by the Bears, already has been converted
to defensive back . . . Dave Meggett has finished school at Towson
and is expected to sign with either Cleveland or Tennessee next
week . . . Todd Burger, the offensive lineman cut by Parcells after
one year on the Jets' roster, is about to resurface again with
either Tampa Bay or Carolina. Burger was signed to a major deal
after Parcells lost out on Rucci. It may or may not be a
coincidence that Burger was the only Jet who didn't show for the
offseason conditioning program last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local agent Brad Blank said defensive lineman Jeff Lageman has
retired after 10 years, the last four with Jacksonville, but he may
pull a Charles Haley and resurface when a contending team is in
need of a pass rusher. In the meantime, Lageman, a newlywed, may
try his hand at broadcasting . . . Patriots fullback Tony Carter
was married two weeks ago . . . The Patriots managed to avoid one
of those overseas exhibition games that can mess a team up for a
week. Last year, the Patriots didn't make out too badly in Mexico
City, but this year, on Aug. 7, the Chargers and Broncos play in
Sydney's Stadium Australia, site of the 2000 Olympics . . . Members
of the rookie quarterback class will face each other in three
exhibition games. Cleveland's Tim Couch opposes Minnesota's Daunte
Culpepper Aug. 21, Chicago's Cade McNown faces Philadelphia's
Donovan McNabb Sept. 2, and McNabb faces Culpepper Aug. 26. That's
providing the players are signed and ready to go . . . Parcells
praised Zolak in minicamp last week. Zolak arrived in decent shape
and has thrown the ball well. Tupa also impressed with his punting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tests are certainly the fad in this country. We hear of the MCAS
tests for students and tests for teachers, etc. Now agents are
being given 50-question tests on the collective bargaining
agreement, which was due at union offices last Friday. The union
hasn't said what it will do if agents fail it, but they are serious
about agents responding to it . . . Brace yourselves for the new
jargon during NFL telecasts next season when the new instant replay
system is born. The system will use digital computer technology
rather than videotape, as was used from 1986-91. The new system
gives quicker access to replays because there's no tape to rewind.
The four individuals in the replay booth will be called the
``replay assistant, technician, video operator, and communicator.''
The replay assistant is the only link to the referee on the field.
The head coaches can challenge two plays per game, but in the final
two minutes of each half and in overtime, the replay assistant
makes the call as to whether the play is reviewed. The replay
assistant will be someone who has an officiating background. There
will be a buzzer system in place in which the head coach, wearing a
belt pack containing a buzzer, can buzz if he wants to challenge a
call. The buzz goes to the referee and the umpire and to the replay
booth. The communicator has 90 seconds to make the call. Sounds
like a good system, except why is human error no longer acceptable?
``It's a good system,'' said Carroll, who was introduced to it at
the owners' meetings in Atlanta last week. ``It adds a whole new
set of things a head coach has to think about during the game. You
have two shots to challenge and you have to pick those spots
carefully. Like anything else, it'll take a little practice.'' . .
. Boston agent Jack Mula was playing in the Ted Johnson Golf
Tournament in a foursome with taxman Mitch Halpern, and financial
analysts Gino Ellison and Kevin Leahy. The celebrity chosen to play
with Mula's group was Patriots defensive end Brandon Mitchell. ``He
shows up in jeans and work boots with golf clubs that Bobby Jones
probably used,'' said Mula. ``He had never played golf in his life
and he makes two eagle putts from 30-40 feet. On the first hole he
drove the ball about 310 yards. It was unbelievable.'' Mula's group
won the tournament with a 10-under-par score.
</P>
</TEXT>
