<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT TAKES BLAME FOR `TIRED' HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 60th running of the Massachusetts Handicap Saturday
had just finished at Suffolk Downs and Bob Baffert was asked to
give an analysis of the race his horse, Real Quiet, had just run.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who never looks or sounds flustered in the biggest of
races, offered no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Quiet,'' said Baffert, ``was real tired.''
</P>
<P>
   After a mile-and-an-eighth endurance race on a track that
Baffert said Real Quiet never quite took too, no one would argue
with the trainer's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just came up empty,'' said Baffert, who a year ago watched
Real Quiet come within a nose of winning the Triple Crown, getting
edged out in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk crowd had expected a match race between Behrens and
Real Quiet, the two heavy betting favorites at post time.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet came into Boston as the biggest celebrity in the
race. Baffert, had done radio promos, highlighting the fact that
the MassCap had a Kentucky Derby winner in its field.
</P>
<P>
   When Real Quiet worked out Thursday morning, the Suffolk stable
hands came out for an up-close-and-personal look.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday Baffert recognized a sluggishness in his horse.
</P>
<P>
   Although he showed no initial effects from the plane trip from
Kentucky to New York and a nearly five-hour trip by van to Suffolk,
Real Quiet showed signs of fatigue that Baffert and jockey Gary
Stevens hoped would not show up Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't seem to like the track,'' said Baffert after a race
in which Running Stag took the lead early and forced Real Quiet to
extend himself in trying to stay with both Behrens and Running
Stag. ``He was having trouble with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the race, Real Quiet was calm coming out of Barn 22 and
in the paddock as Baffert talked casually with Stevens and owner
Michael Pegram. Baffert gave every indication that his horse was
fit to run _ and run well.
</P>
<P>
   But later, after Real Quiet came down the stretch and Stevens
asked him to give the extra boost that had won the Kentucky Derby
and Preakness, there was not enough left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got beat,'' Baffert said. ``The other horses just beat
him. He just didn't kick in. That was my fault. I didn't do a good
enough job in preparing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Baffert said that Real Quiet's unfamiliarity with
the track was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't used to the race track,'' reiterated Stevens, using
an explanation that many beaten favorites use. ``It's a little
different type of track than he's used to. It's a little deeper and
more sandy. But we really had no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuses. No one to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet ran his race and got beat. And as quickly as the race
was run, Baffert and Stevens, who is headed for a long engagement
of racing in England, were gone, running to catch planes.
</P>
<P>
   As for Real Quiet. He spent Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Suffolk. By 6
a.m. Sunday, he was also on the move, sharing a van back to New
York's Belmont Park with Running Stag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
