<HEADLINE>
ASU RUNS ITSELF OUT OF SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ In the instant that Erica Beach forgot a
lifetime of softball, Arizona State's hope of staying alive at the
Women's College World Series disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was just the first inning of an elimination game
against California on Saturday, but chances are few in college
softball at the highest level. And having runners on second and
third with one out against a flustered pitcher is almost a
mandatory scoring situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very main opportunity,'' ASU Coach Linda Wells
said. To fail to score in what ended up a 2-0 loss before 3,558
fans at Don Porter Hall of Fame Stadium was ``killer, it was a
killer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made multiple mistakes on the play,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Missy Hixon ran from third toward home on Beach's grounder, a
break so unexpected that Cal first baseman Kirsten Drake almost
froze. But she threw home in the nick of time. Hixon was ruled out
on a play in which umpire Lisa Harvey could have blinked and seen
the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze was left to Beach, the first-team All-American, who
turned to watch the play at the plate _ ``I was about to complain
about the call,'' she said _ and forgot to finish running to first.
She was doubled up on a relay from catcher Megumi Takasaki to
second baseman Lisa Iancin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much went through my mind,'' Beach said. ``I can tell
you I'll never do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   In dropping the rubber game of five against California this
season, ASU (41-28) ended its first CWS appearance since 1987 with
an 0-2 record. The Sun Devils (41-28) are on a six-game CWS losing
streak dating back to 1982, the first year of NCAA sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   But with its Fab Five (Beach, Hixon, Kirsten Voak, Erin Wardein,
Nichole Thompson) here as freshmen, and with offensive help coming
next year in recruits Kara Brun and Sara Kahler and the return of
injured outfielder Devyn Braga, the Sun Devils expect a quick
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot just being here,'' said Beach, whose father
perhaps set the tone for next season when he won a contest for
tickets to the 2000 CWS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll learn a lot from this,'' Beach said. ``Some of the
things we can't fix, but most of them we can learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing runners would be a start.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, sixth and seventh innings, the Sun Devils put the
leadoff batter on base but were able to advance only one, and that
on a wild pitch. In the sacrifice situations, Chris Gill, dropped
from cleanup to eighth, popped out on a bunt, while Jennifer
Langenhuizen and Holly Smith struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are signs of freezing up in the clutch,'' Wells said.
``We've been riding on the shoulders of our freshman pitchers
(Beach and Voak), and it didn't work out this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, we owe an apology to Nebraska for not taking this
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 16-ranked ASU won two of three from Nebraska to capture the
Region 6 tournament. But the Sun Devils stranded four in the first
three innings of a 4-1 loss to Washington that was scoreless
through five innings and similar to the wasted opportunities
against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears' hero was Lisa Iancin, who homered to left off Beach
(16-14) in the fourth and singled in an insurance run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Nicole DiSalvio (19-11) improved to 2-1 against ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Hixon slapped the next pitch for a single to left, then beat a
throw to second on Langenhuizen's sacrifice, with Voak moving both
runners to third. But the bizarre double play followed, swinging
momentum to Cal that it carried into a Saturday night elimination
game by beating Fresno State, 1-0. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
