<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDB-ACKS-METS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A BOW: KIM IMPRESSIVE IN EARNING SAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter walked toward his
newest player, Korean right-hander Byung-Hyun Kim, and bowed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a matter of respect and recognition for a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   With the flames of a New York comeback flickering at his feet,
and the Mets' top three hitters _ Edgardo Alfonzo, John Olerud and
Mike Piazza _ waiting to take their swings, the 20-year old Kim was
unflappable in his major league debut on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He retired Alfonzo and Olerud on fly balls and struck out Piazza
on a foul tip to preserve Arizona's 8-7 victory in a 3-hour,
40-minute marathon at Shea Stadium and help the Diamondbacks
(29-21) increase their National League West lead to 1{ games ahead
of San Francisco, which lost again at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're lucky to be in the big leagues and see something like
this,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The skipper had hoped to bring in Kim for the first time in a
situation with a little less pressure, but in this case, he didn't
feel like he had a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Gregg Olson, who saved Friday night's victory for
Arizona, had thrown 30-plus pitches. Right-hander Darren Holmes
still had not recovered from stiffness and soreness in his lower
back that led him to receive an epidural injection earlier in the
week. Right-hander Amaury Telemaco, the only remaining member of
the bullpen, is not accustomed to the closer's role.
</P>
<P>
   As the gate opened to the Diamondbacks' bullpen beyond the
left-field fence, Kim walked through and gazed around at vast
expanse of outfield and the multi-colored seats and heard the roar
of the crowd, which had been pumped up by Benny Agbayani's solo
home run in the sixth inning and a run-scoring double by veteran
Rickey Henderson that brought the Mets within 8-7 in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if it was a dream or real,'' said Kim, who
signed for a $2.25 million bonus on Feb. 19 but didn't arrive in
American until about a month later. He began the season with
Double-A El Paso and later was promoted to Triple-A Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   It was real, all right.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's first pitch to Alfonzo was a ball, followed by a strike.
He became confused by catcher Damian Miller's signals. The
6-foot-2, 212-pound Miller put his arm over the shoulder of the
5-11, 176-pound Kim, straightened things out and reassured him that
he was doing what he was supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo ran the count to 3-2, including a couple of fouls,
before hitting a liner to right-center that was tracked down by
center fielder Steve Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's first pitch to Olerud also was a ball. But Olerud, who hit
a two-run homer off former Met Armando Reynoso to tie it at 5 in
the fifth, took two strikes before lining out to Luis Gonzalez in
left field.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Piazza's turn. Kim watched him walk to the plate as
he had many times while watching the Los Angeles Dodgers on TV back
home in Korea, when Piazza was fellow Korean Chan Ho Park's battery
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was watching Piazza all the way, then he (Kim) kind
of smiled,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Did Kim know who it was?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes!'' Kim said emphatically, without the use of a translator.
</P>
<P>
   A called strike was first. Then Piazza fouled away three pitches
before swinging and tipping a rising slider that landed in Miller's
glove.
</P>
<P>
   A rising slider? Yes. It rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws a Frisbee,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said, ``He had nasty stuff, obviously. Some of those
pitches to Piazza were `Nintendo sliders,' like the ones you see on
video games that have a big bend to them. For him to show the poise
that he did in a situation like that was a big plus for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Jay Bell provided the margin of victory, hitting
a three-run homer off left-hander Rigo Beltran in the sixth inning
to make it 8-5. Henderson couldn't get to it as the ball landed
just beyond the left-field fence. Scoring ahead of Bell were Tony
Batista, who led off the inning with a single, and Steve Finley,
who hit a one-out double.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it might have a chance,'' Bell said. ``The ball
carries pretty well here in the daytime. I figured the least I
would get out of it was a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part about this was watching the kid out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Olson is still the closer, and that Kim will be
used on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just let him revel in the moment right now,'' Showalter
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
