<HEADLINE>
AS LANDRY BATTLES ODDS, WHITE ACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny White was sidelined with a broken wrist. So his job that
night in Anaheim was to relay plays from Tom Landry to quarterback
Steve Pelluer.
</P>
<P>
   White was standing next to the Cowboys coach when a team
employee, a former FBI agent, approached Landry and whispered in
his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Without explanation, Landry handed White the game plan and
walked hurriedly to the locker room. He returned a few minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on?'' White asked.
</P>
<P>
   Landry said a threat had been made on his life. A sniper might
be in the stands. ``They said I had to wear this,'' he said.
Opening the front of his dress shirt the coach revealed a
bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later Landry turned to give White a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach,'' Danny called out, ``you're gonna have to speak up!''
</P>
<P>
   White had moved 15 feet away. Coach and player shared a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who know Tom Landry, White always thought of his
coach as bulletproof. Maybe it's because he flew B-17s over Germany
during World War II or because he led Dallas to 20 consecutive
winning seasons and five Super Bowls. Landry was the stoic man in
the hat.
</P>
<P>
   Then the other day White received a call. The news shook him.
His former coach had received another death threat _ this one no
joke. Landry has leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   If cancer were a willful football player, Landry would put the
disease in its place with what White calls ``the look.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny never will forget his coach's glacial stare. There was
that game in Pittsburgh when White decided on his own to fake a
punt and run for a first down. The Steelers stopped him a yard
short.
</P>
<P>
   White returned to the sideline filled with dread. He knew Landry
would find him. And when he did, ``I'll never forget the way he
looked at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Recreating the moment, White slowly turned his head, and fixed
me with a withering gaze. `` `You just can't do it,' '' Landry
said, biting off each word, and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That look,'' White recalled, ``could make more impact on a
player than if he made you run 900 wind sprints or fined you a
million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   They had disagreements. But when you ask White about the 13
years he played for Landry, he speaks of his coach with admiration
and deep respect.
</P>
<P>
   Danny still can see the front-page photo that appeared in a
Dallas newspaper the day after Landry was fired after the 1988
season. White and Landry, who left the Cowboys the same year, were
pictured together. What Landry said to White that day surprised
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny,'' Landry said, ``I'm really going to miss coaching with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With'' you? White had never spoken of a desire to join the
Cowboys staff. ``I just think he knew I could be a coach,'' White
said. ``As a player my arm wasn't overpowering. Roger (Staubach)
relied on his will and his legs. I relied on my knowledge of the
game. Anticipating what defenses were going to do. But I never said
anything about being a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't recall what his mentor once said about him _
``Danny White was probably as fine a winner as we've ever had'' _
the man who moved back home and became head coach of the Arizona
Rattlers can talk at length about what Landry gave him and what he
means to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still find myself asking, `What would Coach Landry do in
this situation?' '' White said. ``I'm not talking so much about X's
and O's. It was the way he handled people. He had such a profound
impact on so many players. The way he dealt with people and
adversity is his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The day of his firing, Landry called his team together to say
goodbye. The stone-faced coach became emotional. As he groped for
words, his voice cracking, the room grew quiet. White thinks of
that raw moment now as his 74-year-old coach lies in a hospital
bed, battling the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, what Landry said to the team seems prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the last thing he told us,'' White said. ``How you
handle a crisis is more important than the crisis itself.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
