<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY500-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUYENDYK KNOWS EMOTIONS WILL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ This is it. One more walk. One final trip down
memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Turn out the lights, Arie Luyendyk. It's almost over.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk, 45, is calling it a career after today's Indianapolis
500, and saying goodbye to the circular beast is about as easy as
saying goodbye to a daughter on her wedding day.
</P>
<P>
   Tears?
</P>
<P>
   Are you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll still be around to experience the cool-down
lap (after the checkered flag),'' said Luyendyk, a two-time Indy
500 winner (1990 and 1997). ``Then, I think I'll be taking a long
time to compose myself before I get to the pits.''
</P>
<P>
   If the gods of Indy are really kind, they'll put Luyendyk in
victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Nah, too corny.
</P>
<P>
   Even A.J. Foyt didn't win the final race of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk, however, has been driving as if he's planning to give
some Hollywood producer a script to drool over.
</P>
<P>
   Although Luyendyk hasn't suited up for a race since winning the
1998 season finale at Las Vegas, he's notoriously fast at Indy and
won the third pole of his career here a week ago. Luyendyk also was
runner-up in 1993 and third in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I've done well here,'' said Luyendyk, who
moved to Scottsdale nine years ago. ``I know I can run with
anybody. And I've envisioned myself winning. It would be
unbelievable to finish my career like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I won't be devastated if it doesn't happen. I think
there's 10 or 15 guys who can win this race. Really, it might be
too much to ask (to win).''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk is right. The lineup is formidable, starting with the
front row, which includes Greg Ray and Billy Boat of Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Ray bullied everyone for nearly a week before coming up a nickel
short on pole day, concluding his four-lap qualifying run with an
average speed of 225.073 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk clicked off blistering laps at a 225.179 average, and
Boat rode home third at 223.469 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the kind of month we've had, but I don't know if I want
to be considered a favorite,'' Ray said. ``I was a favorite for the
pole, and look what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat warned not to read too much into qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg and Arie have had the most speed in practice, but the
thing about this race is everything changes on race day,'' Boat
said. ``The race brings the field closer together. Instead of two
or three running at a certain top speed, there's 15 all running
about the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to back the engine down. It's an endurance race. It
doesn't do any good to be the fastest car for 100 laps if you're
not there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the past several years, the 500-mile race, many
believe, has evolved into more of a sprint than a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   It may take longer to complete, but drivers are flexing their
machinery's muscles almost from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really don't coast around for 150 laps, then start
charging,'' Luyendyk said. ``I remember when I won in 1990, guys
were going really fast and blistering their tires. A couple of
years ago, (Tony) Stewart and I were running 220 miles per hour
halfway through the race. We were running as hard as we could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what you'll see (today).''
</P>
<P>
   What you might see even more than a blurry pace is Canadian
Scott Goodyear sticking his nose into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, who is starting on the outside of the third row, has
come within 10 seconds of being a three-time Indy 500 champion, not
a zero-time winner.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, who won at Phoenix International Raceway in March,
drove to the closest runner-up finish in race history, crossing the
line a scant .043 seconds behind Al Unser Jr. in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Goodyear finished .057 seconds behind Luyendyk.
Although Goodyear was seventh in 1993, he was only 7.911 seconds
behind winner Emerson Fittipaldi.
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget 1995, when Goodyear led with five laps to go, was
penalized for passing the pace car on a re-start and wound up 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I look at it, `Yeah, I could have won a few,' '' he
said. ``But sometimes I think I've been pretty lucky. I've been a
contender. I understand how to get the car around the track, and I
understand how to get the car to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Luyendyk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
