<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6519 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PARK'SFUTURE-AZR &LR;      05-30 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PARK'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK DECLARES FUTURES IS NOW  
 SHUNS ENDORSEMENTS TO START 
</HEADLINE>
 FUTURE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She has been referred to as the best women's player to come
along in golf in the past 10 years. But Grace Park plans to take a
drastically different path to the pros than some of her celebrated
peers, most notably Se Ri Pak and Kelli Kuehne.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who recently turned 20, said she will not sign any
contracts, or join any agency, when she turns pro after this week's
U.S. Women's Open in West Point, Miss. She enters the tournament as
an amateur on the exemption she received for winning last year's
U.S. Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, (signing contracts) is not my priority,'' said the
two-time All-American, who decided to skip her final two years at
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to concentrate on the Futures Tour for the rest of the
summer and hopefully get my LPGA card (by finishing among the top
three money winners on the Futures). If that fails, I'll try to get
my card at Q-school (in October).
</P>
<P>
   ``But until I get my LPGA card, whenever that is, I'm just going
to stick with golf and not worry about (financial matters).''
</P>
<P>
   For Pak and Kuehne, who both signed with International
Management Group before they were officially on the LPGA, the cart
came before the horse.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, the defending champ in the U.S. Open, turned pro at age 19.
At that time, she signed a one-year, $1 million contract with
Samsung, the electronics giant in her homeland of South Korea, the
same country where Park was born. That contract, however, came
before Pak's rookie season of 1997 and has since been renegotiated
into a 10-year, $10 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, who just recently found her feet on the LPGA, got a $1
million deal from Nike when she skipped her final two years at the
University of Texas. Kuehne, who failed in her initial attempt at
LPGA Qualifying School in 1997, also was 19.
</P>
<P>
   But Park is so committed to playing her way into professional
golf via the Futures Tour that she recently turned down exemptions
into three LPGA events later this summer _ the Rochester
International, the Shoprite Classic and the Jamie Farr Classic.
</P>
<P>
   According to Park's father, Soo-Nam Park, a wealthy restaurateur
from Seoul, playing on the LPGA at the moment is of no consequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace told me that (winning an LPGA event and receiving
immediate playing status) is not realistic,'' he said. ``Plus, by
playing the Futures, she can adjust to the (rigors of travel)
slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said his daughter made up her mind to turn pro after the
Dinah Shore in April, an LPGA tournament where she tied for 39th
just a week after finishing 21st in the Standard Register PING in
Phoenix. He added that winning the individual championship last
weekend at the NCAA Championship in Tulsa had no bearing on her
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Dinah Shore, she went back to playing college
tournaments, and shortly after that, she said, `Dad, there's not
enough competition for me (in college),' '' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   But deciding to turn professional rather than get her college
degree was not as easy as it might sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace always planned to go to school and get her degree,''
Park said. ``When she decided (to turn pro), she cried all night.
It was hard on her emotionally, even though she knew she was
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Soo-Nam Park said he realizes that his daughter is lucky to be
from a well-to-do family and not have to worry immediately about
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are not trying to (drive up her market value) by doing
this,'' said Park, who plans to travel with his daughter on the
Futures Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only gives her the chance to do what she wants without a
lot of distractions. She is very happy with this idea of playing
the Futures.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who already has missed eight Futures events, has 10
tournaments remaining on the women's equivalent of the men's Nike
Tour. Her first event will be the Aurora Health Care Classic in
Pewaukee, Wis., June 10-13.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Eunice Choi leads the Futures money list with
$23,374, while the No. 3 player on that list, Elizabeth Bowman, is
at $17,765. However, with prize money that ranges from $6,600 to
$9,900 for first place, Park still has time to finish among the top
three players and earn the exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Zayra Calderon, the chief executive officer of the Futures Tour,
said Park's arrival ``is great for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is joining a talented group of women golfers,'' Calderon
said. ``But she certainly brings us some star power and adds great
talent to our tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Futures money is a pittance when compared with the
$36.5 million that is offered this year on the LPGA. But Soo-Nam
Park insists this is not about money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very close family, and when Grace and I are not
traveling (on the Futures Tour), we plan to visit her brother and
sister, who are going to college in New York City, and her
mother,'' he said. ``So we are really in no hurry. We want Grace to
develop at her own pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is about Korean culture, to play for your family
and country, and to win tournaments that make everyone proud.
Everything else will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim McNulty, an agent with Cornerstone Sports, one of several
agencies pursuing Park, said the family is doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's good for the player is often lost in the mix these
days,'' McNulty said. ``I don't think for one minute that they're
holding out to make more money on her accomplishments. They simply
want to give her time to adjust and to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty said that with Park's resume, which includes 55
victories in 118 starts, as well as every major amateur and junior
title in women's golf, ``She is head and shoulders above anyone (in
college).
</P>
<P>
   ``She's possibly the best woman to come along in golf in the
past 10 years, because she's photogenic, feminine and has a golf
game that is all-world,'' he said. ``Especially her length off the
tee. Few women can hit the ball as far as Grace. That in itself
will take her a long way in terms of her marketability . . . when
the time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said moving from the amateur to pro ranks has given her
butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm nervous,'' she said. ``But it's a good
nervousness.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
