r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-WILLIAMS-K     05-30 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-WILLIAMS-KIM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS DEFENDS ROOKIE FROM METS' HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The barbed-wire tattoo that Matt Williams got in the
off-season means ``protector.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks third baseman filled that role Saturday when
20-year-old right-hander Byung-Hyun Kim entered the game against
the New York Mets in the bottom of the ninth for his major league
debut.
</P>
<P>
   As Kim warmed up, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine came out of the
dugout and stood next to plate umpire Larry Poncino, gesturing
toward the mound. It was Valentine's goal to see what pitches Kim
was featuring, but the greater purpose was to disrupt the pitcher
by trying to lure Poncino out to the mound to check Kim's glove.
</P>
<P>
   It was apparently a form of retaliation for Mets right-handed
reliever Turk Wendell having to go into the dugout Friday night to
change gloves when umpires noticed that it had two color tones.
Wendell said afterward that Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter was
behind it, but Showalter denied it, saying it was all the work of
Friday night's third-base umpire, Steve Rippley.
</P>
<P>
   So Valentine apparently figured, why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in the dugout thought it was an oversize glove,''
Valentine said. ``It figures, these guys (umpires) have a thing
about gloves. All they said was that it's one color and it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't OK with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He walked between the plate and the mound and stared at
Valentine, walking in his direction as Valentine headed back toward
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high-school BS,'' Williams said, his blood pressure
obviously rising. ``What purpose could there be for standing there
while the kid is warming up for his major league debut, other than
to try to (expletive) him up? It's stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Hey, get the (expletive) back into the dugout.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was one of the first to greet Kim after he preserved
the 8-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed as confident as he could be,'' Williams said. ``He
handled himself really well. I think having a lot of international
experience probably helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Williams asked Kim to throw his slider that
rises instead of drops. He was amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he does it. He's got two of them, one that
drops and one that rises. He's amphibious,'' Williams said, smiling
at his intentional malapropism.
</P>
<P>
   Kim is certain to become more popular among his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told the team that he was being called up on Thursday,
I told the players, `Put yourself in his shoes. You would want to
be welcomed,' '' Showalter said. ``And they have responded. They've
taken him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim's exploits were chronicled in Korean newspapers in the
United States and back in his home country, but there also was an
interested party in England _ Diamondbacks Managing General Partner
Jerry Colangelo. He called team public relations director Mike
Swanson four times to get updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him Kim was facing Mike Piazza with two outs,'' Swanson
said. ``He predicted Kim was going to strike him out. He said,
`He's going to get my ``paisan''.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kim followed through, striking out Piazza on a foul tip.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the road take Kim from here?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows, except that he has Williams as his bodyguard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
