<HEADER>
A6524 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NOTE     05-30 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAAL'S SHOULDER PROBLEM WON'T KEEP HIM FROM NEXT START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Omar is OK.
</P>
<P>
   That's the latest word on the Diamondbacks' medical front.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander &UR; Omar Daal, who left Friday night's game against the
New York Mets after seven innings because of stiffness in his
shoulder, is expected to make his next start on Wednesday night in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Daal was examined by one of the team physicians, &UR; Dr.  &UR; Roger
McCoy, and took some anti-inflammatory medication Friday night. On
Saturday, he reported to Shea Stadium and went through some
range-of-motion exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the doctor about any red flags we should look for and
there weren't any,'' Manager &UR; 
 &UR; Buck Showalter said. ``It was actually the flip side. Omar should
be ready to go by Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal (5-4) said, ``I'm OK. I'm a little sore, but that's usually
what happens after a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal, who commonly throws in the bullpen the second day after a
start, said he will skip today and might throw in the bullpen on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it feels,'' he said. ``I might skip that, too.
An extra day of rest never hurts.'' &QL;  &QL; 
With friends like these . . . &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder &UR; Luis Gonzalez made some new ``friends'' on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Mets fans beyond the left-field fence arrived early,
many perhaps, with a little extra octane running through their
veins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on us even during batting practice,'' Gonzalez said.
``I said, `Uh-oh, they know us even without our numbers,' We got a
couple runs early (two in the second inning) so that quieted them
down a little. But I've heard words I've never heard before.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans got to talk a little more trash Saturday, when the Mets
scored two runs in the first inning. &QL;  &QL; 
Is it fall already? &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third-base coach  &UR; Brian Butterfield made an interesting side
trip on Friday afternoon. He took a few players to watch a New York
Jets minicamp workout at Hofstra University. Butterfield is an
acquaintance of Jets Coach  &UR; Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   During the workout, Parcells called for a defensive alignment,
referring to it as ``baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned to us and said, `How did you like that one?' '' said
Butterfield, a native of Maine who was an avid fan of the New
England Patriots when Parcells was there and still is.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Butterfield wore a Jets cap in the clubhouse. Does
that mean Parcells wears a Diamondbacks cap in the Jets' locker
room?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're darned tootin,' '' Butterfield said. &QL;  &QL; 
Gentlemen, start your . . . &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander &UR; Gregg Olson found an innovative way to draw
interest in the annual Indianapolis 500 pool _ he marked the bottom
of tiny toy cars with the appropriate Indy car number and teammates
made their choice by taking the car. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
