<HEADLINE>
AL, NL TEAMS NEED NEW FOES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next weekend will bring the latest round of interdivisional
play. Baseball officials continue to call it interleague play, but
it's simply not so.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive year, baseball's two leagues will mix
it up, but only within their own rival divisions. So once again,
the Oakland Athletics will play the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopee!
</P>
<P>
   This was not what baseball said was going to happen when
interleague play was introduced in 1997. At that time, then-acting
Commissioner  &UR; Bud Selig said these match-ups would rotate, with
each division playing other divisions in ensuing years.
</P>
<P>
   But all we've had is the same division playing its equal in the
other league. If this keeps up, interleague play will mean nothing
in years to come. Baseball officials need to realize that
interleague play needs to be kept special.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better way of achieving that goal than to create a
rotation of divisions playing each other. For instance, the
American League East should have played the National League East in
1997, then the NL Central last season and should be getting ready
to play the NL West this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we have the NL East playing the AL East for the third
straight year, with all the other divisions following in line.
That's plain wrong.  &UR; Bernie Williams and the Yankees should be
coming to the desert for a series at Bank One Ballpark instead of
playing the Mets for a third straight year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Bombers coming to play the Diamondbacks, who are
managed by their former skipper,
 &UR; Buck Showalter, would make for a far more riveting series. It also
would be a way to introduce clubs to unfamiliar places, and that's
what building interest is all about.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves and  &UR; Greg Maddux and Co. could be making a
trip to meet  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. and Seattle this year. Or the St.
Louis Cardinals with  &UR; Mark McGwire could be visiting Tampa Bay.
Whatever the match-up, it would keep interleague play a fresh
concept instead of one that will start to lose its appeal before
long.
</P>
<P>
   There is enough fan interest in the Valley for high amounts of
anticipation if the Boston Red Sox and  &UR; Pedro Martinez were coming
to town. By the same token, imagine the Diamondbacks making a trip
to Baltimore's Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Then you could still have the Yankees and Mets playing each
other in games that would have three years worth of buildup, making
their games that much more special. Instead, get ready Diamondbacks
fans, the Texas Rangers will be in town next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Oh boy, can't wait till next year, when Minnesota and St. Louis
should be playing for the fourth straight year. Oh, the
excitement. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; With last week's trade that sent closer  &UR; Rick Aguilera from
Minnesota to Chicago, the Cubs can lay claim to having had seven of
the top 12 on the career saves list. Name the other six besides
Aguilera, who entered the weekend series ranked 12th with 281
saves. &QL; 
Dancing with the devil &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Devil Rays have gone through a stretch of games
that the most mean-spirited person might not wish on their worst
enemy. The Devil Rays, who came into the majors with the
Diamondbacks, have truly been snakebit (no pun intended) of late.
</P>
<P>
   To recap:
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, rookie  &UR; Ryan Rupe gave up one hit while needing
only 87 pitches through nine innings of a scoreless game against
Texas before being pulled in favor of closer
 &UR; Roberto Hernandez, who gave up four runs on 31 pitches in the 10th
for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Quinton McCracken, voted the MVP of last season's
inaugural club, tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right
knee while attempting a catch against the wall. He's considered out
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Vice president  &UR; Mike Veeck, the son of former White Sox owner
 &UR; Bill Veeck, resigned abruptly to spend time at home with his
7-year-old daughter, who is going blind. Veeck was hired to boost
attendance, which continues to plummet in Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's lone All-Star Game representative, pitcher  &UR; Rolando
Arrojo, landed on the disabled list because of tendinitis in his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that has been replayed to death, pitcher  &UR; Tony
Saunders, the first overall expansion pick, broke a bone in his arm
and will miss the balance of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we get a blow, it seems more and more
gut-wrenching,'' Hernandez said. ``I don't know if this team can
take any more blows.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of their unceremonious homestand, the Devil Rays
were in third place in the AL East, trailing Boston by 2{ games and
second-place New York by one game. Tampa Bay started the weekend
three games under .500 and 5{ games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Devil Rays have a major league-high 14 players
on the disabled list, including 10 from the opening day roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit some tremendous voodoo,'' outfielder  &UR; Dave Martinez
said. ``I don't know what it is. I've never seen anything like it.
We have guys going down every day.'' &QL; 
Thar's a feud a brewin' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for St. Louis Manager  &UR; Tony La Russa and Los Angeles
Manager  &UR; Davey Johnson to exchange pleasantries anytime soon. The
two took pointed verbal shots at each other last week after their
two clubs had an on-field brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson believed Cardinals utility player  &UR; Shawon Dunston
overreacted when he charged the mound after becoming the third St.
Louis player hit during last Sunday's game between the two teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got hit three times today,'' La Russa said. ``At some
point, enough is enough. But they did us a favor. Every time they
hit us, guys got ticked off and that gave us better at-bats. If
they wouldn't have hit us, we probably would have just beaten them
5-3 (instead of 8-3). They were upset with him for running the
bases hard (Dunston stole with a four-run lead in the seventh).
That's Dodger baseball. Didn't they invent that game?''
</P>
<P>
   The benches emptied after Dunston, who plays the game as hard as
anyone in the league, flipped his bat down and raced at Dodgers
rookie  &UR; Jamie Arnold, who was body-slammed to the field by Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three points for a takedown,'' Cardinals pitcher  &UR; Juan Acevedo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Johnson took La Russa to task for insinuating that
Arnold purposely threw at Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a little respect for La Russa for accusing the kid of
nailing him,'' Johnson said. ``That was the farthest thing away.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa said, ``Losing respect can go both ways.'' &QL; 
Looking in the mirror &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After attempting to nail Phillies management over being too
cheap to field a competitive club, Philadelphia ace  &UR; Curt Schilling
poked fun at himself while taping a commercial for the club's local
ALS ( &UR; Lou Gehrig's disease) auction on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling appears in the spot with his wife, who is expounding
on the merits of coming to the auction. All the while, Schilling is
next to her with a piece of tape over his mouth, giving the thumbs
up to everything she says. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Cubs listed among the career saves leaders are headed by the
top dog himself,  &UR; Lee Smith, whose 478 saves rank first. Also
joining that fraternity are  &UR; Dennis Eckersley (third all-time,
390),  &UR; Randy Myers (fifth, 347),  &UR; Goose Gossage (eighth, 310),
 &UR; Bruce Sutter (ninth, 300) and
 &UR; Doug Jones (11th, 294). &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at pedro.gomez &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
