<HEADLINE>
SMITH IS GIVEN OK FOR COACH INTERVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith has received permission from
at least two NHL teams to interview candidates for the club's head
coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, reached Saturday in Toronto, where he is scouting junior
players for next month's draft, would not identify the candidates
or the teams he has contacted.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that one of the candidates is Detroit Red Wings
assistant coach Barry Smith, who was a late finalist for the job
two years ago just before the hiring of Jim Schoenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule him out, but I wouldn't put him front and
center, either,'' Bobby Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say this, I ``have'' been talking to some people. I've
talked with both agents and teams, but that's about all I will say
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The only candidate Smith has confirmed is Coyotes assistant John
Tortorella, who will be given a formal interview Tuesday in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's a good candidate,'' Smith said. ``I've already had a
lengthy, productive discussion with him, and as I've said before,
he is a very serious candidate. I have great respect for John and
his hockey ability, and we will talk again soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith probably will interview at least three candidates and
possibly four or five before naming the new coach. He said again
Saturday that he has no timetable for a decision. He added,
however, that he has been contacted by several coaches at the NHL
and minor league levels who have expressed an interest in replacing
Schoenfeld, who was fired Monday after two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard from a lot of people, from a lot of agents,'' Smith
said, adding that out of the dozens of inquiries he has had, 10 to
12 could be considered legitimate possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't met with anybody yet, but I've been on the phone,''
Smith said. ``I'm working. I'm making calls and taking calls. . . .
I wouldn't rule out anybody at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   One name that can be ruled out is former Los Angeles Kings Coach
Larry Robinson, a former teammate of Smith's with the Montreal
Canadiens. Robinson accepted an assistant coaching job with the New
Jersey Devils last week.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keenan, who has coached the Philadelphia Flyers, Chicago
Blackhawks, New York Rangers, St. Louis Blues and the Vancouver
Canucks, said from the day Schoenfeld was fired that he would be
seriously interested in coaching the Coyotes. Keenan's aggressive
pursuit of power and his extreme intensity likely will preclude him
from being a serious candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Former Kings Coach Barry Melrose, a hockey analyst for ESPN, has
told friends that he might like to meet with Smith. But Smith
showed little interest in Melrose two years ago while seeking a
replacement for Don Hay.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, representatives of former Buffalo Sabres Coach Ted
Nolan apparently have telephoned Smith to gauge his interest in
their client, the NHL's Coach of the Year in 1996-97. Nolan
interviewed for the Kings job last week.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible candidates include Bryan Trottier, an assistant
coach with the Colorado Avalanche; Dave Jackson, an assistant with
the Pittsburgh Penguins; Dave King, an assistant with the Montreal
Canadiens; and Ted Green, an assistant with the Edmonton Oilers.
Both King and Green have former head coaching experience, Green
with the Oilers and King with the Calgary Flames.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, who will be paid the full $400,000 salary he was
scheduled to make next season, told ``The Republic'' that he plans
to stay in the Valley for at least another year. He said he has not
ruled out coaching again, but added has no immediate plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family and I will probably go up to Canada for a month or
so this summer,'' he said. ``Other than that, I can see myself
doing a lot of golfing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
