<HEADLINE>
`ARMCHAIR DRIVER' GRADUATES TO BIG TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Eight years ago,  &UR; Greg Ray climbed inside a race
car for the first time. He was 25.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he will attempt to win the Indianapolis 500 from a
middle front row starting position.
</P>
<P>
   Time flies, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had my midlife crisis at 25 instead of 45 or 55,''
Ray said. ``In 1991, I think I became an armchair driver. You know,
when you watch football and basketball and say, `Man, why did you
do that? That was stupid.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, a little voice in my head said, `If you think you're so
good, why don't you do it?' For the first time in my life, I didn't
have an answer for the question. I jumped up and went to the store
and bought a racing magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't read racing magazines at the time, but I had seen the
ads on the back for driving schools. So I called and signed up.
From that day on, I have yet to smoke a cigarette or drink a drop
of alcohol. If you want to be successful, you have to eliminate all
of your excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray attended the school and won the Sports Car Club of America
Formula 2000 championship the next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I stood up in the school and said, `My name is Greg
Ray. I'm from Dallas, Texas. I'm an entrepreneur. And I've never
driven a race car, but I'm getting my driving license because I
want to win the Indy 500,' '' Ray said. ``They all laughed their
(butts) off, and I sat down with my tail between my legs. But I won
the school race, the most aggressive driver award and the kamikaze
award.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Ray will try to win the Indy 500. &QL; 
Classy field &QL; 
Of the 33 drivers in today's race, 32 have attended college.
</P>
<P>
   Ray (University of Texas) and front-row starter  &UR; Billy Boat
(Arizona State) are college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buzz Calkins (row nine) is working toward a master's degree in
business at Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hideshi Matsuda (fourth row) graduated from Ryukoku University
in Kyoto, Japan, and is an ordained Buddhist priest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jack Miller (row 11) is a practicing dentist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mark Dismore (row two) never took classes beyond high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a graduate of the school of hard knocks,'' Dismore said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eliseo Salazar attended the University of Chile for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the first lap, there'll be a lot of stupid
moves, anyway,'' Salazar said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
