<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTOROLA-300-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRETTI WINS A THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Ill. _ This is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Andretti, winless since last year's season opener,
survived a robust challenge from Helio Castro-Neves and won the
Motorola 300 on Saturday at Gateway International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti's heart, still pounding with emotion from the
exhausting pursuit by Castro-Neves, made it nearly impossible for
him to voice how much the win meant at this point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti is Championship Auto Racing Teams' all-time leader with
38 career wins, but until the .329-second victory over
Castro-Neves, he had gone 23 starts without a kiss on the cheek
from a trophy girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, I was driving as hard as I've ever driven,'' said
Andretti, his distinctive voice quivering. ``I was right on the
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   And right there with Andretti was Castro-Neves, whose dogged
pursuit over the final 41 laps of a 236-lap race nearly reduced him
to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking in my helmet, `This is Michael Andretti and
this is me,'' said Castro-Neves, a 24-year-old second-year driver
from Brazil. ``He has such great experience and we're racing
together. I can't believe we're racing together,' '' he continued,
his voice cracking. ``Next one, I'm going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti's emotional triumph in a Swift-Ford ended super rookie
Juan Montoya's three-race winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya finished 11th, but still nearly stole the show with an
assortment of pulsating passes over the tricky 1.27-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was Andretti and Castro-Neves who had a crowd
of nearly 40,000 standing on their tip-toes, their necks craning to
see the next minute of the electrifying battle unfold.
</P>
<P>
   It started on Lap 189, when the front-runners all pitted during
the last of nine caution flags.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti drove in fifth, but emerged the leader after taking
fuel only.
</P>
<P>
   Castro-Neves was sixth on the grid on the restart and began
picking off drivers as if he were knocking down ducks in a shooting
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   By Lap 199, Castro-Neves was third. Four laps later, he was
second, 1.8 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   By Lap 206, Castro-Neves was within 0.4 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Although an unrelenting Castro-Neves made valiant efforts to
squeeze by Andretti, it was like trying to pass through a metal
detector with a pocketful of quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Beep-beep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not taking on fresh tires during that last stop was a
gamble,'' Andretti said. ``I was praying the whole time they would
hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro-Neves was praying, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think he heard me,'' said Castro-Neves, who tied a
career-high finish in an unsponsored Mercedes-Lola owned by Carl
Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Castro-Neves made one last effort to overtake Andretti on Lap
234.
</P>
<P>
   But Andretti diligently protected the inside line entering Turn
3 to shut the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Michael's car moving around with about 30 laps to go and
I talk to myself to be patient and wait for the traffic before I
make a pass,'' Castro-Neves said. ``But Michael's excellent and he
made perfect passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On Lap 234), I didn't want to go from hero to zero, so I
stayed back.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the finish, Montoya retained the lead in the driver
standings over Dario Franchitti, who made it to the podium with a
third-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti made the biggest jump, from sixth to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (win) was for the old men,'' said Andretti, who is 36.
``We definitely had to stop (Montoya's) streak. And I'm glad I was
the one to do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
