<HEADLINE>
SABRES PUSH LEAFS TO BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Either the Buffalo Sabres are getting better, the
games are getting easier, or the Toronto Maple Leafs already have
left for their summer cottages without notifying NHL security.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, the red-hot Sabres now may be only 60 minutes
away from returning to the Stanley Cup finals for the first time
since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the least, I'm pleased with our effort,'' said coach
Lindy Ruff, after his Sabres embarrassed the Leafs in a 5-2
thumping here Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Marine Midland Arena. ``We came at
'em in waves.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, Buffalo's seventh straight on home ice this
postseason, handed the Sabres a 3-1 lead in the best-of-seven
Eastern Conference finals. They now have three chances, beginning
Sunday night at Toronto's Air Canada Centre, to advance to the
finals, where they would face either the Colorado Avalanche or the
Dallas Stars (that series is deadlocked at 2-2).
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres rolled to their 11th postseason victory with the aid
of a four-goal second-period outburst that built a 5-0 lead over
the hapless Maple Leafs. Ex-Whaler Geoff Sanderson, his career in
the doldrums for the better part of five years, popped in two of
the second-period strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs, just as in Game 3, repeatedly made errors in their
own end of the ice, either blatantly giving up the puck or failing
to cover rebounds for their star netminder, Curtis Joseph. They
allowed three goals on only four shots in a span of only 2:35. When
Sanderson rifled home a shot for a 5-0 lead with 5:50 to go in the
second, the dispassionate, listless Leafs looked as if they were
watching the credits scroll down on their season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't respond well,'' said Toronto coach Pat Quinn, who
challenged his Leafs after their loss in Game 3, to the point of
labeling them ``pretty boys.'' Their response was anything but
pretty. ``We didn't respond hardly at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, there were times they looked like the Maple Leafs of
old. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   --They were working with a power play in the first period when
Dixon Ward broke out and zapped in the go-ahead goal, good for the
Sabres' team-record third shorthanded goal in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   --They watched Steve Sullivan throw a blind pass into the slot,
in his defensive end, that was instantly cashed in by Brian
Holzinger for the 2-0 lead. ``It was such a nice pass, it caught
everyone by surprise _ including Curtis,'' said Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   --They even watched Rob Ray, without a goal in 110 straight
games, chop down a pass from Stu Barnes that would turn into the
3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' said Quinn, the ex-Toronto defenseman Boston
fans might remember for decking Bobby Orr with a brutal elbow in
the playoffs 30 years ago, ``that's a good hockey club we are
facing. I didn't expect we'd win, necessarily, but I didn't expect
that kind of response.''
</P>
<P>
   Mats Sundin scored Toronto's two goals, the first on a penalty
shot at 6:59 of the third when Jay McKee was caught for closing his
hand on the puck in the crease. He popped in the second with 1:57
to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
