<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS COMES ALIVE FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ May is almost over, and Troy Glaus can breathe again.
</P>
<P>
   After a tortuous month that finally resulted in his benching the
night before, Glaus' sixth-inning home run Saturday helped give the
struggling Angels a 4-3 victory over the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't often a pitcher can be overshadowed when he takes a
no-hitter into the sixth inning and a chance for his first career
shutout into the ninth, but Angels starter Steve Sparks (2-4)
gladly stepped aside to watch Glaus' 410-foot blast clear the
center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have dropped into last place in the American League
West because of a sputtering offense. At the center of the problem
has been Glaus, who had just three RBI in May and no homers since
April 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been frustrating, but not overwhelming,'' Glaus said.
``You just have to keep working hard and hope you get a little
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   And a little reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   After a terrific April, he was three for his past 44 and manager
Terry Collins wondered aloud if putting a guy two years out of
college in the heart of the order was too much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus even looked miserable striking out in the second inning
against winless rookie Chris Fussell.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere between that at-bat and the thought of a trip back
to Triple-A, Glaus came alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so great to see him finally break out,'' Collins said.
``When a youngster struggles this long you have to wonder how long
you can go. You think about getting him his swing back and getting
his head on straight. Yes, the minor leagues could have been a
possibility, but were we ready to do that? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus said his teammates have been very supportive during the
slump. Some offer advice, some keep their distance. Everyone stayed
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have (hitting instructor) Rod Carew and (coach) George
Hendrick to work with you,'' Glaus said. ``But it's your teammates
that really get you through this. Everyone has gone through it, but
having your teammates behind you really means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus shouldn't have even come to the plate in the sixth,
batting only after Fussell misplayed a two-out throw to first for
an error.
</P>
<P>
   Fussell (0-3) then fell behind 2-1 and threw a belt-high
fastball. The Angels' three-game losing streak was over and so they
hoped Glaus' slump.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as easy as it sounds. Sparks loaded the bases in the
ninth and Troy Percival was brought in to close out the game, but
pinch-hitter Scott Pose hit the first pitch to the gap in
right-center for a three-run double. Suddenly it was a 4-3 game
with the tying run at second.
</P>
<P>
   But Percival recovered to strike out Carlos Febles and retire
Carlos Beltran on a fly ball to center to end the game and record
his 13th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch was right down the middle,'' Collins said. ``I
wanted Sparks to finish the game, but I couldn't do it. We needed
Troy to close it out.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   He said the home run would have been pretty hollow if the team
had blown a four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so important what I did,'' Glaus said. ``The win was
much more important. If we lost, I wouldn't have felt very good
right now. As it is, it's only a start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
