 AM-NYT-BUDGET
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, May 31:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night supervisor will be Lynn Hoogenboom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and four of his top officials have now been indicted for
war crimes in Kosovo. But by all accounts here, the person with the
most influence over him is his dreamy and complicated wife, Mirjana
Markovic, whose life-long sense of persecution will only be
intensified by this new threat to her husband and her family. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ The latest on the fighting. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Refugees once determined to wait out
the war on the border with Kosovo in hopes of returning are
beginning to despair and to prepare for life abroad. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ Update on Indian-Pakistani
fighting over Kashmir. Two days after Pakistan offered to hold
peace talks with India about the current crisis along the
cease-fire line in Kashmir, the Indians said on Sunday that they
are still unsure whether they want to participate in any such
negotiations. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   NEPAL-POLITICS (Katmandu, Nepal) _ With 22 million people, Nepal
is an Arkansas-sized nation landlocked between India and China.
Until 50 years ago, it was largely isolated from the rest of the
world. The annual per capita income is still only $210. The adult
literacy rate is 40 percent. Life expectancy is 57. In 1990,
political agitation forced Harvard-educated, walrus-mustached King
Birendra to give up most of his absolute powers and to accept a
constitutional monarchy. But the years of democracy have been
marked by a hapless cavalcade of seven prime ministers, most them
the product of bizarre alliances cobbled together only to fall
apart. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Sowetos) _ A look at South African politics
before the presidential vote. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SUB (Jerusalem) _ The Israelis find a submarine, 31 years
after it sank. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Istanbul) _ In a legal and political
confrontation likely to attract worldwide attention, the Kurdish
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan is to be tried for treason in a
Turkish court beginning on Monday. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DROUGHT (Torreon) _ In Torreon, a city in Coahuila State
600 miles north of the capital, and all across the country's arid
north, Mexicans have been praying for rain. In recent days, the
federal government has declared 10 northern states, covering about
half of the national territory, as disaster zones because of the
drought. Officials have explained the mounting water shortage as
one of the vagaries of nature, since for several years rainfall has
been lower than usual in northern Mexico. But Torreon residents,
and several experts as well, contend that deforestation, wasteful
irrigation, and water-intensive industrial processes ill-suited to
an arid region, have worsened the crisis. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-JUDAISM (Undated) _ More than a century ago, leaders of
Reform Judaism declared such practices as wearing skullcaps and
prayer shawls and using Hebrew in services to be the dated relics
of the past, and emphasized instead a focus on social ethics and a
highly cerebral approach to the faith. But in a symbolically
resonant gesture, and with an eye on the approach of a new century,
Reform's rabbinic arm, the Central Conference of American Rabbis,
last week adopted a document that encourages the movement's members
to explore traditional rituals. By commending study of the mitzvot,
the sacred obligations that include traditional rituals that are
required in more conservative branches of Judaism, the rabbis
positively acknowledged a trend among many of the 1.5 million
members of their movement. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-MEDICINE (Washington) _ As modern medicine extends the
lives of people with chronic diseases (from diabetes to cystic
fibrosis), the rate of divorce among them is increasing, leaving a
growing number without income, health insurance, or support at
home, health analysts say. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-YOUTH (Undated) _ A look at a little-noticed fight over
whether to expand the federal drug-fighting agency's mandate to
alcohol abuse by young people. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLITICS (Los Angeles) _ Former Los Angeles Mayor Tom
Bradley died last year. But the battle for his legacy is looming
large in a tight city council race, centering on a hotly disputed
campaign mailer asserting that Bradley, just before he died,
endorsed the incumbent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   FLAG-LAW (Washington) _ One of these days _ not on Flag Day,
June 14, and not even by the Fourth of July, but probably sometime
before the end of the year _ Republicans in the Senate will bring
up a proposed constitutional amendment that would permit laws
banning flag-burning. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   GANSKE-PROFILE (Washington) _ Every session of the House of
Representatives has its own personality, its own emblematic types,
from the comfortable Democratic incumbents of the late 1980s to the
Republican revolutionaries of 1994. Maybe Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa,
is a fitting symbol of the current House: the edgy, ever-shifting
House where Republicans are trying to govern with 222 votes, the
slimmest majority in 45 years, meaning that every vote counts. When
a Greg Ganske gets frustrated and decides to buck the leadership,
as he did last week, it matters. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-POLITICS (Washington) _ Older Americans, once among the
most loyal of Democratic voters in congressional elections, are
drifting toward the Republicans for a number of reasons. By Robin
Toner.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by William Safire;
details later.
</P>
