<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-NYT &LR;      05-30 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OF KURDISH REBEL LEADER STARTS IN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ In a legal and political confrontation likely
to attract worldwide attention, the Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan is to be tried for treason in a Turkish court beginning
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 until his capture in February, Ocalan headed a
guerrilla army that has been fighting to establish a Kurdish
homeland in southeastern Turkey. The authorities call it a band of
terrorists, and blame Ocalan for the more than 30,000 deaths the
war has caused. Among the dead are more than 5,000 Turkish soldiers
and security officers.
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders, enthusiastically backed by the mass media,
have for years been denouncing Ocalan as a brutal killer dedicated
to sowing chaos and ultimately splitting Turkey apart. In most of
the country he is an intensely hated figure, and there seems no
doubt that he will be found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the top lieutenant to Ocalan, Semdin Sakik, was
sentenced to death, and in all probability Ocalan himself will be
sentenced to hang. But it is uncertain whether the sentence will be
carried out. Death sentences in Turkey must be confirmed by
Parliament and the president, and there have been no executions
here since 1984. Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit opposes the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit has said that he will seek to change the composition of
the three-judge panel that will try Ocalan by replacing its
military member with a civilian. When the trial opens Monday, there
may be a motion to postpone it until Parliament can approve such a
change.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will be held on the remote prison island of Imrali in
the Sea of Marmara, where Ocalan is the sole inmate. He will
reportedly be placed in a bullet-proof glass box in the specially
designed courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ocalan will only be able to communicate with the chief judge
through a microphone,'' said one of his lawyers, Ercan Kanar. ``He
will not be able to hear his own lawyers or anything else in the
courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanar also complained that he and other defense lawyers have
been allowed only limited access to their client, and that their
interviews with him have been monitored by hooded soldiers. He said
Ocalan has not been allowed to read the charges against him or
other trial documents.
</P>
<P>
   This week, two New York-based groups complained about the
conditions under which Ocalan has had to prepare his defense. Human
Rights Watch said he should not have been held in ``incommunicado
detention,'' and the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights asserted
that his lawyers have had to work in an ``atmosphere of
intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 10 million Kurds among Turkey's 65 million
people, most of them with roots in the southeastern provinces,
which have been shaken by violence for the last 15 years. Some say
they have been oppressed under Turkish rule, but the government
insists that they are granted the same rights as other citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish authorities say they have all but wiped out Ocalan's
guerrilla force, the Kurdistan Workers Party. Although they report
fatal clashes every few days, they say the capture of Ocalan has
been a devastating blow to the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kurds in the southeast disagree. ``This movement is not
going to be finished by arresting or executing one person,'' said a
Kurdish businessman from the southeastern city of Diyarbakir who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``One is going, but thousands are
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Many details of how Ocalan's trial will be conducted are still
unknown. Human Human rights advocates and many foreign governments
are anxiously awaiting its beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the world will understand if Ocalan is found guilty
and even if he is sentenced to death, but only on condition that he
gets a trial that meets international standards of fairness,'' said
a foreign ambassador based in Ankara. ``He has to have access to
the lawyers of his choice. The lawyers have to be able to work
freely. Ocalan himself has to be given the right to say whatever he
wants in the courtroom. Neutral parties need to be allowed to sit
in the back and take notes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this happens, most of us will be satisfied,'' the
ambassador said. ``Otherwise the trial is just going to reinforce
negative stereotypes about the Turkish justice system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
