</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA STILL UNDECIDED ON PEACE TALKS WITH PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Two days after Pakistan offered to hold peace
talks with India about the current crisis along the cease-fire line
in Kashmir, the Indians said Sunday they are still unsure whether
they want to participate in any such negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that the proposal is under consideration,''
said Raminder Singh Jassal, spokesman for India's Ministry of
External Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to elaborate other than to say that certain ``ground
realities'' must be observed. ``Ground realities'' is a term
frequently invoked by the Indians and can be taken to mean that
they believe they are now succeeding in turning back the incursion.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth day, Indian fighter jets pounded away against a
force of several hundred militants who have taken positions in the
grand but treacherous Himalayan peaks of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Infantry fighting at such altitudes _ as high as 17,000 feet in
what is called the Kargil sector _ requires special training and
expensive cold-weather gear. The Indians say the Pakistanis have
not only provided this logistical support, but have disguised some
of their own troops and sent them into the battle as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistanis deny this, and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has
offered to send Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz to New Delhi for a
round of discussions.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Aziz said he remained hopeful that there would be a
meeting ``in the next few days.'' He had read press reports that
Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee called such talks
unnecessary, but ``we have not been officially communicated any
such thing,'' he said. ``We have asked the Indian side which dates
suit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1947, when India and Pakistan were born into nationhood
from the dying British Empire, the countries have been in conflict
over Kashmir, a vast territory of geographical extremes _ some
parts lush, other utterly barren _ that lies between them.
</P>
<P>
   In the complicated and emotional give-and-take of Partition,
India, which is predominantly Hindu, ended up with Kashmir, which
has a Muslim majority. India considers Kashmir to be one of its 25
states, while overwhelmingly Muslim Pakistan insists that the
Kashmiris should be allowed to vote on which of the two nations it
wants to join.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have fought two wars over Kashmir, the result
of which is a cease-fire line that runs jaggedly through the
western part of the region. Fighting across that line has continued
year after year, slowing but never stopping.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Pakistan has wanted to involve the United
Nations or another third party in talks to settle the conflict _
something India has resisted. Commentators throughout India suspect
that Pakistan has now contrived a plot in the Himalayas to draw the
world's nervous attention to an old dispute between two new nuclear
powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bomb has not deterred Pakistan from its Kashmir
cross-border terrorism; it may have even persuaded Islamabad to
step up its involvement on the grounds that the world would have to
take notice,'' wrote one columnist, M.J. Akbar.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the world cannot help but notice. On Sunday morning,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke with India's
foreign minister, Jaswant Singh, by telephone to discuss the
crisis, according to Jassal. Britain's foreign secretary, Robin
Cook, called Saturday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The crisis in the snow-capped mountains has left India's
caretaker government with its own political avalanche. Vajpayee's
Bharatiya Janata Party is facing elections in September. The BJP _
self-described defense hard-liners who tested nuclear bombs a year
ago _ are not only being faulted for the massive incursion into
Indian territory but also for a peace gesture last February.
Vajpayee rode a bus across the Pakistani border and embraced
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   To many here, that gesture in February now seems naive _ and it
has the government back on its heels defending its olive branch. On
Friday, India's defense minister, George Fernandes, partially
exonerated the Pakistani prime minister of blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this entire episode, the Pakistan army has hatched a
conspiracy to push in the infiltrators, and the Nawaz Sharif
government did not have a major role,'' Fernandes said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sniping at the BJP, the Indian public has rallied
around the war effort. The five-day air campaign has produced
absorbing daily dramas _ the tragedy of two lost planes and a
helicopter gun ship, the derring-do of soldiers charging up
mountainsides. Combat has pushed the ongoing World Cup of cricket
off the top of the news.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, during briefings for the press, Indian military
spokesman Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh reported the results of an autopsy
of a downed Indian flier whose corpse had been returned. There were
two bullet holes in the body, the general said.
</P>
<P>
   This was ``a cold-blooded murder,'' he said, calling it ``an act
of cowardice.'' Later in the day, a Pakistani military spokesman
called the report baseless.
</P>
<P>
   More exuberantly, Singh then described a battle on Saturday
where Indian troops encircled and overran one of the militants'
hard-to-attack perches. In this ``very gallant action,'' an Indian
major ``made the supreme sacrifice and laid down his own life,''
though not before he ``shot dead four of the intruders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
