<HEADER>
A6645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TRAGEDY31-COX     05-30 2719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRAGEDY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    END of the INNOCENCE: Racing hype a heart-breaking reminder of
tragedy for N.C. family
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONNELLY SPRINGS, N.C. _ It had been a typical Saturday for the
Pyatte family, and life was good.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaughter's tee-ball game that morning was entertaining,
and the dinner in nearby Lincolnton that evening was excellent.
Vickie Pyatte was glad that her husband, Roger, seemed to be
holding his own with his heart problems, and her 21-year-old son,
Randy, who was attending an open-wheel auto race in Concord that
night, had moved back home.
</P>
<P>
   As the couple returned from Lincolnton that evening with Roger's
nephew and wife to the modest Pyatte home, a doublewide trailer,
they chose conversation over television. So they muted the volume
on the TV and talked. An hour later, an emergency bulletin
scrolling across the bottom of the screen caught their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Accident at the fourth turn at Lowe's Motor Speedway. Spectators
hurt, maybe killed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps out of curiosity, maybe motherly concern, Vickie began
searching for a business card, which had the number of the cellular
telephone Randy had purchased that afternoon. He was attending the
VisionAire 500 race at Lowe's with two cousins and a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie quickly dialed the number. No answer. She tried again. No
answer. She tried again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   Her curiosity and concern turned into fear, and she began
thinking something was terribly wrong. Roger noticed. In an effort
to calm his wife, he told Vickie that Randy probably left the cell
phone in the car, because that's the way he takes care of his
things.
</P>
<P>
   But Roger decided it would be a good idea to leave a message. So
he dialed again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy, this is your daddy,'' Roger said. ``Call me as soon as
you can. It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   They waited.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Growing into an adult
</P>
<P>
   As a shipping clerk at Synthetics Finishing, a company in
Hickory that applies Scotchgard to fabrics, Randy Pyatte loaded
trucks and packed orders. He liked the job, especially talking with
the truck drivers, who had tales of traveling cross-country.
</P>
<P>
   Work helped ease the pain of personal problems. Randy was
engaged to be married to his high school sweetheart on March 27,
but his bride-to-be broke the engagement two weeks before the
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty broken-hearted about it,'' his father said. ``He
always talked to me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy moved back into his parents' home, and Roger cleaned out
the largest bedroom in the well-kept trailer. Randy always kept his
room immaculate. He polished his silver dumbbells and wrapped them
in towels after every workout.
</P>
<P>
   Randy, who graduated from high school in 1995, was a good
athlete, and his father thought he might become a football player
because of his son's 6-foot-1,180-pound frame. But Randy's first
love was basketball. When he was younger, his father built a cement
basketball court in the backyard with some money he inherited from
an uncle. That's where Randy imitated his idol, former University
of North Carolina and Chicago Bulls star Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Randy and his cousins, Chuck Bess and Rodney Pyatte,
left their small community off I-40, about 60 miles east of
Asheville, and went to Charlotte for the ``Hoop-It-Up'' Tournament,
a citywide three-on-three competition. ``The Mystery Boys,'' as
Randy's mother dubbed them, came home from the big city with the
first-place trophy for their division.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, ``The Mystery Boys'' would head to Charlotte
again.
</P>
<P>
   When Rodney, a truck driver, was given complimentary tickets to
the May 1 IRL race by a client, he asked Randy to come along. Randy
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Randy talked briefly with his parents
during breakfast before he left to buy the cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always hugged him and told him how much I loved him,''
Vickie said. ``That Saturday, I didn't get to talk to him much
because he was so excited and was getting everything ready for the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   After buying the telephone, Randy drove to Rodney's house in
Hickory. Rodney, 29, is married and has two children, with another
baby on the way. They spent the early afternoon at Rodney's
8-year-old son's Little League game, then returned to Rodney's
house to leave for Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 p.m. Saturday, the four men -- Randy, Rodney, Chuck Bess
and Jeff Patton, a close friend of Rodney from Connelly Springs --
loaded into Rodney's champagne-colored Ford Explorer to make the
drive to Lowe's, a few miles north of Charlotte on I-85.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly Springs is located in the heart of the stock-car-racing
world; life-sized advertisements of NASCAR drivers Jeff Gordon,
Richard Petty and the late Davey Allison greet customers in the BP
gas station where Diane McGee, Randy's aunt, works. But Randy
wasn't brought up in a racing family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really liked racing, but my parents liked it, and I
had to go to the races when I was younger,'' Vickie said. ``I
always cried when the cars wrecked because I thought someone was
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   So Randy was a rookie, attending his first race. Patton, married
without children, was the biggest racing fan in the group, dragging
Rodney to the paved half-mile track at Hickory Speedway the
previous three Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour drive to Charlotte, the men rarely talked
about the race. They didn't really know about any of the drivers in
the IRL. The real attraction was speed: Rodney explained to Randy
that Indy cars could go as fast as 220 mph on the high-banked oval.
</P>
<P>
   During the trip, Rodney played a recording of the sermon his
pastor, Mark Robinson, had delivered the preceding Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about heaven and hell,'' Rodney said. ``He was talking
about how it's going to be when we get to heaven's gates. After we
listened to it, I told them, `Isn't it great to know that we're
going on to heaven, regardless of how or when we die?'''
</P>
<P>
   Randy agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: New market for IRL
</P>
<P>
   When the group arrived at the track around 4:30 p.m., the scene
at the speedway resembled nothing like the two NASCAR races held
each year at Lowe's. Around the track, the open grass fields,
usually transformed into a makeshift campground of RVs, tents and
converted school buses, were not filled with fans. The crowd was
estimated at less than half of the 175,000 fans who cram the
facility for Winston Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   The track had been known as Charlotte Motor Speedway before its
naming rights were sold to Lowe's earlier this year. It was 40
years old before millionaire Bruton Smith, a Charlotte automobile
dealer and president of Speedway Motorsports Inc., allowed
open-wheel cars to run on the 1.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a bold gamble at the time, bringing the
unfamiliar cars and foreign drivers to the South, where stock-car
racing grew from bootleggers running moonshine in the mountains to
the multi-billion-dollar business it is today.
</P>
<P>
   The sport lost much of its appeal after Indianapolis Motor
Speedway president Tony George broke away from the Championship
Auto Racing Teams (CART) circuit, which had controlled Indy-car
racing since 1979, and formed the Indy Racing League (IRL).
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling IRL negotiated a three-year contract with Smith's
Speedway Motorsports Inc. in 1997, allowing the series to race on
ovals in such bigger markets as Atlanta, Charlotte, Fort Worth and
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   CART endured its own problems in July 1998, when three
spectators were killed and six injured during a race at Michigan
Speedway. A car driven by Adrian Fernandez of Mexico slid into the
wall, and the right front tire and suspension broke off and flew
into the crowd in the fourth turn. The parts cleared a four-foot
wall with an 11-foot fence before killing fans in the eighth and
10th rows.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney said he and his friends knew nothing about the sport's
dangers. They never discussed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought we'd go to Charlotte, have a good time at the
race and go back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Moved to different seats
</P>
<P>
   About 4:45 p.m., the four found their seats in Section D of the
fourth-turn terrace -- row 9, seats 4 through 7. Before the IRL
race started at 8 p.m., though, they became irritated by a group of
five men and a woman sitting behind them, who apparently were
drinking. Rodney said one of them made a ``smart remark'' to Randy,
so the group decided to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of empty seats around us,'' Rodney said.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't move far, dropping down to some vacant seats in
the eighth row. Randy sat in seat 1, next to the aisle between
sections C and D. Rodney took the seat to Randy's left, and Patton
sat two seats to his left in seat 4. Bess moved to seat 1 in the
seventh row, in front of Randy.
</P>
<P>
   When the IRL race started, the conversation stopped. The cars
were so loud that the four were wearing ear plugs and were limited
to hand signals and facial expressions. From their seats close to
the track, the cars seemed like a blur when they zipped down the
front straightaway. The first 50 laps were mostly uneventful; the
bumping and grinding often found in NASCAR were absent.
</P>
<P>
   During lap 59 of the race, however, something went very wrong.
</P>
<P>
   According to an IRL report, driver Stan Wattles crashed alone in
turn 4, breaking a right-side wheel, probably the rear one. The
track's 15-foot-high catch fence initially contained the tire,
deflecting it back on the track, but then a trailing car driven by
John Paul Jr. knocked it into the grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   Bess says he saw a puff of smoke and turned to his left to see
the accident. A month later, he still can't let go of the memory of
what he saw: a tire flipping end over end, hurtling into the
bleachers. The tire seemed like it was moving in slow motion, but
it was flying at nearly 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a puff of smoke, and then I saw a tire flying into the
crowd,'' Bess said. ``As soon as I saw the tire, I hit the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney was looking to his right, watching the leaders exit turn
1 when he heard the wreck. As he turned to his left, he saw a black
object in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked back at turn 4 and saw something in the corner of my
eye,'' he said. ``I pulled around really quick and saw something. I
thought it was a bird or something black. It was flying right at my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney said Patton probably never saw the tire. He was struck in
the face and died instantly. The tire bounced right and struck the
left side of Randy's head, killing him, also instantly. Another
man, Dexter Mobley, 41, of Statesville, N.C., a native of Albany,
Ga., sitting a few sections away, also was killed before the tire
came to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney and Bess embraced after realizing what happened, and then
they wept on the metal bleachers. Eyewitnesses said that Rodney
avoided the tire's path when he leaned over to talk to Bess,
sitting in front of Randy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people behind us said Rodney was leaning down and talking
to me, and that's the reason it didn't hit him,'' Bess said. ``We
probably wouldn't have been hit if we hadn't moved down a row.
That's what's ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL and Lowe's officials canceled the rest of the race and
refunded the costs of tickets to fans, many of whom donated the
money to a trust fund for the victims. Eight other spectators were
injured, including a 9-year-old girl, who recently was released
from a Charlotte hospital to start rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I never want to see again,'' Bess said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bess relived the scene on page 86 of the May 10 issue of
Sports Illustrated, which published a photograph of two of the
three dead spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Their bodies are wrapped in white sheets, lying in a pool of
blood in the bleachers. The right leg of one of the victims sticks
out from under a sheet. The man is wearing blue jeans and brown
Rockport shoes. That man is Randy, wearing the shoes his sister,
Wendy Grigg, gave him as a present.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Parents' fears confirmed
</P>
<P>
   The telephone finally rang at the Pyatte home about an hour
after the original television bulletin. Roger Pyatte said track
officials had called his sister first, because Rodney and Chuck
were in too much shock to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, Rodney called his uncle, but he couldn't
talk when Roger answered the telephone. A chaplain took the phone
and told Roger that his son had been hit and that he and Vickie
needed to come to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were holding out hope the whole way there,'' Roger said.
``We even took an extra set of clothes with us because we thought
he was coming back with us.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Pyattes arrived at Northeast Medical Center in
Charlotte, however, the chaplain delivered the devastating news:
Their only son was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``How in the world are you expected to get back to a normal
life?'' Vickie said. ``My son wasn't supposed to die watching a
race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pyattes buried their son on May 5, following a visitation
that lasted four hours and included more than 1,600 mourners.
Lowe's Motor Speedway president Humpy Wheeler attended the funeral.
So did George and several other IRL officials. The owners of
Synthetics Finishing came all the way from Philadelphia to pay
their respects.
</P>
<P>
   Roger left his son's funeral in an ambulance, after relatives
worried he might suffer another heart attack, like the one he had
18 months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought, 'Well, I'll leave this world first, and
Randy will still be here to take care of his mother,''' Roger said.
``I never would have thought I'd be picking out a casket for my own
son's funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage of that tragic night at Lowe's Motor Speedway never
will go away fully. Rodney said he often is afraid to go to sleep
at night, but counseling has helped him deal with his friends'
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Roger and Vickie have had trouble sleeping and are under a
doctor's care.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie tried to return to her job as a waitress on May 18, but
she left after only a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: A lawsuit in the making
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with today's Indianapolis 500, the IRL will require
all cars to use wheel tethers, devices designed to keep wheels and
suspension parts attached to the cars during accidents. Formula One
and CART already require the safety measures. Earlier this month,
SMI announced that it would raise fences to 21 feet at its tracks
that host IRL events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against the cars running,'' Roger said, ``but if the
tracks aren't designed to hold them, then they don't need to be on
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger said he is considering legal action against the IRL and
SMI. ``It's like every day you get angrier and angrier. You want to
know why they didn't do anything before this happened. If I'd known
the dangers, I wouldn't have let my son go. There isn't any amount
of money in the world that will bring my son back.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday night, Roger stood in front of a congregation of
about 60 people at the Icard Church of God and thanked them for
their support and prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not questioning God about this matter,'' he told
them, ``but I would kind of like to know why things like this
happen. When my son was living, after he'd broken up with his
fiance, he told me, `Daddy, if she would just tell me how she
feels, I really think I could deal with it and go on with my life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If God would give me some sort of sign, maybe it would help me
heal my heart. We're in a lost world. People don't understand what
we're going through.''
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, Vickie and Roger Pyatte said, they
received their sign from God.
</P>
<P>
   While Vickie slept in their bedroom in the front of the house,
she said, she saw her son in a dream. She saw angels flying in a
blue sky and she asked them if they'd seen her son. She called out
his name, but he never answered. Finally, she saw her son standing
next to a stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my son, and he looked like he was so happy,'' she said.
``I kept saying, `Randy, I'm here!' But he just looked like he was
so happy, and it was so beautiful down there. If you could have
seen the expression on his face, he just looked like he was so
happy and peaceful. It was comforting. We feel like it's some kind
of answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
