<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-30 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
(c) 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO LIVE LIKE A CELEBRITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Profiles in the latest issue of Harper's Bazaar reveal that:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Kate Capshaw  &LR; _ producer and star of ``The Love Letter,''
wife of  &UR; Steven Spielberg &LR;  _ makes challah every Friday night and
isn't shy about touting her chest (``A lot of designers don't
design for breasts'') or her husband (``I live with a genius'').
</P>
<P>
   - Actor  &UR; Anthony Hopkins &LR;  can't be bothered with dinner parties
but will reluctantly meet friends in restaurants (``if you meet
someone in a restaurant you can eat very fast, pay and then go'').
</P>
<P>
   - Modernist clothing designer  &UR; Yohji Yamamoto &LR; , who doesn't own
paintings (``It hurts his eyes to look at art unless it's in a
museum,'' says his assistant), told his architect to design him a
house that looked like a prison (``because it's a very easy way to
live'') but drives a Rolls-Royce (``I do have one weakness, and
it's for British cars'').
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The chic bathroom fixture _ ``like having a Sub-Zero in the
kitchen,'' one decorator told the New York Times _ is the home
urinal. The Times lists a number of celebrities who are
urinal-compliant, including restaurateur  &UR; Keith McNally &LR; , filmmaker
 &UR; Ethan Coen &LR;  and director  &UR; Barry Sonnenfeld &LR; .  &UR; Tom Hanks &LR;  is still
waiting for installation.
</P>
<P>
   Neo-Metro makes a modern residential version of this
convenience, which,  &UR; Lisa Ryan &LR;  points out, bears a stylish
similarity to steel prison urinals, which just goes to prove
Yamamoto's cutting-edge sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVERY PROBLEM SOLVED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So what's bothering you?  &UR; Clayton Barbeau  &LR; received a mailing
advertising a book _ which shall go unnamed herein _ available for
order from Henderson, Nev., promising the following little things:
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of physical appearances, you will be having sex
with beautiful women of your choice''; ``You will be such a
superior lover, those women will fall in love with you''; ``You
will be making thousands of dollars each week''; ``You will get rid
of your recurring illnesses''; ``You will lose all your fat'';
``Everyone will become interested in you''; ``Beautiful women and
powerful men will almost beg to be your friends''; ``You will get
an instant promotion''; ``You will become very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   This last may mean you will realize the value of every promise
that came before it.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Oh, one more problem you may have missed worrying about:
 &UR; Jim Bakker &LR; , born-again born-again, cq &LR; is predicting that an
asteroid is going to crash into the Earth. ``Y2K is going to be a
Sunday picnic compared to what else is going to happen,'' he said
in a recent sermon. ``All I say is don't fall in love with this
world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Cher &LR;  told Ladies' Home Journal she's been celibate for six
years. In related news, Entertainment Weekly reports that a pair of
 &UR; Pamela Anderson Lee &LR; 's panties sold for $400 on eBay, but
 &UR; Elizabeth Berkley &LR; 's panties went for only $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   - Teen magazine provides answers to questions you never asked:
an ounce of cheese is the same size as a lipstick; 2 &LR; two
tablespoons of peanut butter equal a golf ball; and two to three
ounces of meat are the same size as a tape cassette.
</P>
<P>
   - When she visited a Macedonian clothing factory a few weeks
ago,  &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton  &LR; was told of workers' fears of being
laid off because Liz Claiborne Inc. had been cutting orders there.
When she returned to Washington, the first lady called Liz
Claiborne executives to discuss the cuts. The Washington Post
reports on the success of her call: Claiborne has issued a
long-term order for 4,000 units of clothing a week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Lisa Rogak &LR; , author of a forthcoming novel she says is based
on her own experiences as the straight wife of a man who came
``roaring out of the closet,'' has proclaimed June Straight Spouse
Awareness Month.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Geraldine Ferraro &LR; , whose Senate aspirations came to naught,
is joining Weber McGinn, an Arlington, Va., public relations firm,
to advise clients on women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   - In response to the angry New York restaurateur who sought
revenge on a New York Times reporter by giving out his home phone
number as the reservation line,  &UR; Mark Talbot  &LR; suggests that if he
had been the reporter, ``I would have cheerfully accepted the
reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough affluence in Southern California that they can
say you have to have both the BMW and the breast implants.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Robert Joas &LR; ,  &LR;  anesthesiologist and president of the Medical
Board of California, in a Los Angeles Times story about teenagers
getting breast implants, often as high school graduation presents.
</P>
</TEXT>
