<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6653 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENIORS-POLITICS-ART-     05-30 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTWARD SHIFT AMONG OLDER VOTERS CAUSES PARTIES TO ADJUST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif., Fla., Mo., Texas, Minn.) (ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Older Americans were once among the most loyal of
Democratic voters in congressional elections, reliably returning
the party of Roosevelt and Truman to power on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But the New Deal generation of older Americans is passing _
World War II veterans are dying at a rate of more than 1,000 a day,
by one government estimate _ and their successors are more likely
to have Ronald Reagan as a reference point than Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   According to surveys of voters leaving the polls, Republicans
carried the 60-and-over vote in House races in the last three
elections, a source of considerable soul-searching among Democrats.
The power of older voters is magnified because of a simple fact:
They turn out at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   And strategists in both parties now see older Americans as a
critical swing vote in elections next year, a factor that could
determine control of the House of Representatives, where
Republicans hold a scant 222-211 majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtually impossible to take back the House or win the
presidency without taking back seniors,'' said Celinda Lake, a
Democratic pollster. ``That makes them the key battleground, and
both parties know it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some Democratic analysts think that their party would
control the House today had it not lost the older vote so
decisively last November, by 55 percent to 45 percent, while
winning or breaking even with every other age group.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened competition for the 60-plus vote affects the
policy agenda in a variety of ways, strategists say. It helps
explain why the gaps in Medicare benefits, like prescription drug
coverage and long-term care, are getting more attention on Capitol
Hill these days. As Bill McInturff, a Republican pollster, puts it,
``We're having a policy debate over a prescription drug benefit
instead of what do we do about the uninsured.''
</P>
<P>
   This competition also makes it harder, in the short term, to
reach bipartisan consensus on the financial difficulties of Social
Security and Medicare, which both need shoring up before the baby
boom generation retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each party is trying to one-up the other,'' said Rep. Thomas
Davis III, R-Va., chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, while adding that he was ultimately optimistic about a
solution. ``It's difficult now because everybody wants the other
guy to go first and take a shot at their proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is quite sure why the older vote has shifted, but
demographics are clearly part of it. Many analysts note that as a
group, older Americans are substantially more affluent today than
they were 30 years ago. The poverty rate for Americans 65 and older
dropped to 10.5 percent in 1997 from 35 percent in 1959, according
to the Census Bureau. Their median income, in constant 1992
dollars, more than doubled between 1957 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more affluent, more educated, more mobile, healthier,
wealthier, and I'd go a step further and say more positively
disposed to the private sector,'' said Susan MacManus, a political
science professor at the University of South Florida in Tampa,
speaking of people who are just now joining the ranks of older
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, their political allegiances were formed in a different
era. ``Many of the elderly today were in the prime of their working
lives during the Reagan era,'' said Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif.
``They were Reagan Democrats. So ideologically, they're probably
more centrist and to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Teeter, a pollster who long worked in Republican
politics, noted that such generational shifts have occurred before.
In the 1950s and 1960s, Teeter said, older Americans were
considered reliably Republican voters. By the 1970s, he recalled,
``you'd sit through all kinds of meetings'' with Republicans trying
to figure out why they were losing that vote. The voter surveys
showed Democrats carrying the 60-and-older vote in House races from
1980 through 1992, with one exception: the Reagan landslide year of
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Binstock, a professor of aging, health and society at
Case Western Reserve University, has argued for many years against
the notion that older Americans are a monolithic group voting
solely on the basis of their age and their benefit programs. Other
factors, like economic status and gender, affect their voting
behavior, just as they do with every other age group, Binstock
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are significant differences between older women
and older men. Republicans began winning the 60-and-over male vote
in 1994; they did not carry older women until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts argue that older women are much less
economically secure than older men, and therefore more open to
Democratic appeals based on protecting benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from demographics, there are also short-term explanations
for the shifting allegiances of older Americans. Strategists in
both parties say the scandal leading to President Clinton's
impeachment probably played a role in the size of the Democrats'
loss among the 60-and-over vote last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors are somewhat more sensitive to the values issues,''
said Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, ``and we have not always
presented our strongest face on those issues in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   The voter surveys support this analysis: Social Security was the
top issue on the minds of 60-and-over voters last November, but
moral and ethical standards ranked No. 2; and 89 percent of those
who said the moral issues were the determining factor in their vote
selected a Republican candidate for the House.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists and candidates have also gotten better at
campaigning for the votes of older Americans, strategists in both
parties say. For years, Republicans were on the defensive, battered
by Democratic campaigns accusing them of plotting to cut Social
Security or Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., remembers one particularly rough
election in 1982, after the intense maneuvering around Social
Security of the early Reagan administration, including a Senate
Republican plan calling for $40 billion in unspecified Social
Security savings over three years. The plan quickly died, but the
issue did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have vivid memories of the bumper sticker: Save Social
Security, Vote Democratic,'' Shaw said. ``I went home and I changed
every political ad I had going, and everything was Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Republicans have learned to anticipate those
campaigns. Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster, said, ``Rather than
wringing our hands and waiting for the Democrats to use their scare
tactics on Social Security and Medicare, we've been getting out
there and saying, `This is our position, and don't believe the
scare tactics of the last few weeks.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the current maneuvering over the budget, Republicans have
been promoting their ``lockbox'' proposal, pledging to ``lock
away'' the Social Security surpluses. The House passed a version of
the proposal last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Social Security and Medicare are neutralized'' as issues,
Davis said, ``Republicans do very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats see what the Republicans are doing as ``fuzzing up
these issues,'' in the words of Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the
House minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt added, ``We have not done a good enough job pointing
out the real differences between the two parties on issues of real
importance to seniors _ i.e., the patient bill of rights, getting
prescription drugs to people on Medicare at a good price, long-term
care insurance and tax breaks for long-term care, shoring up and
keeping strong Social Security and Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, chairman of the House Democratic
caucus, argued that when Democratic candidates campaign hard for
older votes on the traditional issues, they prevail. Democrats, in
short, remain convinced that their party, which pushed through the
legislation creating Social Security and Medicare, should, by all
rights, have a natural advantage with older voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Lawrence Jacobs, associate professor of political science at
the University of Minnesota, and an expert on public opinion and
the elderly, argues that the differences between the two parties
are muted on some of the key issues today _ like putting more
managed care into Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   `They don't really perceive the kind of massive differences they
have in the past,'' Jacobs said of older voters.
</P>
<P>
   All of these issues are the subject of intense speculation in
both parties right now, with one fact adding urgency to it all.
Older Americans are not simply a growing population, but one that
continues to vote at a remarkable rate. They made up 28 percent of
the total House vote in 1998, but can account for a third or more
of the vote on Election Day in states like Florida and
Pennsylvania. And in recent elections, people age 65 and up were
more than twice as likely to vote as people age 18 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   So the struggle continues: A Gallup Poll released last week
showed Democrats and Republicans essentially in a dead heat among
voters 65 and up, when asked whether a Democratic- or
Republican-controlled Congress would be better for the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
