<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Monday, May 31. The N.Y. Times News Service late-night
supervisor will be Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and four of his top officials have now been indicted for
war crimes in Kosovo. But by all accounts here, the person with the
most influence over him is his dreamy and complicated wife, Mirjana
Markovic, whose life-long sense of persecution will only be
intensified by this new threat to her husband and her family. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ Update on Indian-Pakistani
fighting over Kashmir. Two days after Pakistan offered to hold
peace talks with India about the current crisis along the
cease-fire line in Kashmir, the Indians said on Sunday that they
are still unsure whether they want to participate in any such
negotiations. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-JUDAISM (Undated) _ More than a century ago, leaders of
Reform Judaism declared such practices as wearing skullcaps and
prayer shawls and using Hebrew in services to be the dated relics
of the past, and emphasized instead a focus on social ethics and a
highly cerebral approach to the faith. But in a symbolically
resonant gesture, and with an eye on the approach of a new century,
Reform's rabbinic arm, the Central Conference of American Rabbis,
last week adopted a document that encourages the movement's members
to explore traditional rituals. By commending study of the mitzvot,
the sacred obligations that include traditional rituals that are
required in more conservative branches of Judaism, the rabbis
positively acknowledged a trend among many of the 1.5 million
members of their movement. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Seattle) _ Just as Congress is on the verge of
approving measures like background checks for gun buyers and safety
lock devices, gun-control measures that had been languishing in
many states are now advancing, from an Oregon plan to require
criminal background checks for people buying firearms at gun shows
to a bill that would make New Jersey the first state to require
that all handguns sold there have ``smart-gun'' features, allowing
a gun to be used only by its registered owner. By Sam Howe
Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WEALTH (New York) _ In a city where the well-worn paths
to success have led through the trading floor or the ranks of large
media corporations, the emergence of sudden Internet-bred wealth
holds out the promise of much quicker rewards. It is exposing New
Yorkers to the Silicon Valley culture of entrepreneurial risk. And
it is prompting resentment, envy, and a scramble to be a part of
it. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-POLITICS (Washington) _ Older Americans, once among the
most loyal of Democratic voters in congressional elections, are
drifting toward the Republicans for a number of reasons. By Robin
Toner.
</P>
