<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEMORIALDAY-COX     05-30 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIALDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virtual Wall is a cyberspace version of the real Vietnam
memorial
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    PACKAGES WITH: MEMORIALDAY-SIDE
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His photo album from basic training in his lap, his
fingers clickety-clicking across his computer keyboard, Max Falls
punches in the names of old Army buddies on a new Internet site _
trying to find out how many didn't make it back from Vietnam as he
did, 29 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Methodically entering the names of the other 170 young men in
his 1968 Ft. Benning basic training company, and other servicemen
he recalls, Falls repeatedly gets the comforting answer, ``No
matches.'' That indicates the soldier wasn't among the 58,219 slain
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not long before a name yields a ``hit,'' eliciting a
muffled groan from Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donald Queen,'' he sighs. ``What a shame. He was from my neck
of the woods in north Georgia, a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the click of his mouse, another page pops up on The Vietnam
Veterans Virtual Wall web site, providing details. It turns out
Queen died from grenade wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Another click invites Falls to post a remembrance under Queen's
name for anyone to see, or in a general area for reflections.
</P>
<P>
   Falls, 54, owner of Furniture Clinic of Georgia in Austell, had
just about given up trying to find out what happened to many of the
men he once knew. He's enthralled with the Virtual Wall site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered,'' says Falls. ``You hear about the people
from your home town, but now you can find out in a flash about the
others. This is a really neat thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored jointly by the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund and
WinStar Communications, a telephone/Internet service provider, the
Virtual Wall web site was launched a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cyberspace version of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in
Washington, listing all the names that are etched on the famous
black-granite wall. Web surfers can call up the names of those who
died in Vietnam, punch up details of their deaths, and post
tributes, including color photographs and sound recordings.
</P>
<P>
   So far, about 5,000 tributes have been left. Jan Scruggs, head
of the the Washington-based Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund, expects
that number to mushroom as more ex-servicemen, and loved ones of
those who died, learn about the site, which is getting an
escalating number of hits weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slow-burning fuse whenever you come up with a new
idea,'' he says. ``But the word is getting out, and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs says the site is meant to be an extension of the real
wall, a place people can visit without trekking to Washington. A
major purpose, he adds, is to educate America's youth about the
Vietnam War. The site provides histories, commentaries, chat rooms
and photographs that can be called up with a mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   A committee reviews all tributes before they are posted, usually
within about three days. Many remembrances are painfully personal.
</P>
<P>
   One, for example, was posted by a vet who identified himself as
``just a grunt'' who served with Johnny Ray Bryson of College Park,
who was killed in action Jan. 7, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was near him when he was killed and when I rushed to help
him it was clear that he was gone,'' the grunt wrote. ``He did not
suffer, and he was not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, posted for William D. Sizemore of Augusta, was penned
by his son, Gary _ only 12 when his dad was ambushed in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi Dad,'' it begins. ``I just wanted to say hello. As your two
grandaughters grow into beautiful young women, it hurts me even
more that they will never know you as their grandfather. You would
be very proud of them, as they are proud of you. I love you. Your
son, Gary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore, contacted by phone, said he finds the virtual wall
``cathartic'' and plans to communicate more with his dad. ``I plan
to post some pictures of his grandchildren, my kids, he never got
to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Many postings are from relatives searching for vets who knew
their dads. Some leave phone numbers and e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who lost our fathers in Vietnam are searching,''
says Jen Branch Denard, of Tampa, who was 2 when her dad was
killed. ``We're growing old enough to begin to ask questions that
we don't have answers to, and realizing we weren't taught about
Vietnam in school....
</P>
<P>
   ``I check my dad's name often to see if more men who knew him
have checked in.''
</P>
<P>
   George Marlow, 50, of Lawrenceville, has spent a lot of time on
the site tracking down aquaintances. ``You just lose track,'' says
Marlow, who spent a year as a grunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through the site, city by city. I just found there were
guys who went to Athens High with me who died in 'Nam. I didn't
know Herman Fields was dead till I found the virtual wall.''
</P>
<P>
   He sighs. ``But I almost don't want to know who didn't make it.
There's still a lot of hurt there.''
</P>
<P>
   Falls, of Austell, felt better after running through many names
in his basic-training book, relieved that most survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine, after all these years, now I know,'' says Falls.
</P>
<P>
   He thumbs through his album, checking more names on the
computer. It takes a while, but eventually he learns that at least
a half-dozen others from his basic training unit didn't come back:
Michael Dean Brown, Donnie Lee Hackney, Robert G. Guinn, Jimmy Lee
Castleberry, Carlton Lee Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Then he points at album pictures of men whose names didn't
``hit.'' He still keeps up with some of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy Abercrombie, he made it and has a business in Atlanta,''
Falls says. ``There's Davenport. And Danny McFarland. And Ralph
Brown. Larry Everson, a real cut-up. Warren Long. Look here, here's
Mauldin, the only college graduate in my bunch. Wonder if he made
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin's name is punched in.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam Veterans Virtual Wall: www.thevirtualwall.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
