<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RALLY LATE TO TIE, WIN IN 10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A strange night for the Rangers ended on a
strange but victorious note when two wild pitches gave them their
fifth consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Twins reliever Mike Trombley delivered the wild
pitches after a Ivan Rodriguez double, giving the Rangers a 4-3
victory at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez started the 10th with a double into the left-field
corner. Trombley got two strikes on Juan Gonzalez, but then bounced
two pitches in the dirt past catcher Terry Steinbach to bring home
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Rangers their longest winning streak of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed at the start for 30 minutes by rain. The
Rangers had to play without ailing pitcher Mike Morgan and
outfielder Rusty Greer (sprained shoulder) and lost shortstop Royce
Clayton in the fifth inning with a bruised shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   They still prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty good win to come from behind,'' Rodriguez
said. ``These are games we may need later in the season. We were
just happy to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers trailed 3-2 going into the eighth, but rallied to
tie the game. Rodriguez singled off Twins reliever Bob Wells and
Juan Gonzalez was hit by a pitch. Left-hander Travis Miller came in
and got Rafael Palmeiro to pop out, but Todd Zeile lined a single
to left off Trombley, scoring Rodriguez with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was 2-for-3 last night, extending his hitting streak
to 18 games. He is hitting .375 (27-72) during the streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins loaded the bases with two outs in the ninth, but
reliever Tim Crabtree got Ron Coomer on a grounder to third to end
the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree pitched 1 1/3 scoreless innings, his 15th consecutive
appearance without giving up a run. That breaks the club record he
shared with Darren Oliver, who had 14 consecutive scoreless
appearances in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett, removed from the rotation two weeks ago, was
pressed into emergency service when Morgan was scratched before the
game because of swelling and pain in his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett showed all signs of giving his best performance of the
year, allowing two hits through four scoreless innings. But he ran
into trouble in the fifth, starting when Marty Cordova and Doug
Mientkiewicz dropped a couple of soft line drives into left field
for base hits.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Steinbach then grounded a run-scoring single through the
left side, and Denny Hocking loaded the bases with a bunt hit that
third baseman Todd Zeile couldn't come up with on the wet grass.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates decided that was enough, bringing in
reliever Mike Venafro to face Todd Walker. But, in a lefty vs.
lefty matchup, Walker lobbed another single into left field,
scoring two runs to give the Twins a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he threw the ball well,'' Oates said of Burkett.
``He was pitching ahead. He just ran out of gas. Before the game, I
was just hoping for four or five innings from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored in the first two innings but nothing more
until the eighth-inning heroics. They got one in the first when Tom
Goodwin reached on an infield single, stole second and, after
Rodriguez walked, scored on Juan Gonzalez's single to right.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers then tried to steal a run after Palmeiro flied out
to center for the second out, moving Rodriguez to third. Gonzalez,
with Todd Zeile at the plate, broke for second, got caught in a
rundown but was tagged out a split-second before Rodriguez could
cross home plate for a run.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile then started the second with a home run to center, his
ninth of the season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
