<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINGER-POINTING CONTINUES IN WAKE OF CHINESE SPYING SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fallout from a congressional report pointing to
China's theft of U.S. nuclear secrets continued Sunday with an
administration official confirming that there will be firings and
demotions at the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another administration official charged that a key
GOP senator who has been among the most critical of the White House
policy on China was briefed about the security problems at the
Energy Department labs almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of accusations and threats of disciplinary action
came in response to last week's release of a report on Chinese
espionage by a congressional committee headed by Rep. Christopher
Cox, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox report cites security lapses at the Energy Department's
nuclear labs over several decades that allowed the Chinese to steal
U.S. weapons technology.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson was asked whether there will be firings and
demotions at his agency within the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Richardson. ``And I think the reason is that there
were communications breakdowns, there were incompetent acts,
security was not considered important and counterintelligence was
not considered as important as it should be, and at least under the
people in my department, there should be accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he has insisted since the report was released last week,
Richardson said that many of the security lapses have been
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it is not clear how much China has benefited from
the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very valuable report of Congressman Cox, but the
extent of the damage _ I think the jury is still out,'' Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The finger-pointing over the Chinese spying, which began as soon
as the report was issued, continued on the Sunday talk shows.
Republicans have blamed the Clinton administration for failing to
notify lawmakers of the Chinese spying and of not taking quick
action to halt the activity.
</P>
<P>
   But a former CIA officer who now works for the Energy Department
asserted that members of Congress ignored warnings given to them
several years ago about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Curran, director of counterintelligence for the Energy
Department, said on ABC-TV's ``This Week'' that in 1997 he had
provided information about problems at the Energy labs and
recommendations to remedy the security lapses at the request of
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala. Shelby, the chairman of the Senate
Select Committee on Intelligence, has been among the most critical
of the administration's handling of the China situation.
</P>
<P>
   Curran said he never got a response from Shelby to his report,
which had 26 proposals, including a recommendation to share the
information with other oversight intelligence committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report was very alarming as to the present state of
affairs at counterintelligence,'' Curran said.
</P>
<P>
   Curran said Congress also rejected a $12 million request that he
argued was needed to help detect people breaking into computer
system at the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that in his previous role at the CIA he regularly
briefed Congress about sensitive security lapses but that neither
Shelby nor his staff bothered to attend most of those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``His staff wouldn't even accept our briefings. They got up and
walked away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on ``This Week,'' Shelby responded that Curran was
``out of bounds'' with his accusations, arguing that the Senate
Intelligence Committee did respond to the concerns in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said he did not attend all of the private briefings but
did attend the formal hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby also said he hoped that President Clinton's national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, would testify before the Senate on
the issue. Some members of Congress have asserted that Berger, who
is in charge of China policy, failed to address the security
problems when he learned about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a pivotal position for a long time,'' said Shelby.
So far, Berger has declined to testify before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
