r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-WITH-TRIPLE-CROWN     05-30 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WITH-TRIPLE-CROWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A LOOK AT THE TRIPLE CROWN WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
SIR BARTON (1919) Owner: J.K.L. Ross
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trainer: H.G. Bedwell
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: John Loftus
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Believe it or not, Sir Barton had never won a race
prior to the 1919 Kentucky Derby, his first start as a 3-year-old.
The colt with sore feet and a hot temper was entered in the Derby
as a ``rabbit,'' but he led all the way and upset stablemate Billy
Kelly by five lengths. He won the Preakness the same way and added
the Belmont despite a slow start.
GALLANT FOX (1930) Owner: Belair Stud
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: ``Sunny Jim'' Fitzsimmons
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Earl Sande
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Sportswriter Charles Hatton was the first to coin the
phrase ``Triple Crown'' when he covered Gallant Fox's march through
the races. ``The Fox of Belair'' was born with a wild right eye
that was said to frighten other horses, and legendary jockey Sande
came out of retirement to ride him. Gallant Fox is the only Triple
Crown winner to capture the Preakness before the Derby and was the
first to break out of a mechanical starting gate.
OMAHA (1935) Owner: Belair Stud
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: ``Sunny Jim'' Fitzsimmons
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: William Saunders
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Omaha was a son of the first stallion crop of Gallant
Fox, making them the only father-son horse combination to take the
Triple Crown. Calumet Farm filly Nellie Flag was the Derby favorite
that year, but Omaha won all three races comfortably, although he
never was considered a great horse. He remains the only Triple
Crown winner to lose during the series: He was defeated in the
Withers Stakes as a prep for the Belmont.
WAR ADMIRAL (1937) Owner: Glen Riddle Farms
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: George Conway
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Charles Kurtsinger
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Man O' War never won the Triple Crown because he didn't
run in the Kentucky Derby. But the legendary horse made his mark on
the series, anyway, as the sire of War Admiral. Owner Samuel Riddle
almost didn't run War Admiral in the Derby, either, but after a
11/4-mile allowance prep four days before the race, the colt was
entered and won. He took the Preakness by a head and won the
Belmont despite stumbling at the break and suffering a deep cut on
his leg.
WHIRLAWAY (1941) Owner: Calumet Farm
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Ben Jones
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Eddie Arcaro
</P>
<P>
   Notable: To put it bluntly, Whirlaway was a nut. He liked to
head for the outside rail during his races and was so unpredictable
it seemed he would never fulfill his limitless potential. But
trainer Ben Jones worked tirelessly with the horse and employed
jockey Eddie Arcaro to help. In the end, Calumet Farm's long-tailed
come-from-behinder became one of history's greatest horses. He
shattered a track record in the Kentucky Derby, swept the Triple
Crown convincingly and twice was named Horse of the Year.
COUNT FLEET (1943) Owner: Mrs. John D. Hertz
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Don Cameron
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: John Longden
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Owned by the Hertz rent-a-car founder, Count Fleet
liked to grab the lead at the start and dare anyone to keep up his
pace. Few could. Initially believed to be a clumsy sort, he was
voted a champion as a 2-year-old, and demolished his competition so
conclusively in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness that only two
horses lined up to oppose him in the Belmont. He crushed them by 25
lengths, setting a track record, but suffered an injury to his left
front ankle during the race and never ran again. His Derby was
known as the ``Streetcar Derby,'' because travel was restricted
during World War II.
ASSAULT (1946) Owner: King Ranch
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Max Hirsch
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Warren Mehrtens
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Almost as unlikely a Triple Crown hero as Sir Barton,
the Texas-bred Assault stepped on a surveyor's stake as a youngster
and mangled his right front foot. As a result, he walked with a
noticeable limp. But he could run. Nicknamed ``The Clubfooted
Comet,'' the King Ranch colt continued to defy expectations. He was
8-to-1 in the Derby, barely held on to win the Preakness, and again
surprised many handicappers by capturing the Belmont to earn his
place in history. Unfortunately, however, he was sterile at stud.
CITATION (1948) Owner: Calumet Farm
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Jimmy Jones
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Eddie Arcaro
</P>
<P>
   Notable: The late Eddie Arcaro called Citation not only the best
horse he ever rode, but perhaps the best anyone ever rode. The
Calumet Farm wonder won 19 of his 20 starts as a 3-year-old, and
rolled to dominating Triple Crown victories. He even tuned up for
the Kentucky Derby by outrunning his older stablemate Armed, the
1947 horse of the year, in an allowance race. He later became
racing's first millionaire. Citation didn't lose a race for two
years and five months, and was the last Triple Crown winner for a
quarter-century.
SECRETARIAT (1973) Owner: Meadow Stable
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Lucien Lauren
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Ron Turcotte
</P>
<P>
   Notable: By the time ``Big Red'' came around, people were
wondering if there would ever be another Triple Crown winner. But
Secretariat captivated the nation with his 3-year-old heroics, and
secured his place in history as one of the most sensational
racehorses of all time. The muscular chestnut set a track record in
the Kentucky Derby that still stands, was robbed of a Preakness
record by a misfiring teletimer, and his other-worldly 31-length
Belmont romp might be the single-best performance by any American
thoroughbred.
SEATTLE SLEW (1977) Owner: Karen Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Billy Turner
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Jean Cruget
</P>
<P>
   Notable: An ugly duckling bought for only $17,500 as a yearling,
`Slew'' became the epitome of a professional racehorse. He won all
three of his starts as a juvenile, won three prep races to begin
his 3-year-old season, and swept through the classics to become the
only undefeated Triple Crown champion. The Slew Express was nearly
derailed by a slow start in the Kentucky Derby, but he quickly
bulled his way between horses to reach the front and refused to
turn loose of the lead.
AFFIRMED (1978) Owner: Harbor View Farm
</P>
<P>
   Trainer: Laz Barrera
</P>
<P>
   Jockey: Steve Cauthen
</P>
<P>
   Notable: The nifty chestnut had a nose for the finish line, and
at the expense of his archrival Alydar, he used it to give the
sport its first-ever back-to-back Triple Crown winners. Fueling
what became modern racing's quintessential rivalry, Affirmed
clearly outran Alydar in the Kentucky Derby, then battled him
throughout the stretch of the Preakness and Belmont. In the
Belmont, Alydar moved alongside Affirmed with six furlongs to run,
and they raced in tandem to the finish. Alydar appeared to put his
neck in front of Affirmed in midstretch, but Affirmed, under
18-year-old ``boy wonder'' Steve Cauthen, tenaciously battled back
to win by a head.
Best of the best A look at the average winning margins of Triple
Crown winners in the Kentucky Derby, Preakness and Belmont Stakes:
Horse Average margin Count Fleet 12 lengths Secretariat 12 lengths
Citation 5.7 lengths Sir Barton 4.7 lengths Whirlaway 4 lengths
</P>
<P>
   Closing the deal The fastest 11/2-mile Belmont Stakes by Triple
Crown winners: Horse Time Secretariat 2:24 Affirmed 2:264/5
Citation 2:281/5 Count Fleet 2:281/5 War Admiral 2:283/5
</P>
<P>
   Near-misses Kentucky Derby and Preakness winners who have lost
the Belmont: Burgoo King (1932) Bold Venture (1936) Pensive (1944)
Tim Tam (1958) Carry Back (1961) Northern Dancer (1964) Kauai King
(1966) Forward Pass (1968) Majestic Prince (1969) Canonero II
(1971) Spectacular Bid (1979) Pleasant Colony (1981) Alysheba
(1987) Sunday Silence (1989) Silver Charm (1997) Real Quiet (1998)
</P>
<P>
   Triple trivia Records among Triple Crown winners include: Best
career win percentage: Seattle Slew, .824 (17 starts, 14 wins)
Shortest cumulative margins: Affirmed, 13/4 lengths Most horses
faced: War Admiral, 35 Fewest horses faced: Count Fleet, 17
Smallest win payoffs in series: Count Fleet, $7.20 total Shortest
period for series: Assault, 28 days Youngest jockey: Steve Cauthen,
18
</P>
<P>
   Do you know? Sir Barton died in 1937 at age 21 on a Wyoming
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Gallant Fox died Nov. 13, 1954 at age 27 at Claiborne Stud in
Paris, Ky. He has a marker in the farm's cemetery, but was actually
buried on a hill.
</P>
<P>
   Omaha lived his final years on a Nebraska farm, died in 1959 at
age 26 and was buried at Ak-Sar-Ben racecourse in _ appropriately _
Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Details about War Admiral's death are sketchy, but he is
believed to have died at Faraway Farm in Kentucky, where he was
foaled.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlaway was sold to French breeders, and died April 6, 1953,
at age 15 at Haras de Fresnay-le-Bouffard in the southern Normandy
region of France.
</P>
<P>
   Count Fleet died on Dec. 3, 1973, at age 33, at Stoner Creek
Stud in Paris, Ky., the farm where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   Assault was put down after fracturing a leg at King Ranch in
Kingsville, on Sept. 1, 1971, at age 28.
</P>
<P>
   Citation died at Calumet Farm in Lexington, Ky., where he was
born, on Aug. 8, 1970, at the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat was put down due to complications from laminitis at
Claiborne Farm on Oct. 4, 1989, at age 19.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Slew stands at stud at Three Chimneys Farm in Midway,
Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmed stands at stud at Jonabell Farm in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
