<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK, HARTLEY SEE PAST IS TIE THAT BINDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever might be happening on the ice between their teams,
there's definitely no feud between Stars coach Ken Hitchcock and
his Colorado counterpart, Bob Hartley.
</P>
<P>
   When Hitchcock walked by Tuesday morning as the Avalanche was on
the ice practicing in Denver, Hartley pounded on the glass to get
his attention, then came out to spend five minutes talking to the
Stars coach, offering him the use of the Avalanche's offices and
video room if he needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Why so friendly? Perhaps because the two are kindred spirits,
both having climbed almost identical ladders to get to the NHL.
Hartley began coaching on the side while he was working a full-time
job in an auto factory in Ontario, installing car windshields.
Hitchcock, of course, was a sporting-goods salesman in an Edmonton
suburb when he began his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to work 40 hours and punch clocks and have two weeks
vacation,'' Hartley says of himself and Hitchcock. ``I know it's
different now. If I could handle 3,000 windshields in a day and not
break one, there would never be 17,000 fans cheering me. But then
if I broke three in a row, there wouldn't be 17,000 booing me,
either. Hitch is basically in the same situation, and that's why we
kind of have mutual respect for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Hitchcock: ``Our careers are perfect parallels. He's gone
the $3.49 pregame meal route. He's gone the bus route. He knows
what it's like. It's water after the game if you lose and
milkshakes if you win. The bus ride has been the same for both of
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we've talked about is how much we appreciate
where we're at. Winning and losing is part of it, but being able to
coach is the biggest part, and I don't think either one of us would
take that for granted. I think either one of us could deal with not
coaching at the NHL level, but we'd both have a problem not
coaching at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Deja Nieu
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Nieuwendyk made the cross-slot pass that Jamie
Langenbrunner fired home for the Stars' second goal in Game 3's 3-0
victory Wednesday night, it came one day short of the 10-year
anniversary of an almost identical pass he made to Calgary's Lanny
MacDonald in '89. MacDonald's goal clinched the Game 6 victory for
Calgary in the Flames' Stanley Cup triumph. ``''That pass was over
the stick \Rof the defenseman\S,'' Nieuwendyk says, ``and this pass
was under it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, both wound up in the net.
</P>
<P>
   Awed by the Cup
</P>
<P>
   In its tour of the Fort Worth-Dallas area last week, the revered
Stanley Cup _ yes, the very same one the Stars are so desperately
trying to win _ made its way to the Star-Telegram sports
department, where a crowd of 60 or so employees got a chance to
touch it, hug it and pose for photos with it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is Lord Stanley's Cup, the one from which Wayne
Gretzky, Mark Messier and many another NHL stars have sipped
victory champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Copy editor Joe Guerrini even brought his dog, Maude, up to pose
with the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   No, he didn't let Maude lick the cup.
</P>
<P>
   We do have some sense of protocol, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its stop at the Star-Telegram and various malls, the Cup
also made it out to the Dick Bosman-Big Brothers Charity Golf
Tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Old friends not forgotten
</P>
<P>
   If you're composing a list of pitchers the Rangers might try to
trade for by the July 31 trade deadline _ Kevin Appier, Kenny
Rogers, etc. _ don't forget old friend Darren Oliver. Oliver is
pitching well for St. Louis, but he'll be a free agent after this
season, and if the Cards are out of the race, they'll be looking to
dump him to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Rangers are already interested.
</P>
<P>
   Zim-zam man
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates continues to rave about reliever Jeff Zimmerman _
and why not? _ and his three quality pitches, making him, it would
seem, an ideal candidate to become a starting pitcher. That's not
going to happen this season, but don't rule it out for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now's not the time,'' is all Oates will say. ``It would be
like robbing Peter \Rthe bullpen\S to pay Paul \Rthe rotation\S.
What would I do without him the other four days?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Ricky?
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday through Wednesday last week, the NFL brought 32 of its
top rookies for 1999 to Disney World in Orlando, Fla., to have
photos taken for their rookie cards by Topps, Fleer, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The players were sent plane tickets and had hotel arrangements
made for them. All they had to do was show up. Only one did not.
</P>
<P>
   You guessed it _ Ricky Williams. He never phoned to say why he
wouldn't be there, either.
</P>
<P>
   Just another fumble by Williams and his agent, Master P.
</P>
<P>
   Port Where?
</P>
<P>
   Port Charlotte is apparently convinced the Rangers will leave
for either South Texas or Arizona once their current contract
expires and is already thinking about life without them. There's
talk the Rangers' training facilities might be turned into an
equestrian center or a minor-league soccer facility. It's already
used for high school cross country meets when the Rangers aren't
there.
REVO'S GRAPEVINE SAYS:
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for the Cowboys to make any announcement concerning
Deion Sanders as early as Tuesday. That's the first day they could
do something, but they're more likely to give themselves a chance
to see how his rehab is coming along before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ranger Ruben Sierra, trying to keep his fading career
alive while playing for Atlantic City in the independent Atlantic
Coast League, is basically on life support, hitting only .200
(14-for-70) in his first 20 games with no homers and four runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers-Stars president Jim Lites is in the process of
finalizing a divorce from his wife, Denise, daughter of Tigers-Red
Wings owner Mike Illitch.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ticket talk-show host Rocco Pendola has landed the
midafternoon gig with Sports Fan Radio Network in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Reese Ryan, youngest son of Nolan and Ruth, wed Fort Worth lass
and TCU student Alison Schlegel yesterday in San Antonio. They'll
be honeymooning in Paris (ooh, la la).
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe that now-retired Associated Press sports editor
Denne Freeman could find a way to play any more golf than he
already was, but count on it. He's having a new home built on a
golf course in Salado. Jaime Aron has replaced Freeman as the AP's
Texas sports editor.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ranger Jim Sundberg is holding a weeklong
baseball-softball camp in conjunction with South Grand Prairie's
Jennifer McFalls, a member of the USA National Softball Team,
starting tomorrow at Texas Star in Euless. Call (817) 461-6121 for
more info.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
