<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANSKE-PROFILE-ART-61     05-30 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANSKE-PROFILE-ART-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPUBLICAN WITH AN INDEPENDENT VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every session of the House of Representatives has
its own personality, its own emblematic types, from the comfortable
Democratic incumbents of the late 1980s to the Republican
revolutionaries of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, is a fitting symbol of the
current House _ the edgy, ever-shifting House where Republicans are
trying to govern with 222 votes out of 435, the slimmest majority
in 45 years, meaning that every vote counts. When a Greg Ganske
gets frustrated and decides to buck his leadership, as he did last
week, it matters.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske, a 50-year-old plastic and reconstructive surgeon from
Des Moines, was one of six Republicans who signed a Democratic
petition that seeks to force an early vote on campaign-finance
legislation. The Republican leadership had not scheduled a vote on
the issue until September, which proponents of the bill said
guaranteed that it would not make it out of the House soon enough
to overcome resistance in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske offered a simple enough explanation for his action. ``I
really think we need to reduce the influence of big-money donations
in this capital,'' he said, while his colleagues scattered for the
Memorial Day recess. ``I think the bill is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the cool rationale, the frustration was palpable.
Ganske said that he and some of his colleagues had urged their
leadership earlier this year to move faster on several issues,
including campaign finance and patients' rights in managed care,
which is a special cause of Ganske's. The issues had to be dealt
with sooner or later, he said, and letting them slide ``just leaves
the Senate off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   He began to check off the inexorable calendar: the budget issues
that will cloud the fall, leading quickly into the holidays,
leading quickly into the presidential campaign. ``And then people
will use as an excuse, in the year 2000, `Why don't we wait and see
how the presidential election comes out, then we'll have a better
idea of what to do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Are we frustrated, Ganske?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I am. I mean, it's not the way I would run the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is not a small thing to say no to your leadership,
even for a member with a reputation for independence and a
traditionally Democratic district that probably expects it. ``He's
not a wise guy, he's not a guy out there trying to be difficult,''
said Rep. Michael Forbes, R-N.Y., another of the gang of six. ``He
believes in his heart in these issues, as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds terribly civilized, as Ganske tells it. He had a
``civil conversation'' with Speaker Dennis Hastert about what he
planned to do. ``We don't agree on the bill,'' Ganske said. ``I
think he thinks the bill is tilted against Republicans. I think the
bill is evenly balanced.'' Then Ganske ran into Rep. Tom DeLay, the
majority whip, a k a the Hammer, and complimented DeLay on his golf
game.
</P>
<P>
   His decision was hardly unprecedented, he noted _ he broke ranks
more dramatically last year by signing on to a Democratic patients'
rights bill _ and, he argued, not all that unusual within the
Republican caucus. ``I've been an independent voice on a couple of
issues that are very important to me and that I think are important
to the country,'' he said. ``Other members have done the same thing
on different issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Ganske, who is married to a physician and still
practices surgery on periodic charitable missions abroad, agrees
that medicine is easier. ``When I'm in the operating room, I can
get a hemostat or a scalpel slapped in my palm and I can fix the
problem in a short period of time,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet he ran for Congress in 1994, he said, in part because he was
tired of sitting around all those doctors' lounges, ``hearing
everyone whine and moan and groan about this or that.'' A political
newcomer, he defeated Rep. Neal Smith, a Democrat who had served in
the House since 1958.
</P>
<P>
   One of six children, a deep-rooted Iowan who grew up working in
his father's small-town grocery store, Ganske went to Congress as a
citizen legislator with that revolutionary class of '94. But he
said he always thought the rhetoric was overblown, and in fact he
showed his independence early on. ``I didn't come to Congress to
cause a revolution,'' he said. ``I came to fix some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he worry about his party, which looked very much besieged
in the House last week, divided on a variety of issues?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I come from a Midwest Republican tradition of what I
would call progressivism, in the tradition of Bob LaFollette and
the reformers, sort of the Teddy Roosevelt branch of our party, the
trust busters,'' he said. ``And I think our party needs to
recognize that there are some populist issues that are well within
the principles of being a Republican, and that it would help us to
emphasize some of those issues.'' One of those issues, he said, is
``reforming'' the managed-care system.
</P>
<P>
   His flight to Iowa was approaching, so Ganske told one last
story, a fitting one for these difficult days in the House. Not
long after he was elected to Congress, he contracted encephalitis
while on a medical mission abroad. Quite ill, he awoke in the
hospital one day to see his family priest asking, ``Greg, would you
like to receive the Sacrament of the Sick?''
</P>
<P>
   As a former altar boy, Ganske said he realized, with some degree
of panic, that ``they used to call that Extreme Unction, last
rites.'' At which point, the priest leaned over and whispered in
his ear, ``And Greg, with your new job, I would highly recommend
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
