<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will soar toward 100 degrees across western Texas
Monday as a wedge of hot air invades from Mexico. The hot-air
invasion will not likely trigger thunderstorms because temperatures
at an altitude of 5,000 feet will be as high as 86 degrees,
creating a warm barrier or lid aloft that will halt the ascent of
air rising from the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, where the lid will not be as warm or strong,
thunderstorms will erupt across parts of the central Plains as
humid air from the Gulf of Mexico is lifted by a jet stream
disturbance approaching from the Rockies. Storms may become severe
over parts of Kansas, Nebraska and eventually Missouri, with hail
and damaging winds posing a threat in spots where potent storms
erupt. Isolated tornadoes are also possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers and thunderstorms will develop from
the central Gulf Coast states and the Tennessee and Ohio Valleys to
the eastern Great Lakes as humid air streaming north from the Gulf
of Mexico is lifted by a jet stream disturbance. The heaviest
storms will occur in the central Gulf Coast states, where humidity
levels will be highest.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will build across the interior Northeast as a sprawling
area of warm high pressure centered off the Atlantic coast ridges
westward to the Appalachians. High and middle clouds from the
disturbance over the Ohio Valley and eastern Great Lakes will
temper heat west of the Appalachians. Also, sea breezes will temper
the warm-up along parts of the New England coast. Patchy fog may
also help to delay the warm-up along the Maine coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Waterspouts
</P>
<P>
   Waterspouts were spotted near Key West Saturday evening
underneath thunderstorms that bubbled up as a weak disturbance
passed over southern Florida. Waterspouts often develop over the
warm, relatively shallow seas surrounding the Florida Keys in
summer, but many of these spouts form in the absence of
thunderstorms, spinning to life under fair-weather cumulus clouds.
Though ``fair-weather waterspouts'' seldom produce winds in excess
of 65 mph, boaters must respect these whirlwinds. On average, about
100 waterspouts are observed near the Florida Keys in each of the
three summer months.
</P>
</TEXT>
