<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW WAY TO PREVENT DRUNK DRIVING  
 YOUR PEARLY WHITES SMILING BACK AT YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif)  (rk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One way to cut down on drunk driving is to keep a car from
starting if its driver has been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, a number of states have allowed courts
to order convicted drunk drivers to install electronic
ignition-lock devices in their cars. Each time a driver wants to
start a car, he or she must blow into a breath analyzer that is
connected to the ignition. If alcohol is detected, the car will not
start.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ways to cheat, especially if the drinking driver
is accompanied by a sober friend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three Tucson, Ariz., inventors believe they have a
solution. They have patented a laser-based device that can
continuously detect alcohol fumes inside a car _ even one with its
windows open _ and cut off the car's ignition.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say their design improves upon existing breath
analyzers by using a laser that operates nonstop, detecting alcohol
in air samples much smaller than needed for conventional analyzers,
and eliminating the need for a driver's cooperation with the test.
All a driver has to do is breathe while driving.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the device can transmit data about a drunk driver to
the police.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say their laser device is faster and more
sensitive than conventional ignition-lock devices, and has the
additional advantage of operating continuously.
</P>
<P>
   George Atkinson, one of the inventors, acknowledges that the
invention could err if a nondrinking driver was chauffeuring a
carload of heavy drinkers, or if an open container of liquor was in
the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly would detect the total concentration in the
car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the object, he added, is to reduce the number of drinking
drivers. ``Do you want to err on the side of stopping a driver and
testing him, or having that person continue to drive?''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson is a professor of chemistry and optical science at the
University of Arizona, as well as founder and president of the
company that owns the patent, the Innovative Lasers Corp. He
patented the device along with Markus Wolperdinger and Jeffrey
Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   The device won a patent because it uses a sensor called an
intracavity laser spectroscopy; the inventors prefer solid-state
lasers because they are small and require little power. The housing
contains a mirror and a lens to concentrate the laser, and has a
port on one side to draw in air. The laser operates continuously,
and can measure alcohol because molecules absorb light.
</P>
<P>
   ``A laser is basically a device that allows competition between
the production of light, called the gain, and the loss of light,''
Atkinson said. Loss is created when alcohol molecules absorb light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Molecules have a distinct signature,'' Atkinson continued.
``At certain wavelengths they absorb light, at others they don't.
There is a clear signature for water, alcohol, CO2. The intensity
of the absorption, or how much light is absorbed by the molecules
at a particular wavelength, is used to measure the concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasers are so sensitive that ``you don't need too many molecules
of alcohol,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say that because the sensor can register changes
in alcohol levels within seconds, it not only can detect alcohol in
parked or moving cars, but it can also tell whether a driver is
consuming alcohol while on the road. They say their sensor is so
sensitive it can even pick up alcohol vapors in the vicinity of a
driver when car windows are open.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are clever enough, they can defeat it,'' Atkinson
acknowledged. For example, a driver might disconnect the device or
allow a strong wind to blow through the car. But Atkinson thought
those problems could be overcome. ``Perhaps you wouldn't be able to
start the car if this device wasn't functioning,'' he said. ``Or
maybe it should be interlocked to the windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Once alcohol fumes are detected, the system can respond in a
number of ways. Cars can be programmed not to start if the alcohol
level registers above a minimum level. The information can be
conveyed to the driver so he or she could let someone else drive.
Or it could be transmitted outside the car _ either generally with
flashing headlights, or specifically to police in nearby patrol
cars via satellite. Finally, the system might generate a signal
that could be picked up by roadside police.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say the laser they use poses no danger to the
health of people inside a car, since radiation is contained in the
sensor's housing.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have tested aspects of the invention, Atkinson said
they have not built a prototype unit to install in cars. He said
his company would consider manufacturing the device, ``depending on
demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson, Wolperdinger and Pilgrim received patent 5,907,407.
</P>
<P>
   Your Pearly Whites Smiling Back at You
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon to a video near you _ your teeth.
</P>
<P>
   A newly patented system enables dentists to make videos of
dental X-rays, so both they and their patients can see pictures of
teeth more clearly than possible with those tiny negative X-ray
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Technology exists for digitizing dental X-rays and transferring
them to video. It involves using an expensive sensor card instead
of X-ray film. Like film, the card is placed behind the teeth to be
photographed, and an X-ray head shoots radiation through the teeth
and onto the card. The card is connected to a computer, and
transmits the image to be stored on a hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   But because the cards are expensive, cannot be washed between
patients, and create a fuzzy image, Stephen Blume, of Laguna Hills,
Calif., looked for a way to make video from conventional X-ray
film.
</P>
<P>
   His invention uses a film development tank with a window in one
side, connected to a video camera and a computer. The camera
captures the image on the X-ray film in what Blume calls the
``opaque stage,'' which he says occurs when the first chemical is
added to the reaction tank.
</P>
<P>
   This developer solution causes an opaque image of teeth to form
on the film, similar to a black-and-white photo. Later, water and
other chemicals cause the film to turn into the ``negative'' image
of familiar dental X-rays. Blume believes these negative images are
harder to see.
</P>
<P>
   After capturing the ``opaque'' image, the camera transfers it to
the computer to be stored, edited or transmitted in turn to another
computer, a printer or a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Blume received patent 5,870,172.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
