<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-1940S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETE OF THE '40S: DOAK WALKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America had fought a war and was settling down to raise families
and rebuild a nation still shaking off the effects of the Great
Depression. Doak Walker was the right kind of hero for the age:
handsome, friendly, photogenic and above all, humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess `I' was the least-used word in his vocabulary,'' SMU
teammate Kyle Rote of Walker.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time All-America selection (1947-49), Walker was popular
enough to draw overflow crowds at SMU. During the 1948 season, SMU
moved its games from Ownby Stadium (seating 23,000) to the Cotton
Bowl, which could handle double the capacity. Before season's end,
another 20,000 seats were added to the Cotton Bowl, thereafter
known as ``The House that Doak Built.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that all this happened because a little blue-eyed boy
could run with a football,'' said Emma Walker, his mother.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Life'' magazine cover boy, member of the college and Pro
Football Halls of Fame and a Heisman Trophy winner, Walker
exemplified the best that his generation had to give to America.
</P>
<P>
   His name lives on with the Doak Walker Award, given annually to
the nation's top running back. RUNNERS-UP
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson: Best single season in golf history in 1945, with
18 victories, including 11 in a row, and the single-season scoring
record (68.33 stroke average).
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan: Won three majors in the 1940s and 34 PGA tour events
in a five-year span (1944-48). Had 13 victories in 1946,
second-most in history to Nelson's 18 in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams: Red Sox outfielder won two Triple Crowns (1942,
1947) but didn't get voted MVP in either year. Won MVP honors in
1946 and 1949. Lost three years in his prime to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio: Yankees center fielder had 56-game hitting streak
in 1941. Won MVP award in 1941 and 1947 during decade that the
Yankees won four World Series.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
