<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-1940S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM OF THE 1940S: NOTRE DAME FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Elmer Layden, one of Notre Dame's famed ``Four Horseman,''
resigned as Irish coach to become NFL commissioner in 1941, few
could have known that a diminutive former Boston College coach
named Frank Leahy was going to add even more luster to the Golden
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   His first decade in South Bend produced four national
championships (1943, 1946, 1947, 1949), three Heisman Trophy
winners, two Outland Trophy winners and 18 All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame finished 8-0-1 in Leahy's first season, 1941.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, the 9-1 Irish won their first national championship of
the decade, as voted on by The Associated Press media panel after
the conclusion of the regular season. Quarterback Angelo Bertelli
won the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two seasons _ when Army won its two titles _ Notre
Dame went 15-4-1. The Irish did not lose again in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy finished his career with an .864 winning percentage,
second to Knute Rockne among all coaches with at least 10 seasons
at four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only played for two coaches in college and in pro ball,
Frank Leahy and George Halas,'' said John Lujack, the 1947 Heisman
Trophy winner. ``I think Leahy was 10 times better than Halas. I
thought Leahy was the all-time greatest coach who came down the
pike.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
