<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF THE 1940S: 1941
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Two legendary baseball rivals, Ted Williams and Joe DiMaggio, made
1941 a memorable year for sports fans. Williams hit .406, going
6-for-8 in a doubleheader on the final day of the season when he
could have take the day off and still been credited with a batting
average of .400. No player since has hit .400 or better.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Williams' spectacular season included a game-winning home run in
the All-Star game. His feats were overshadowed, however, by
DiMaggio, the New York Yankees center fielder who hit in 56
consecutive games, a record that has not been seriously challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The Most Valuable Player Award?
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio won that.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Colonial Country Club was the scene of the U.S. Open
golf tournament, won by Craig Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Whirlaway, ridden by Eddie Arcaro, won the horse
racing Triple Crown, the first of four Triple Crown winners of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   After Dec. 7, 1941, when the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor,
sports took a backseat to World War II for four years.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
