<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Tom Oder at (office) 404 526-5456 or (pager)
800-495-2461 or pagetom(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Elliot Jaspin at (home) 703 551-1033.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIALDAY _ AUSTELL, Ga. _ As Americans celebrate Memorial
Day, many are turning to the popular ``Virtual Wall'' website,
which features lots of writing and postings from Vietnam vets.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIALDAY-SIDE _ Remembrances that have been posted on the
virtual Vietnam Wall. With list of Memorial Day internet sites of
interest to veterans and their families. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CEMETERY _ MARIETTA, Ga. _ Bill Frazier and Jim Trapp,
caretakers at Marietta National Cemetery, have found unopened beers
left at gravesides of military men. They've found cards, military
mementos, as wel as letters expressing undying love and some
begging forgiveness. The cemetery is a place where people come to
find peace in the Garden of Stone. (Nurse, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CIVILWAR-LETTERS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Using a cigar box of letters
found in an attic, Joyce Fogle of New Lebanon, Ohio, has found the
answers to questions about David Rohrer, one of her husband's
ancestors. On July 21, 1862, David, the son of Simon Rohrer, went
to Dayton, along with many other local youths, and joined Co. I of
the 93rd Ohio Volunteers to do his part for the Civil War. On Aug.
20, he left the family farm, the brick house, which still stands on
U.S. 35 just west of New Lebanon. He would not return. (Schmidt,
Dayton Daily News freelancer). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Saturday. Still good for use with Memorial Day
stories.
</P>
