<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-DEACCESS-(2TAK     05-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-DEACCESS-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NO LONGER ON THE WALLS OFFERS CLUES TO MUSEUM'S PHILOSOPHY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When ``Museum as Muse: Artists Reflect'' closes at
the Museum of Modern Art on Tuesday, nearly all the 188 works in
the show will be crated and shipped to the exhibition's next stops,
in San Diego and then Madrid. But one will stay behind, in the
homes of various visitors to the exhibition and also in the
museum's bookstore: a slim 15-page publication with a bright red
cover titled ``Painting and Sculpture From the Museum of Modern
Art: Catalog of Deaccessions, 1929 Through 1998.'' It is the work
of Michael Asher, a 55-year-old Conceptual artist from California.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Museum as Muse'' the very concept of the museum is sliced
and diced to a fare-thee-well. Among the show's mostly contemporary
artworks, some mimic the museum's habits of accumulation and
classification; others examine its role as a repository of cultural
memory, and still others criticize it as elitist or colonial.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing gets as close to the heart of the matter as quietly
and cleanly as Asher's catalog. Compiled with the Modern's
permission and cooperation, it simply lists every work of painting
and sculpture known to have been sold or traded from the Modern's
collection since its founding in 1929. Throughout the run of the
show, several copies of it have been available for study in the
side pocket of a heavy wood bench near the end of the exhibition,
just beneath a discreet wall label.
</P>
<P>
   With this work, Asher reveals one of an art museum's most
private and sometimes controversial practices: the shedding, not
the accumulation, of artworks. And not just any museum is under
scrutiny. The Modern's history and its renowned collection are
virtually inseparable from the history of modernism: each has
played a major role in shaping our understanding of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with other museums, the Modern is relatively open about
its deaccessioning; still, this information has never been
assembled before. To have an overview of how the Modern has shaped
its own vaunted collection _ and thus its version of modernism _ is
something of a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   The names and numbers alone, even though they do not tell the
whole story, are keenly interesting if not titillating: among them,
21 Picassos, eight Cezannes, four de Chiricos, three Stuart Davises
and on and on. Altogether, a group that many museums would be happy
to own. One might almost expect the catalog to come in a plain
brown wrapper, not a red cover, and it seems singularly appropriate
that it can be taken home for careful examination in private.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Museum as Muse'' opened, the catalog has been available
in the the museum's bookstore, free to anyone with a Museum of
Modern Art ticket stub. ( Asher settled on a method of distribution
that required a bit of initiative because he wanted only people who
were genuinely interested to have access to the catalog.)
</P>
<P>
   Some 1,000 copies of a print run of 5,000 have been given out.
And the catalog will continue to be available in the bookstore at
least until July 6, the closing date of Claes Oldenburg's ``Mouse
Museum,'' which is not traveling with the show because of its
physical complexity.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Asher's piece will not travel has nothing to do with
physical properties. Like most of his works, this one barely exists
_ it is part of a strain of invisible art that has coursed through
Conceptual Art since its inception. But it is so site-specific that
it would be meaningless in the galleries of any other museum.
</P>
<P>
   Asher is one of several artists of the early 1970's who helped
raise site specificity to, well, an art form. You could also say
that absence itself is one of his favorite materials. He is
especially known for simply rearranging or removing, in order to
make more visible, certain aspects of a particular spatial or
institutional setting, presaging the efforts of younger artists
like Reinhard Mucha and Rirkrit Tiravanija.
</P>
<P>
   Asher once created a fantastically beautiful installation piece
simply by removing the windows and casements from a large square
gallery at the Clocktower in TriBeCa, transforming the space with a
dramatically different sense of light, sky and wind.
</P>
<P>
   So what does his list of removed artworks reveal about the
Modern and its past? All kinds of things, even if you extrapolate
exclusively from the information in the catalog and don't call the
museum's press department with questions, as I was able to do.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the ground rules. The Modern's deaccession policy,
restated by Kirk Varnedoe, chief curator of painting and sculpture,
in the catalog's brief essay, is simple. Like all museums
accredited by the American Association of Museum Directors _ which
means all major and most smaller museums in the country _ the
Modern sells or exchanges works of art only to purchase or acquire
other works of art.
</P>
<P>
   In addition it may sell or exchange a work by living artists
only to acquire another by the same artist, a rule that many but
not all museums adhere to. ( Asher's catalog indicates artists who
have been traded up, as this process is sometimes called, include
Larry Bell, Donald Judd, Loren MacIver, Jules Olitski, Sol LeWitt
and Jack Youngerman.)
</P>
<P>
   Not all these transactions occurred during the artists'
lifetimes. An Andy Warhol ``Campbell's Soup'' (1965) left the
collection in 1996, a decade after his death, when the Modern
acquired the entire set of Warhol's first series of ``Campbell's
Soup Cans,'' done a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In all 360 works by 177 artists are listed alphabetically
according to artist, with title, date, material, dimensions and
acquisition number, which includes the year the work entered the
collection. In addition, the Modern has deaccessioned 32 works by
unknown American folk artists and eight African masks and utensils.
</P>
<P>
   As with any other work of Conceptual Art, Asher's latest one
exists mostly in the mind's eye. As the names roll by, one tries to
conjure the works, to mass them together into their own salon de
refuses. On paper, it reads a bit like a who's who of modernism and
proto-modernism.
</P>
<P>
   Nine out of 10 names are famous, well known or at least vaguely
familiar. It is a fabulously motley crew: the Modern has rid itself
of works by Renoir, Monet, Daumier, Degas, van Gogh and Gauguin,
but also Edward Hicks and John Frederick Peto. The most frequently
deaccessioned artists are those who loom largest in its modernist
pantheon: Miro (seven), Matisse (nine) and Leger (13) as well as
the eight Cezannes and the 21 works by Picasso, the high scorer.
</P>
<P>
   But the same numbers have different meanings for different
artists. That the Modern has deaccessioned six works by Charles
Despiau, the French sculptor who began his career as Rodin's
assistant, probably does not indicate that it values Despiau almost
as much as Miro. The museum owns 11 works by Despiau, a not
insignificant number, but 33 by Miro.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases the low numbers reflect low productivity. The work
of Juan Gris, who died young and left a relatively small body of
work, has been subjected only four times to deaccessioning at the
Modern.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the museum's holdings in Georges Braque, Picasso's
partner in the invention of Cubism, who did not die young, have had
only five deaccessions. Does this mean that the Modern's Braques
have all withstood the test of time exceptionally well, or that the
museum's interest in his work lagged? Numbers appear to bear out
the latter theory: the Modern owns 84 paintings and sculptures by
Picasso and 8 by Braque. (In other words, fewer than Despiau.)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the museum acts stem from an embarrassment of riches,
as when the museum accepts a gift of several works of art among
which one closely duplicates a work it already owns. For example
the recent bequest of the architect Gordon Bunshaft included a
second cast of Miro's ``Moonbird,'' a large bronze sculpture from
1956. The museum accepted it with the intention of comparing the
two casts and keeping the superior one, which turned out to be the
Bunshaft version.
</P>
<P>
   But low numbers may or may not reflect relatively low interest.
The number of deaccessions of American works made between 1900 and
1939 is roughly one-third of the total of European ones from the
same period. That is not surprising; the museum was not deeply
interested in American art at that time.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to artists working after World War II,
deaccessions drop off across the board, which may reflect rising
prices, the expansion of the art market or perhaps institutional
uncertainty. For whatever reason, there are fewer than 40 from the
Abstract Expressionist generation and fewer than 15 from younger
postwar American artists; the figures are roughly similar for the
Europeans. Certain historically central artists, like Jasper Johns
and Joseph Beuys, have never been deaccessioned.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern's relatively heavy trade in the modern masters belies
the misconception that museums routinely dump the work of forgotten
artists. There is something comforting about this: The museum
probably owns hundreds of works by artists virtually unknown today,
artists who play little or no role in its well cultivated version
of modernism. But their works remain in place for the very reason
that they lack market or historical currency. This also preserves
and protects them for possible rediscovery by future curators and
historians.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the Modern's judgments remain shrouded in a mystery
that could be lifted only by seeing the works it let go next to
those by the same artist that it kept. But taken as a whole,
Asher's catalog stands as itemized evidence of institutional
consciousness, of the museum's desire continually to improve and
reshape itself. It is a quest both admirable and awful, since its
pursuit destroys part of its past.
</P>
<P>
   But questions large and small fill the mind. If this collection
of rejected works were reassembled today, how many would the
museum's current curators wish were still on hand? Why did the
Modern get rid of that little painting by Julian Levi? Two works by
Henri Rousseau? What did they look like? What was gained by getting
rid of something as quirky as Eugene Speicher's painting of
Katharine Cornell as Candida, from 1925-26, or Ernest Leonard
Blumenschein's ``Jury for Trial of a Sheepherder for Murder''? The
title's parting rhyme alone might have qualified it for permanent
residency.
</P>
<P>
   Asher's catalog could have gone further. It would have been
interesting to list the year of deacquisition. (The museum said
that Asher wanted to include such information, but that there was
not time to assemble it.) Of equal interest would have been each
work's method of entry into the Modern's collection in the first
place: whether by purchase or gift, and if a gift, from whom. But
this might be getting a little too personal.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the catalog is most valuable as an exhibition that
will never happen and as an act of remembering, mourning and
gratitude. These absent paintings and sculptures are the ghosts in
the machine that is the Museum of Modern Art. Today the museum may
be without them, yet paradoxically it would not be what it is today
without them. Despite their absence, they are almost as much a part
of its history as the works that remain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
