<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LITTLETON-MEDIA-2T     05-30 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LITTLETON-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIES OF CHECKBOOK JOURNALISM AFTER ABC PAYS A SOURCE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ABC News paid a friend of one of the teen-age gunmen
in the Columbine High School shootings $16,000 for the exclusive
broadcast rights to home videos and other materials containing
details about the killers. Then last Monday, the network presented
what it called an exclusive interview with the 18-year-old, Nathan
Dykeman, on its news program, ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   The network did not disclose on the air that it had paid
Dykeman, saying only that it had ``recently obtained the rights to
his home video,'' and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News executives said that the payment and the interview were
not connected. But critics and executives from competing news
organizations said ABC's action at least approached a line that has
long been considered uncrossable for network news organizations:
paying a subject for an interview, a practice that could encourage
news sources to embellish stories.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives said the decision to pay for the material was
consistent with its editorial policies. It was the latest example
of what several network news executives called a growing trend: the
willingness of network news divisions, all of which have policies
forbidding payment for interviews, to pay for material like videos
and photographs that are related to news stories.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Shapiro, the executive producer of the NBC news magazine
``Dateline,'' said that while paying for the use of video was
considered an acceptable practice, it must be unrelated to an
interview subject. He said his program would never buy material
from someone it intended to interview. ABC said in this case the
material needed the context of the interview to be understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Morning America,'' was the second news outlet to pay a
fee for such material supplied by Dykeman, a Columbine senior.
Dykeman has been widely sought for in-depth interviews by numerous
news organizations because of his friendship with Dylan Klebold,
one of the two gunmen. Dykeman had previously received $10,000 from
a tabloid newspaper, The National Enquirer, for much of the same
material and had turned down other interviews while he said he was
under contract to that newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   News executives from competing networks also criticized ABC's
decision to pay Dykeman on the grounds that it was helping someone
tangentially connected to the case make a profit from a tragedy,
and for the sheer amount of money ABC paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is gross on some level to profit off this tragedy,'' said
Jeff Zucker, the executive producer of NBC's show ``Today'' when
informed of ABC's actions. ``It's a clear example of buying a story
and it's an unseemly thing for ABC to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bode, the dean of Northwestern University's Medill School of
Journalism, said: ``I think it's both exploitative and completely
improper. One of the things that distinguishes these network news
organizations from exploitative infotainment shows like `Hard Copy'
and `Inside Edition' is that they demand second sources, they don't
do re-creations of events and they don't pay for interviews. This
is out of bounds. I think the people of Littleton have earned the
right to be left alone by the media. They deserve a little
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Goldstein, the dean of Columbia University's Graduate
School of Journalism, said, ``I find the whole notion of checkbook
journalism very complicated. Some of the greatest photographs ever
taken were by passersby or participants. It makes us uneasy that
somebody is profiting from the misfortune of others, but that's
what a lot of journalism is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein did say that ABC was wrong for not telling viewers it
had entered into a deal to pay Dykeman. ``It would certainly be
better if they had said they paid for it. A lot can be cured by
disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior executive with another news magazine show, who
acknowledged paying for video material on some stories, said the
price seemed unusually high. Even one ABC news executive expressed
surprise at how much the network agreed to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Another ABC executive, Shelley Ross, the executive producer of
``Good Morning America,'' said the program decided to buy the
materials because it believed they significantly advanced the
story. ``We are still trying to learn every nugget about who these
kids were and what leads to teen violence,'' she said. She added,
``I know what the journalism purists say. But we don't do checkbook
journalism. This was not checkbook journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross also said, ``There was competitive network bidding on
this,'' although she refused to identify the other bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Phone messages left at the homes of Dykeman's father and
stepfather were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   For its money, ABC received a home video showing Dykeman driving
to school with Klebold, in which the latter makes a passing,
apparently joking reference to sending torpedoes toward the school,
as well as a music video, in which Klebold, wearing a black trench
coat, pours lighter fluid on the school football field.
</P>
<P>
   ABC also received access to Dykeman's yearbook, which contained
some messages filled with hate and murder threats from both Klebold
and the other killer, Eric Harris. Finally, Dykeman gave the
network a copy of the videogame Doom, which had been customized by
Harris to include especially violent images of death and gore. ABC
used the materials, along with the interview with Dykeman, on the
opening segment of ``Good Morning America'' last Monday. The
program labeled the segment on Dykeman a ``Good Morning America
exclusive.'' The network promoted it throughout the previous
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ABC can re-use the material anytime it chooses because it bought
the rights ``in perpetuity,'' according to Eileen Murphy, a
spokeswoman for ABC News. Ms. Ross said she planned to use some of
it again for a segment this Friday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine story has been a particularly competitive one for
news outlets with many of the school's students and parents
aggressively pursued for interviews. (The New York Times has also
sought to interview Dykeman.)
</P>
<P>
   For television news operations the Columbine story has taken on
some of the same elements that turned previous national news
events, like the O.J. Simpson trial, the Jon Benet Ramsey murder
case and the Clinton sex scandal, into the big story that generates
continuing viewer interest _ and reliable ratings. In such stories,
program producers seek to plumb every conceivable angle to keep
fresh elements on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The contention over the Columbine story is taking place at the
same time that the morning news shows have become the most
important area of competition among the network news divisions
because advertisers are pouring so much money into that time of
day. ``Today'' dominates the ratings in the morning hours, and in
recent months ABC has attempted to revive the sagging ``Good
Morning America'' by bringing in two of its most prominent news
anchors, Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson. Ms. Ross joined the
program at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   She said the program first interviewed Dykeman on April 30 but
felt it had only got part of his story. ``He was on our radar,''
she said. ``We felt there was more to get from him and we were so
hungry for any information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross said she did not find it unusual that Dykeman asked to
be paid. ``It was all business as usual,'' she said. ``I wouldn't
call it unusual.'' But one other morning news show producer said
that the purchase of material related to a news story was not
common at the morning programs, although it had become prevalent at
the prime-time news magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross, who had previously worked as a producer for ABC's
prime-time magazines ``Prime Time Live'' and ``20/20,'' said she
had purchased items like videos from sources in news cases on
numerous occasions, mainly, she said, when she was in charge of
much of ABC's coverage of the Simpson murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things came with rights fees a lot during that case,'' she
said. One example she cited: ABC bought some video scenes of Brian
``Kato'' Kaelin, one of the witnesses in the case, acting in what
she called ``a B-movie.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shapiro, the executive producer of ``Dateline NBC,'' said
buying material like this, though acceptable, is not routine.
Shapiro said the only routine purchase of video material would be
in the case of amateur video of events like tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, an executive with CBS News suggested that news magazine
programs do frequently buy photographs, letters and other materials
to illustrate certain stories. This executive said ABC's purchase
might be justified if the material was truly new and valuable in
adding to the story.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker of the ``Today'' show openly questioned the propriety of
the decision. He said, ``I can assure you we would never pay anyone
for anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that as far as every member of his staff could recall,
``Today'' had never paid an interview subject for related story
material.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross dismissed Zucker's criticism as the product of the
increasingly nasty competitiveness among the morning shows. ``I
think you can see what's going on with comments like that,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She also dismissed the charge that ABC should not have permitted
Dykeman to profit from his participation in the story. ``I'm not
judgmental,'' she said. ``Some people want money. It's a fact of
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
