<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA'S PARTY DWARFS THE OPPOSITION AS ELECTION NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOWETO, South Africa _ A political cartoon in South Africa shows
the front-running presidential candidate, Thabo Mbeki, dressed as
Snow White looming with an unconcerned smile over seven miserable
dwarfs who represent the opposition parties _ labeled Grumpy,
Shorty, Whiny, Crazy, Bully, Murky and Choppy.
</P>
<P>
   They are a colorful lot. ``Grumpy'' depicts the
often-cantankerous Zulu Chief Mangosuthu Gatsha Buthelezi;
``Crazy'' is Gen. Constand Viljoen, still pining for an Afrikaner
homeland; ``Bully'' is Louis Luyt, a fertilizer magnate turned
rugby czar who has been fighting with the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choppy'' is the Rev. Stanley Mogoba, a Methodist bishop who
has advocated chopping off the hands _ and other body parts _ of
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But all seven together may not collect one-third of the vote in
South Africa's second post-apartheid national elections on
Wednesday. Black South Africans _ more than 75 percent of the
population _ have largely remained loyal to President Nelson
Mandela's African National Congress, which has, in a snappish
election season, repeatedly reminded voters that it was their
liberator.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can the National Party call themselves new?'' Mbeki,
Mandela's heir-apparent, recently said about the party that created
apartheid, but now calls itself multiracial. ``Some of the members
of the NNP have got gray hair, some have got bald heads, some of
them have big stomachs, some carry walking sticks, but they call
themselves new.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the governing party held its final campaign rally here
Sunday _ five years after South Africa's first all-race election _
the struggle for freedom was still the dominant theme. Riding
together into the stadium here in a white golf cart, Mandela and
Mbeki, his deputy president, reminded the more than 80,000 black
South Africans in attendance that it would still take time to erase
the harm caused by the past.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the ``long, hard path to arrive here,'' Mandela urged
them to vote ``to continue the struggle to overcome 300 years of
white domination.'' He drew tumultuous cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Though polls indicate that black South Africans are very
concerned about growing unemployment and a crime rate that is among
the highest in the world, they also indicate that the majority of
blacks have decided to give the governing party at least another
five years to address those problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even the retirement of the 80-year-old _ and still much beloved
_ Mandela does not faze the party's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mandela or Mbeki, it is the same,'' said Gail Bokaba, 31, who
attended the rally Sunday. ``The ANC is an investment in our
future. It is for our children. They will make things right. They
need more time.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the party's campaign has combined emphasizing
accomplishments with admitting some failures. Audiences have heard
over and over about the number of new houses, electric lines,
telephone poles, water taps, health clinics and school feeding
programs put in place in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of you can challenge the statement that whites have been
in this country for more than three centuries, and no government
has ever achieved the progress this government has achieved,''
Mandela often says.
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki and Mandela have admitted _ and deplored _ corruption
in the new government, acknowledged huge unmet needs and promised
speedier change in the future. The polls indicate that their
strategy has worked.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the year, the party _ which won 62.5 percent of
the vote in 1994 _ was getting ratings of about 53 percent. By last
week, the polls indicated the party is still gaining votes and
could well get 67 percent of the vote _ enough even to change the
constitution, though Mbeki has said he has no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has a parliamentary system in which the voters
select a party rather than individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition parties, which in some cases have attacked each
other as much as the governing party, have essentially only
redivided their slice of the pie. The big loser appears to be the
National Party, which won about 20 percent of the vote in 1994,
getting the bulk of the white and mixed-race vote.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not expected to get more than 10 percent this time and
it may be locked in a battle for the official opposition spot with
the once-tiny, liberal, always anti-apartheid Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   When former President F.W. de Klerk retired from the National
Party in 1997, the party elected Martinus van Schalkwyk to be its
leader. But at age 37 and nicknamed ``short pants'' by his enemies,
he lacks charisma and de Klerk's stature. He has tried to sell his
party as the one that knows how to run things. But the party,
inexperienced in opposition politics, has hardly been a force in
the last five years _ and polls indicate its support is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Most of its votes seem to be going to the Democratic Party,
which has the pugnacious slogan ``The Guts to Fight Back,'' and a
rapier-tongued leader, Tony Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate Leon is gaining support from conservative
Afrikaners. Some of them have apparently come to believe that the
party's support of federalism and vocal criticism of government _
even though it holds only seven of the 400 seats in Parliament _
may be their best protection.
</P>
<P>
   The Zulu nationalist party, the Inkatha Freedom Party, won about
8 percent of the vote in 1994, after fighting a long and bloody
civil war against the African National Congress in the
KwaZulu/Natal province. The party leader, Buthelezi, has since been
wooed by the African National Congress and allowed to stand in as
president when both Mandela and Mbeki are out of the country. He
has not seemed to show much enthusiasm for campaigning this time
around, and polls indicate his party might get only 4 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The upstart United Democratic Movement appears likely to get 3
to 5 percent of the vote. It was started by Bantu Holomisa, a
former governing party official thrown out of the party for
insubordination, and Roelf Meyer, a former National Party official
who was pushed out for advocating more change than the party's old
guard wanted to hear about.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the African National Congress' most blistering attacks
have been aimed at this party, which has cut into the governing
party's support _ particularly in the Eastern Cape province, where
Mandela and Mbeki were born. Holomisa is a former leader of an
apartheid-era homeland _ an area marked out for blacks _ and he
used to offer governing party leaders shelter there.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, Mandela has been warning supporters to beware of
``former employees of the apartheid regime.'' Both men have spent
the last few weeks shoring up their support in that province.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the dwarfs are not expected to get more than a
percentage point each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
