<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-BOOKSTORE-NYT &LR;      05-30 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BOOKSTORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL BOOKSTORE NOT BOUND BY ITS WALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GAYLE FELDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What was Sebastian Junger, best-selling author of ``The Perfect
Storm,'' doing in a high school gymnasium in Greenwich, Conn.,
filled with 500 children?
</P>
<P>
   First, feeling ``nervous,'' since he had not been near that many
teen-agers since he was one himself. Second, sharing a podium with
Linda Greenlaw, a fishing boat captain featured in his book, whose
own memoir, ``Hungry Ocean,'' has just been published.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, he was being party to the kind of creative
marketing that an independent bookstore must mount if it is to
survive in a business increasingly dominated by discount stores,
warehouse clubs, chains and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A report to be published Tuesday by the Book Industry Study
Group, a nonprofit research organization, shows that in 1998,
independents represented only 16.6 percent of outlets where books
are sold, down from 21.6 percent in 1994, and falling.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by Junger and Ms. Greenlaw to the students of
Brunswick Academy and its sister school, Greenwich Academy _ and
their speaking engagement before 200 adults later that day at the
Indian Harbor Yacht Club down the road _ had been arranged by an
independent bookseller, Warren Cassell. His quid pro quo was to
have already sold each of those 500 children a copy of Junger's
book as enrichment reading. Although Ms. Greenlaw's book was
published too late for that, by day's end it had sold 135 copies.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not all. Cassell has arranged with Brunswick to
provide speakers and books on a continuing basis. The school
benefits because it gets top-of-the-line speakers for free. Cassell
benefits because he will sell at least 500 copies of each book.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Just Books, Cassell's store in tony Greenwich,
seems an unlikely font for marketing wisdom. It is a hole in the
wall without armchairs, with cramped, poorly lighted aisles and
water-damaged ceilings and walls. The kind of comfortable,
coffee-selling bookstore people have come to take for granted in
the 1990s it definitely is not.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with annual sales running about $850,000 for 600 square feet
of selling space, Cassell is doing something right. This is
recognized by the major publishers, who are clamoring to feed him
their best authors for events. What Cassell and thriving
independent retailers like him have succeeded in doing
``brilliantly,'' said the president of Time Warner Inc.'s trade
publishing operation, Maureen Egen, is ``to take the store out to
the public and cater to their tastes and interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine times a year, Cassell organizes literary breakfasts at a
nearby hotel. On May 27, almost 800 people paid $18 each to hear
George Stephanopoulos, John Feinstein and Dan Rather while downing
their coffee.
</P>
<P>
   They also bought 425 books. In September, the best-selling
authors Frank McCourt and Dava Sobel will have their hot buttered
toast alongside their hot-off-the-press books; in October, it will
be George Bush's turn. Not every author is so A-list: If Cassell
really believes in a book, he has been known to sneak an unknown
author onto a panel.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Brockett, publicity director at Junger's hard-cover
publisher, W.W. Norton, and Jennifer Landers, her equivalent at Ms.
Greenlaw's publisher, Hyperion, a unit of Walt Disney, point to
other variations on the theme. For example, when a customer buys a
ticket to a literary lunch or breakfast organized by Elaine
Petrocelli, owner of Book Passage in Corte Madera, Calif., the
ticket price includes a signed copy of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell, meanwhile, who says he has lost 15 to 20 percent of his
total business to the Internet the last 18 months, is busy making
it up on that front as well. The store's Web site, which is updated
every two weeks, and a monthly newsletter, mailed to 7,000
customers, keep the breakfasts humming to capacity, along with
events at the Garden Education Center, a yacht club and a
synagogue. He also does a brisk Internet business in signed copies,
collectibles and out-of-print searches.
</P>
<P>
   How does he keep costs down? Cassell has four computers, but
only 3,500 books in his store. ``We consider the wholesalers our
inventory,'' he said, as his phone rang on a recent Friday with
customers requesting titles.
</P>
<P>
   They would get them the following Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
