<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONORARY-DEGREES-2TAK     05-30 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONORARY-DEGREES-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORARY DEGREES GRANTED FOR DIVERSE REASONS TO DIVERSE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Calif., Fla., Ill., Ga., Md., Mass., N.Y., Pa., Texas,
Va.) (rk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson had strong opinions about what a university
ought and ought not to do. One was that it should not grant
honorary degrees. Founder of the University of Virginia, Jefferson
feared that its board might get carried away with political or
religious enthusiasms rather than choose a recipient based on
scholarly considerations. To this day, the University of Virginia
gives no honorary degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia is unusual. To receive their highest award, many
colleges and universities line up a stage full of high achievers at
commencement day _ actors, authors, government officials, business
executives and, to be sure, scholars.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this commencement season, Elizabeth Dole will have
received 40 honorary degrees. By his library's last count, December
1996, President Bush had been given 30; his son, the Texas
governor, has but four. Quincy Jones, the music impresario who
received honors this month from the University of Miami, New York
University and Tuskegee University, has 15. Historian Arthur
Schlesinger Jr. received his 27th on Friday, from the City
University of New York Graduate Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby, one of the all-time favorite honorary degree
recipient, doesn't even know how many he has, said his spokesman,
David Brokaw, who guessed more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``The honorary doctorate _ that's lovely, he enjoys getting
them,'' said Brokaw, noting that Cosby had actually earned a
doctorate in education from the University of Massachusetts. ``But
what's important to him is getting the podium so he can say
something profound and funny to the students and their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   To the university, the honorary degree is a way to recognize
achievements of people respected within the institution as well to
add glitter to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they are used to reward donors who have given money;
sometimes they are used to draw celebrities to make the graduation
special,'' said Arthur E. Levine, president of Teachers College at
Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the university secured its usual well-calculated mix:
Muhammad Ali, Noam Chomsky, Tito Puente and Julie Taymor, along
with two scientists, an engineer and a historian whose names are
less well known on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always viewed it as a last lesson a college can teach, by
showing examples of people who most represent the values the
institution stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   The honorary degree is also a useful way to enhance a
relationship with someone who can benefit the university. This
month Georgia State University honored J. Mack Robinson, who last
fall gave $10 million to its College of Business. Chapman
University in Orange, Calif., awarded an honorary degree to author
John Fowles after he agreed to let them create a writing center and
literary festival in his name.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the only condition is that the recipient show up, don a
robe and sit on a platform for a few hours _ and sometimes the
university will waive even that requirement. Last September,
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa became one of only three
people to receive an honorary degree from Harvard University at a
time other than commencement. The other two were George Washington
and Winston Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Honorary doctorates, in categories from letters to law to fine
arts, have little function other than being, well, an honor. But
the custom of bestowing them is centuries old, one that American
colleges borrowed from their English forbears.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At Oxford, the ceremony at which they are granted is known as
the ``encaenia,'' a Greek word meaning festival of renewal, and
calls for the honorees to be introduced in Latin. American
ceremonies are less formal and citations more chatty _ and usually
in English.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1753, Benjamin Franklin was big, receiving honorary
degrees from both Harvard and Yale, according to John S. Brubacher
and Willis Rudy, authors of ``Higher Education in Transition''
(Transaction Publishers, 1997). They wrote that nearly 200
different kinds of honorary degrees were granted between 1870 and
1939, including the DFF _ a doctor of fortitude and faith.
</P>
<P>
   When William Barton Rogers, a former University of Virginia
faculty member, founded the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
in 1861, he brought with him the opposition to honorary degrees
inherited from Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Institute honored Winston Churchill in 1949, James
R. Killian, MIT's president designate, invited him to be ``an
honorary member of the company of scholars which is MIT,'' since he
could not give him an honorary degree.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Chicago ran into a similar problem when Edward
H. Levi, then dean of the law school, invited the Queen of England
to receive an honorary degree. But when he presented the idea to
the faculty, it asked to review her scholarly accomplishments and
turned her down.
</P>
<P>
   Levi had to withdraw the invitation, but years later, he laughed
about it, saying proudly that Chicago never gave honorary degrees
to ``businessmen or famous personalities as a way of currying
favor,'' only to people who had made contributions to knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Salinger, an alumnus of Ursinus College in Collegeville,
Pa., is one recipient who turned down an invitation. He did write
back, said John Strassburger, president of Ursinus. He was
flattered but it violated his principles.
</P>
<P>
   Most people, however, are happy to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very complimentary, especially for someone who majored in
cafeteria in high school,'' said Larry Gelbart, who wrote the
television series ``MASH'' and the Broadway musical ``A Funny Thing
Happened on the Way to the Forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelbart never went to college but received an honorary degree
from Hofstra University on Long Island this year _ his second.
``It's awfully good for the ego,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Catharine R. Stimpson, dean of the Graduate School of Arts and
Science at New York University, who is receiving her 12th honorary
degree next month, from Santa Clara University, says she still
feels thrilled every time she receives an invitation. But she also
views it as recognition of the fields she works in, including
women's studies and gender studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always aware of that fact that this is not just Catharine
R. Stimpson who is receiving an award,'' she said, ``but that I am
a symbolic figure and it represents the work of many other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also perks. ``You get the hood, which is very cool,''
said Bill Nye, host of PBS's ``Science Guy,'' who received honorary
doctorates from Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and Goucher
College in Baltimore this commencement season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John E. Brooks, president emeritus of Holy Cross
University, recalls how in 1983 Joe DiMaggio was so moved by the
honor that he broke down in tears and asked if he could keep the
rented gown he had worn at Holy Cross' commencement.
</P>
<P>
   But if most recipients relish the degrees, the same cannot be
said of the college officials who have to line them up _ especially
at less well-known institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for small colleges,'' said Levine, who recalled
that as president of Bradford College, a small liberal arts college
in Massachusetts, he had to be creative. One year, the college
honored people in the local community. ``The day after
commencement, you start trying to line up the ones for next year,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Old Dominion University in Norfolk, Va., has already started
thinking ahead. Its recipient for May 6, 2000, is Fred McFeely
Rogers, the children's television show host. For Mister Rogers, the
honor will be No. 36.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
