<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6727 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-WEALTH-ART-3     05-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-WEALTH-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISE OF THE PAPER MILLIONAIRES OF SILICON ALLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By AMY HARMON 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was something about the wave of unrepentant
jubilance sweeping through iVillage downtown Manhattan offices the
day the 31/2-year-old Internet company went public that made Susan
Weaver uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   As employees who had been allowed to buy stock for as little as
$6 per share watched it climb to $103 in its first afternoon of
public trading, Ms. Weaver _ at 46, an elder in a company whose
average hire is 31 _ addressed a cigar-wielding group gathered in
the hall. ``I just want everyone to realize this is Disneyland,''
she remembers saying that day in March.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weaver, iVillage's vice president for programming and a
former NBC producer, later explained: ``I didn't want them to feel
that they were entitled to what was happening to them. This doesn't
happen all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, it didn't used to. Particularly not in New York, where
the cluster of new-media companies known as Silicon Alley has
always been viewed by its Western namesake as an also-ran in
innovation and wealth creation.
</P>
<P>
   But since March, with Wall Street's valuing infant Internet
companies that have never made a profit in the same range as
automakers and airlines, Silicon Alley has witnessed initial public
offerings at the rate of one a week. And as investor fervor for
Internet companies threatens to fade, the sprint for IPOs, as the
offerings are known, has only picked up speed.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Internet stocks faltered last week _ iVillage, for
example, lost almost 10 percent of its value in one day _ three New
York-based companies launched themselves on the public market to a
respectable reception. And shares of StarMedia Networks, the most
highly anticipated of last week's offerings, closed 74 percent
above its initial offering price of $15 per share on Wednesday, its
first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable, it's surreal _ it's good, I guess, would be
the sound bite,'' said Fernando Espeula, 32, who three years ago
created StarMedia, which provides Internet access in Latin America.
The IPO, he said, has made him worth $162 million on paper. ``Wow,
that's the first time I've said it out loud. It's kind of weird.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet boom has created as many as a thousand paper
millionaires among the founders and executives of Silicon Alley
companies, said Uri Kaufthal, the president of AST StockPlan, which
administers the stock benefit packages for several of them. Many
junior employees among Silicon Alley's more than 100,000 workers
have collected enough to pay off student loans or consider buying
an apartment, maybe even in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where the well-worn paths to success have led through
the trading floor or the ranks of large media corporations, the
emergence of sudden Internet-bred wealth holds out the promise of
much quicker rewards. It is exposing New Yorkers to the Silicon
Valley culture of entrepreneurial risk. And it is prompting
resentment, envy and a scramble to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us had friends on Wall Street who always made so damn
much money,'' said Sunny Bates, an executive recruiter for New
York-based Internet firms. ``Now you can make a lot of money and
you don't have to be an investment banker. Everybody wants to get
on the train.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Silicon Alley is not embracing the IPO lifestyle without
a healthy dose of apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the seeming arbitrariness of who is getting rich
and exactly how rich they are getting can be disconcerting, even
for those who are now buying BMWs to go with their Palm Pilots.
Those at start-ups that have yet to issue a prospectus wonder
whether their chance will come before it is too late. Workers in
the Internet divisions of traditional media companies yearn for
their operations to be spun off and taken public.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, veterans of other industries worry that a generation
is emerging with the expectation that working late nights for a
couple of years at the right company should make them set for
retirement. And among some early denizens of the Alley, many of
whom started out with the conviction that technology could
democratize society and create new modes of expression, there is a
sense of loss as talk turns from changing the world to when their
options vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a sense that we were on the cusp of a
significant change that was at once economic and cultural,'' said
Jason Chervokas, the editor of (at)NewYork, an industry newsletter
that was recently bought by MecklerMedia. ``But the original idea,
which was, hey, let's build a medium with a new hip, gender-neutral
image, has fallen by the wayside, and I regret that, I really do.
The sense that you're allowed to experiment has been replaced by
pressure for quarterly results.''
</P>
<P>
   For Alley veterans and newcomers alike, it can be hard getting
used to running into 20-year-old millionaires at parties in
downtown lofts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around this kind of gargantuan `monetizing' day in, day
out _ it warps your mind,'' Marisa Bowe, the editor of the online
magazine Word, wrote in a recent essay in The New York Observer
about watching her Silicon Alley friends cash in. ``Just a few
years ago, we were dance or literature majors, actors with day
jobs. Now we live in a strange world where it seems as if every
10th person has won the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But for bystanders, the logic of IPO winnings is somehow harder
to swallow than the luck of the lottery. Paul Debraccio, who spent
15 years selling advertising at the magazine publisher Conde Nast
before doing the same at a lower salary for an Internet firm,
Tripod Inc., says some of his former colleagues have a hard time
understanding how he has come to be bidding on real estate in the
Hamptons this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person just can't conceive that in two or three
years you can become a millionaire without having started your own
company,'' said Debraccio, whose options in Tripod were converted
to stock worth over $1.5 million when the company was sold to New
York-based Lycos Inc. last year. ``The ones who do understand it
call me looking for jobs or advice. At Conde Nast, the most you
could make is $500,000 a year, and that's if you were a
publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Debraccio is now the senior vice president for advertising at
Uproar, an Internet games company in New York that trades on the
Vienna exchange but may soon offer shares in the United States. As
is typical for Internet company employees, he accepted a lower
salary in exchange for stock options. ``Part of it is about riding
the money wave,'' he said. ``This is probably going to turn out
good as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, the editor of the online financial news service
thestreet.com, is less sanguine about his paper wealth, which
hovers around $9 million and has in recent days served as a
somewhat obsessive topic of conversation in The Wall Street
Journal's newsroom, where he used to be a reporter. (On May 11, the
day his company went public, Kansas received several e-mail
messages from former colleagues along these lines: ``Dave, I was
just going to lunch, but I'm a little short today. Do you think ...
'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sacrificed a lot over the last three years,'' said
Kansas, 32. ``Can I value it at $9 million? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even the biggest evangelists of the Internet wealth
culture wax insecure about its scale _ and its future. That is in
part because federal regulations require that institutional
investors and senior executives hold onto their stock for six
months after the initial public offering. (Junior employees are not
subject to those restrictions.) Moreover, stock options that are
granted to employees typically vest over a four-year period, so
just how rich somebody is depends on how many options he actually
owns and whether the stock price holds up until he can exercise
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Monopoly money. I don't count it,'' said Fred Wilson, a
co-founder of Flatiron Partners, the New York venture capital firm
that has financed several of the most successful Internet companies
to go public lately, including thestreet.com, theglobe.com and
StarMedia. ``You can watch your value go up and down millions a day
and you can't do anything about it. It's surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   The giddy tone at many of the city's cyber-celebrations and the
frequency with which new-media employees check the company stock
price underscores the anxiety that their net worth is housed within
a speculative bubble that is destined to pop. It is a fear that
plagues the industry well beyond New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, to make a gazillion dollars in the computer
business you had to have a good product, and there was pretty clear
evidence about what made it good _ i.e., people bought it,'' said
Jonathan Weber, the editor of the Industry Standard, a trade
publication that follows the Internet economy. ``The Internet boom
and the IPO phenomenon is so speculative that what separates
certain companies from the pack is not always that obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many who have benefited even modestly from the boom
remember when their friends and families scoffed at their choice to
forsake more traditional careers for this strange thing known as
the Internet. They do not quite see why the risk of their own
opportunities should be deemed less worthy of reward than the
risks, say, that investment bankers take with other people's money.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Kate Hanley's starting salary at iVillage in 1996
was $15,000 less than the book editing job she was offered at
Fairchild Communications. But as one of the first 30 employees of
the company, a provider of online information and discussion forums
for women, she was granted 333 stock options at $6 per share.
(iVillage's shares closed Friday at $47.875 _ less than half the
price attained on the day it went public but still a healthy
premium for Ms. Hanley's options, three-quarters of which have
vested. She has not cashed them in.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hanley was also given ``friends and family'' options, which
allow employees and others designated by the management team to buy
stock at the initial offering price. The proceeds from that stock,
which Ms. Hanley bought at $24 and sold at the opening price of
$95, netting her about $25,000, served as a down payment for the
Chelsea apartment that she moved into this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``People act as though I found this money in a bag on the
street,'' said Ms. Hanley, 29, a producer for iVillage's computing
site. ``It's like, where were you when I was working for the last
three years till 9 or 10 at night and on weekends?''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Hanley's friend Annie Rhodes, 28, who works at
ToggleThis, another Internet company three blocks away, the
iVillage public offering was bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they went public, I was sort of kicking myself,' '' said
Ms. Rhodes, who left iVillage two years ago and missed out on
cashing in. ``But it's also exciting. Until you know people who
have hit it big with options, it doesn't really seem real. Now it
seems like ... it's not a joke. This could happen to us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Filled with that sense of promise, business school students who
used to head straight to the finance courses that would get them to
Goldman Sachs are packing into the electronic commerce class at
Columbia and oversubscribing the entrepreneurial course at New York
University.
</P>
<P>
   Those with MBA's are not the only ones to be drawn by the
prospect of entrepreneurial freedom and fabulous wealth. Ken
Perlin, a professor of computer science and the director of the
Media Research Laboratory at New York University, said the Internet
boom had changed the orientation of his students, particularly
since Yahoo bought Webcal, the Web calendar that one of the
laboratory students developed, for $12 million in stock last July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people in this field think they should be millionaires,
and that's a new phenomenon,'' Perlin said. ``The concern is that
it's deceptive. I know a number of students who tried to make a go
of it and it didn't work. And it wasn't fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there is angst or self-loathing among some of those who
have tried their hands in Silicon Alley, Jeff Dachis, a co-founder
of Razorfish, an Internet services company that went public April
27, does not share it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be lumped in with the hucksters of the world,
because we have the real deal,'' said Dachis, 32, who bought a BMW
5-series as an IPO gift to himself. ``I feel completely and utterly
entitled to whatever success comes our way. Not everybody's good,
not everybody has the winning idea, not every idea deserves to be
funded or to be public. I'm sorry, but there are sheep and there
are shepherds, and I fancy myself to be the latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Zolli, the vice president of the interactive division of
the advertising firm Siegal &AMP; Gale, said he spent a week of
sleepless nights pondering his past and future after watching
friends and former colleagues at Razorfish make millions this
month. Finally, though, he came to peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job, and ultimately I believe this is still the most
important medium of the next half century, and our ultimate judge
is not the size of our bank accounts,'' said Zolli, 28. ``When this
insanity passes, what will matter is who had the really good ideas
and good work. I really believe that.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
