<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-NYT &LR;      05-30 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 TOP COUNSEL AT MORGAN STANLEY REPORTEDLY WAS AWARE OF PAYMENT TO
INFORMANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The general counsel of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
learned of an in-house lawyer's decision to pay $10,000 to an
informant involved in the arrest of a former employee shortly
before the payment was made, according to people close to the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Christine A. Edwards, the general counsel, was told about the
payment to Charles Joseph Luethke, the informant, just hours before
a wire transfer was completed. She did not try to stop it, this
person said, largely because she had only fragmentary knowledge of
Luethke and his role in the police sting operation against the
former employee, Christian L. Curry, last August.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Morgan Stanley called the payment a ``mistake in
judgment'' and suspended with pay Monroe R. Sonnenborn, a managing
director, and Carol Bernheim, an experienced litigator, pending the
completion of an internal investigation. Both are senior officials
in the firm's legal department who had extensive dealings with
Luethke during July and August last year. Both report to Ms.
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Luethke was cooperating with Morgan Stanley and the
New York Police Department to catch Curry conspiring to plant
racist e-mail messages on the firm's computer system to buttress a
discrimination suit against the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney is conducting a criminal
investigation of Morgan Stanley's payment to Luethke. The district
attorney's office is examining why the firm did not notify
prosecutors of the payment to an informant who had an important
role in the Curry arrest. Luethke is also under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Records of communications within Morgan Stanley provide ``rock
solid'' evidence that Ms. Edwards was told about the payment to
Luethke only a short time before the wire transfer was sent on Aug.
26, 1998, said the person, who agreed to speak only if he was not
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards had earlier received a telephone message from
Luethke, whom she did not know, demanding payment for the services
he provided the firm in connection with the Curry arrest. She made
inquiries about Luethke and found out that Sonnenborn had already
committed Morgan Stanley to pay him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not saying that Edwards could not have stopped the
payment. But she learned of it only after the commitment had been
made. Monty made the commitment, and he does not dispute that,''
the person said, referring to Sonnenborn.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenborn did not return phone calls seeking comment. Ms.
Edwards could not be reached for comment over the long holiday
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's decision late last week to punish Sonnenborn
and Ms. Bernheim for the payment rankled some fellow executives at
the firm. People close to Sonnenborn say he is furious about being
singled out for blame.
</P>
<P>
   A managing director who has been at Morgan Stanley for about 15
years, Sonnenborn was clearly the point man in dealing with
Luethke, people close to the firm said. But he was also cautious.
</P>
<P>
   For example, just before paying $10,000 to Luethke, Sonnenborn
sought legal advice from one of Morgan Stanley's outside law firms,
Davis, Polk &AMP; Wardwell, the people said.
</P>
<P>
   The advice did not dissuade him from making the payment. The
interaction indicates that Sonnenborn did not cavalierly commit the
firm to pay Luethke.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very unhappy about this being hung on Monty,'' one
Morgan Stanley executive who did not have a personal role in the
Luethke payment said. ``He's not a cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards has been general counsel for Morgan Stanley since
1997, when the white-shoe investment bank merged with Dean Witter,
the mass-market retail brokerage house. Ms. Edwards had served as
Dean Witter's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley has not officially identified Sonnenborn and Ms.
Bernstein as the two suspended legal officers. Nor has the firm
stated why the two were singled out for suspension. Asked whether
any other executives knew about the firm's relationship with
Luethke or about the $10,000 payment, a Morgan Stanley spokeswoman
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the firm has clearly drawn the line of responsibility
outside the doors of the executive suite. Philip J. Purcell,
chairman and chief executive, and John J. Mack, the president,
issued a statement Thursday disavowing knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If either of us had known about Luethke's request for money,
no payment would ever have been made,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke disputes Morgan Stanley's version of its relationship
with him. In an interview, he insisted that top Morgan Stanley
executives were aware of negotiations with him both before and
after Curry's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke, a 29-year-old native of Haworth, N.J., who is not now
employed full-time, said the firm dangled the prospect of full-time
employment and consulting and money-management arrangements to
induce him to cooperate with the police sting operation against
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke had known Curry since 1993, when they were both
attending Columbia University. It was Luethke who first brought to
Morgan Stanley's attention what he described as Curry's plan to
plant fake e-mail on the firm's computers. He later played a role
in the elaborate police undercover operation against the former
employee.
</P>
<P>
   After Curry's arrest, Luethke made a series of phone calls to
top executives at the firm. Luethke said those calls were to
discuss the terms of a business contract with the firm. People
close to Morgan Stanley said Luethke repeatedly demanded the
$10,000 payment for services he provided.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the $10,000 payment was wired, Luethke made
phone calls to the direct lines of Purcell, Ms. Edwards, Sonnenborn
and Ms. Bernheim, telephone records show. The records show
completed calls from Luethke's home telephone, but do not reveal
the length of the calls. Luethke declined to say whether he spoke
to the executives in question or only left messages for them.
</P>
<P>
   But the person close to Morgan Stanley said Luethke's account of
his communications with the firm was distorted. This person
acknowledges that Ms. Edwards received a vague message ``from
someone named Luethke wanting his money.'' But she had no idea at
the time who Luethke was. The person said Purcell also had no
knowledge of Luethke and never received messages or other
communications from him.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after Ms. Edwards followed up by asking Sonnenborn
about Luethke's demand for payment that she learned of the
commitment that Sonnenborn had made to pay the informant for his
services. At that point, this person said, it was not considered
prudent to renege on a commitment the firm had made.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke has played a cat-and-mouse game with the firm ever since
the payment was made. He says he never withdrew the $10,000 from
the third-party account to which it was wired, and that he offered
to return it. He insisted in a letter he sent to Morgan Stanley,
addressed to Purcell, that without the full business contract he
sought, the payment for services in the Curry arrest might be
illegal. The letter is dated Sept. 29, 1998, a month after the
$10,000 payment.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Morgan Stanley said they now believed that
Luethke intended to use the $10,000 payment as leverage to get a
great deal more money from the firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
