<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit filed against IRL, track
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Attorneys representing the estate of a man killed
during an open-wheel automobile race at Lowe's Motor Speedway in
Concord, N.C., filed a lawsuit Friday against the track's owners,
the Indy Racing League and Lowe's president H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Mobley, 41, an electrician from Statesville, N.C., and a
native of Albany, was one of three spectators killed at Lowe's on
May 1 when a wheel and other debris flew into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The accident came less than a year after three fans were killed
during a CART race at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to the attorneys in Michigan and we've agreed to
put the whole industry on trial,'' said Robert Beauchamp, an
attorney representing Mobley's three children, who live in Cairo,
Ga. ``Between Michigan and the VisionAire 500, why didn't they do
anything to improve safety? Six people shouldn't have to die to
change something.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports Inc. owns Lowe's and three other tracks
that stage IRL races, including Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims that the defendants contributed to the deaths
by allowing Indy cars to race on the high-banked, 1.5-mile oval,
and by failing to erect higher catch fences around the track. Since
the accident, SMI has decided to raise fences to 21 feet from 15
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also alleges that SMI and the IRL are negligent for
failing to require the wheels and suspension parts to be tethered
or secured to the car bodies. Officials also said this week that
the IRL would begin to require tethers. The suit also claims that
SMI, the IRL and Wheeler failed to notify fans of the ``potential
lethal risks'' associated with flying debris.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
