<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTUREFINDER-950(2TA     05-30 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTUREFINDER-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMCAST PUTS UP $3.75 MILLION FOR CULTUREFINDER.COM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Comcast Corp., a cable giant with diverse holdings
that include stakes in the television and online versions of the
QVC shopping channel and E Entertainment Television, has added a
more highbrow investment to its portfolio: Culturefinder.com.
</P>
<P>
   Culturefinder is a Web site that lists arts events and sells
tickets to exhibits, operas, symphonies, dance and theatrical
performances around the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For Julian A. Brodsky, vice chairman of Comcast and chairman of
the six-month-old fund, Comcast Interactive Capital Group, that
announced the $3.75 million investment two weeks ago, the move was
part of his company's effort to ``leverage our involvement with the
Internet and create an investment hedge against the changing
relative values of content, commerce and distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   For Eugene Carr, the founder and chief executive of
Culturefinder.com, the investment by Comcast, which is based in
Philadelphia, represented even more: further validation of a
business that has enabled Carr to combine his entrepreneurial
impulses with a lifelong affinity for the performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, a cellist who studied at the Juilliard School of Music
while still in high school, earned an MBA at Columbia University.
He was the executive director of the New York-based American
Symphony Orchestra when he started Culturefinder.com in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I perceived that the Internet would be big, and so would
massive sites that collected around specific interests,'' he said
in an interview in Culturefinder's crowded offices, which are
situated, appropriately, near Carnegie Hall. ``I knew that someone
would do an arts site, and I thought it would be an incredible
opportunity to do it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After polling administrators of 50 arts groups to see if they
would support a site that listed their programs, Carr invested
$50,000 of his own to start Culturefinder.com. He also got $300,000
from America Online to participate in its Greenhouse project _ an
effort, since dropped, that backed content providers in their
infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Some other Web publishers, like the Sidewalk operation of
Microsoft Corp., list concerts and other performance arts. And
some, like Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch Inc., sell tickets. But
Culturefinder.com is the only national online directory of arts
events and seller of electronic tickets for more than 2,200
organizations in some 1,300 cities. The institutions, which vary
from the New Century Chamber Orchestra in Mill Valley, Calif., to
the New York Philharmonic, do not pay Culturefinder to be included
in the listings. Instead, much of Culturefinder's revenue comes
from the fees _ ranging from $2 to $4.50 _ it charges for each
ticket sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizations like Ticketmaster Online compete with
Culturefinder only on high-profile events,'' said James McQuivey,
senior analyst for Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
``Focusing on art and culture gives Culturefinder an extra market
Ticketmaster is not in.''
</P>
<P>
   In partnerships with the online retailers Amazon.com, CD Now,
Image Exchange and Reel, Culturefinder also peddles compact disks,
arts posters and videos. For patrons who might want to venture far
afield in search of a good scherzo, it has an alliance with
Microsoft's Expedia online travel agency. The site also offers
various articles, program notes and primers about the arts aimed at
its estimated 250,000 different visitors each month, an audience
that surveys indicate is two-thirds female, largely urban, highly
educated and, on average, 36 years old. That gives Culturefinder a
desirable demographic for its online advertisers, the largest of
which is Baldwin Piano and Organ Co.
</P>
<P>
   Carr and his staff of 14 ``bring passion, experience and an
intense focus on arts consumers and arts organizations,'' said
Brodsky, the Comcast executive. ``This, combined with superb
technology and the dramatically quick adoption of e-commerce among
upscale consumers, bodes well for Culturefinder's future.''
</P>
<P>
   To stimulate sales, Culturefinder.com recently reached ticket
sales-referral agreements with three other Web sites: the search
portal Lycos.com, America Online's city guide service
Digitalcity.com, and Ovationtv.com, the site of the arts-oriented
cable television network.
</P>
<P>
   As a privately held company, Culturefinder.com does not report
its financial results. But Carr said he expected revenue this year
of about $1.5 million and a loss that he declined to quantify. He
predicted that the company would become profitable as soon as 2001.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that institutions in the United States like those
represented by Culturefinder sell close to $3 billion worth of
tickets annually. But he said those organizations typically sell
only 70 percent of their available tickets _ representing an
opportunity for companies like his to help fill lots of empty
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Besides America Online and Comcast, a number of prominent
individual investors have put a total of $1.75 million in Carr's
venture. They include Arthur Zankel, a partner in First Manhattan,
a New York-based investment advisory firm, and a member of the
board of Carnegie Hall; Robert H. Lessin, whose privately held Wit
Capital Group specializes in Internet-related investments; Thomas
G. Stemberg, chairman and chief executive of Staples Inc.; Stuart
G. Moldaw, chairman of Gymboree, and David Horowitz, former chief
executive and president of MTV Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him money for the American Symphony Orchestra and had a
high opinion of what he accomplished with it,'' Zankel said. ``I
have great admiration for Gene's marketing skills and imagination,
and I haven't been disappointed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   David Kitto, director of marketing and ticket operations for
Carnegie Hall, said Culturefinder could help arts organizations of
all sizes expand their audiences, whether or not the arts groups
have their own Web sites. ``All of us are looking for ways to
connect with the audience,'' Kitto said. ``Culturefinder is not
competing with us; they're providing an alternate means to purchase
tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kitto's view, the biggest challenge Culturefinder now faces
is creating identity and brand awareness. ``They need to work to
become the place arts consumers go to to find out about ticket
availability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Carr wants Culturefinder.com to expand to include
arts listings outside the United States. And to generate new
commission income, he intends to begin offering special tour
packages late this year, like an individually tailored Broadway
weekend in New York with hotel accommodations, theater tickets,
meals and museum admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many Internet start-ups at this stage of business,
Culturefinder is not now destined to be sold or to issue stock in
an initial public offering, Carr said, though he does not rule this
out in the longer term. ``We've been very focused on raising the
venture capital round,'' he said, referring to the Comcast
infusion. ``At the appropriate moment, to raise additional funds,
every financing option will be considered _ including an IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, the Comcast money will help Culturefinder promote its
brand more actively, Carr said. ``I'm trying to be Mr. Arts in
cyberspace,'' he added, ``to be front and center so when
opportunities present themselves, I'm first in line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
