<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDIA WEB UNITS POSITIONED TO RIDE THE INTERNET WAVE
</P>
<P>
   Just as investor enthusiasm seemed to dampen for Internet
stocks, three media companies _ Tribune Co., The New York Times Co.
and the publishing company IDG, with an investment from CNN _ said
they would consolidate their Web businesses into Internet units,
complete with spinoff potential.
</P>
<P>
   How, when and whether these online divisions go public is
uncertain. But the prospect of getting high stock valuations for
such properties is obviously attractive, in part because
high-flying stocks can be used as currency in other deals. And the
reputation of well-known newspapers might help these new units
catch up and compete in an area where they trail broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE START-UP DRAWS INVESTORS
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer and Microsoft have invested in Digital
Entertainment Network, a start-up company developing youth-oriented
television programming for delivery over the Internet, as part of a
$26 million round of venture capital being announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   COMCAST ADDS CULTURE TO PORTFOLIO
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, the cable giant with diverse holdings that include
stakes in the television and online versions of the QVC shopping
channel and E Entertainment Television, has added a more highbrow
investment to its portfolio: Culturefinder.com, a Web site that
lists arts events and sells tickets to exhibits, operas,
symphonies, dance and theatrical performances. For Eugene Carr, the
founder and chief executive of Culturefinder, the $3.75 million
investment is further validation of a business that has enabled him
to combine his entrepreneurial impulses with a lifelong affinity
for the performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANCE SALES STRONG FOR TV ADS
</P>
<P>
   The sale of commercial time by the broadcast television networks
in advance for the fall season is ending on an even stronger note
than optimistic forecasts had predicted. Based on current
estimates, the six broadcast networks will sell $7 billion to $7.2
billion worth of commercial time during the prime-time programs in
the 1999-2000 season, about 9 percent higher than the $6.4 billion
sold ahead of the 1998-99 prime-time season.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKSHOPS COMPETE CREATIVELY
</P>
<P>
   To compete with the giant book-selling chains and Internet
retailers, independent bookstores like Just Books in Greenwich,
Conn., are marketing themselves creatively through events like
speeches by authors at local schools and literary breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE-EDGED SWORD OF DISCOUNTS
</P>
<P>
   As e-commerce sites sell goods at a loss to attract customers
and build a brand name, it is no surprise that consumers expect the
Web to be an around-the-clock fire sale. But that sense of consumer
entitlement could come back to haunt companies that rely too
heavily on discount pricing. Analysts and executives say that
unless Web retailers find other sources of revenue, such as
advertising, there is simply no way to sustain a viable business
without building a profit margin into most sales.
</P>
<P>
   HUGHES `BIOGRAPHY' FINALLY IN PRINT
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Irving, who was imprisoned for 17 months in connection
with his creation of a bogus biography of Howard Hughes in 1972, is
selling a newly edited version of that rejected manuscript, now
billed as an ``imaginative biography,'' through a start-up Internet
publisher called Terrificbooks.com. The company, based in Santa Fe,
N.M., sells books directly to customers online.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   All financial markets and banks in the United States are closed
Monday in observance of Memorial Day. Most markets overseas,
however, are open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
