<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT &LR;      05-30 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANES HIT MAJOR BRIDGE; CIVILIAN DEATHS REPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Pa.)  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-BRIDGE) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four NATO warplanes bombed a major bridge in
southern Serbia Sunday, as the alliance seized on clear skies to
intensify daytime bombing raids across Yugoslavia, allied officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said that at least nine people
were killed and 28 wounded in the attack on the bridge in Varvarin,
110 miles south of Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital. Four NATO planes
apparently struck the bridge once, and then struck it again.
Reports from the scene said civilians had gathered at the bridge
between the attacks to help others who had been wounded.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials said that pilots saw no civilians and that
they could not confirm any casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a major line of communication for the Serb army and
was a legitimate military target,'' a NATO official in Brussels,
Belgium, said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the nine-week air war, a NATO fighter-bomber
destroyed a passenger train crossing a bridge when the pilot
spotted the moving train too late to break off the attack. In a
second incident earlier this month, NATO said one of its missiles
accidentally hit a bus in Kosovo but insisted the bridge it was
crossing was a legitimate military target.
</P>
<P>
   These and other bombing mishaps that killed civilians forced
NATO to tighten the rules of engagement for its pilots. ``If
there's any question in the pilots' minds, they won't strike the
bridge,'' the NATO official said. ``They did not see any civilians
when they executed this strike.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the bridge followed a third consecutive night in
which NATO warplanes took advantage of good weather to fly more
than 300 attack missions. Overnight, allied jets flew 309 bombing
runs against tanks, mortars, anti-aircraft radars and airfields.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon Sunday in Varvarin, four allied fighter-bombers
attacked the bridge, dropping precision-guided bombs in two passes
in a six-minute raid, the NATO official said. According to one
report, the official said, bystanders came onto the bridge after
the first attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no way a guy flying at X-thousand feet, at a
pretty good clip, will be able to pick out individuals or warn
them,'' the NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing attacks on civilian infrastructure, like electric
power grids that operate hospitals and water-pumping stations, as
well as civilian casualties, have prompted some NATO allies like
Italy and Greece to call for a moratorium in the air campaign, as
an incentive for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to meet
NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO's military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, on Sunday
strongly opposed that approach. ``I don't think it's either a
bombing pause or diplomacy,'' Clark said on CNN's ``Late Edition.''
``I think it's the opposite. I think it's the bombing that is
impelling the diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark continued, ``Any bombing pause now will give the Serbs a
chance to continue their campaign against some 500,000-plus Kosovar
Albanians that are still inside Kosovo. It will give them a chance
to reconstitute and refit their forces. It will raise the risk to
our NATO pilots when we resume operations over Kosovo. So from a
military perspective it's a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NATO's political body authorized Clark to expand the
bombing to attack telephone networks as a way of bedeviling
Yugoslav military computers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NATO's claims that the bombing is wearing down
Milosevic's forces, especially in Kosovo, allied commanders
acknowledged again Sunday that there were no signs of surrender
from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NATO conceded that the Yugoslav military continues to
repair damaged runways and replace troops and equipment destroyed
by the bombing. A NATO spokesman said Sunday that the 203rd
battalion operating northwest of Nis had replaced some of its
damaged artillery units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the Serb forces are trying to replace the losses,''
Clark said. ``It's not surprising. They are taking a real pounding,
and they are trying to scramble back and keep their forces in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   In what he suggested was a sign of Serb desperation, Clark said
that Yugoslav forces had seized houses belonging to ethnic
Albanians, and forced their occupants to live inside the homes with
them as ``live-in human shields.''
</P>
<P>
   As the military campaign moved into its 68th day, hopes for a
diplomatic settlement seemed clouded. The Yugoslav government last
Thursday said it accepted the principles for a settlement issued
two weeks ago by the Group of Seven industrial nations and Russia.
But Western leaders want more concrete evidence that Milosevic is
coming around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wait and see what that means in terms of the
details,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Sunday. ``One could
interpret those conditions in different ways and we want to make
sure that Milosevic interprets those in the way that we interpret
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have left Capitol Hill for a week-long holiday recess,
but the debate over strategy carried on. Attacking civilian
targets, like the power grids, plays into Milosevic's hands, some
legislators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives Milosevic more support, and it begins to undercut our
own moral claim,'' Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said on ``Fox News
Sunday.'' ``I would put my emphasis on diplomacy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But other lawmakers say the air campaign needs to intensify and
run its course. ``The diplomacy is getting nowhere,'' Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., said on the same program. ``The only thing
Milosevic understands is real force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
