<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-TV-LADN     05-30 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S WEEK AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TODAY: The Memorial Day baseball lineup includes Mike Piazza,
Mark McGwire, Raul Mondesi and Larry Walker. Remember when pitchers
used to get top billing? Cincinnati at N.Y. Mets, ESPN, 10:15 a.m.;
Dodgers at Pittsburgh, Channel 5, 10:35 a.m.; St. Louis at Florida,
ESPN, 1 p.m.; Colorado at Atlanta, TBS, 4:35 p.m.  &QL; 
TUESDAY: It's the last hurrah for TNT with the NBA playoffs in '99,
but NBC pays the bills and needs the programming after this game to
break up ``Must See Summer Reruns.'' Tell Ernie Johnson Jr. _
didn't he play Ernie on ``My Three Sons''? _ to make it count
today. NBA Eastern Conference finals, Game 2: New York at Indiana,
TNT, 5:30 p.m. (NBC has Game 3 at New York on Saturday at 3:30 p.m.
as well as the San Antonio-Portland Western Conference final Game 2
today at 2:30 p.m., Game 3 Friday at 6 p.m. and Game 4 Sunday at
3:30 p.m.) &QL; 
WEDNESDAY: If need be, Darth Hasek shuffles back to Buffalo for a
sixth game, careful not to aggravate anything. Especially the
Leafs. NHL Eastern Conference finals: Toronto at Buffalo, Game 6
(if necessary), ESPN, 4:30 p.m. (ESPN also has a possible Game 7
Saturday at 4:30 p.m., as well as the Colorado-Dallas Western
Conference finals Game 6 Tuesday and possible Game 7 Friday at 4:30
p.m.)  &QL; 
THURSDAY: For ESPN's annual coverage of the national spelling bee,
we admit this year we're pulling hard for 14-year-old Michael
Yeranosian, an eighth-grader from Manoogian-Demirdjian Middle
School in Canoga Park _ the Daily News is officially sponsoring
him. You try spelling his school's name _ that should be enough to
qualify. Meanwhile, four high schools will be after two L.A. City
baseball titles today. That spells trouble for someone. National
Spelling Bee, ESPN, 9 a.m., ESPN2, 4:30 p.m. L.A. Division baseball
final, 4 p.m., Channel 58; L.A. City Championship baseball final, 6
p.m., Channel 58.  &QL; 
FRIDAY: If you're looking for a Freeway World Series preview here,
take into account neither team may be over .500 when this game
happens. That's highway robbery. Angels at Dodgers, Channel 9, 7
p.m. (Fox Channel 11's weekly national coverage begins Saturday
with these teams at 1:05 p.m.; Fox Sports West 2 has the Sunday
finale at 1:10 p.m.) &QL; 
SATURDAY: For the third year in a row, horse racing has a
four-legged phenom that's one leg away from the Triple Crown. ABC's
Al Michaels had the best line recently about Charismatic, who went
off at 30-1 in the Kentucky Derby and 8-1 at the Preakness but won
'em both. ``We're all sick of hearing athletes talk about getting
no respect. But here's a first: One who can't even say it, and we
believe him.'' As for intrigue, will Chris Antley flash three
fingers after the finish line, or will he be a gentlemen and escort
Silverbulletday across the threshold? Belmont Stakes, Channel 7,
1:30 p.m.  &QL; 
SUNDAY: It's pick-your-poison Sunday. May the remote be with you.
French Open men's final, Channel 4, 7 a.m. (NBC has the women's
final Saturday at 9 a.m. and the men's semis Friday at 7 a.m.);
U.S. women's soccer vs. Canada, Channel 7, 11 a.m.; U.S. Women's
Open golf, final round, Channel 4, noon (NBC has third-round
coverage Saturday at noon while ESPN has the first two rounds
Thursday and Friday at noon); MLS: Kansas City at Galaxy, ESPN,
12:30 p.m.; New York Mets at New York Yankees, ESPN, 5 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
