<HEADLINE>
RYAN MEETS KOUFAX IN HO-HIT HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the anniversaries that will occur this week in Los Angeles
sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from the book
``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles Sports
History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   June 1, 1975: Angels' Nolan Ryan throws his fourth career
no-hitter, 1-0 over Baltimore, to tie Sandy Koufax's all-time
record. !ital!(28)
</P>
<P>
   June 3, 1989: The Dodgers play the longest night game in NL
history _ a 7 hour, 14 minute struggle against Houston that goes 22
innings before third baseman Jeff Hamilton, called on to pitch,
takes a 5-4 loss.
</P>
<P>
   June 3, 1984: Lakers' Magic Johnson sets an NBA Finals record
with 21 assists in a game against Boston.
</P>
<P>
   June 4, 1964: Dodgers' Koufax throws his third no-hitter, a 3-0
win against Philadelphia. He strikes out 12 and walks just one.
</P>
<P>
   June 4, 1990: Dodgers' Ramon Martinez strikes out 18 Atlanta
Braves at Dodger Stadium in a 6-0 win to tie Koufax's team record.
Martinez struck out 14 of the first 19 batters.
</P>
<P>
   June 5, 1993: The Forum hosts a Stanley Cup final for the first
time when the Kings play Montreal to a 4-3 overtime loss in Game 3
of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   June 6, 1998: USC outlasts Arizona State 21-14 to win the
College World Series. Yes, that's a baseball score. Wes Rachels
drove in seven runs with a five-hit game.
</P>
<P>
   June 6, 1989: The Kings' Wayne Gretzky is voted the NHL's Hart
Trophy winner for a league-record ninth time.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Today: Former Rams quarterback Joe Namath (56) and
former Lakers forward Happy Hairston (57). Tuesday: Former Angels
pitcher Dean Chance (58). Wednesday: Former Kings coach Larry
Robinson (48), former Rams running back Lawrence McCutcheon (49)
and PGA Tour player and former USC star Craig Stadler (46).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
