<HEADER>
A6747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-MARKETPLACE-NYT     05-30 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER COMPANIES SETTING UP WEB UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tables were turned at the newspaper publishers' annual
meeting last month: Instead of being grilled by Wall Street
analysts seeking to poke holes in glowing corporate presentations,
the publishers questioned three leading analysts.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the publishers said, you tell us where to find the money for
the Internet investments (which you say will push our stock prices
up) without hurting our quarterly earnings (which you know will
push our stock prices down).
</P>
<P>
   The three analysts offered versions of the same answer: tap into
the irrationally brimming rivers of capital flowing through
Internet land.
</P>
<P>
   But that was last month. Last week there was a lot less water
coursing through those streams. Online media upstarts like
TheStreet.com and Marketwatch.com saw their valuations fall to half
of what they had been at the peaks reached shortly after their
initial public offerings earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   And a couple of new Internet offerings, like Juno Online
Services Inc. and Edgar Online Inc. actually saw their stock prices
fall on the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Still, just in time for the sudden dampening of investor
enthusiasm, three media companies have made announcements showing
that they agreed with the analysts' earlier advice. Consolidated
Internet divisions, all with spinoff potential, were rolled out
with full-dress news releases and conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   In military terms, Tribune Co., Time Warner's CNN and The New
York Times Co., have assembled Web troops for basic training.
</P>
<P>
   How, when and whether they will go into online, stand-alone
stock combat is unclear. And, given the current volatile investment
climate, they very likely would not know the size of their
financial arsenal until they are already on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Co., owner of The Chicago Tribune newspaper and 17
television stations, moved on May 18 to create Tribune Interactive,
a business unit which combines the Web sites of all of its media
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a focused management strategy,'' explained Jeff R.
Scherb, the chief executive of the new entity. ``And it is focused
much more clearly on building a business that may end up being
independent'' of Tribune Co., he added. The words ``initial public
offering'' were not spoken, but implicitly hovered around the word
``independent.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Martin A. Nisenholtz, president of Times Company
Digital, the new division announced last Monday by The New York
Times Co., stopped well short of such a suggestion. The assets of
Times Company Digital will be its nearly 50 Web sites, which
include The New York Times on the Web (www.nytimes.com), The Boston
Globe's Boston.com and the California-based Winetoday.com.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Nisenholtz said, is to ``reach critical mass'' in the
online world by achieving the maximum possible reach into the 30
percent of American households that have Internet access,
particularly those that would be a natural audience for The New
York Times Co.'s publications. ``This is the first step in
achieving that goal,'' he said. ``Stay tuned for more. We're not
saying we've decided to do an IPO, because we haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Times Co. took a 7.5 percent stake in
TheStreet.com, which translated into $105 million immediately after
the Internet company's stock offering two weeks ago _ but had
eroded to $62.85 million by last Friday, after investors started
winnowing their online portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, some media executives see an opportunity in this moment
of ``dot-com'' disillusionment. Larry Kramer, chief executive of
Marketwatch.com, the online financial news site that is now a CBS
partner, theorized: ``The Internet investor is tired. The Internet
concept is still strong in terms of the multiples, but it's going
to be harder to slap a dot-com on and go public.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``What makes a blue-chip Internet stock has a lot to
do with pedigree. It goes to deep pockets, it goes to the knowledge
base and the talent base you possess. A proven media company should
do a better job in the media business.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Kramer argued, newspaper companies have been slow to invest
in online properties, compared with broadcasters. ``The irony here
is that the newspaper companies have been left in the dust,'' he
said. ``The broadcasters beat them to it. CBS, NBC, ABC, have
substantial Internet holding and have gotten the public to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS, with Marketwatch.com and Sportsline.com, NBC, with Snap and
Xoom, among others, and ABC, with ESPN Sportzone, Infoseek and the
Go Network, have all staked their claim to the Web. And, Kramer
said, the broadcasters have been able to make their investments at
least partly in the form of on-air promotions, which can help build
brand-name recognition that helps sites stand out amid the clutter
of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CNN upped its Internet ante by announcing a $50
million deal with IDG, the magazine and book publishing company
that specializes in technology titles like PC World. As a result of
the agreement, IDG's editorial material can be used by CNN-owned
Web sites, IDG will buy advertising on the cable news channel, and
a weekly consumer-technology CNN program will be broadcast this
fall, with both groups contributing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, taking steps along the same path as Tribune Co. and
Times Co., IDG said it would consolidate its 240 Web sites into one
unit _ while CNN agreed to invest about $18 million in the IDG
venture.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of getting high stock valuations for such
properties is obviously attractive, in part because high-flying
stocks themselves can be used as currency in other deals. And at
least one analyst, Lauren Rich Fine, a media analyst with Merrill
Lynch, thinks that the reputation of well-known newspapers is
likely to help them compete.
</P>
<P>
   As she told the publishers in San Diego: ``Look at the three
national brands that exist today _ USA Today.com, Wall Street
Journal.com, New York Times.com _ that have been able to command
traffic levels, revenue levels, something that would be of
interest. You know, in my heart of hearts I really want to see
those entities go public.''
</P>
<P>
   Would investors care? Scherb of Tribune Co. contends that they
might. ``I don't believe the last great business on the Internet
has been created _ that there are no more good ideas, and that
Amazon.com and Ebay.com got it all,'' he said. ``The market's
always going to reward a great growth idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
