<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEA' AND `WIND': DAREDEVIL RACERS AGAINST LIFE-THREATENING OCEANS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men will do the maddest things, and women, too.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, they will sail in boat races like the Vendee
Globe, a single-handed regatta through the most dangerous waters in
the world under the most challenging circumstances. As Derek Lundy
sums up the bare facts of the race in his eloquent ``Godforsaken
Sea: Racing the World's Most Dangerous Waters,'' ``27,000 miles,
three and a half to five months alone at sea, chilling casualty
rates, the unrelenting strain of handling 60-foot boats day and
night, the absolute certainty of weather and waves that could
destroy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sailing nonstop and unassisted, competitors in the Vendee Globe
start out from the town of Les Sables-d'Olonne on the Vendee coast
of France, make their way south through the Bay of Biscay and down
the Atlantic Ocean, swinging southeast around the Cape of Good Hope
and farther south into the high latitudes of 40 and 60 degrees, the
formidable Southern Ocean, one of the wildest and most isolated
places on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boats then begin the long dash for Cape Horn, keeping well
south of Australia and New Zealand,'' Lundy explains. ``In effect,
the route is a circumnavigation of Antarctica. But sailors usually
describe it as going `south of the three stormy capes' _ Good Hope,
Leeuwin and Horn. Once around Cape Horn, the boats retrace their
route north through the Atlantic and back to France.''
</P>
<P>
   Using as his model the third Vendee Globe _ which began on Nov.
3, 1996, with 16 competitors (among them two women) and ended on
March 24, 1997, with only six official finishers _ Lundy explores
how and why humans feel drawn to the extreme risks and almost
inevitable disasters that single-handedly sailing the Southern
Ocean entails.
</P>
<P>
   The race provided him plenty of material. Almost from the start
equipment kept breaking down. The battering seas tore away keels,
knocked down masts and tossed up chunks of ice and flotsam that
sheared off rudders and smashed in hulls. The breadth and flatness
of the theoretically best designed boats _ ``ocean-going
surfboards,'' Lundy calls them _ led to their inability to right
themselves when knocked over by killer waves. As a result, three
boats capsized and stayed upside-down in the Southern Ocean,
exposing the skippers to deadly conditions until rescued. (One
racer was so nearly frozen that when his finger was chopped off by
a closing hatch, he scarcely noticed the pain.)
</P>
<P>
   Out of these incidents, Lundy not only makes stirring narrative
drama but also draws the lineaments of an archetypal hero, a human
driven by fear, addicted to adrenaline, in need of the edge.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback to the story is that Lundy, a lawyer, writer
and amateur sailor, views events from afar, depending on pre- and
post-race interviews, reports on the Internet and his own sailing
experience to piece the narrative together. A result is that the
action seems relatively remote, the exhilaration of the race is
missing, and it is hard to keep the various participants straight.
</P>
<P>
   These shortcomings seem all the more apparent in ``Close to the
Wind,'' by Pete Goss, who was one of two Englishmen to compete in
the '96-'97 Vendee Globe and who figured in one of the central
incidents recounted in Lundy's book.
</P>
<P>
   In a relaxed, colloquial style Goss describes how he fell in
love with sailing; how he raised money and helped to build the Aqua
Quorum, which because of limited funds had to be only 50 feet long,
or 10 feet shorter than the rest of the boats, and how he at last
found himself in the thick of battle. You are there; you feel the
excitement and dread.
</P>
<P>
   Then, planing along in the stormy Southern Ocean, he received a
Mayday call from a stricken fellow racer, Raphael Dinelli. He was
asked by race directors to go to the rescue; he turned back and
against all odds he beat his way to Dinelli's sinking craft and
pulled the near-dead man aboard in the nick of time. After reviving
Dinelli and delivering him to Hobart, Tasmania, he got back into
the race, only to suffer an infected elbow that pained him so
severely that he eventually had to cut it open and drain it,
following the faxed instructions of a surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Goss' tale is everything Lundy's is not: tense, fast-moving and
illustrated with color photographs that put you in the middle of
the action. Yet the grandeur that Lundy conveys is somehow missing.
While Goss is capable of deep emotion, like the depression and
frustration he felt when he realized he would not compete with the
race's leaders, his attitude toward his own heroism is
matter-of-fact. This may hint at an answer to Lundy's question
about what forms such heroes: the attributes are simply built into
some people.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why these two books should be read consecutively,
Lundy's for its overview, Goss' for its close-ups. Together they
make more comprehensible why some people fling themselves into the
jaws of death. Together they offer a taste of the experience, while
permitting you throughout to stay warm and dry.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `GODFORSAKEN SEA'
</P>
<P>
   Racing the World's Most Dangerous Waters
</P>
<P>
   By Derek Lundy
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 272 pages. Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE TO THE WIND
</P>
<P>
   By Pete Goss
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 273 pages. Carroll &AMP; Graf. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
