A6751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-UPFRONT-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      05-30 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UPFRONT-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS SPEND EAGERLY FOR TV TIME IN FALL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sale of commercial time by the broadcast television networks
in advance for the fall season, known as the up-front market, is
ending on an even stronger note this year than the optimistic
forecasts in recent weeks had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is even more demand than we had expected,'' said Jamie
Kellner, president of the WB Network in Burbank, Calif., which is
owned by Time Warner Inc. and Tribune Co. ``We were in a position
to increase rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on current estimates, the six broadcast networks will sell
$7 billion to $7.2 billion worth of commercial time during the
prime-time programs in the 1999-2000 season. Though negotiations
are not entirely wrapped up _ some dickering is to continue this
week and into June _ the estimates are about 9 percent higher than
the approximately $6.4 billion worth of commercial time sold ahead
of the 1998-99 prime-time season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was amazing speed and earliness'' to the demand, said
Joe Mandese, editor of The Myers Report, a media newsletter, who
tracks the annual performance of the up-front market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day parts were pretty strong, too,'' he added,
referring to sales of commercial time during morning, news and
late-night programs. ``It all speaks to the underlying strength of
the media economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The robust results came despite continued declines in ratings
for most of the prime-time programs on the broadcast networks
during the 1998-99 season, which ended last week. But even as
viewership continues to erode, those six networks _ ABC, CBS, Fox
Broadcasting Co., NBC, UPN and the WB _ still offer marketers the
chance to pitch products before large audiences.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the networks focusing their programs on the younger
consumers most coveted by advertisers performed particularly well.
WB, for example, which seeks viewers ages 12 to 34, sold about $450
million worth of commercial time in the up-front market, compared
with $300 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone looking for young eyeballs was showing up,'' Kellner
said. ``There were a lot of new advertisers, and then incumbent
advertisers were asking for more inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the unit of News Corp. that aims its programs at viewers
ranging in age from 18 to 34 and 18 to 49, sold more than $1.3
billion worth of commercial time, compared with about $1.15 billion
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Demand was consistent among advertisers for many categories of
goods and services, Mandese said, with retail and
telecommunications advertisers especially eager to make
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Internet and so-called dot.com marketers were ``not a big factor
so far,'' he added, but should be later, when the networks sell
commercial time during the season in what is called the scatter
market.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for broadcast commercial time augurs well for the
cable networks, which conduct their up-front market after that of
their broadcast counterparts. Ratings for many cable programs rose
during the 1998-99 season as viewers sought alternatives to
broadcast fare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
