<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAMBA31-COX     05-30 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMBA31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spoleto brings `Mamba' home to Charleston after 60 years
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Well before William Faulkner and Carson
McCullers, DuBose Heyward (1885-1940) broke the color barrier of
Southern fiction. Though a descendent of Carolina rice planters, he
was able to put Southern white privilege aside in two novels that
explore, without a trace of condescension, the lives of poor blacks
whose labor supports the illusions of this elegant city.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``Porgy'' (1925), which became the American folk opera
``Porgy and Bess.'' The other is ``Mamba's Daughters''(1929), about
the entwined black and white Wentworth family.
</P>
<P>
   The stage drama, adapted for theater by Heyward and his
playwright wife, Dorothy, made a household name of Ethel Waters
when it played on Broadway in 1939. But it took ``Mamba's
Daughters'' 60 years to come home to Charleston, where it is being
performed as a headline event of the 1999 Spoleto Festival.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be here at all if not for Target Margin Theater, an
8-year-old New York company that specializes in ``neglected works
of literary and historic significance.'' It is Target Margins' Obie
Award-winning 1998 production that plays through June 13th at the
Dock Street Theater, a beautiful, intimate house more than a
century old _ and therefore off-limits to black audiences for most
of its life _ in the downtown historic district. There is nice
irony in that.
</P>
<P>
   In rethinking the novel for the stage, the Heywards focused
almost wholly on the black Wentworths; three generations of gutsy
women led by Mamba, (the first syllable is pronounced `ma'am'). She
has only one daughter, the ``big slow brute'' Hagar, a laundress.
But she becomes mother to Hagar's child, the angelic Lissa, when
Hagar is sentenced to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Director David Herskovits wants his production to live in two
worlds; Charleston of the '20s and contemporary America, with its
primal burden as a country built on slave labor. So ``Mamba'' is
set on a stage of Southern screen doors, where a fly drones lazily
across the testimony in a judge's chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the costumes mix lowcountry (as Charlestonians spell it)
cotton and '90s sass. Grown-up Lissa carries one of those
itty-bitty backpacks over a filmy white slip dress, and we can see
why Hagar, in her shapeless ``bes' dress'' marvels at the swan she
has hatched.
</P>
<P>
   All the costumes have a strip of adhesive fabric across the
shoulder blades, exactly where the stenciled name and ID number on
a prison work shirt would go _ symbolizing, I think, the
imprisoning social system in which all the characters play out
their roles.
</P>
<P>
   And all the actors have a dab of blue paint on one earlobe and
under the lips. This color, called ``haint blue'' among the Gullah,
is used as a protective device; for Mamba and her daughters, it
marks the safe passage of song and story from one generation to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the title, this play is clearly the story of Hagar _ the
role Waters played in 1939. Heather Gillespie, who won an Obie for
her Hagar, is elfin-slim, so the production coarsens her with
platform shoes, ugly clothes and braids tied with twine. She towers
above everyone, a hulk of a woman. There is a suggestion, too, that
Hagar is simple-minded; but her words, child-like and guileless,
become a poetry of direct passion; a determined woman, a protective
mother, an avenging spirt.
</P>
<P>
   Besides this indelible earth woman, Melody Cooper's Mamba barely
registers and the Lissa of Billie James is best forgotten. The rest
of the company, thought, is a Greek chorus of quirky individuals,
from a feisty grandmother to a sleazy pimp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamba's Daughters'' feels like a dramatized novel and not
really a play. It meanders more than it strides, and despite
extensive cutting, it feels long. But the woman whom I overheard
call it ``a loser'' is selling it short. Hagar is an incandescent
character _ all the more so because she was created by a white man
looking from the outside on a culture he realized he could never
really know.
</P>
<P>
   for information of the 1999 Spoleto festival: 222.spoletousa.org
</P>
<P>
   Mamba's Daughters
</P>
<P>
   By Dorothy and DuBose Heyward.
</P>
<P>
   Target Margin Theater. Through June 13th. Dock Street Theater.
Spolto Festival USA, Charleston, S.C. $35 843-723-0402; To order by
fax, 843-720-1121.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
