<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-COMPETE-MEDIA-     05-30 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-COMPETE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING FOR DOMINANCE, DENVER'S 2 DAILIES KEEP READERS IN MIND
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ In the frenzied first hours of the Columbine High
School shootings last month, an editor of The Denver Rocky Mountain
News slipped away from the fray and called newspapers in towns that
had endured similar events: Paducah, Ky.; Jonesboro, Ark., and
Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their readers had wanted newspapers to show the importance of
the people who were killed and injured _ the killers were the
aberration,'' recalled John Temple, The News' top editor. Flipping
through back issues from that maelstrom, he said: ``So that's how
we did it in our pages _ the victims first, then the suspects. Not
the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Denver Post, the editor, Dennis A. Britton, reflected,
``We were able to deal with 13 grieving families, and the families
of the wounded, without getting anything substantially wrong or
them angry at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many in the national news media took a hit-and-run
approach to Columbine, the two newspapers here knew that showing
insensitivity to a wounded community could be a costly misstep in a
fiercely contested newspaper war, possibly the toughest in the
country these days.
</P>
<P>
   Fought with street vendors hawking extra editions, two-year
subscriptions going for a penny a paper and advertising discounts
that produce some of the world's fattest newspapers, the flagship
papers of two big newspaper empires are locked in combat here.
While most American cities are one-newspaper towns, Denver has a
war that pits The Post, a broadsheet owned by Media News Group, the
nation's seventh-largest newspaper chain, against The News, a
tabloid owned by E.W. Scripps Co., the eighth-largest chain.
</P>
<P>
   While newspaper circulation stagnates around the nation, trucks
in Denver deliver 360,000 more newspapers each week than they did
at this time last year. Based on a 10.4 percent year-over-year
circulation jump for the first quarter, The News now describes
itself as ``the fastest-growing major daily newspaper in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekday circulation race is a virtual dead heat, with The
News reporting 359,068, and the Post reporting 370,423. In the
Sunday race, The Post has a wider margin, selling 523,324, compared
with 461,000 for The News.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reversing eight years of circulation declines,
The News is also creating the editorial buzz in town. Repositioning
itself as an upscale tabloid, it is generously using color,
publishing new sections and showing that it can turn on a dime to
respond to breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, we asked focus groups to compare our newspaper to a
car, and they said we were a pickup,'' said Linda Sease, The News'
vice president for marketing. ``Two years later, they said, `a
sports utility vehicle.' Hey, I'll be an SUV any day _ they are
hip, trendy, young, expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   For a paper that did not have a separate business section four
years ago, The News now wins praise for its Sunday section, Wall
Street West. Dean Rotbart, the editor here of TJFR, a national
newsletter critiquing business reporting, said, ``A lot of
companies here have told me that the Rocky does a better job with
its business coverage than The Post does.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post's counterattack has been to open nine bureaus around
the state, giving Denver readers news from areas they love to visit
when off work. But after seven changes of editors in 14 years, The
Post has been hurt by low newsroom morale. The leadership of
Britton, the current editor, has produced such unhappiness that
dissidents maintain a ``Dennis Britton Go Home!'' Web page. Britton
said, ``It has been pretty hurtful.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood began soon after Britton took over three years
ago, when he encouraged the departure of about 30 experienced
reporters and editors. Many reporters called his style abrasive.
``The inmates were running the asylum,'' he said. ``I am not
namby-pamby. I believe in discipline. I believe in order.''
</P>
<P>
   But, although The Post has almost 20 percent more reporters than
The News, it seems to have lost its journalistic edge, at least by
one measure. Recently, the Colorado chapter of the Society of
Professional Journalists announced that The News had won 47 awards,
including 19 first-place awards. In contrast, The Post won six,
including one first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awards don't mean much,'' said William Dean Singleton, who is
president of Media News and chairman of The Post. ``We are playing
to our readers, not to our peers.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Columbine coverage, both papers occasionally tripped.
On April 24, The News printed an Internet ``message from the
grave,'' purportedly written by Eric Harris, one of the killers.
The note threatened new violence for April 26. The next day, a
police spokesman called the note a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Though Post editors shied away from the Internet message, one of
their front-page headlines that day said, ``Investigators Close In
on 3rd Suspect.'' Five weeks later, no one has been arrested for
helping Harris and Dylan Klebold plot and carry out the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Both papers say they make a profit. But Singleton's Media News
is privately held, and he is parsimonious with details. Scripps Co.
declines to give after-tax earnings for individual papers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, analysts got a peek into Post finances when
one of the paper's investors, Media General Inc., filed a report
with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Comparing the first
quarter of this year with the corresponding period last year,
earnings from Media General's investment in The Post ``decreased
from income of $616,000 to a loss of $514,000 in the first quarter
of 1999.'' A few days later, the company announced plans to sell
its stock in Denver Newspapers Inc., The Post's parent company, to
Media News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been trying to buy them out for a long time,''
Singleton said. With the purchase, he said, his company's ownership
of The Post will rise to 80 percent from 60 percent, allowing him
to cut administrative costs. He said he was investing heavily in
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The News also benefits from big investments by Scripps, which is
based in Cincinnati. Scripps owns six papers in Denver's northern
suburbs: The Boulder Daily Camera and five weeklies. In a
circulation strategy, The News has dropped expensive statewide
delivery and concentrated on Denver and five surrounding counties,
home to 56 percent of the state's population and 60 percent of its
retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   In a time of expansion, there may be room for two newspapers.
Over the last decade, the population of greater Denver has
ballooned by almost one-quarter, hitting 2.3 million people today.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Dubroff, editor of The Denver Business Journal, notes
that in the last six months, the four largest companies with
headquarters in Colorado have merged with outside companies.
Dubroff, a Post veteran, said, ``There is nothing to prevent
Scripps and Media News from going into the proverbial smoke-filled
room and coming out with a single company, the Denver Post-News.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
