 Column: If You'd Like To Speak to a Live Person, Don't Press 1  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Customer service _ a stultifying brew of 1-800 telephone numbers,
monotone-voiced representatives, Muzak and interminable time on
hold _ finally may be entering the digital age.
<P>
   LivePerson.com ( &LR; www.liveperson.com &LR; ) has designed software that
lets consumers exchange instant e-mail messages with living,
breathing sales reps at some 50 commercial Web sites _ among them,
CBS SportsLine's IGoGolf.com, FragranceCounter.com and
NationsBanc's Carfinance.com. Users can ask questions about
products and billing, seek links to related sites and provide a
personal profile for future orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an epiphany while waiting for someone on Dell's site to
help me configure a PC,'' said Robert LoCascio, president and CEO
of LivePerson.com in New York. ``If you can buy goods instantly
online, why not be able to talk to the same company instantly?''
</P>
<P>
   LoCascio, whose company is expected to receive financial backing
from former Apple Computer CEO John Sculley this week, predicts
that the hands-on approach will jolt not only e-commerce sales, but
reduce telephone charges for online merchants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ALL IN THE FAMILY &LR; : ``The Dickers'' sounds like it could be a TV
dramedy. Driven father strikes it rich in the cutthroat business
world. Equally ambitious son duplicates his success straight out of
college.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday, a Hollywood producer will fashion a script based
on the real-life exploits of Tom and Russell Dicker, the father-son
tandem that may be the Net's first multigeneration success story.
</P>
<P>
   This Internet saga is all true. Its story line is developing
into a high-tech version of ``Dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom, who will only admit that he is ``north of 50,'' last week
ended a furious five-year run at Netscape Communications as senior
director of the professional services group. He joined the Internet
pioneer in fall 1994, when it was called Mosaic Communications.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest son, Russell, 23, is a software-development engineer
at Amazon.com. He joined the online retailer in July 1998, shortly
after graduating from Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Today, both are millionaires, based on ``dot com'' stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Dicker grew up in Palo Alto, where he attended high
school with one of William Hewlett's sons. ``Growing up with HP and
Intel around you, you can't avoid getting into it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tech bug bit Dicker  &LR; pere,  &LR; who was an executive at Grid
Systems and NeXT Computer before joining Netscape. ``I lived and
breathed this stuff at home,'' he said. ``The boys couldn't avoid
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Youngest son, George, 18, recently was accepted at Stanford
University, where he will major in computer science.)
</P>
<P>
   Russell remembers banging away at personal computers ``shortly
after I started walking.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``My dad would bring Grid PCs from work, and I would play
football games on them. When I wasn't doing that, I would go to
work with him on weekends,'' he said. &UR;  &LR; As a teenager, the younger
Dicker met Apple co-founder Steve Jobs and former StarWave
President Mike Slade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Despite being raised in the heart of Silicon Valley, Russell
said, ``There was no active pressure on me to do this; I was just
always interested in computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom, meanwhile, is taking a rest after ``going full blast'' for
five years at Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to recharge the batteries and enjoy things before
joining another startup _ probably next year,'' the elder Dicker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a possibility that the startup might include other
members of the Dicker clan?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the opportunity were right, sure,'' Russell said, before
hastily adding, ``Although my dad is pretty busy helping friends
with some early stage companies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AT BAY &LR; : Customers of eBay's popular online auction service may
have noticed a change in the bidding format this month.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, users entered their bid, screen name and password
all on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, only bids are registered on one page. Screen names
and passwords are logged on a separate page to eliminate password
theft.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose company tightened security after a Canadian user
warned that sellers theoretically could trace the bids of
individuals to their accounts and steal passwords.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Kevin Pursglove said no password pilfering was
reported but that eBay decided to take no chances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; VASE CASE &LR; : Credit iMac, Apple's rainbow line of Internet
computers, for helping redefine peripheral devices. The metallic
iVase ( &LR; www.freeverse.com &LR; ) is a snazzy flower holder to show off
tulips with your grape iMac or red roses in your strawberry model.
A distant cousin to the New Beetle's color-coordinated vase, iVase
costs $8.95, plus $3 for shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; A NOVEL IDEA &LR; : Longtime Chronicle staffer Leslie Guttman took a
novel approach with her first book, ``Message Pending''
( &LR; www.messagepending.com &LR; ), a love story told through exchanges of
e-mail. It's part of a rapidly growing trend: Novels published
entirely online.
</P>
<P>
   Likened by readers to an online version of ``Tales of the
City,'' it's about the ``power and intimacy of e-mail, the problem
of pesticides, and the blanderization of media,'' according to
Guttman.
</P>
<P>
   It also is for a good cause. Half of the net proceeds from the
$14.95 novel go to the nonprofit Pesticide Action Network
( &LR; www.panna.org &LR;   &LR; /panna &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT'S IN A NAME &LR; ?: At least one Internet expert isn't thrilled
with the choice of ExciteAtHome as the newly minted moniker for the
merged AtHome and Excite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yech! Sounds like an online vendor of marital aids (or
variously, aids for lonely hearts),'' David Simons, managing
director at New York-based Digital Video Investments, said in an
e-mail message. ``I'll stop at the double entendre of `buzz' and
won't even think about logos.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither will we, David.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SITES OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Linda Tripp, beware. You, too, might face the same cyber wrath of
fellow turncoat, Lucianne Goldberg. A Web camera is trained 24
hours a day on the New York apartment of Goldberg
( &LR; www.iseelucy.com &LR; ), the conniving literary agent who set up White
House intern Monica Lewinsky _ whose tryst with Bill Clinton nearly
brought down his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Flirtation was never this anonymous. Your rendezvous address
online is  &LR; www.winkat.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Finally, join the national debate on Social Security at
 &LR; www.network-democracy.org &LR;   &LR; /social-security &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got any interesting or quirky Web sites you'd like to share? If so,
drop me an e-mail at jswartz &LR; sfgate.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
