<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HP to Sell Printers, PCs Direct Via Web  &HT;       
 By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In another move to catch up with the Internet wave, Hewlett-Packard
soon will begin selling personal computers and printers directly to
business customers via the World Wide Web.
<P>
   The new distribution scheme is the latest in a flurry of recent
changes at the Palo Alto company, which is trying to boost its
growth rate and shed its reputation as a slow-moving behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   In March, HP announced plans to spin off its measurement
business and seek a new leader to replace chief executive Lew
Platt, who plans to retire. Last month, it proclaimed an updated
corporate vision, focused on providing hardware and software for a
new generation of sophisticated ``e-services.''
</P>
<P>
   The new online selling site, to be called the HP Business Store,
will be announced tomorrow and is scheduled to open for business
June 8. It will carry the company's complete line of business
desktop and notebook PCs, its popular LaserJet and OfficeJet
printers and other products such as scanners, CD-ROM drives and
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, HP announced a separate plan to expand online
sales of products geared to home users.
</P>
<P>
   Prices at the new business store, according to HP officials,
generally will match retail ``street prices,'' which typically are
well below list prices.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Zitzner, president and chief executive of HP's Computer
Products group, predicted that ``more than a third'' of HP's PC
sales will be transacted electronically within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy will put HP into head-to-head competition with
younger companies such as Dell and Gateway, which have grabbed
market share by focusing exclusively on direct sales to customers
by phone and over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   HP said it hopes to win over customers in part by making it
easier to order equipment from its Web site than from competitors'
sites. Among the innovations it's promising are easy access to
information about availability, and instant price updates when
customers change the configuration of products they're ordering.
Most online stores currently require users to click on a button to
see a new price when they specify extra memory or a higher-capacity
hard drive, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, most of HP's sales have been indirect, through retail
outlets and ``value-added resellers'' that provide hardware and
services to businesses. By cutting out the middleman, the
direct-business model helps manufacturers keep prices low and their
own margins high.
</P>
<P>
   Several other computer-makers, notably Compaq, have stumbled
badly when they tried to combine the direct and indirect models.
The risk is that the manufacturer will alienate its dealers by
undermining their prices and stealing away their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Zitzner said he's confident that HP won't experience the same
problems Compaq has. ``We don't intend to undersell our
resellers,'' he said. The new Web site, he said, simply will give
customers more choices about how they want to buy HP products.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kim Tchang, an HP sales and marketing exec who
focuses on small-business customers, the online store is aimed
mainly at ``buy now'' customers, who generally purchase in low
volumes, know in advance what they want and demand fast answers and
immediate fulfillment. It's hard for dealers to make money off such
customers anyway, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Spang, an analyst at Technology Business Research in
Hampton, N.H., said she thinks that HP may have better luck with
its new hybrid distribution approach than Compaq has had. ``One of
the things HP has always been good at is keeping its dealers well
informed and up to date,'' she said. ``As long as they're up front
about what they're doing and dealers understand what role they
still have, I think it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   HP expects, according to Tchang, that only about 15 percent of
its small-business customers will fall into the ``buy now''
category. The other 85 percent need the kind of consulting and
support that local dealers can provide, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Web site will include features to help customers locate
nearby dealers, plus case studies and other information about the
services they offer.
</P>
<P>
   By providing an array of tools and tips on the site, HP aims to
encourage ``e-intimacy'' between the company and its customers,
Tchang said.
</P>
<P>
   HP also will announce that it's beefing up support for large
corporate customers who contract to have HP meet all their
computing needs. One feature of the new program, called HP Prime,
will be Web sites customized specifically for such customers. That
concept was pioneered by Dell, which has used it to strengthen its
position in the corporate market.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has reacted favorably to HP's recent initiatives.
Its stock, which closed on Friday at $94.31, has more than doubled
since October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
