<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Column: Biochip Might Hasten Rip Van Winkle Pace for
Drug  Approval  By Tom Abate  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Investors rap biotech because it takes a decade to produce a hit
drug whereas the computer world can churn out two or three new
industries in the same amount of time.
<P>
   But at a small biotech conclave last week in Napa, I got a
glimpse of what might happen as biological advances in DNA
screening get mated to the rapid product-improvement cycles of
silicon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if you could do a person's genetic sequence in as much
time as it takes to scan a grocery item,'' posited Mitch Eggers,
chief executive of Genometrix Inc. in Woodlands, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Genometrix is one of an emerging class of firms that produce
biochips, sometimes called labs-on-a-chip. Several similar firms
shared the biochip stage at last week's conference in Napa. They
include Aclara BioSciences Inc. of Hayward, Caliper Technologies
Corp. of Mountain View and Orchid Biocomputer of Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers explained what all these firms aspire to do: miniaturize
the electrochemical tests that extract the genetic code from DNA.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, DNA tests were exotic. Now, we can do them on
PC-sized devices. Eggers and his ilk are trying to pack these tests
onto chips. They already have working chips with canals the
diameter of a human hair. Inside, fluid samples flow past
electrochemical charges that decode the DNA as it passes.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers suggested that biochips could improve at the rate
predicted by Moore's Law, which states that silicon chips double in
power every 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the most powerful biotech tools are focused on getting
one complete readout of the human genome. It still remains just
beyond our grasp. But what will happen in a decade or two when the
power to do walk-by genetic scans can be packed into a Palm Pilot,
Eggers asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of what to do with this information will be facing
us in the next generation,'' he warns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the investors who dominated the audience at Napa
probably were more interested in what biochips can do in the next
few quarters. But even if these firms still are in the red-ink, R&AMP;D
phase, at least biochip-makers don't face the safety concerns that
put drug-discovery companies on a Rip Van Winkle time line.
</P>
<P>
   Other devices caught my eye in Napa. Russell Kerschmann and Paul
Gotcher of Advanced Pathology Systems in San Francisco were there
to talk about a new system for producing microscopic, 3-D images of
tissue samples. So what, you say.
</P>
<P>
   But think about how doctors do biopsies for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they extract a sliver of suspect tissue. A lab worker
cuts a few slices from the biopsy and mounts each slice on a slide.
The doctor examines the slides under a microscope. This examination
may reveal the telltale signs of cancer, or perhaps the lab worker
missed the slice with the first sign of cancer. Kerschmann thinks
that he's invented a better way.
</P>
<P>
   His automated system cuts razor-thin slices of the biopsy
sample, like a butcher slices bologna. A digital camera takes a
high-resolution image of each slice. When the slicing-imaging
process is done, the system reassembles the images, allowing the
viewer to see detailed, 3-D images of the entire bologna _ I mean,
biopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Kerschmann, who has been supporting his tiny company on research
grants, thinks that the 3-D system will provide better diagnosis
than any 2-D slide. ``We're going to obsolete the microscope,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOSE FOR BUSINESS: &LR;  Steven Sunshine of Cyrano Services in Pasadena
was getting attention for his company's electronic nose. The device
detects the minute electrical changes that result when different
types of gas vapors hit a special polymer inside the sniffer unit.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine said the device will be aimed at all the jobs no boss
could pay your nose enough to do _ such as sniffing chemical
tankers at a rail yard to make sure they're carrying the right
load.
</P>
<P>
   Among other potential tasks, Sunshine suggested that the e-nose
might be handy to detect the ovulation cycles of cows. Now, I
thought bulls would have it pretty well figured out by now when
it's snorting-and-pawing season.
</P>
<P>
   But in case they have lost the knack, the species isn't doomed.
Sunshine said that later this year, Hewlett-Packard Co. will help
Cyrano come out with a handheld, industrial e-nose.
</P>
<P>
   Can't wait till that gets into Radio Shack!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your biofeedback to Tom Abate by e-mail, abate(AT
SIGN)sfgate.com; fax, (415) 543-2482; or phone, (415) 777-6213 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
