<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dodgers beat Braves on error again
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a disturbing pattern, the Braves lost to Los
Angeles Sunday for the second time in less than 24 hours on an
unearned run which was set up by a first baseman's error.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko's inarticulate glove-work led to a second straight
loss and a blown 1-2 series with the Dodgers. As for the real
significance of the 11th-inning 5-4 loss, starter Greg Maddux
pegged it at: ``None. Zero. None.''
</P>
<P>
   But the frustration was palpable in the Atlanta clubhouse over
another game fumbled away. Saturday night, a grounder through Brian
Hunter's legs led the way to two Dodger runs, both scoring on bases
loaded walks in a 2-1 loss. On Sunday, Klesko got away with a
throwing error in the third, but his failure to catch Chipper
Jones' high throw on Mark Grudzielanek's roller allowed the winning
run to score from second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always hurts when you lose on a play you feel should be
made,'' said Jones. ``Anytime that happens, it's particularly hard
to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown has never lost at Turner Field and was leading 4-1
in the eighth. Maddux's second homer of the year in the third had
been Atlanta's only run until Jones, Brian Jordan and Klesko all
doubled on three successive pitches to tie it and knock Brown out.
</P>
<P>
   It came apart after Eric Karros's one-out double off Mike
Remlinger in the 11th. After Adrian Beltre was intentionally walked
to set up the force out, Grudzielanek barely got a bat on an 0-2
pitch that rolled to the left side. Jones barehanded the ball and
made a rising throw to the dugout side of first. Klesko tried to
hold the bag and lost the ball off the tip of his glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I come off the bag, you've got bases loaded and one out,''
Klesko said. ``I just took the chance there. When he throws from
down there, the ball of course is going to rise on you. I guess the
best thing I should have done was maybe come off the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Klesko and Hunter, first basemen have already committed
eight errors in 402 total chances. The absent Andres Galarraga
committed 11 errors in 1,310 chances last year while the Braves led
the league in defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have any arm left,'' Klesko said.
</P>
<P>
   TONIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Opponent: Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 7:40 p.m.; Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Pedro Astacio (4-4), Kevin Millwood
(5-3).
</P>
<P>
   TV; radio: TBS; WSB (750 AM).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
