<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    SMOLTZ TO PITCH TUESDAY AGAINST ROCKIES
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz will pitch Tuesday against Colorado and
the Braves were so anxious to make it happen that they've juggled
the rotation in Smoltz's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz will face the Rockies' Bobby Jones on the first day he is
eligible to come off the 15-day disabled list. Kevin Millwood,
whose usual turn would come up Tuesday, has been moved up to pitch
the series opener tonight. Rookie Bruce Chen, who made two starts
in Smoltz's place, was scratched from working tonight but will be
available for relief work before being optioned back to Class AAA
Richmond Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Odalis Perez, who was in jeopardy of being passed over,
will pitched Wednesday in his regular turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only thing we can do,'' manager Bobby Cox said.
``You've got to keep Odalis in there and I know Chen is throwing
good but Smoltz is ready to come off. He's worked hard to get back
and he's ready to go. He's been pointing to that date for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood will work on three days rest for the first time in his
career. The Braves would only contemplate moving Millwood up one
day due to his 85 pitch-count in his last start Thursday in
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good (Saturday) throwing on the side,''
Millwood. ``I don't see it being any kind of problem at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than anything, the moves convinces Perez his place
in the rotation is secure. He has stated his fears that he is only
one bad start or two from losing his job to Chen and after he
brought the issue up again after Perez's masterful job in Friday's
4-2 win over Los Angeles, the club shot down the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought about it,'' Cox said. ``It hasn't crossed my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: The lineup
</P>
<P>
   Cox picked Kevin Brown's day to pitch to give starts to left
fielder Otis Nixon (his first in a week) and second baseman Keith
Lockhart (his first in a month). They were a combined 1-for-7.
Though Cox had planned on playing Lockhart anyway, Bret Boone was
used to pinch-hit in the ninth but otherwise used the day off to
loosen up his left knee, which was struck by a Carlos Perez pitch
the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was fine lying there,'' said Boone, who initially
collapsed in the batter's box but was able finish the game. ``But
it's like somebody hits your funny bone and you need a minute. I
always go into antic when I get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was making his fourth straight start for Walt Weiss, who
is nursing a tender right quadriceps. Weiss is expected to return
to action tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: A change in heart
</P>
<P>
   Official scorer Mark Fredricksen changed a ruling from Saturday
night's game, after initially charging L.A. shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek with an error on a ball hit by Chipper Jones. Though
Grudzielanek was in pefect position to field the ball on one hop,
it was hit too hard to get a glove on it. When Fredricksen visited
the Braves clubhouse to inform the team of the change, he
encountered batting coach Don Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him Ozzie Smith is retired,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Synder, the team's director of scouting and player
development, is among the newest inductees to the South Atlantic
League Hall of Fame announced over the weekend. . . . The club went
over the 1 million attendance mark with Sunday's crowd of 47,166.
It took 26 home dates to draw the first million. Last season, it
took 28 dates. . . . The Braves were not sad to see L.A.'s Raul
Mondesi leave town. He was 6-for-12 (.500) for the series with two
doubles and a homer. He is hitting .435 against Atlanta this season
and .340 lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
