<HEADLINE>
2 SENATORS SEEK LIMITS ON FCC  
 JOSTLING FOR SHARE OF E-MORTGAGES  
 HIP JOINS HIP WITH LITTLE ADO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   2 SENATORS SEEK LIMITS ON FCC
</P>
<P>
   Firing their latest shot at the Federal Communications
Commission, Senate leaders have introduced legislation that would
eliminate the agency's authority to review most mergers in the
industries it regulates.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who heads the commerce committee,
announced the legislation Wednesday, the same day his committee
held a politically charged oversight hearing on the FCC's
operations.
</P>
<P>
   During that hearing and in an earlier statement on the Senate
floor, McCain took William Kennard, chairman of the five-member
commission, to task for his office's handling of the pending merger
of the regional Bell companies SBC and Ameritech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, the FCC's already faltering merger process hit
rock bottom when a staff member and ostensible antitrust expert
heading up the FCC's review of the SBC-Ameritech merger _ which the
Department of Justice has already approved _ publicly proclaimed
that unless the FCC imposed major conditions, the proposed
transaction `flunks the public interest test,''' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine either the Federal Trade Commission or DOJ
countenancing such happenings during the course of their merger
review processes?'' McCain asked, referring to the Department of
Justice. ``I think not. This appalling unprofessional behavior by
the FCC staff drove the value of SBC and Ameritech stock down over
$4 billion, and it confirmed that if this is what passes for FCC
merger review expertise, the FCC has no business being in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill by McCain and Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who is chairman of
the judiciary committee, would end the FCC's authority to
investigate telecommunications mergers except when the Department
of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission declined to review
them. In those cases, the FCC's oversight would be limited to 60
days.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the telecommunications industry was the only
industry subject to multiple reviews.
</P>
<P>
   At the FCC, Kennard defended his agency's role in the process,
saying that the FCC's review goes beyond that of the Department of
Justice by looking at the impact such mergers have on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   _ JERI CLAUSING
</P>
<P>
   JOSTLING FOR SHARE OF E-MORTGAGES
</P>
<P>
   The online mortgage business is heating up.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit's Quicken Mortgage is planning to introduce an updated
World Wide Web site on Wednesday that will include offers of home
equity loans and loans to people with spotty credit histories.
Meanwhile, the industry leader in online mortgages, E-Loan, is
awaiting final approval from the Securities and Exchange Commission
for an initial offering of stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 1 percent of all home mortgages were arranged
online last year, the business is gaining momentum. Quicken
Mortgage, whose users took out $600 million in loans in 1998,
arranged $400 million in loans in the first three months of 1999,
said Alison Berkley Wagonfeld, an Intuit group product manager.
</P>
<P>
   On the Quicken Mortgages Web site, at www.quickenmortgage.com,
customers will be able to do more than shop for mortgage rates and
types. They will be able to check, at no charge, whether their
credit is solid enough to qualify them for mortgages and, for $6.95
plus tax, obtain credit reports. Users will also be able to get
preapproval for mortgages, download preapproval letters and shop
for second mortgages and home equity lines of credit. Quicken
Mortgage has at least 15 lenders in each state available through
the site, Ms. Wagonfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan, based in Dublin, Calif., closed $1 billion in loans last
year through its Web site, www.eloan.com. More than half of its
loans are outside California, where it started in 1992 as a
mortgage broker before moving to the Web in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   HIP JOINS HIP WITH LITTLE ADO
</P>
<P>
   Think different. Dress casual. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The culture of khaki joined the colorful world of the iMac
computer last week, when Millard S. Drexler, president and chief
executive of Gap Inc., joined the board of Apple Computer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from an Apple news release noting Drexler's
``expertise in marketing and retail,'' the companies did not seem
to have much to say about the move, which adds a seventh director
to an Apple board that already included Larry Ellison, chief
executive of the Oracle Corp., and Jerry York, former chief
financial officer of IBM and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler, formerly the chief executive of the fashion designer
Ann Taylor and now also overseer of the Gap brands Banana Republic
and Old Navy, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   He ``is pleased to join the board; that much can be assumed,''
said a Gap spokesman, Alan L. Marks. ``Beyond that, there's really
nothing else to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about the presumed synergies between the two hip San
Francisco Bay Area companies? Or maybe combining Gap's toned-down
palette with the iMac's fruit-candy color options? ``You'll have to
ask Apple that,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A khaki-colored iMac?'' said a deadpan Greg Jones, an Apple
spokesman. ``I'm not going to speculate on that at the moment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
