<HEADLINE>
CLIFFORD IRVING GETS THE LAST LAUGH VIA THE NET 
JOURNALISTS COMING HOME FROM THE WAR 
SHARING A LAWYER RAISES QUESTION OF ETHICS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFFORD IRVING GETS THE LAST LAUGH VIA THE NET
</P>
<P>
   It has taken 27 years, but one man's fabled literary hoax is
finally a hardcover book _ bound, printed, packaged and sold
exclusively over the Internet as an ``imaginative biography'' of
Howard Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Irving, who was imprisoned for 17 months in connection
with his creation of a bogus biography of Hughes, the eccentric
billionaire, is selling a newly edited version of that rejected
manuscript through a start-up Internet publisher called
Terrificbooks.com.
</P>
<P>
   The first copies of the gold-embossed book, ``The Autobiography
of Howard Hughes,'' arrived at Irving's temporary home in Santa Fe,
N.M., last week. ``It's like an abandoned child _ I've found this
child after 27 years,'' said Irving, 68. ``I put one copy on my
bookshelf with all my other books. It was like it had come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Hughes hoax in 1972, Irving repaid his original
publisher, McGraw-Hill Book Co., his $765,000 advance and tried
unsuccessfully to persuade mainstream companies, including McGraw,
to publish the book as fiction. ``I had always gotten a cold
shoulder,'' Irving said. ``I think there was a view that the whole
thing had bloodied the nose of publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving has published more than nine books since the Hughes
incident, but he didn't find a publisher for this ``biography''
until after he became an investor and part-owner of
Terrificbooks.com. The company, also based in Santa Fe, sells books
directly to customers online. The Hughes book is its first
offering.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades since the hoax drove him to prison, Irving said
it had been hard to feel much emotion about the entire incident.
``I probably did it because I was bored and it was a challenge and
it was an adventure and I was stupid,'' he said. ``It's hard to
regret something from so long ago. I was on a talk show and
somebody asked me are you the Clifford Irving who perpetrated the
Howard Hughes hoax, and I said no. I said that because I'm not that
same person anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Irving was outraged when ``60 Minutes II''
broadcast an interview with him in May that revisited the hoax and
labeled him a ``World Class Con Man'' on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's grossly unfair to label me a con man,'' Irving said. ``I
use the analogy of a man who gets drunk and is then arrested, but
for 27 years doesn't touch a drop. And then they still call him a
drunkard.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALISTS COMING HOME FROM THE WAR
</P>
<P>
   The misery of Kosovar refugees has tugged on heartstrings across
America. But it tugs a little less frequently now, with the crisis
two months old and American television networks showing fewer
pictures of the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CBS and NBC have all scaled back the number of
correspondents they have stationed in Albania and Macedonia and
have reduced the number of reports filed from the refugee camps to
an average of one a week, per network, for the last four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Since the school shootings in Littleton, Colo., on April 20,
television coverage of the entire Yugoslavia conflict has declined,
and coverage of the refugees' situation has declined even faster.
Refugee stories made up about 30 percent of the overall coverage in
the first month after the refugee exodus began, and they make up
less than 10 percent now, according to the Tyndall Report, which
tracks subjects covered by ABC, CBS and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Although the networks still have correspondents covering the
combat inside Yugoslavia, NBC now has only one correspondent
covering the refugees (from a peak of five); ABC has one (from
three), although Peter Jennings, the anchor of ``World News
Tonight,'' plans to go to the camps this week, and CBS has none.
CNN has five, a cutback by one correspondent, and Fox News Channel
brought home its own crews and relies now on its partner B Sky B
for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Two main reasons are given for the cuts: The refugee outpouring
has tapered off, and the shootings in Littleton diverted attention
and resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the refugee crisis has eased, we've been airing fewer
reports from the camps, but we've kept enough resources in the area
to cover any developments,'' said Bill Wheatley, vice president of
NBC News, which also feeds the MSNBC cable network. ``Now you see
occasional flurries of refugees coming across, maybe 5,000 or so in
a day, but not comparable to what was happening in the early days
of the war,'' when the tide often reached 30,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Major newspapers have also cut back slightly on correspondents
in Albania and Macedonia. The Washington Post and The New York
Times have each shifted one reporter out recently, going from four
apiece to three.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   SHARING A LAWYER RAISES QUESTION OF ETHICS
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, anybody who is anybody knows everybody. But does
that mean that any journalist can write about anybody?
</P>
<P>
   It might. In its July issue, Vanity Fair is planning to publish
an article by Kim Masters about Jeffrey Katzenberg's case against
Walt Disney Co. _ even though Ms. Masters and Katzenberg share the
same lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Though most writers do not usually require legal services, right
now Ms. Masters does: Last week, Broadway Books, a division of
Random House, announced that it had canceled her book about Michael
Eisner, the chairman of Disney, and his ascension to Hollywood
power. Random House said the book was unpublishable; Ms. Masters'
lawyer _ the well-known Hollywood litigator Bertram Fields _ said
Eisner had exerted his powerful influence to have the book killed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Masters _ who is known for juicy Hollywood reporting and is
a co-author of the best-selling book ``Hit and Run: How Jon Peters
and Peter Guber Took Sony for a Ride in Hollywood'' _ hired Fields
when Broadway first suggested that it would not publish her book
earlier this year, while she was reporting her article for Vanity
Fair. At the time, Fields was representing Katzenberg, the former
Disney studio chief, in a fraud and breach-of-contract suit against
Disney, and he continues to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Masters has been sitting in on hearings on the Katzenberg
lawsuit. Disney executives are complaining, saying that Ms. Masters
cannot write fairly about a trial overseen, quite publicly, by her
own lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Masters said that before she hired Fields, she discussed the
matter with her editors at Vanity Fair, who approved the decision
as long as she disclosed the conflict in the article.
</P>
<P>
   One critic said that disclosure was not enough. Marshall Loeb,
the editor of The Columbia Journalism Review, said, ``You don't
write a story about a situation prominently involving your own
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Schieffer, a spokeswoman for Vanity Fair, said it was the
magazine's policy not to comment on articles in coming issues.
Graydon Carter, the magazine's editor, did not return phone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
