<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION OF SETTLEMENTS ANGERS PALESTINIANS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Alarmed by 11th-hour moves by the departing Israeli
government to expand Jewish settlements, Palestinian officials
warned Israel's prime minister-elect, Ehud Barak, Sunday that they
would not resume peace negotiations without a halt to settlement
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings, at a conference in the West Bank city of Ramallah,
were coupled with a call for a ``day of Palestinian rage'' against
settlements on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The actions reflected worries that Barak, who is trying to form
a broad governing coalition, might not move firmly to curb
settlement building despite his pledge to revive dormant peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian concerns were heightened on Friday when it was
disclosed that the outgoing defense minister, Moshe Arens, had
recently approved a master plan extending the boundaries of the
biggest West Bank settlement, Maale Adumim, to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would double the size of Maale Adumim, a town with a
population of 25,000, to an area larger than Tel Aviv, taking land
from five Arab villages.
</P>
<P>
   It would create a swath of land for Israeli construction
extending from the West Bank to East Jerusalem, isolating
Palestinian communities from the city. Palestinians view East
Jerusalem as the capital of a hoped-for state in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department called the move ``a provocative act by an
outgoing government'' that would ``not only sour the environment,
it would unquestionably complicate negotiations between Israel and
the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has also recently allowed
groundbreaking work for a new Jewish housing complex in the Arab
neighborhood of Ras al-Amud in East Jerusalem, and for building at
Har Homa, another East Jerusalem site known in Arabic as Jebel Abu
Ghneim.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who soundly defeated Netanyahu on May 17, has said
nothing about the recent settlement moves, avoiding policy
statements as he negotiates with parties on the right and the left
to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak is called upon to break his
silence and to take steps that will prevent the government of
Benjamin Netanyahu from continuing to make decisions that destroy
the peace process,'' said Tayeb Abdel Rahim, a senior aide to the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Rahim spoke on behalf of Arafat at the Ramallah gathering,
which was called ``The National Conference to Confront
Settlement.'' The meeting had been planned before the actions on
Thursday but took on a new urgency in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``No peace with settlements,'' Abdel Rahim said. ``The next
Israeli government must halt settlements immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Khoury, the speaker of the Palestinian legislative
council, said further talks with Israel should be made conditional
on a cessation of settlement activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not undertake any negotiations or conclude any
agreements before we hear loud and clear from the new Israeli
government and the prime minister-elect that he has decided to stop
settlement,'' said Khoury, who is better known as Abu Alaa.
</P>
<P>
   A final statement issued by the conference echoed his remarks,
declaring, ``Completion of the peace process by the Palestinian
side is conditional on immediate nullification of settlement
decisions and measures taken by the Netanyahu government.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he takes office, Barak will have the authority to suspend
settlement building and, Arens has said, even reverse the decision
to expand Maale Adumim. Barak has said he wants to keep most Jewish
settlers under Israeli sovereignty in large settlement blocs,
presumably in West Bank areas close to Israel proper, like Maale
Adumim.
</P>
<P>
   He has also pledged to maintain Israeli control over all of
Jerusalem, ruling out a withdrawal to Israel's boundaries before
the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
