<SLUG> BC-EXP-SMALL-BOOKSTORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL BOOKSTORE NOT BOUND BY ITS WALLS 
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(ms) 
 By GAYLE FELDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What was Sebastian Junger, best-selling author of ``The Perfect
Storm,'' doing in a high school gymnasium in Greenwich, Conn.,
filled with 500 children? First, feeling ``nervous,'' since he had
not been near that many teen-agers since he was one himself.
Second, sharing a podium with Linda Greenlaw, a fishing boat
captain featured in his book, whose own memoir, ``Hungry Ocean,''
has just been published.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, he was being party to the kind of creative
marketing that an independent bookstore must mount if it is to
survive in a business increasingly dominated by discount stores,
warehouse clubs, chains and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A report to be published Tuesday by the Book Industry Study
Group, a nonprofit research organization, shows that in 1998,
independents represented only 16.6 percent of outlets where books
are sold, down from 21.6 percent in 1994, and falling.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by Junger and Ms. Greenlaw to the students of
Brunswick Academy and its sister school, Greenwich Academy _ and
their speaking engagement before 200 adults later that day at the
Indian Harbor Yacht Club down the road _ had been arranged by an
independent bookseller, Warren Cassell. His quid pro quo was to
have already sold each of those 500 children a copy of Junger's
book as enrichment reading. Although Ms. Greenlaw's book was
published too late for that, by day's end it had sold 135 copies.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not all. Cassell has arranged with Brunswick to
provide speakers and books on a continuing basis. The school
benefits because it gets top-of-the-line speakers for free. Cassell
benefits because he will sell at least 500 copies of each book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
