<SLUG> BC-BBA-TWINS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CLAIM SIXTH VICTORY IN A ROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ A bizarre statistical twist transpired yesterday
in Tom Hicks' sports empire. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars scored five goals in an NHL playoff game and lost. The
Rangers scored three runs in an American League game and won. Who
would have thought Rangers pitcher Mark Clark would out-perform
Stars goalie Eddie Belfour? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He did and the Rangers enjoyed a significant victory when they
beat the Minnesota Twins, 3-2, at The Ballpark in Arlington. For
the first time this season, the Rangers scored fewer than four runs
in a game and won. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very important,'' outfielder Roberto Kelly said.
``Eventually we're going to run into a team with good pitching and
they won't let us score seven or eight runs. We've got to find
little ways to score.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, in a 2-2 game, did that in the eighth inning.
Rafael Palmeiro and Juan Gonzalez started the inning with singles,
Todd Zeile moved the runners up with a sacrifice bunt, and Lee
Stevens blooped a single to center to drive home the winning run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, coming off a 4-3 victory the night before, will
need more of that in the weeks to come. The Minnesota Twins are in
their rearview mirror. So are the Baltimore Orioles and the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers open a three-game series tonight against the Kansas
City Royals, who were second in the American League in pitching
going into yesterday's game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the Royals comes a road trip against the pitching-rich
Arizona Diamondbacks and Los Angeles Dodgers. Later in June the
Rangers face the Boston Red Sox and New York Yankees, two other
teams with formidable pitching. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers more than likely will have to win a few games
against those teams scoring fewer than four runs. They were 0-11 in
those games before yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In tight games, the pitching has to step up and the defense
has to step up,'' Stevens said. ``They did today. It's nice to win
a close game. It will help down the line in crunch time, knowing
you have the confidence to pull these kind of games out.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In doing so yesterday, the Rangers won their sixth consecutive
game, a winning streak that has come about with the resurgence of
their starting pitching. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clark did the job yesterday with his best outing of the
season, holding the Twins to two runs on four hits in seven
innings. He didn't walk a batter and struck out four. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went out there, kept the ball down, threw strikes and
got ahead of hitters,'' Clark said. ``These are the kind of games
we have to win. It's easy to go out there and win when you score 10
or 12 runs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers haven't had to do that during the winning streak.
Their starters have a 4.84 earned-run average during the streak, a
significant improvement considering they were giving a seven runs
an outing before the streak started. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You look over the last six days, I'm very pleased with the
pitching staff,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``I thought it would
only be a matter of time before they got it together. Our staff has
a much better track record than that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has a 0.46 ERA in the past six games. Jeff Zimmerman
pitched a scoreless eighth yesterday for the victory and John
Wetteland worked the ninth for his major-league leading 16th save.
He has converted 10 consecutive save opportunities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All our pitching was outstanding today,'' Oates said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars only wish their guy could have been as good. &QL; 
 &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760 &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
