<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6787 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      05-30 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Monday, May 31,
and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-AFTERMATH (SHORELINE, Wash.) _ His eyes red and
stinging Sunday from the tear gas fumes that still lingered in his
house, Fred Westphal pointed to the blood-soaked sheets crumpled on
one of his sons' beds. It was on the bed that 21-year-old Lonnie
Davis stood gasping for breath through a shattered window as he
made his last furious stand before a police sniper killed him with
a bullet to the head, after Davis' bloody rampage through two
Seattle suburbs on Friday. Westphal returned Sunday to the
four-bedroom home he's rented the past 11 years _ and for the first
time witnessed the ghoulish spectacle that took his breath away.
</P>
<P>
   By Ellis E. Conklin. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
