<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT MINDS THINK ALIKE AND DINE ALIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guess what Bill Gates served media giant Martha Stewart, the top
executives of Ford and Alcoa, and the other guests the first night
of the Microsoft CEO summit last Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   Halibut and asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what my wife and I had for dinner last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, halibut and asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   No, there were no e-mail messages passing between our kitchen
and a somewhat more elaborate one at the Gates' mansion in Medina,
Wash. But I can tell you how we both chose the same menu. Sometime
Monday morning, Bill or Melinda Gates heeded the newspaper ads and
headed for the supermarket to pick up some first-of-the-season
Copper River salmon. So did we. Obviously, we had the identical
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   At exactly the same moment we were all hollering at the top of
our lungs, ``Twelve ninety-nine a pound!!!???''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Gates' relationship with Netscape, Yahoo or the
attorney generals of 19 renegade states.
</P>
<P>
   There is a new national scandal on display at your neighborhood
seafood counter.
</P>
<P>
   What have they been feeding those fish: high-octane Winnebago
juice? Or are some Western tribes trying to run up the price of
whale blubber?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates and I aren't going to take it anymore. We opted for
halibut. If brokers drive up the price of halibut, we are prepared
to fall back and form a new defensive line adjacent to the sardine
and anchovy display at our favorite supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   To the barriers! Don't shoot until you see the white of their
tartar sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, halibut is just about my favorite seafood meal and I'm
not just saying that because I'm cheap. Even though that happens to
be the case.
</P>
<P>
   My mother prepared halibut steaks like this and I've never been
able to improve upon her simple recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Mom's Halibut
</P>
<P>
   2 halibut steaks
</P>
<P>
   10 or 12 saltine-style crackers
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs or equivalent of egg substitute
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Butter or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Bust up the crackers with a rolling pin. Don't use a food
processor or you'll have cracker dust, not crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the eggs and add a tablespoon or two of water. Mix again.
</P>
<P>
   Add salt and pepper to the crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Heat enough butter or oil to coat the bottom of a skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Dip each steak in egg, press into the cracker crumbs, then
repeat on other side.
</P>
<P>
   The steaks should produce a slight sizzle when you put them in
the pan. Lift up with a spatula after a couple of minutes. When the
cracker crumbs are golden brown, turn the halibut and cook the
other side. When steaks are golden brown outside, the halibut
should be perfectly cooked inside.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with poached asparagus and boiled new potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   If his company's stock drops to $35, Gates may have to rethink
the menu before next year's CEO summit. He could use lingcod or
some other inexpensive fish fillets to create this spicy meal,
which might have been brought back to Seattle after one of
Microsoft's recruiting trips to Bombay Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   Bombay Fish
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   One and one-half pounds fish cut into 4 fillets
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   one-half teaspoon ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   one-half teaspoon red chili flakes
</P>
<P>
   One and one-half tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup water
</P>
<P>
   Chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper the fish fillets and dust lightly with flour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a skillet and saute the fish fillets for 1
minute on each side or slightly longer for thick portions. Remove
to a warm plate.
</P>
<P>
   Add the onion and garlic to the pan and saute over medium heat
until soft, adding more oil if needed. Add to the pan the
coriander, cumin, turmeric and chili flakes and cook 30 seconds.
Add the ketchup and water and moosh everything around with a carved
wooden (or uncarved plastic) back scratcher. In the event you have
not acquired any souvenirs from the last business trip to Bombay,
you could use a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   When ingredients of the pan have been mooshed, return the fish
fillets and cook 1 minute on each side or until done.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the pan sauces over the fillets and scatter cilantro over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   This will serve Stewart, Janet Reno and two corporate CEOs. But
keep an eye on those two industrial moguls. I've heard unconfirmed
reports that they sent out last Wednesday night for pizzas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
