<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6794 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLOTREK-SFCHRON-CORR     05-30 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLOTREK-SFCHRON-CORRECTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editors: Restores credit line)   Millennium Jet Founder Has Sky-High Ambitions 
 &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Millennium Jet Inc. founder Mike Moshier is chasing two dreams that
humans have pursued almost since the dawn of time.
<P>
   He wants to fly like a bird.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants to make money.
</P>
<P>
   He's hoping that his invention, the SoloTrek Exo-Skelitor Flying
Vehicle, takes off and makes both dreams come true. And right now,
Moshier's not worried that the idea sounds as improbable as if he
were trying to fly by flapping the mythical wax wings of Daedelus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so different than anything else that exists today,''
the former Navy jet combat pilot said of his one-person flying
machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pumped a million dollars into this thing, and if I
thought it were not doable, I know I could find better uses for
that million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, secretly working out of a Santa Clara
office-warehouse, Moshier, 51, and partner Robert Bulaga, 47, an
aerospace engineer, have developed the SoloTrek XFV with money that
Moshier made from other successful Silicon Valley ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Now Millennium Jet is about three months away from the first
test flight of the SoloTrek, an eight-foot-tall contraption
designed to let a single passenger/pilot fly as fast as 80 mph, for
as long as 90 minutes and as high as 10,000 feet, all on a single
tank of regular 87-octane gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The four-cylinder, 130-horsepower engine spins a set of two
injection-molded rotor blades positioned above the pilot's head
like wings. The blades provide the thrust for vertical takeoffs and
landings and for forward motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can land anywhere the size of a dining room table,''
Moshier said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot is strapped into the SoloTrek in a standing position
and tilts the rotors to go up, down or forward using two
hand-controlled joysticks. The craft employs a high-tech retinal
eye-scan system to prevent untrained pilots from taking off. It has
sensors that adjust the craft to the pilot's weight and experience
and that can warn of engine trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Moshier says it's different than the rocket belt, the Buck
Rogers-style fuel-burning jet pack used in the opening ceremonies
of the 1984 Olympics _ also familiar from movies like ``The
Rocketeer'' and the James Bond series. Rocket belts exist and
actually fly _ but only for about 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, single-person flying machines have come and
gone, from Renaissance inventor-artist Leonardo da Vinci's 15th
century ``Orthinocopter'' to Hiller Aircraft's ``Flying Platform''
in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never gone anywhere because they've never been
practical,'' Moshier said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Silicon Valley entrepreneur believes the SoloTrek
will go where no other flying machine has gone before. Imagine, he
said, being able to soar high above the maddening rush-hour traffic
on the Bay Bridge or the Sunol Grade.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, he said, immigration agents in SoloTreks flying patrol
over the country's borders, or search and rescue workers swooping
down to help an injured hiker deep in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Jet's detailed Web site, at www.solotrek.com, even
imagines ``journalists who use SoloTrek XFV as a vehicle for their
reporting assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshier hesitated to say what he thought each SoloTrek might
cost though he guessed that it one day could sell for the price of
``a very expensive car.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Moshier and Bulaga, the company's only two employees,
believe that Millennium Jet's first customers will be the military
or government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Bulaga, who has 25 years of experience as an aeronautical
engineer, imagines ``it would be a cool thing to see'' a phalanx of
400 flying Marines headed for a beach invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Millennium Jet still has to prove that the SoloTrek actually
can fly before the company can get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   And even then, Bay Area industrialist and air historian Stanley
Hiller said the company faces a long and costly road trying to get
clearance from stringent aviation and government safety
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish them every success, but I have seen nothing new
technically to think that it's a practical machine,'' said Hiller,
who knows more than a few things about inventing newfangled flying
machines.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager in the 1940s, Hiller designed the first helicopter
to fly on the West Coast. His XH-44 ``Hiller-copter'' laid the
foundation for his Hiller Aircraft Co. of Palo Alto, one of four
companies that started the helicopter industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Hiller Aircraft designed and flew the Flying
Platform, a single-person craft that used similar ``ducted fan''
technology as the SoloTrek. The company also produced a one-person
rescue aircraft for use in the Korean War, but the conflict ended
before the aircraft could be mass produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every back yard tinkerer has an idea for a vertical takeoff
machine,'' said Hiller, who helped found the Hiller Aviation Museum
that opened last year at the San Carlos Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a single-seat rocket belt or rotor system
(aircraft) comes and goes like a wave,'' Hiller said. ``Hundreds of
people per year try and take a dream of an everyman's and
everywoman's aircraft, make it safe and sound and quiet and easy to
fly. And that has never been accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum had a panel of 20 highly regarded university
professors and aerospace engineers look into the future of aviation
and ``they did not see a practical market for small one-man
aircraft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a dream but an impractical dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moshier, though, said he is confident that he will make SoloTrek
a reality. He has made enough money from his earlier ventures
though he would welcome ``strategic partners.''
</P>
<P>
   He sold his previous venture, Talus Corp., a precision
sheet-metal fabrication company in Santa Clara, in 1997. Before
that, he was co-owner of MOPAR LLC, a Silicon Valley real estate
development company. He also had owned a company that made
workstations used for silicon wafer fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the concept of building a solo flying machine
remained ``my lifetime passion,'' he said. In a way, he already has
achieved one of his goals with the Millennium Jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is defined by doing what you like to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moshier, however, won't be trying to copy the Wright brothers
and be the first to fly the SoloTrek. He will hire a test pilot for
the experimental flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife made me promise I won't fly any higher than I am
willing to fall,'' Moshier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
