<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER BRADLEY'S ENDORSEMENT OVERSHADOWS CITY COUNCIL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The battle over the legacy of former Mayor Tom
Bradley, who died last year, is looming large in a tight Los
Angeles City Council race, centering on a disputed campaign letter
asserting that just before his death, Bradley endorsed the
incumbent councilman.
</P>
<P>
   The councilman, Nate Holden, a three-decade veteran of Los
Angeles politics who ran against Bradley for mayor in 1989, issued
the mailing days before the April 13 primary. It consisted of a
letter, written by Bill Elkins, a longtime associate and confidant
of Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins wrote that Bradley had met with Holden several times not
long before his death and at the last meeting ``made a commitment
to ask the residents of the 10th District to support Councilman
Nate Holden.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden finished first in the four-candidate primary, but he did
not garner enough votes to win outright and now faces a runoff with
the second-place candidate, Madison Shockley, a pastor and
community advocate.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement letter outraged Shockley's camp, as well as
Bradley's friends, aides and daughter Lorraine Bradley. They have
all come forward as the June 8 runoff election approaches to
express anger and skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   They say that there had long been hostility between Bradley and
Holden and that after a heart attack and a stroke, Bradley had been
unable to speak for the last two years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no Mayor Bradley endorsement,'' said David Cunningham,
whom Bradley had backed to succeed him in the 10th District when he
was elected mayor. Holden succeeded Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really wanted to see this man get animated,''
Cunningham said, ``all you had to do was mention Nate Holden's
name.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Holden said he had reconciled with Bradley in
recent years. He said he had led an effort to name the top floor of
Los Angeles City Hall after Bradley and to commission a $13,000
bust of him to be placed there. Holden said the doubters were
political and personal enemies, and he recounted the meeting in
which he said Bradley gave him his endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go out and meet him in the district, and he'd point at
things he wanted me to do _ planting trees, pulling weeds, stuff
like that,'' Holden said, adding that Bradley could communicate
with a few words and the thumbs-up sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, you know, I'm running for re-election,'''
Holden said. ``And he'd say, `good, good, good,' thumbs up. And I'd
say, `Can I count on your endorsement?'''
</P>
<P>
   Holden said Bradley had nodded yes and given him a thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins, who wrote the letter describing Bradley's endorsement,
did not return several phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said Bradley had continued to express his dislike for
Holden until three weeks before his death. City Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas, who represents the neighboring Crenshaw District,
accused Holden of deceitful politics and said the endorsement claim
had been met with disbelief and derision by council members.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th District, among the most densely populated in Los
Angeles, covers parts of Koreatown, South Central and the mid-city
area. The district has seen rapid shifts in its demographics in the
last 30 years, going from a majority white district in the early
1960s, to a majority black district in the late 1970s to a majority
Hispanic district today, as it retains pockets of Asian and
non-Hispanic white residents.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who had a reputation as a builder of coalitions across
racial lines, got his political start in the 10th District, serving
as the district's councilman in the 1960s before becoming mayor in
1973. The value of his endorsement is incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   Holden's assertion has turned what was otherwise a heated
election over municipal issues into a considerable controversy in
Los Angeles politics.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mailing, Shockley, a pastor at the 265-member
Congregational Church of Christian Fellowship and advocate of
changes in the police department and improvement in race relations,
had campaigned on plans to develop more parks and open space, bring
in more business development and give voters more opportunity for
civic participation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Shockley has sent out his own mailing, in which Lorraine
Bradley remarks: ``It is impossible for me to say whether or not my
father wished to endorse Nate Holden. I do know for a fact that my
father consistently refused to support Councilman Nate Holden on
numerous occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden counters: ``No. 1, if Bill Elkins said the mayor did it,
he did it. No. 2, I was there when he did it. They can put that in
their pipe and smoke it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
