<SLUG> BC-EXP-DENVER-COMPETE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING FOR DOMINANCE, DENVER'S 2 DAILIES KEEP READERS IN MIND
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(ms) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With street vendors hawking extra editions, two-year
subscriptions going for a penny a paper and advertising discounts
that produce some of the world's fattest newspapers, the flagship
papers of two big newspaper empires are locked in combat here.
While most American cities are one-newspaper towns, Denver has a
war that pits The Denver Post, a broadsheet owned by Media News
Group, the nation's seventh-largest newspaper chain, against The
Denver Rocky Mountain News, a tabloid owned by E.W. Scripps Co.,
the eighth-largest chain.
</P>
<P>
   While newspaper circulation stagnates around the nation, trucks
in Denver deliver 360,000 more newspapers each week than they did
at this time last year. Based on a 10.4 percent year-over-year
circulation jump for the first quarter, The News now describes
itself as ``the fastest-growing major daily newspaper in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekday circulation race is a virtual dead heat, with The
News reporting 359,068, and the Post reporting 370,423. In the
Sunday race, The Post has a wider margin, selling 523,324, compared
with 461,000 for The News.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reversing eight years of circulation declines,
The News is also creating the editorial buzz in town. Repositioning
itself as an upscale tabloid similar to Newsday, the Long Island
daily, it is generously using color, publishing new sections and
showing that it can turn on a dime to respond to breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, we asked focus groups to compare our newspaper to a
car, and they said we were a pickup,'' said Linda Sease, The News'
vice president for marketing. ``Two years later, they said, `a
sports utility vehicle.' Hey, I'll be an SUV any day _ they are
hip, trendy, young, expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
