<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-QUINN-BROTHERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUINN BROTHERS LEARN FROM EACH OTHER IN MAKING `THIS IS MY
FATHER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The eyes are the giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   You'd never know Aidan and Paul Quinn were even related if you
hadn't gazed into their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They're steely blue, intense and kind.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers are visiting Seattle for the second time to promote
their film, ``This Is My Father.'' They were here last June, along
with big brother Declan, when their movie concluded the Seattle
International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Aidan, of course, is a movie star. He's made two films a year
since his big-screen debut in 1984's ``Reckless.'' He's since acted
with the likes of Annette Bening in ``In Dreams,'' Madonna in
``Desperately Seeking Susan,'' Sandra Bullock in ``Practical
Magic'' and Brad Pitt in ``Legends of the Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   He's worked on such high-profile projects as Kenneth Branagh's
``Mary Shelley's Frankenstein,'' Barry Levinson's ``Avalon,''
Roland Joffe's ``The Mission,'' Neil Jordan's ``Michael Collins,''
Jeremiah Chechik's ``Benny and Joon'' and Al Pacino's ``Looking for
Richard.'' He's been in more than 30 films.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, on the other hand, began as an actor in the theater,
working with John Cusack and Tim Robbins (Cusack has a small role
in the film) before turning to filmmaking. ``This Is My Father'' is
his directorial debut.
</P>
<P>
   Declan provided the brooding look. The cinematographer, who
worked on such visually distinguished films as ``Leaving Las
Vegas'' and ``Kama Sutra,'' creates the mood for this poignant,
fragile film, which follows the journey to Ireland of Chicago
high-school teacher Kieran Johnson, played by James Caan.
</P>
<P>
   With his mother ailing, Johnson, accompanied by his nephew,
travels to Galway in an effort to unravel the mystery of his
long-gone father. Through the stories of an old traveler, he's
transported back to 1939. Kieran learns the story of the
star-crossed love affair between his mother and father _ also named
Kieran.
</P>
<P>
   He discovers his dad, a quiet, religious farmer, fell in love
with his mom, the 17-year-old daughter of the small town's rich
widow and landowner. Their unlikely romance brought intermittent
joy _ and ultimate tragedy _ to the couple. But it also held a
future.
</P>
<P>
   Paul says he originally wrote the script as a 1939 period piece
but struggled with it and wondered why he was telling the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading some screenplay writing notes from a class
taught by Robert McKee and he asks, `What do you want to tell a
modern audience when you're writing a period piece?' I couldn't
answer the question so I came up with the idea of a teacher and
that gave it a context and then I easily could put the generations
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Aidan says he gained quite a bit of weight to play the elder
Kieran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't hard with all the Guinness and fries, sausages and
eggs you get for breakfast over there. I had false teeth too. We
worked very hard against making the character good looking. We
wanted him to be a little on the outs in society. He's a farmer. I
felt like I knew this man; they're in my own family: shy, awkward,
simple men who speak with their bodies, not words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is My Father'' had an even more personal investment for
the Quinns. Paul says he entered into the project ``with a certain
amount of fear'' at working with his family but acknowledges it
became a blessing because they had already ``left a ton of baggage
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a shorthand with Declan and Aidan,'' he said. ``I knew
their aesthetics. If I had worked with other actors or a different
cinematographer, it would have taken weeks to learn their
sensibilities. And we didn't have time for that sort of
education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is My Father'' is, as the 39-year-old director and writer
insists, not about the Quinn clan's own professor father, but a
spin on a childhood story their mother told them. It co-stars a
shining bunch of Irish talent _ Brendan Gleeson, Stephen Rea, Donal
Donnelly and Colm Meaney.
</P>
<P>
   The cast worked for scale and Paul's vision impressed everyone
involved with the film. Aidan _ who says the best directors ``allow
all the departments to contribute; they aren't auteurs'' and the
way to go is to ``hire creative people and actors and let them do
their jobs'' _ says his younger brother is a natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the best films I've been in and possibly the
best part I've ever played. I've played Hamlet, though, and,'' he
says, laughing, ``I can't quite compare it to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this film has spoiled me in a way and spurred me on to get
involved with creating my own work. I'm really frustrated with the
lack of good parts that come my way from the studios. There are
those top five guys and that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to work with my brothers and sister again but
it's a matter of logistics. Our sister Marian has just written a
beautiful script that we may do in December. I'll have a small role
and Declan will shoot it, so once again, three of us will be
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Aidan says part of his enthusiasm for creating his own work
stems from the fact that he turned 40 in March. And while Hollywood
is known for being rough on its leading ladies, Quinn, who just
finished ``50 Violins'' with Meryl Streep, says he's ``going
through a complete crisis right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read this report that came out that says actors turning 40
face a significant drop in roles. Of course it's worse for women,
but I'm definitely concerned about it. So again, I have to create
my own options, get things produced and buy little novels to
develop for film.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, he sheepishly acknowledges that he could go on ``ad
nauseum'' about Streep.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's remarkable,'' he gushes. ``I've never met anyone as
graceful; she has a sense of humor, she's very funny, down to earth
and a great mom. And she loved our film,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   But Aidan isn't as generous about the up-and-coming troop of
young actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet a lot of actors who ask for advice and when I query
them and look into their eyes and say `What do you want?' you
realize what they really want is to be famous. They aren't drawn
into the craft for the love of it. That's a dangerous way to
approach it. Certain people can do it, but not many. Most fall into
obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really been scared of obscurity before,'' he
laments, ``but now I am because of the age factor. And obscurity
happened to me once. I did `Reckless' and made 15, 20 thousand
dollars. I remember thinking there was no way I could spend all
that money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I partied and took everybody I knew out to eat. And I ran out
of cash. I took a job waiting tables. I was so embarrassed because
I'd meet all these actors from the theater and they'd sit in my
section and say, `Hey Aidan, how ya' doin'? Didn't you just make a
movie. What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   With his salad days behind him, could he depend upon his family
for a juicy role?
</P>
<P>
   Paul says he never thought of Aidan to play Kieran when he wrote
his script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew that,'' says Aidan. ``I thought you wrote it with
me in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think of anyone when I was writing the script,'' Paul
responds. ``After I finished I thought, `How stupid. Why didn't I
tailor this for Aidan?' In retrospect I'm glad I didn't. He became
more soulful and touching than I imagined because he came from the
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Paul admits he learned a valuable lesson from his
first foray into mainstream filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned how much an image can tell a story. You don't need
many words. But I had to learn the lesson by going through the
process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
