<HEADER>
A6800 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     05-30 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASAMAYOR BOXING AS MUCH FOR HIS FUTURE AS PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oscar De La Hoya won the United States' only
boxing gold medal in the 1992 Olympics. In the same Games, Joel
Casamayor captured one of the seven golds won by Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   To say that they have taken divergent paths since then is a
gross understatement: De La Hoya has parlayed his triumph into fame
and riches, while Casamayor, one of the great amateurs of his time,
has largely faded from memory outside his Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
   Until now?
</P>
<P>
   Casamayor, 27, defected from his communist homeland three years
ago and, working with trainer Joe Goossen in Van Nuys, could become
the first Cuban of his generation to win a professional world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   He faces Antonio Hernandez on June 19 in Miami for the right to
challenge WBA junior lightweight champion Takanori Hatakeyama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get the belt,'' he said through his co-manager
Leonardo Edgar, who heads Miami-based Team Freedom, which is
composed of a dozen Cuban defectors and other Latin American
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I'll decide what I'm going to do with my life.
Right now, that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, life wasn't so bad in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Casamayor, who grew up in Guantanamo, where as a child he'd
watch in awe as American jet fighters flew to and from the U.S.
military base, is close to his family. He treasures his 5-year-old
daughter, with whom he said he was inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   And he was a star, at least by Cuban standards. Wherever he
went, people knew him and treated him like the gold of his medal.
He was poor but he was special
</P>
<P>
   His success in the ring also allowed him unique privileges, the
most cherished being travel. He had the opportunity to compete
around the world, while the vast majority of his countrymen were
trapped within Cuba's borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in sports, in any sport, are definitely treated
differently,'' Casamayor said.
</P>
<P>
   They're also treated poorly, which was one reason he ultimately
fled.
</P>
<P>
   Casamayor had trained diligently and intended to compete in the
1996 Olympics in Atlanta. However, by the time he and the Cuban
boxing team traveled to Guadalajara, Mexico, to train in the months
before the Games, he had made a decision: He had accepted an offer
while still in Cuba from someone who would help him and teammate
Ramon Garbey defect in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He agonized over the decision.
</P>
<P>
   He would have to leave his family for an indefinite period of
time, perhaps forever. He couldn't even tell them about it
beforehand. He trusted no one, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the risk of being caught. If the plan failed, he
could say goodbye to his privileged life and any hopes of gaining
what he coveted most _ freedom and the opportunity to fight
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Then he thought of the suffocating pressure applied to him and
his teammates by Cuban boxing authorities _ which, to him, was
symbolic of the country's oppressive society _ and he knew what he
had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had doubts (in Guadalajara), I thought of the pressure
they put on me to make 119 pounds,'' he said. ``It was very, very
difficult to make that weight but they threatened me: `If you don't
make weight, we'll send you back to Cuba.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That stayed in my head; that made me strong.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, he told his chaperone that he was going to walk down
the street to buy a bottle of water and would be right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still waiting there for me I think,'' he said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment wasn't easy in the United States, even in his new
home of Miami, which has a large Cuban population.
</P>
<P>
   One, he was no longer a star.
</P>
<P>
   He would be recognized occasionally. For example, he attended an
autograph session in Miami with close friend and fellow defector
Livian ``El Duque'' Hernandez of the Florida Marlins, and a few
people of Cuban heritage asked for his signature.
</P>
<P>
   However, that was the exception. In fact, he had become just
another promising fighter who dreamed of a world championship and
the money that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   And, two, he pined for his family _ particularly his little
girl, who he had with a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He cried as he lay in bed many nights in the beginning, he said.
And, even now, he misses his mother, siblings and daughter
terribly, particularly because Cuban authorities pressured his
mother to sever ties with him and he hasn't spoken to anyone back
home in four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter, that's the toughest thing,'' he said. ``It's
very, very painful. In Cuba, I used to be with her all the time. I
even took her to my fights. I'm sure she misses me a lot, I'm sure
it's frustrating for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is more important than anything, believe me. But,
here, I'm able to help them. I always find a way to get them money,
and my dream is to bring them here. That's my biggest dream.''
</P>
<P>
   First things first: Casamayor (17-0, with 11 knockouts) must win
a world championship before the money rolls in.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, who took over Casamayor's training about a year ago
largely because of distractions in Miami, described the left-handed
fighter as a cross between Pernell Whitaker and Michael Nunn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his boxing skills, honed in Cuba's remarkable amateur
system, are impeccable. Sparring partner Carlos Hernandez, a
contender himself, described Casamayor as ``sooooo smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he has had to adjust to the professional style of
boxing. That includes adding power to his punches and the ability
and willingness to exchange blows inside.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has learned a great deal under Goossen. And Goossen
likes what he sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won everything there is to win as an amateur,'' Goossen
said. ``The Pan Am Games, the Olympic Festival, the Olympics,
everything. He's a winner. He wins no matter the difficulties along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see him falling short of winning this title,
especially because Joel made the commitment to leave Florida and
his old trainer and come out here. Even after his last two fights
he went home for one, two weeks and then came right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's giving me 100 percent. That makes me work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, as Casamayor said, ``I want to be a star
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Add Casamayor: The Casamayor-Hernandez fight is for the
``interim'' WBA title, according to the fight organizers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the winner must face Hatakeyama to become the true
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Felix and Oscar: Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad did what he had to do
Saturday. He whipped relative unknown Hugo Pineda of Colombia in
four rounds to set up the tentative Sept. 18 bout against Oscar De
La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the fight, Trinidad said he expects a deal to
be reached very soon. His father, Felix Sr., the biggest obstacle
to the agreement, wouldn't go as far as his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can reach an agreement, especially after this
demonstration that Tito just gave,'' he told a Puerto Rican
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, machine-like, looked spectacular Saturday. However,
such a victory over a no-name like Pineda means very little. De La
Hoya has rendered such opponents _ Patrick Charpentier, for example
_ just as helpless.
</P>
<P>
   Weighty issue: Trinidad reportedly had to shed 18 pounds in two
months to make the 147-pound limit for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He could be in trouble if he has difficulty getting down to
welterweight for the De La Hoya fight. That kind of weight loss,
while not unusual, tends to sap energy.
</P>
<P>
   Another walkover?: Light heavyweight champion Roy Jones Jr.
(39-1, 33 KOs) will face one of his biggest challenges when he
climbs into the ring with Reggie Johnson (39-5-1, 24 KOs) on
Saturday in Biloxi, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   However, that doesn't mean it's a !ital!significant!off!
challenge. The fact is no one in or near his weight class is
capable of giving him serious trouble. That includes Johnson, who
will lose a one-sided fight.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will be the only fighter in the world to have a
unified title. Jones holds the WBC and WBA belts while Johnson is
the IBF champ.
</P>
<P>
   Also on that card, which will be televised by HBO, Robert Garcia
(32-0, 24 KOs) of Oxnard will defend his IBF junior lightweight
belt against Derrick Gainer (27-4, 17).
</P>
<P>
   Garcia had trouble against the slick Gainer before winning a
close decision the first time the two fought. It probably won't be
any easier this time.
</P>
<P>
   And Vassili Jirov (20-0, 18 KOs), who fights capable Arthur
Williams (30-4-1, 22 KOs), remains intriguing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
