</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Swede it is for Indy 500 winner
 &HT;    By Ron Ware
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Nobody waves the red, white and blue, especially
on Memorial Day weekend in the heartland, quite like Anthony Joseph
Foyt, who till his dying breath will insist the grittiest race car
drivers are those who learn their trade on the dusty, backwater
dirt tracks.
</P>
<P>
   With maybe a few exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Brack, a slightly built 33-year-old from Karlstad, Sweden,
ended more than two decades of frustration for Gasoline Alley's
leading denizen with a stunning victory in Sunday's 83rd
Indianapolis 500, taking the lead with just over a lap to go when
Robby Gordon lost a gamble trying to stretch his fuel.
</P>
<P>
   For the 64-year-old Foyt, how Swede it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody laughed when I got a foreigner,'' said a grinning
Foyt, who scored the last of his four victories here as a driver in
1977 and has competed solely as a team owner since 1993. ``But I
changed his papers and moved him to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't too bad, is it?'' he asked, turning to his protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little hot,'' Brack politely responded. He didn't
specify whether he was talking about the weather or his owner's
legendary temper.
</P>
<P>
   But Foyt, a twinkle in his eyes, was all smiles after Brack led
a 1-3-6 finish for his three-car team, with red-blooded Americans
Billy Boat and Robbie Buhl following him across the line. He
finished 6.5 seconds ahead of Jeff Ward, with Gordon salvaging
fourth place, the last driver on the lead lap. Rookie Robby McGehee
- whose crew chief, Steve Fried, was critically injured in a
pit-road accident - completed the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring two-time champion Arie Luyendyk and brash Greg Ray were
considered the men to beat, but each took himself out in crashes
just five laps apart after combining to lead 91 of the first 120
trips around the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the door for Brack - whose name is pronounced
``Breck'' - but Gordon rolled the dice and pitted for fuel under
caution with 35 laps to go while the other contenders remained out.
When Brack and the others came in during another yellow six laps
later, Gordon moved to the head of the pack - seemingly in command,
provided his fuel supply lasted.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Brack, driving an Oldsmobile Aurora-powered Dallara,
was conceding anything. He sliced what had been a 3.5-second
deficit with five laps to go to just 1.5 seconds with two laps
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   And then Gordon, the only CART regular competing in the Indy
Racing League event, veered onto pit road, his tank nearly dry,
eliciting a roar from the crowd of 330,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to take second,'' Brack said, insisting he
would have caught Gordon, anyway. ``That's why I was running so
hard at the end. I took a few chances, really. Being second in a
race like that isn't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, alternately nicknamed Flash Gordon and Crash Gordon for
his full-throttle style, was devastated. One of Foyt's many former
drivers, he was trying to provide billionaire John Menard his first
victory at Indy in a drought nearly as long as Foyt's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just very frustrated,'' Gordon said. ``We just made one
mistake - it didn't pick up the last two gallons (of fuel) or we
didn't get the last two gallons in the car. One mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also all it took to sideline Luyendyk, who crashed on lap
115 trying to get past 20th-place Tyce Carlson, and Ray, who pulled
into the path of Mark Dismore exiting his pit five laps later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving with so much confidence,'' said Luyendyk, who
announced last year he would retire following the race. ``Maybe the
confidence bit me. Maybe I should have waited longer to pass the
yellow car (Carlson). I thought he moved to the right, then he
moved back (down) on me. I had to slow down, and that upset the
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carlson: ``I gave him all the room in the world. I don't
know why everybody's asking me all these questions.''
</P>
<P>
   One mistake also was all it took to produce the day's only
serious injury. With spectator safety at the forefront following
the deaths of three fans at an IndyCar race earlier in the month -
cars were equipped to keep wheels and suspension pieces attached in
the case of a wreck - the only harm came not to a spectator or
driver but to a crew member.
</P>
<P>
   Fried, crew chief and right front tire changer for McGehee, was
catapulted through the air when Jimmy Kite tried to leave his pit
on lap 10, collided with the incoming Jeret Schroeder and veered
into Fried. The Mentor, Ohio, resident was listed in critical but
stable condition Sunday night at Methodist Hospital, where a
spokesman said he was alert and following commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hard on the brakes, but there was nothing I could do,''
said Kite, whose steering was broken in the collision. ``It's the
most helpless feeling you can have.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack, who averaged 153.176 mph and stands to collect more than
$1.5 million at tonight's victory dinner, was still basking in his
victory nearly an hour later when a phone call came from his
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, his patience wearing thin after several minutes, finally
implored him to hurry up and get back to the garage area with him.
</P>
<P>
   A smile reappeared when somebody informed Foyt the caller was
the king of Sweden, Carl XVI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to show you the King of Houston,'' he bellowed.
</P>
<P>
   Brack hung up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
