<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT-BAT BY AT-BAT, JETER'S STAR IS ASCENDANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ As he waits his turn to bat from the on-deck circle,
Derek Jeter glances curiously at the fans sitting in box seats
nearby, like a playful seal checking for youngsters outside his pen
at the zoo. If somebody engages him, Jeter will answer with a grin.
Sometimes he sees a child and asks, ``Think I should swing at the
first pitch?''
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, dozens of fans can say they chatted with Jeter
in 1999, the season he evolved from a star to perhaps the American
League's best player. With three more hits in the Yankees' 8-3 easy
victory Sunday over David Wells and the Blue Jays, Jeter improved
his batting average to .374. He has reached base in each of the
Yankees' 48 games this season, and it is as if he is getting better
and better every day.
</P>
<P>
   How good is Jeter now? ``If he makes an out,'' Scott Brosius
said, ``then you know he's due for a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu threw five and one-third innings effectively _ good
enough, said Manager Joe Torre, to keep his spot in the rotation,
and good enough to push the Yankees' string of victories to five.
As the Yankees begin a homestand Monday against the Cleveland
Indians, they have won eight of their past 10 games and are playing
exceptional baseball once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees beat on Wells, who did a great impression of a
pitcher who is hurt or distracted. Wells recently complained of a
bad back, and the left-hander _ who usually has impeccable control
_ threw a ball on the first pitch to eight of the first 10 batters
he faced, generally struggling to bend forward and finish his
delivery. He walked Chuck Knoblauch to start the game, the eighth
time Wells has walked a leadoff hitter this year; he walked a
leadoff hitter only three times last year. He allowed 29 walks in
1998, and he has surrendered 27 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Wells had hoped to sign a three-year contract extension with the
Blue Jays, but Toronto officials slowed negotiations, and Wells is
apparently not happy about it. After he gave up eight runs in five
and two-thirds innings and saw his earned run average increase to
6.30 Sunday, Wells did not hang around to discuss his impressions
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Wells might be the best postseason pitcher of this era and was
the Yankees' best pitcher during their remarkable 1998 season, but
all the doubt that swirls around Wells _ about his physical
condition, about his attention to detail throughout the regular
season _ is why the Yankees rushed to trade him for Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of innings,'' Toronto Manager Jim Fregosi
said, ``he threw 50 pitches. Then he had some easy innings and then
he just lost it. He started huffing and puffing a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter had three hits against Wells _ a hit-and-run single in the
first inning, a two-run single in the second inning and a
run-scoring single in the sixth inning. He went 8-for-12 in the
three-game series and leads the league in hits with 70. Before
Sunday's game, Jeter ranked in the league's top 10 in batting
average, runs, total bases, triples, on-base percentage and
slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is on track to compile 236 hits, the most for a Yankee
since Don Mattingly had 238 hits in 1986. He is on a pace to score
138 runs and drive in 112. A .374 average over a full season would
be the highest since Joe DiMaggio batted .381 in 1939, when he was
24. Jeter turns 25 next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't paused a bit to look in the mirror and say, `How
good I am,''' Torre said.``He's just concentrating on getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter used to chase pitches out of the strike zone, particularly
when he was behind in the count, but his final at-bat against Wells
is as good example as any of how he has improved. He fell behind,
no balls and two strikes, and fouled off a low curveball, effective
defense against the strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Wells tried to get Jeter to swing at an inside fastball, but he
did not; then, when Wells threw another inside fastball, Jeter
fought off the pitch with his inside-out swing, punching the ball
to right field. ``He's made great adjustments from last spring to
where we are now,'' Torre said. ``His approach at the plate is much
improved.''
</P>
<P>
   His two-run single gave the Yankees a 4-1 edge, but the Blue
Jays rebounded in the third inning, scoring two runs. Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, went to the mound and
encouraged Irabu to stop being so tentative, to throw his pitches
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Joe Girardi began calling for Irabu's curveball, over
and over, and time and again Irabu used this to get ahead in the
count, before finishing off hitters with his fastball and forkball,
as well as his new pitch _ a cut fastball he used only against
right-handed batters. Irabu settled down, and while walking off the
field one inning, Jeter came by and encouraged him.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that is what Irabu thinks Jeter was saying. ``I put
on a face like I understood him,'' Irabu said through his
interpreter, George Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Irabu can tell his grandchildren that Jeter said
something to him in 1999, the year Jeter evolved from a star into
perhaps his league's best player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
