<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-LEGISLATURE-ANAL     05-30 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LEGISLATURE-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS `CORE AGENDA' DONE IN TEXAS LEGISLATURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Analysis logo needed) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ So much attention has been focused during the
76th Legislature on Gov. George W. Bush's presidential aspirations
that one lobbyist recently quipped that Texas lawmakers were
wrapping up their ``New Hampshire session.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has had some rough moments during this biannual session,
which ends its regular run Monday. And until he was forced to
personally try to salvage a significant part of his tax cut
package, his leadership was usually so low-key as to be invisible.
</P>
<P>
   But if he does as well in next winter's New Hampshire primary as
his program did overall during the past five months in Austin, he
will face an early test of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor's biggest legislative defeat was the
rejection of a pilot program to allow some students to use
tax-backed vouchers to attend private schools. He didn't get the
tough welfare sanctions he proposed during his re-election
campaign, and his tax cuts went down to the wire in the session's
closing hours.
</P>
<P>
   But his wins outnumbered his losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he basically got his core agenda. He was successful,''
said Texas Republican Chairwoman Susan Weddington.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, who battled Bush, at least
indirectly, on the session's most emotional issue, a hate-crimes
bill that died during a nasty partisan fight in the Senate, also
said the governor ``came out well.''
</P>
<P>
   But some detractors questioned Bush's leadership capabilities
and how much credit he personally deserved for the successes on his
score card.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said that if Bush
looks good, it's because of the hard work of Democratic lawmakers.
``He has not showed any leadership. He's been there to say, `Me,
too,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the session's major accomplishments, Bush can list a bill
requiring parents to be notified before their minor daughters can
have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most significant piece of abortion-control legislation
to be passed by the Texas Legislature since the U.S. Supreme Court
legalized abortions 26 years ago. And it could boost Bush's support
among critical conservative voters in Republican primaries
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real test of his ability and the ability of
Republican legislators,'' Weddington said.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.7 billion tax cut compromise being debated late Sunday
was about $1 billion less than Bush proposed during his re-election
campaign. Democratic legislators insisted that more of the state's
budgetary surplus be spent on teacher pay raises and other
education issues than the governor had advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Although lower than the governor's goal, the tax cut is enough
for Bush to describe as ``substantial'' and claim victory, much as
he did two years ago when the Legislature approved a $1 billion
property tax break for homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of tax reductions would vary widely among taxpayers,
and some people would hardly notice any relief. But legislators,
governors _ and presidential candidates _ use collective figures
when they talk about tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be viewed as a good, strong legislative
session,'' predicted Bush, who, nevertheless, had vowed to call
lawmakers back into special session if the tax-cut and education
package failed.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bush-supported proposals that will become law include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lowering the drunken driving limit from .10 to .08 blood
alcohol content.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deregulation of the electric industry to encourage
competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Automatic detention for juveniles caught illegally carrying
guns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restricting lawsuits over the Y2K computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restricting social promotions in the public schools, although
the Legislature softened the governor's original proposal that
promotions be based solely on whether students pass the state's
standardized achievement tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Funding for 380 new caseworkers for abused children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing the state school bond guarantee for classroom
construction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Additional funding for reading programs in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) is coming out on all cylinders. I can't imagine a
better program to do something with,'' said veteran Austin
political consultant George Christian, a Democratic supporter of
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   However, Christian, a former press secretary for President
Lyndon B. Johnson, said that the legislative session's potential
effects on a Bush run for the presidency were overrated _ partly
because of the governor's popularity in Texas and around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is he could have had a disastrous session and done
all right because that's not what people are going to be looking
at,'' Christian said. ``People who are for Bush are for Bush for
other reasons than his legislative program. To them, it's his
style, personality, outreach, the same things that carried him this
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Christian added, he faces a ``weak'' field of opponents
for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not exactly running against King Kong out there.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Malcolm, the state Democratic Party leader,
said it will take more than personality to get Bush to the White
House. ``He's going to have to prove to me that he's more than a
smile, a handshake and a how-do-you-do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's admirers and detractors alike agreed that his budding
presidential campaign overshadowed much of the session's work and
often made lawmakers question the governor's _ and each other's _
motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cafeteria talk from the beginning of the session has been
that this is far more about what's good for New Hampshire than
Texas. This is the New Hampshire session,'' said one anti-voucher
lobbyist, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it (the presidential race) was dominant, but
it was always there,'' added Sen. Troy Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Many Capitol insiders suspected Bush's insistence on tax cuts
was to impress conservative Republican voters in New Hampshire and
other states as much as to help out Texans.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic legislators who fought the governor for a better
deal for teachers and consumers also raised questions in the
supercharged atmosphere of presidential politics. Were their
differences with the governor strictly philosophical, or were they
trying to embarrass Bush before a national audience?
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said presidential politics was the main reason that
Democrats made a strong push for a hate-crimes bill that protected
homosexuals as well as racial and religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, he believes, was to put Bush on the spot on an issue
that has drawn international attention in the wake of a black man's
dragging death last year in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, the Democrat who sponsored the hate-crimes bill, which
was named for the dragging victim, James Byrd Jr., called Fraser's
theory ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've carried that bill for five sessions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said the Republicans, if anybody, were playing politics
with that proposal. Although Bush never publicly endorsed or
opposed the bill, he made it clear that he opposed special
protections for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said that Bush, fearing a negative reaction from
conservative Republican voters, ``twisted the arms of senators to
make sure he never had to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his interest in the presidency was an easy scapegoat.
``There's going to be people who figure out ways if something
doesn't go their way or something's not perfect, they all blame
presidential politics,'' he said during a rare visit to the Senate
less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He received unfavorable national publicity on another volatile
issue when, in the wake of the Colorado school shootings, he
endorsed a bill to require criminal background checks of people
buying guns from unlicensed dealers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   His endorsement, however, came after a House committee had
already killed a gun show bill, which the governor had made no
effort to push. He said the issue should be addressed in federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Sunday how other Americans may view his record this
session, Bush replied: ``I do what I think is right. What we did in
this session is good for Texas, and that's what matters to me the
most.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
