<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DASH-REVIEW-NYT     05-30 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DASH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DASH AND LILLY': THE HELLMAN-HAMMETT ROMANCE, HEAVY ON THE
CLICHES
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(jw) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a delicious escapist quality to mythic romances in
which the characters' rough edges are smoothed away and every
quarrel reflects the lovers' incendiary charm. The decades-long
affair of Lillian Hellman and Dashiell Hammett certainly lends
itself to that treatment, and if ``Dash and Lilly'' had merely
given their legend a romantic gloss, the film might have been
enjoyable pap.
</P>
<P>
   But this trite movie does worse things than clean up Hellman and
Hammett's messy affair. It wastes a perfectly cast Sam Shepard and
a fiercely energetic Judy Davis on an unspeakable script, directed
by Kathy Bates, the actress, with an unfailing adherence to
cliches.
</P>
<P>
   The first shot is so stale it should have been banned years ago:
a typewriter, and a hand stubbing out a cigarette in an ashtray.
Soon the camera moves up the long legs of a glamorous blonde who
turns out to be, amazingly, Hellman. As Kitty Carlisle Hart so
delicately puts it in an American Masters profile of Hellman
(coming next month), ``She was no, what we used to call, oil
painting.'' As that documentary makes clear, Hellman was a
conventionally unattractive woman who believed herself to be sexual
catnip to men. Such fascinating paradoxes have no place here. Ms.
Davis brings so much Hollywood elan to the role that it makes Jane
Fonda's airbrushed portrayal of Hellman in the film ``Julia'' seem
tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dash and Lilly'' begins in 1952, with Hellman about to be
called before the House Un-American Activities Committee. She
flashes back to 1930, and suddenly she is an even more glamorous
redhead in a red dress. She and Hammett take one look at each other
in a nightclub, and they're off. They drink, they throw glasses,
they cheat, they throw bottles, he writes ``The Thin Man,'' she
writes ``The Children's Hour,'' she becomes famous, he writes
nothing, and then they drink some more.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's Hammett is handsomely craggy and gray haired, his
gentle soul apparent beneath his drunken furies. It is an appealing
performance. Since he and Ms. Davis are asked to play icons rather
than people, that is the best anyone can hope for.
</P>
<P>
   The film doesn't ignore the Red Scare politics of the 1950s.
Hammett becomes a trustee of a bail fund for accused Communists and
is imprisoned for refusing to give the government names of the
fund's contributors (names he didn't even know). Ms. Davis delivers
Hellman's famous statement to the House committee, ``I cannot and
will not cut my conscience to fit this year's fashions.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film exists so the characters can float through pretty
period settings of the '30s, airily dropping names: Hellman goes to
an opening night party on Broadway and asks Dorothy Parker (Bebe
Neuwirth, another waste of talent), ``Oh, Dotty, have you seen
Dash?'' This script has managed at least one improbable feat; its
Dorothy Parker is utterly humorless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DASH AND LILLY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Monday on A&AMP;E &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
