<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHEADOFTHECURVE01-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   AHEAD OF THE CURVE COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COBB: Marietta taking up annexation plea
</P>
<P>
   Marietta's Planning Commission on Tuesday will consider annexing
50 acres next to Kennesaw Mountain Battlefield National Park so a
developer can put up 142 houses. The developer, Wilmont Williams,
says he wants a density level of 2.8 houses on each acre. The
county land plan permits 2.5 houses an acre for the land at the
intersection of Barrett Parkway and Stilesboro Road. Meanwhile, the
city planning and zoning department is trying to determine whether
Williams ignored flood plains and wetlands in his calculations.
John Moore, an attorney for Williams, says none of the land
qualifies as flood plain. The subdivision to the northwest of the
park, a Williams development called Parkview at Barrett Greene, is
zoned for 3.5 houses an acre, and townhouses are scheduled to go up
on property across Barrett Parkway. The proposed development also
would adjoin Hardage Farm, a subdivision where residents have
complained about the density of Williams' proposal. After the
planning board makes its recommendation, the City Council could
make a decision at its June 9 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Tire retailer heads for two locations
</P>
<P>
   Competitors might call it ``Tire Wars: The Radial Menace.''
Clearwater, Fla.-based Morgan Tires is bringing its Don Olson
stores to metro Atlanta in a small wave that could swell. Two sites
for the tire retailer are under review in Cobb, and another five
are on the drawing boards for metro Atlanta. The two in Cobb are
headed for the intersection of Wade Green and Wooten roads and at
Johnson Ferry and Lower Roswell roads. The company operates 83
locations in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   COWETA: Horse farm tracts are being developed
</P>
<P>
   Several horse farm developments, with lots 10 acres and larger,
are being carved from some of the bigger undeveloped tracts in
south Coweta County. County officials and developers say the
projects are working because Coweta allows up to three residents to
share a driveway as long as the lots are at least 10 acres each.
That allows the developer to put in a relatively inexpensive gravel
drive instead of the more costly asphalt street with concrete curbs
and gutters. Other counties, like Fayette, don't allow shared
drives unless the street meets county subdivision standards.
Fayette officials say the private drives are often poorly
maintained and hard to find, creating problems for rescue personnel
during emergencies. Developer Sam Bowers and his father, Lisle
Bowers, are developing some of their relatives' property on Bexton
Road into horse farms, and Ed Moor is doing the same thing across
Bexton from the Bowers place. Sam Bowers says lots, which went on
sale last week, will range in size from 10 to 16 acres and will be
priced from $5,000 to $7,000 per acre.
</P>
<P>
   DEKALB: Two commissioners to battle motel plan
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb County Commissioners William Brown and Porter Sanford are
waiting until next week to decide how to fight a controversial
motel project on Covington Highway, hoping to find a magic bullet
to kill the development before a scheduled vote next month. First
the project was to be a Super 8 Motel, then a Days Inn and later,
back to a Super 8. The already-permitted project has been through
three owners, and Sanford has pointed out that could be the
developer's fatal flaw. Not so, insist zoning officials, who say
that changes of ownership during the permitting process are OK, as
long as the permitee lets the county know of the changes. South
DeKalb residents are afraid the motel will be a magnet for crime _
as are some nearby motels, police say. ``It's very difficult to
deny the owners of property their right to develop their
property,'' says Commissioner Gale Walldorff, who says the motel is
properly zoned in the C-1 classification. ``It may be legal but
it's morally wrong,'' says Brown. FAYETTE: Two commercial tracts
being cleared
</P>
<P>
   Earthmovers are quickly clearing and leveling two tracts being
developed by JDN on Ga. 85 north of Fayetteville. A tract north of
Banks Road and south of Fayette Pavilion will be filled by a Lowe's
and several outparcels. Another tract, near the intersection of Ga.
314 and Ga. 85, is being cleared for an Eckerd Drug store, an
Applebee's restaurant and two other restaurants.FULTON: Sandy
Springs fights 'cut-through' traffic
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Springs residents are devising plans to fight
``cut-through'' traffic. River Valley Road is the latest area
targeted for ``traffic calming'' measures. Sandy Springs
Revitalization will host a community meeting Wednesday to discuss a
master plan being developed by consultants for the River
Valley-Amberidge neighborhood. A network of sidewalks and bike
paths and other proposals will be discussed in what organizers hope
will be a demonstration project for the region. The meeting is at 7
p.m. at Riverwood High School at 5900 Heards Drive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writers Anne Cowles, Cheryl Crabb, Rick Minter, Chris
Reinolds and Steve Visser contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
