<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH01-COX     05-30 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    CARL WARE: COKE'S ACTION MAN
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, Carl Ware takes an assignment, a big one.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester last week designated Ware,
his chief of the Africa group, to co-chair a Diversity Advisory
Council and help defuse a controversy regarding fairness in company
employment.
</P>
<P>
   It is a role that could help the company show it treats
African-Americans and other minorities equally. That could deflate
allegations of unfairness, cement good feelings between Atlanta's
black community and the company, and prevent a tarnishing of Coke's
progressive reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Ware, a 25-year veteran of Coca-Cola, discussed his new
assignment and his career in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to talk about the class-action lawsuit against the
company, but he spoke of ways he believes corporations like
Coca-Cola can help the careers of African-Amercans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself am a good example, a proof that glass walls do not
exist at the Coca-Cola Co.,'' Ware said.
</P>
<P>
   Ware's special assignment is to chair the new council with
Senior Vice President Jack Stahl. They'll advise Ivester on
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Ware has been there before. Back in the early 1980s, with
controversy raging around the explosive demands for American
businesses to get out of South Africa, President Donald Keough
asked him to go Johannesburg, study the issues and advise the
company on what policy to pursue. Ware advised the company to
divest its holdings to support the anti-apartheid movement, and the
company did so in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, when Jesse Jackson and Operation Push came calling,
threatening to boycott the company if it did not spend more money
with African-American vendors and business partners, Ware helped to
defuse the explosive impasse that could have been a public
relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Things died down when Chairman Roberto Goizueta announced, with
a drum roll, a $50 million ``plan'' to spend money with black
businesses. Actually the company was already doing business at that
level, though privately, company sources say.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1995, Ivester asked Ware to suggest ways to encourage and
cultivate upward movement in the company by African-American
employees. He did, and in the coming months, as a pending lawsuit
makes its way through the courts, we may learn whether that has
worked.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Ware's primary job is running the Africa group,
which tries to increase Coca-Cola's businesses in 50 countries, he
will spend some time in his original role as an internal advocate
for better race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Ware comes to his job prepared and experienced. He was president
of the Atlanta City Council in 1974 when tapped by Coca-Cola as
external affairs director. He knew politics and the art of
persuasion, and he knew how to accomplish his purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and foes alike acknowledge those skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy you want on your side, in war or peace,''
said one former Coke insider.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a man of both practical and symbolic accomplishments
in race relations.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it was Carl Ware who became the first black member
of the venerable Capital City Club in the early '90s, heading off a
threat by the city to take the liquor license of any club with
restrictions against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ware, who grew up poor on a Newnan-area farm, considers himself
to be an example of what can happen under good employment policies.
</P>
<P>
   In the hourlong interview in his North Avenue office, shortly
before he was to fly to Nigeria, he recalled how various executives
guided a career that has made him one of the top six officers at
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ware was hired personally by J. Paul Austin, company chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in the early 1980s, he was tutored and given star
assignments by Keough, president and chief executive of Coca-Cola.
Ware still recalls a day in 1991 when Keough called him into his
office and made Ware's day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been pretty good about spending the company's money.
How about going out and earning some money for the company?''
Keough asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   With that Ware went to Harvard, boned up on fundamentals and
took off for London six months later for on-the-job training to run
the Africa Group. Two years later he became president of that
group.
</P>
<P>
   He heads an enormous operation that will spend hundreds of
millions of dollars in various African countries setting up
bottling and other operations and contributing to African
economies.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has overall charge of those operations, a major
portion of Ware's time is spent cultivating African governments and
bridging cultural hurdles so the company can do business, often in
partnership with the local governments.
</P>
<P>
   When Ware took his first job at Coke, he said, he occupied an
office the size of a linen closet, at $12,000 a year. That was in
January 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Ware's portfolio of Coca-Cola shares now totals $16 million,
according to recent insider trading reports.
</P>
<P>
   Are there any other senior African-American executives at
Coca-Cola?
</P>
<P>
   Ware cited a number of younger people working for him in the
Africa business, including Paul Graves, vice president for human
resources for that group, and others.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans include Juan D. Johnson, vice president and
director of learning and knowledge management; Ingrid Saunders
Jones, vice president and director of external affairs; Quinton
Martin, group manager for national accounts with independent
bottlers; Darryl Cobbin, an acknowledged whiz at brand management,
who did good work on Sprite; and Thomas Peters, vice president for
international treasury services.
</P>
<P>
   Ware and other insiders say no one outshines Carolyn H. Baldwin.
Baldwin has been controller of Europe as well as South America.
She's now president of Coca-Cola Financial Corp. and could be on a
track to be the top financial officer of the huge company.
</P>
<P>
   Ware disputes the idea that staff people such as human resources
and community relations executives are secondary to the operations
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business you either sell Coca-Cola or you support
somebody who does ....
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it in that context, there are no positions here
that are soft, and others that are cost-centers and therefore more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said, he supports efforts to make sure anybody,
regardless of race or background, has a choice between staff jobs
or ``profit-and-loss centers.'' Said he:
</P>
<P>
   ``What we should be about is to make sure there is no
discrimination against anyone on the basis of color or sex or
cultural origin in access to all kinds of businesses within our
company.''
</P>
<P>
   It is already clear that the lawsuit, whatever its merits, has
already stirred more thought than ever before about employment
policies on North Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Also, though all the talk now is about African-American
advancement, employment opportunities in the global company, with
major projected growth in Africa, South America and Asia, may also
be enhanced for many minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Clearest of all, however, is that Carl Ware seems sure to be
right in the middle of any changes that occur.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
