NYT-05-30-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSIDELINE01-COX     05-30 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDELINE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    INSIDE COLUMN
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Projects planned along Northern Arc(backslash)
</P>
<P>
   The development possibilities spun off by construction of the
proposed Northern Arc will be reduced if the road is built with
interchanges only at expressways. But the Atlanta Regional
Commission's vote last week for a limited version of the
controversial road could still give momentum to some big plans at
the scheduled six exits. Here's a quick inventory of the planned
interchanges and possible projects along the 59-mile, four-lane
road: At I-75 in Bartow, the Rollins family plans a mixed-use
project on 1,673 acres and Anheuser-Busch owns about 3,000 acres
with no specific plans; at I-575 in Cherokee, developers plan a
regional mall; at Ga. 400 in Forsyth County, plans call for
regional retailing; at I-85 and I-985 in Gwinnett, the Mall of
Georgia is under way; and at Ga. 316 in Gwinnett, the area is
planned as business and industrial parks.
</P>
<P>
   Inn, golf resort opening near Barnsley Gardens
</P>
<P>
   A swank inn and golf resort will open Tuesday next to the
historic Barnsley Gardens in Bartow County. The resort in
Adairsville is adjacent to the gardens and the ruins of the Godfrey
Barnsley home, which is more than 150 years old. The 1,300-acre
resort with 33 one-, two- and four-bedroom cottages has 70 suites.
Blue Cross and Blue Shield will hold a board meeting at the inn
this week.The gardens will be open to the public from 10 a.m. to 3
p.m. Sundays. A restaurant opens Tuesday, and the spa opens June
15. German Prince Hubertus Fugger is a partner in the company that
owns the resort, about 65 miles northwest of Atlanta. A banking and
timber baron, Fugger bought the property in 1988 for $1.5 million
and poured another $3.5 million into it.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes keynote speaker at mass transit meeting
</P>
<P>
   A collection of mass transit supporters will gather at Georgia
State University next Monday and Tuesday for a two-day symposium on
riding the rails around metro Atlanta. The keynoter is Gov. Roy
Barnes, whose Georgia Regional Transportation Authority will have a
lot to say about where future rail lines will extend through the
region. Speakers include MARTA representatives, academics and
business executives. They'll take on topics about safety on mass
transit and development around rail stations. The symposium will be
held at Georgia State's Student Center For more information call
404-651-3456.
</P>
<P>
   Henry-Butts water fight is heading to court
</P>
<P>
   Henry County's attempts to gather water for future growth is
getting the once over by a judge. The county's water authority will
be in Butts County Superior Court on Wednesday to fight a motion by
Butts County to intervene in the condemnation of Butts property for
Henry County's planned Tussahaw Creek Reservoir. About 952 of the
1,500 acres to be flooded for the Tussahaw Creek Reservoir are in
Butts, according to the lawsuit. Butts officials are challenging
Henry's authority to condemn land in another county without
permission from that jurisdiction; they are asking the court to
void the Henry water authority's condemnation of 20 Butts parcels
for the reservoir. The counties negotiated for four years over use
of the reservoir's water but wound up in court when Butts filed
suit in April.
</P>
<P>
   Email: horizon(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
