<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDERTRADING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Execs buying at InfoCure
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insider buying remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``No less impressive than the insider buying is the sustained,
relative decrease in insider selling,'' says Bob Gabele of First
Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be sure, much of the recent accumulation has occurred in
the small- to mid-cap stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabele particularly likes the renewed insider purchases _ at
higher prices _ at Atlanta-based InfoCure, a provider of health
care practice management software products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, four insiders bought a total of 30,000 shares.
``Their timing certainly paid off, as the stock climbed from $15 a
share up to $35,'' Gabele notes.
</P>
<P>
   The buying trailed off as the stock rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently, however, insiders appear to be taking advantage of a
dip in the stock and acquiring shares,'' Gabele says. ``On May 3,
three executives purchased 15,000 shares at $26.82 a share.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them were Frederick L. Fine, president and chief
executive; Richard Perlman, chairman and treasurer; and James K.
Price, executive vice president. Each bought 5,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through these acquisitions, insiders certainly appear
confident, particularly given the significantly higher share
prices,'' Gabele says.
</P>
<P>
   InfoCure's shares finished Friday at $36.87 1/2, up $3.87 1/2,
on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Among other Georgia companies
</P>
<P>
   At PAB Bankshares, R. Bradford Burnette, president, bought 2,050
shares on April 1 at $16 each, totaling $32,800. He now holds
184,110 shares directly and indirectly, worth $2,750,143 at
Friday's price of $14.93 3/4 on the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission requires insiders
(officers, directors, persons with policy-making roles) to report
their transactions within 10 days after the month in which they
took place. Beneficial owners, or those owning 10 percent or more
of any publicly held company, also must report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
