<HEADER>
A6817 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLSTREET01-COX     05-30 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market dips, but always up in long term
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock market investors can't get to their morning papers fast
enough each day to see what happened to their stocks or mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   But it never seems to matter which way the price moves _ it's a
stressful situation.
</P>
<P>
   If the price goes up, the investor worries whether it's near the
top and if he or she should sell.
</P>
<P>
   If it goes down, he or she wonders how big the loss will be, how
far the price will fall, and why did I buy that dog anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The investor's mental health might be helped by looking at stock
prices only once a month.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1990s are any guide, that means investors would have two
good months out of every three.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average posted an increase in 77 of the
113 months since Dec. 31, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   That's 68 percent of the time, which means that in only 32
months did an investor suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the decade were there three consecutive down months
for the Dow. That was August through October of 1990 _ the last
bona-fide bear market _ when the Dow fell 16.6 percent from the
beginning to the end of that period.
</P>
<P>
   The next worst decline occurred last year, when the Dow fell
15.9 percent from the start of July to the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the Dow was up 15 percent so far this year,
although it will post a May loss of about 2 percent _ following the
April gain of more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since investors will never buy once-a-month price readings for
their stocks and funds, they might adopt another way of looking at
market trends. They can anticipate what to worry about by what
month it is.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, corporate profit growth is the single most
important engine that drives stock prices higher. But companies
publish their earnings only four times a year _ typically in
January, April, July and October.
</P>
<P>
   In those months, and during several weeks in advance, Wall
Street analysts talk mostly about what impact a company's earnings
will have on its share price or how earnings generally will affect
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Between months when earnings are released, investors can turn
their attention to interest rates and inflation, as we are doing
now.
</P>
<P>
   With no immediate profit trends to focus on, we worry about how
long the economy will continue to grow and whether the long era of
weak inflation is coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Bond investors, who command the heights as world-class worriers,
have been so worried about inflation they have driven bond yields
higher by their trading.
</P>
<P>
   This has given stockholders something else to worry about, since
rising yields make bonds very attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is also worrying about inflation again,
adding to the investor's menu of things to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, about the only thing that looks reassuring is the
stock market's long, steady climb to where it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's been down from time to time. It took a
quarter-century to recoup the losses from the 1929 crash. But the
market has never stayed down.
</P>
<P>
   It has had its bubbles, and its bubbles have always burst _
after which it started the next bubble.
</P>
<P>
   The market has risen slowly, and it has risen rapidly. But over
time, it has always risen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
