r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING02-COX     05-30 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mustang keeps building on its history of success
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps no vehicle, other than the original Volkswagen Beetle,
represents the baby boomer generation more than the Ford Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustang came to the automotive scene with a fever that has
never been equaled. Unlike many of Detroit's nameplates, the
Mustang not only endures but thrives.
</P>
<P>
   To put the phenomenon of Mustang mania into perspective, more
than 6.9 million Mustangs have been sold in the 35 years since the
distinctive little rear-wheel-drive's introduction. The 1 millionth
Mustang was sold in March 1966. By comparison, the other
most-recognized American car, the Chevrolet Corvette, passed the 1
million mark in 1993, some 40 years after its launch.
</P>
<P>
   Like most success stories, the Mustang is built on a solid
history. If you think you are automobile-literate, here is a
Mustang trivia quiz (answers at bottom).
</P>
<P>
   1. When and where did the Ford Mustang debut?
</P>
<P>
   2. What was the original MSRP?
</P>
<P>
   3. How many Mustangs were sold during the car's first 12 months
of production?
</P>
<P>
   4. What were the six ``Grabber'' Mustang colors?
</P>
<P>
   5. When was the Mustang the pace car for the Indianapolis 500?
</P>
<P>
   6. When did the Boss 302 Mustang debut?
</P>
<P>
   7. What was the first V-8 engine offered in a Mustang?
</P>
<P>
   8. When was the 5.0-liter V-8 engine discontinued?
</P>
<P>
   9. What was the first movie in which a Mustang appeared?
</P>
<P>
   10. In the 1988 movie ``Bull Durham,'' Kevin Costner drove a
Mustang. What color was it?
</P>
<P>
   11. Besides President Clinton, name three celebrities who have
owned Mustangs?
</P>
<P>
   12. What is the single difference between a 1997 and a 1998
Mustang?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   1. April 17, 1964, at the New York's World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   2. The '64 Mustang debuted at $2,368 (at a time when the average
cost of a car was around $3,500). It weighed in at 2,572 pounds and
was equipped with a 170-cubic-inch, in-line six-cylinder engine,
and a three-speed, floor-mounted manual transmission.
</P>
<P>
   3. More than 417,000, a record for a new car.
</P>
<P>
   4. Grabber Green Metallic, Grabber Blue, Grabber Orange, Grabber
Green, Grabber Yellow and Grabber Lime.
</P>
<P>
   5. 1964, 1979 and 1994
</P>
<P>
   6. Late 1969
</P>
<P>
   7. 289 cubic inches
</P>
<P>
   8. With the 1995 model year. It marked the end of the V-8
overhead valve/pushrod design.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Goldfinger.'' It was a white convertible.
</P>
<P>
   10. Blue
</P>
<P>
   11. A partial roster would include baseball star Reggie Jackson
and entertainers Cher, Jay Leno, Lindsay Wagner, Jackie Cooper,
Markie Post, Robert Hayes, Debby Boone and the late Sonny Bono.
</P>
<P>
   12. The digital clock mounted on the 1998 instrument panel
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
