<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE01-COX     05-30 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protege worthy of critics' praise
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a name that suggests it's still on an upward learning
curve, the '99 Mazda Protege is a fully realized little sedan.
</P>
<P>
   A redesign has given the subcompact Protege, which seems larger
than that classification, big-sedan styling with crisp lines,
mildly wrapped-around headlamps and an overall appearance that
suggests it's from Europe, not Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Protege falls into that woeful category of
things, people and places that are critically acclaimed but
overlooked by the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our minds, the Protege has always stood out,'' says
Automobile magazine, which usually focuses on upscale cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matches the class leaders in nearly every respect,'' says
Consumer Guide.
</P>
<P>
   As the test Protege ES demonstrated, both the praise and the
mild warning that it may lag behind Ford Escorts, Honda Civics and
other competitors in a couple of areas are deserved. The most
easily noticed shortcomings are lack of initial acceleration and
rear doors that fail to facilitate entry and exit by adults because
the rear wheel wells limit their bottom width.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those areas, it's difficult to fault Mazda for anything
but a propensity _ shared with many manufacturers _ for creating
capitalized phrases to praise its product. The Protege has an
OptiSpace design, Triple-H construction and a Twin-Trapezoidal Link
rear suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares how it's hyped as long as the Protege seems roomy
(front and rear headroom are notably good; rear legroom is limited)
and will actually seat four adults. Too, the method of construction
does produce a car that feels solid, and the ride and handling
characteristics are commendable.
</P>
<P>
   Power is another matter. The base DX ($11,790) and LX ($13,130)
make do with a 1.6-liter four-cylinder rated at 105 horsepower,
while the sportier ES carries a 1.8 four-cylinder that yields 122
hp. The five-speed test Protege ES did move out smartly if pushed
near its redline maximum of 6,500 rpm but didn't do so without
wailing about the effort involved.
</P>
<P>
   A four-speed automatic is offered ($800), and while the
convenience it brings to stop-and-go commuting and highway cruising
is obvious, so, too, is the way it nibbles away power for pulling
off and passing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a stronger engine that gives up only about one
mpg in fuel economy, the ES has suspension changes that are
trade-offs. The 15-inch wheels look better than the standard
14-inchers and improve driveability but do nothing to soften the
ride. Body roll is negligible in all models, thanks to front and
rear stabilizer bars.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising is that anti-lock brakes are not standard. The
Protege redesign also didn't include side air bags. Both come only
in an optional package that includes a power moonroof ($1,350).
</P>
<P>
   The interior boasts easily read instrumentation, easily reached
stereo/climate controls and handy storage spaces. The seats are
firmly supportive and the interior trim, while mostly gray, does
include patterned cloth door inserts. Seat adjustability is good,
with the driver's featuring an adjustment for the angle of the seat
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Protege ES, clearly, is a leader in its class, with
reasonable pricing, plenty of standard equipment and a fun-to-drive
nature that doesn't preclude utility. Its no-frills design isn't
going to become dated anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Make car buying easier with access to Russ DeVault's auto
reviews and other Wheels features through the AJC's Stacks
Information Service. Article reprints are $7 each. Call
404-526-5668 or 1-800-756-4197.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Mazda Protege ES front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $15,455 (base: $14,925)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, side-impact beams,
height-adjustable front shoulder belts
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine with 24 valves (122
horsepower), five-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Standard features include: air conditioning, power windows and
locks, cruise control, rear defogger, tilt steering wheel, CD
player stereo with four speakers
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: floor mats, $80
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 26 mpg regular unleaded city, 30 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
