<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMISSIONS-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      05-30 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMISSIONS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SET TO SIGN COMPROMISE BILL ON GRANDFATHERED INDUSTRIAL
PLANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By BILL DAWSON 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State legislators passed a compromise bill
Sunday to create a new program advocated by Gov. George W. Bush for
older, grandfathered industrial plants to reduce their air
pollution voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he intends to sign the measure, which was approved on
a 22-6 vote by the Senate and later by the House on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, addressing one of the state's most hotly debated
environmental issues, was pieced together in last-minute
negotiations Saturday night by a House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   The version that emerged from the committee omitted a crucial
amendment _ promoted by environmentalists and added by the House _
that would have ended grandfathered plants' pollution exemption in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Although plants that were operating or under construction in
1971 are subject to some rules to protect air quality, legislators
that year granted them an exemption from having state emission
permits and the stricter pollution controls they generally require.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been calling for a voluntary program to reduce these
older plants' emissions since 1997, when it was disclosed that they
still accounted for a large share of the state's industrial
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives had said when lawmakers first approved
the exemption almost 30 years ago that these plants' air pollution
would rapidly decline as they were closed or updated.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, environmentalists and others, including the
city of Houston and editorial boards at the state's five largest
newspapers, have urged a mandatory end to the exemption.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and his industry allies, who opposed removing the
exemption from the Texas Clean Air Act, prevailed after Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry appointed a Senate team to the conference committee that
generally favored their position.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate conferees did agree to a House provision,
that would impose new and annually escalating emission fees for
grandfathered plants that don't apply for voluntary permits by
September 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little incentive in the bill,'' Bush said Sunday,
referring to the fee. ``It's proper. I'm glad it's in the bill to
encourage those that are still grandfathered to meet deadlines for
the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   But a prominent Texas environmentalist blamed the governor _ who
supported the electricity deregulation bill's end to the emissions
exemption for older power plants _ for the Legislature's failure to
get tough with other industries, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's intense opposition to mandating closing the
loophole made it impossible to achieve that goal in the conference
committee,'' said Ken Kramer, state director of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``chose to placate his polluter friends and contributors
rather than move more aggressively against grandfathered
polluters,'' Kramer charged.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Senate vote to approve the measure, Sen. J.R.
``Buster'' Brown, R-Lake Jackson, said more than 50 companies have
already volunteered for the permit program and have pledged to cut
emissions equivalent to removing 2.4 million cars from the road.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the bill's author, said he believes more companies will
volunteer once it becomes law, noting the ``strong incentive'' that
the new emission fee provides for those that don't do so.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, industrial plants pay a fee of $26 per ton of air
pollutants for the first 4,000 tons emitted each year. The bill
would remove this 4,000-ton cap for grandfathered plants that don't
apply for a permit and triple their fee annually for emissions
greater than 4,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   For a non-volunteering grandfathered plant releasing 50,000 tons
of air pollutants annually, the fee would rise from the current
$10,400 to $1.3 million in fiscal 2002 and $3.9 million the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said, however, that he doubts the fee will have a broad
impact, because state records indicate it would apply only to eight
plants in the state that have not already volunteered to reduce
emissions under the program.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, one of the senators voting
against the bill, said 28 years has been too long a time for the
permit exemption to continue in force.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, environmentalists' leading ally
on the issue, said that with the end to the power plants' exemption
in the deregulation bill and the provisions in the bill passed
Sunday for other industries, ``we took a big bite out of the
apple'' of grandfathered emissions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
