A6829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-NYT &LR;      05-30 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRACK'S VICTORY IN INDY 500 DOES COMPUTE, TO THE GALLON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The white flag waved, signaling there was only
one lap remaining in the Indianapolis 500 Sunday, and the only
thing Kenny Brack could do was hope that his calculations were
right. Race cars can run only 30 laps around the Brickyard on a
tank of fuel, right?
</P>
<P>
   Brack did the math. And according to his figures, Robby Gordon's
car should already be out of methanol. But somehow it was not.
Brack, who was in second place, began to sweat. Because the only
thing running out, it seemed to him, was time. And then ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of fuel,'' Gordon screamed under his helmet. Brack
saw Gordon's bright yellow race car slowing on pit lane, and at
that moment, the 33-year-old Swede knew that victory was his. He
completed the final lap and took the checkered flag at the 83rd
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he could run more than 30 laps on one tank of
fuel,'' said Brack, who was last year's Indy Racing League champion
and drives a Dallara-Aurora owned by A.J. Foyt. ``Whether I thought
I could overtake him, I don't know. I would have tried my
hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   But a faulty fuel meter in Gordon's car meant that Brack did not
have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed one more lap of yellow,'' said Gordon, who had two
fifth-place finishes at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. ``My fuel
meter told me we were getting two miles per gallon, and it
indicated 2.3 gallons coming out of Turn 4 on the next-to-last lap.
I thought this was our year. The stars seemed to be all in a line.
It makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what are you going to do?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could cry, I could kick the car, but John Menard would get
mad at me,'' he said of his car owner. ``I could punch our fueler,
but what would that accomplish? We have a big race in Milwaukee
next weekend, so we just have to suck it up and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack (pronounced Breck) ran out of fuel in last year's
Indianapolis 500 because of similar miscalculation. Sunday, he lead
for the most laps, racing around the 2.5-mile oval 66 times in
front and averaging 153.176 miles an hour. ``I've been practicing
drinking milk for more than a week,'' Brack said, joking.
</P>
<P>
   Brack is expected to earn about $1.5 million out of the $9
million in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ward, also in a Dallara-Aurora, was second, finishing 6.562
seconds behind Brack. Billy Boat, Brack's teammate, was third,
completing the podium sweep for the Dallara-Aurora chassis-engine
combination. Gordon, who was in a wreck early in Saturday's
Championship Auto Racing Teams' Motorola 300 in Madison, Ill.,
wound up fourth Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's final-lap misfortune was a dramatic climax to an
Indianapolis 500 _ viewed by a crowd of some 400,000 _ that was
exciting even though many of the race's stars and compelling story
lines had vanished by Lap 150.
</P>
<P>
   Arie Luyendyk, driving in his final race, was dominating Sunday
_ having led for 63 laps _ before crashing on Lap 118. Eddie
Cheever, the defending champion, saw his engine blow up on Lap 139
after leading for four laps. Scott Goodyear, the perennial threat,
was forced to leave the race early with mechanical problems and
finished 27th. Greg Ray, who started second and led for 32 laps,
took himself out of the running by causing a crash on pit lane
midway through the race and was relegated to 21st.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fried, the crew chief of the rookie driver Robby McGehee,
was critically injured on pit lane early in the race when he was
hit by Jimmy Kite's incoming car. As Kite was going into his pit
stall, his rear wheel was hit by Johnny Unser's front wheel,
forcing Kite's 1,585-pound car into Fried, who was taken to
Methodist Hospital, where he was in critical but stable condition
with head and chest injuries.
</P>
<P>
   McGehee finished fifth in a Dallara-Aurora and is likely to be
named rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Brack, Ward, Boat, Gordon _ recognize any of them? That is
probably because of the dispute between the United States' two
major open-wheel circuits, Championship Auto Racing Teams and the
IRL, which is owned by the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. This was
the fourth consecutive Indianapolis 500 to which many of the
sport's biggest names were not invited.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Michael Andretti or Al Unser Jr. No team owners
Roger Penske or Chip Ganassi or Paul Newman-Carl Haas. But that
might not be true for much longer. During the two past weeks,
reports of a reconciliation between CART and IRL have floated
through Gasoline Alley.
</P>
<P>
   A reunification would be embraced by most CART and some IRL
teams. But that was not a topic of discussion on Gasoline Alley
Sunday following the dramatic climax.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk, the sentimental favorite, blamed himself for his
mishap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have known better than to race in traffic,'' said
Luyendyk, whose right-front wheel was clipped by Tyce Carlson while
he making a risky pass between Turns 3 and 4. ``It was my
responsibility as the leader to make the pass cleanly.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk, who won here in 1990 and 1997, announced last year
that he would retire after Sunday's race. He finished a
disappointing 22nd Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get over these kinds of disappointments easy,'' he said. ``I
had so much fun driving today. In thinking back on today, when I
got out of the car, the crowd was going nuts. I was trying to take
it all in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other drivers _ Roberto Moreno and Tony Stewart _ attempted
double-duty this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno, who, like Gordon, drove the Motorola 300 and the
Indianapolis 500, finished fourth on Saturday but settled for a
20th-place finish Sunday after his car succumbed to a transmission
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's attempt was more tricky. Immediately after finishing
ninth Sunday, the 1996-97 IRL champion flew to Charlotte, N.C.,
where he drove in a stock-car race, Nascar's Coca-Cola 600. That is
almost eight hours in race cars and 1,100 miles of racing in one
day. He was the second driver to do this. John Andretti did it
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Eliseo Salazar, the veteran Chilean driver who is notorious for
not finishing races, tested out the IRL's new wheel-restraining
system on Lap 10. The crash was bad news for him and his Nienhouse
Motorsports team, but it was good news for league officials, who
saw the tether system at work for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar lost control of his race car between Turns 3 and 4 and
smacked into the concrete wall. The impact was hard enough to tear
off one of his rear wheels, but the high-strength tethers that were
installed last week kept the wheel from becoming a dangerous
projectile. The tethers were mandated by the IRL after three
spectators were killed and several other fans were injured when a
detached wheel catapulted into the stands at Lowe's Motor Speedway
in North Carolina earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
