   (NYT16) INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. -- May 30, 1999 --
BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-2, 5-30 -- Latrell Sprewell of the New York
Knicks jumps over over members of the Indiana Pacers on his way to
scoring Sunday during game one of the Eastern Conference Finals.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. -- May 30, 1999 --
BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1, 5-30 -- Marcus Camby, left, of the New York
Knicks, and Chris Mullin, of the Indiana Pacers, position
themselves for a rebound on Sunday during game one of the Eastern
Conference Finals. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ATLANTA -- May 30, 1999 -- MEMORIALDAY-COX, 5-30 -- Max
Falls, a Vietnam veteran, talks about the Vietnam Veterans Virtual
Wall web site, a page of which is on his computer screen. Sponsored
jointly by the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund and WinStar
Communications, the Virtual Wall web site is a cyberspace version
of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington. Web surfers can
call up the names of those who died, punch up details of their
deaths, and post tributes, including color photographs and sound
recordings. (Jean Shifrin/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 30, 1999 -- CULTUREFINDER, 5-30 --
Eugene Carr, founder and chief executive of Culturefinder.com,
outside Lincoln Center. Carr's Internet business has enabled him to
combine his entrepreneurial impulses with a lifelong affinity for
the performing arts. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 30, 1999 -- INTERNET-WEALTH, 5-30 -- A
billboard advertises an area of downtown Manhattan known as Silicon
Alley where many of the city's new-media companies have taken up
shop. Since March, with Wall Street valuing infant Internet
companies that have never made a profit in the same range as car
makers and airlines, Silicon Alley has witnessed initial public
offerings at the rate of one a week. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BELMAR BEACH, N.J. -- May 30, 1999 --
MEMORIAL-DAY-FLOATER-2, 5-30 -- Crowds fill the beach on Sunday.
Traditionally, the Memorial Day weekend holiday marks the official
start of the summer season. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 30, 1999 -- MUSEUM-DEACCESS, 5-30 -- An
unidentified visitor to the exhibit ``The Museum as Muse: Artists
Reflect,'' at the Museum of Modern Art, takes part in one of the
art displays. The piece, by Michael Asher, consists of the bench
the woman is sitting on and the red folder in her hands, found in a
rack at the right end of the bench. The folder is titled ``Catalog
of Deaccessions 1929 through 1998'' and contains names and
descriptions of all the paintings and sculptures deaccessioned by
MoMA since 1929. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WILDWOOD, N.J. -- May 30, 1999 -- MEMORIAL-DAY-FLOATER,
5-30 -- Sales were brisk on Sunday for Richard Norda, a retiree who
sells ice cream during the summer monts to make extra cash. While
beachgoers took in the sun, the skies above were also filled with
competiting kites taking part in the Annual National Kite
Championship. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KOSOVO-MACEDONIAN BORDER REGION -- May 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-NATO, 5-30 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from the village of
Lubinje, in Kosovo, flee over the mountains into Macedonia on
Sunday. The refugees claimed Serbian special police had chased them
up the mountain. Despite NATO's claims that the bombing is wearing
down Milosevic's forces, especially in Kosovo, allied commanders
acknowledged again Sunday that there were no signs of surrender
from Belgrade. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KUKES, Albania -- May 30, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2, 5-30
-- Zyrafete Ahmetaj cries as she recalls the violent death of her
10-year-old son and mother after her arrival to a refugee camp on
Sunday. Ahmetaj and several other refugees were among a group of
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo who claim they were used as human
shields by Serbs in the village of Korisa, where they were locked
inside a warehouse that the Serbs knew would be attacked by NATO.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KUKES, Albania -- May 30, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1, 5-30
-- Driton Palishi, 10, whose stomach bears a scar from where
shrapnel was removed recently, sits in a tent along with other
injured relatives, from left, Doruntini Ahmetaj, 4, Zyrafete
Ahmetaj, 30, and Genci Ahmetaj, 4. The refugees were among a group
of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo who claim they were used as human
shields by Serbs in the village of Korisa, where they were locked
inside a warehouse that the Serbs knew would be attacked by NATO.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DENVER -- May 30, 1999 -- DENVER-COMPETE-MEDIA, 5-30 --
Steetside newspaper vendors Bob Ayers, left, of the Denver Rocky
Mountain News, and Tino Sanchez of the Denver Post, looking for
customers last Thursday. Though many in the national media took a
hit-and-run approach to covering the shootings at Columbine High
School, in suburban Denver, the two local newspapers here knew that
showing insensitivity to a wounded community could be a costly
misstep in a fiercely contested newspaper war, possibly the
toughest in the country these days. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 30, 1999 -- GANSKE-PROFILE, 5-30 --
Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, framed by various college and medical
school plaques and honors in his office last Thursday. Ganske is a
fitting symbol of the current House of Representatives where
Republicans are trying to govern with 222 votes, the slimmest
majority in 45 years. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 30, 1999 -- REFORM-JUDAISM, 5-30 -- Maron
Waxman, a Reform jew, signs a bar mitzvah certificate last week.
More than a century ago, Reform leaders declared such practices as
wearing skullcaps and prayer shawls and using Hebrew in services to
be the dated relics of the past, and emphasized instead a focus on
social ethics and a highly cerebral approach to the faith. But in a
symbolically resonant gesture, the Reform's rabbinic arm, the
Central Conference of American Rabbis, last week adopted a document
that encourages the movement's members to explore traditional
rituals. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TORREON, Mexico -- May 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-DROUGHT, 5-30
-- Mounds of dirt which are used in the smelting of lead are moved
by a loader on May 18. Mexican officials have explained the
mounting water shortage in the northern Mexican region as one of
the vagaries of nature. But Torreon residents and several experts
said that deforestation, wasteful irrigation, and water-intensive
industrial processes ill-suited to an arid region, have worsened
the crisis. (Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 30, 1999 -- BRONX-ZOO-GORILLAS, 5-29 --
Paki, one of the residents of the new Congo Gorilla Forest at the
Bronx Zoo, looks at Linda Corcoran, a zoo employee, on Friday. The
new gorilla enclosure opens June 25, and its occupants are still
getting used to the lush surroundings and the newfound freedom.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
