<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDY JOHNSON UNSETTLES THE METS' LINEUP EVEN MORE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing Randy Johnson is punishment enough. But having
to face the 6-foot-10-inch left-hander when your team is struggling
is cruel.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets fell behind by seven runs in the first three
innings Sunday in losing by 10-1 to Johnson and the Arizona
Diamondbacks. No wonder that frustration was the catchword in the
Mets' clubhouse, due to Johnson's pitching and two home runs by
Steve Finley, who drove in five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (6-2), making his first appearance against the Mets
before 38,302 fans at Shea Stadium, struck out 10 in eight innings.
The surging Diamondbacks, who have won their last six games,
completed a three-game sweep of the reeling Mets, the first time
the Mets lost a three-game series at Shea since April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii, who had won four straight, lasted just two and
two-thirds innings, allowing seven earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Because Atlanta lost in extra innings to the Los Angeles
Dodgers, the Mets were able to remain three games behind the Braves
in the National League East. But there are signs of trouble beneath
the surface of the Mets, who are 27-23 through the first 50 games,
and a team meeting was led by Manager Bobby Valentine after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mets had won six of eight games before the
Diamondbacks came to town, there are grumblings on the team.
``There are a lot of guys who are upset that there is no set
lineup,'' one veteran player said over the weekend. ``Look around
at the other teams. They have the same lineup every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine bristled when asked about a set lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just who is it that uses the same lineup every day?''
Valentine said Sunday. ``I watched the Yankees the last three
nights and they used three different lineups. As long as the core's
the same, what difference does it make?''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly who makes up that core remains unclear. Rickey Henderson
was unhappy Saturday because he didn't start. He was in a better
mood Sunday morning when he was in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said he had been upset Saturday because the weather
was good, the field dry and he felt there was no reason to be
overly cautious with his right knee. But Sunday he said he
understood why Valentine had played Brian McRae, Roger Cedeno and
Benny Agbayani in the outfield Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Juggling the lineup will get more difficult for Valentine in
coming weeks, although juggling is one of his strengths. After
Sunday's unsightly loss, the Mets activated Bobby Bonilla from the
disabled list and optioned pitcher Rigo Beltran to Class AAA
Norfolk. Earlier in the day, the Mets optioned outfielder Jermaine
Allensworth to Norfolk and purchased the contract of the utilityman
Melvin Mora.
</P>
<P>
   Now Valentine _ whose team plays three games at home against
Cincinnati starting Monday afternoon and then plays the Yankees in
three games at Yankee Stadium beginning Friday _ must determine
what to do with five outfielders, any of whom could make a case for
starting.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who has been hampered since spring training by a partly
torn right knee ligament, has said he and the Mets ``are on the
same page'' about his being activated. Still, the 36-year-old, who
makes $5.9 million a year, is batting .157.
</P>
<P>
   ``We activated him because he's healthy,'' General Manager Steve
Phillips said. ``And Bobby will make the decisions from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno leads the major leagues in stolen bases with 28 and is
batting .323 after he hit his first home run as a Met, off Johnson.
Agbayani is batting .451.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Mets keep playing Cedeno and Agbayani, who seem to have
become favorites of Valentine? Or does he go back to the starting
outfield he began the season with: Henderson, Bonilla and McRae?
</P>
<P>
   Valentine has had to juggle his lineup since the fifth game of
the season, when catcher Mike Piazza went down with a knee injury.
Bonilla, McRae and Henderson have all missed time because of sore
knees, as has pitcher Al Leiter, who will start Monay.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rey Ordonez, has missed the last two games because of
problems with his right knee. The injury precipitated Allensworth's
demotion, and Mora started at shortstop in place of Ordonez Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine seemed incredulous over Ordonez's injury, especially
because he suited up on Saturday and then refused to go into the
game. Valentine had wanted Ordonez to at least be announced as a
pinch-hitter in hopes of tempting Arizona Manager Buck Showalter to
take out a left-handed pitcher and bring in a right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine benched Ordonez once this season because of a bad
attitude. But Ordonez said Sunday: ``If I can play, I can play. And
if I can't, I can't. A day off is a day off. I have to take care of
my knee early in the season. When it feels better, I'll play. Why
pinch-hit? Do I want to hurt it more and be out longer?''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game, Valentine said: ``I've managed 12 years
and haven't had too many days when a guy couldn't go on the field
and he was in uniform. In fact, it's never happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he couldn't imagine playing Ordonez in the next
couple of games, even if Ordonez said he could play. ``We can't
risk hurting the knee,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, another veteran said that frustration over losing led to
the players' discontent, implying that there would be less
grumbling by the players if the Mets were winning more regularly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
