<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CYBERSCENE: Economists can find plenty of numbers
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When lists are made of all the wild and crazy things a person
can do on the Internet, learning about economics does not often top
any of them.
</P>
<P>
   The average person is keen on learning how to turn a fast buck
through something as comparatively sane as online investing and
Web-based investment sites. People are also interested in the
totally bogus get-rich schemes that are promoted by e-mail and
off-the-wall Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But, without some sort of a basic grounding in economics, much
of the information you'll find is hard to evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the Web is an excellent university for economics and _
by spending a little time learning the lingo and rules of the game
_ you can turn that quick education into knowledge that can be a
practical help.
</P>
<P>
   So let's start our educational journey today with a site called
Selected Economic Resources on the Web at www.lib.umich.edu
</P>
<P>
   /libhome/rrs/classes/econ.htm. OK, so some of it is a little
over your head. For instance, most of us might blink our eyes a few
times at the link for the Heterodox Economics Archive that promises
to take you to the ``mailing list archives for the Post Keynesian
thought discussion group and the progressive economists group.''
</P>
<P>
   But other links, including one to online economics texts, can
help you get your feet planted on admittedly shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   The next site is also a collection of links, perhaps one of the
best. It's simply called Economics Resources and is located at www
</P>
<P>
   .clark.net/pub/lschank/web
</P>
<P>
   /econ.html. Take a quick look at the link called ``Best of the
Economics Sites.'' Clicking there will take you to some sites,
mostly maintained by universities, that will help give you a
relatively simple explanation of some basic laws and theories.
While you're there, check out the link to the archives at the
University of Nebraska _ it's especially complete and down to earth
(well, as down to earth as economics gets).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, at some point in your journey through economics,
you'll want to get a little more practical. Keynesian thought,
after all, is heady stuff, but you're taking this short course in
economics to figure out how to become more prosperous (or at least
understand why it was a real dumb move to buy shares in a buggy
whip factory).
</P>
<P>
   So you'll want to visit a more practical site called
De-mystifying Marketing Plans at gmarketing.com/tactics
</P>
<P>
   /weekly111.html. Here you'll get plain talk on how to take all
your theories and compile them in a way that will impress the most
jaded venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of making money by understanding economics, there's
another site you'll want to visit. It's run by the Motley Fools.
Their page at www.fool.com
</P>
<P>
   /school/dowinvesting
</P>
<P>
   /dowinvesting.htm will help explain an investing method called
Dow Investing.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of the Fools, who occasionally appear in this
newspaper's Sunday business section, here is how it works: ``The
approach teaches you how to select a group of beaten-down (Dow
Jones) stocks and buy and hold them for one year, playing the
likely turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Now will that make you rich?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But, even if you lose your shirt, you now will be
able to explain the whole process to your admiring friends using
the most impressive sort of language.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
