<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH01-COX     05-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web genealogy data can inform, enthrall
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to genealogy for beginners. Don't feel awkward; I'm a
beginner, too.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I wrote a column about my own tedious but ultimately
rewarding search to find out more about my grandparents and
great-grandparents. My search was a hit-or-miss process, and if you
do exactly what I did, chances are your search will be hit or miss,
too. As many people wrote to tell me, there are many libraries,
archives, professional genealogists and software programs that will
help you conduct far better searches than I can. If you're really
serious about researching your family tree as far back as you can,
you will eventually have to leave your computer and head out into
the real word.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you start your search on the Web, I can tell you
there is an exciting element to researching your family or anything
else, for that matter. Sitting at a computer, typing in a Web
address that might eventually bring you to a site or database that
includes information about your family is like a big scavenger
hunt. It also gives you a sense of how much information is
available on the Internet and what a vast store of information is
out there. It may sound corny, but sometimes the information you
suddenly find at your fingertips is breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some links to get you started:
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure who Cyndi Howells is, but she offers up a very
popular and extensive and easy-to-use set of links on her own site
called Cyndi's List of Genealogy Links at www.cyndislist.com.
According to the frequently asked questions list on the site,
Cyndi, with a little help from her husband, maintains this
amazingly detailed archive of genealogy links all by herself. She
encourages users to let her know if they encounter links that are
outdated or just don't work. She says she has 41,700 links on her
site.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great place for beginners to start searching, whether
your family hails from Eastern Europe or Outer Mongolia. Cyndi's
List also features a ``getting started'' section for newbies to
look over before beginning their searches. The site also offers a
mailing list for novice researchers offering even more help and
information.
</P>
<P>
   From Cyndi's List, I went to a site called JewishGen at www
</P>
<P>
   .jewishgen.org/databases. This was where things started to get
rough. The JewishGen site allows users to search for families and
towns all over Western and Eastern Europe. It also offers to
connect you with other researchers looking for the same families or
cities. However, if you don't know the exact spelling of your
ancestor's surname or it was changed entirely by immigration
officials at Ellis Island, you'll be spending a lot of time here
typing in every possible spelling you can think of and finding
yourself at the mercy of the ``Daitch-Mokotoff Soundex.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as I can tell, it takes whatever you give it and searches
something, anything, really, that sounds similar. For example,
entering my grandmother's birthplace, a city called Slonim, turned
up about 40 cities from Albania to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The search also turned up a Slonim and Slonin, a classic example
of how frustrating these searches can be if you have very little to
go on. Luckily I knew how the name of the city was spelled and
could continue on from there. Clicking on the city, I was connected
to an amazing map informing me that Slonim was 107.7 miles west
southwest of Minsk in Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Sites like Cyndi's List or Ancestry.com will also take more
advanced researchers to databases that will give you birth,
marriage and death records for nearly every city and state in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   If your family has been in America for a significant period,
you'll find the links from Genealogy.com particularly useful. From
this database, I was able to find my grandfather's birthday and
Social Security number, two shreds of information that might come
in handy when I try to discover exactly when he came to the United
States and from where. Some of the information on Ancestry.com is
free, while some you'll have to pay for. Even if you opt not to pay
for information, you'll be amazed at the types of information you
can locate here from New York State Civil War rosters to
biographies of Underground Railroad operators.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, if you are just starting out on the genealogy trail,
don't expect to trace your family back to a 17th century French
chateau on your first try. There's a lot of trial and error, a lot
of dead ends and an awful lot of Web sites that are nothing more
than shopping sites to entice you into buying one software package
or other. And always, always keep in mind when it comes to surfing
the Web, sometimes the journey can be just as important and
enjoyable as the destination.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
