r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-TOOLS01-COX     05-30 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHTOOLS: APX-4620 speakers help computer sound
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labtec, the computer speaker company, sent me its APX-4620
system for review, and it has certainly transformed the way my
computer sounds _ as well as the way it looks.
</P>
<P>
   The APX-4620 is a three-piece system, two tweeter-midrange
satellite speakers and a subwoofer. Much to my surprise, the specs
say each satellite speaker contains two tweeters and a midrange
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny fellows, considering each satellite is only about 10 inches
tall. The outside edge of each is curved and is about 3 1/2 inches
wide at its fattest point.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-cream-colored satellite speakers come with adhesive
brackets to attach them to the sides of the monitor. I've never
mounted speakers on a monitor before. Each of these speakers has
little rubber feet on it, too, so obviously they can be set on the
desktop, although the instructions make no mention of that.
</P>
<P>
   I obediently set them up on the monitor, which makes the whole
thing look like the head of a huge, bat-eared robot whose body is
hiding under the table. I find this a little intimidating, but I
suppose I could get used to it, and it does free up some desktop
space.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanically, there is a great deal to like about this system.
The woofer, which is a heavy black box that sits on a little
platform stand under the table, is the only portion that has to be
plugged in to an electrical outlet. It supplies power for the
entire audio system. The right-side tweeter-midrange carries all
the controls _ knobs for volume, treble and bass adjust, and
Labtec's Spatializer stereo imaging system.
</P>
<P>
   This panel also has receptacles for headphones and a microphone,
a very nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   The entire system is quite simple to set up. All the cables are
color-coded, and the instructions are clear and simple. The base of
each of the high-range speakers is hollow and contains the plug
receptacles and a post, around which excess wire can be wrapped.
You still wind up with one wire on the left and three on the right
running from the speakers to the back of the table, but if you
never look at anything but the front of the monitor, that's no
problem.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who looks at the side of a monitor? And what real
computer user worries about a rat's nest of wires? Comes with the
territory, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The sound of the Labtec system takes a little getting used to,
at least for me. With the speakers mounted even with the front of
the monitor, they are more or less in your face, so to speak, and
it's fair to say the sound is more or less in your ears.
</P>
<P>
   I don't listen to music CDs through my computer; I've got a
pretty good stereo system here in the engine room with speakers
that, to my wife's everlasting disgust, are 3 feet tall. Compared
to that, the Labtec system is a little anemic. But if the monitor
looks a little odd with two speakers for ears, think how bizarre it
would look suspended between a couple of tower speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Once the physical affront of listening to speakers that are only
2 feet from my ears wore off, the Labtecs began to sound quite
good. The spatial imaging circuitry works very well. It seems to
spread the sound curtain out beyond the edges of the speakers
without leaving a hole in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   If you turn the volume up enough to actually hear the subwoofer
woofing, and if you stay close enough to the system to keep your
hands on the keyboard, you are getting very near the threshold of
pain.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen this system advertised at less than $140, and it's
well worth it to anyone serious about computer sound.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
