<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By cell phone and e-mail, our electronic future has arrived
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox news Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a typical day in the life of a modern man.
</P>
<P>
   My friend in Frotheim, Germany, let me know that she was off on
a bicycle trip with her husband and kids. And, just a few minutes
later, while taking a walk in the park, I got an update on a friend
who has a sick cat. Then I came back here to the newspaper and made
arrangements _ coordinating it with my boss and someone in another
department _ for one of our reporters to write about the results of
a technology survey.
</P>
<P>
   I found out about the bicycle trip in an e-mail that popped on
the screen of one of my two work computers. The news of the sick
cat came in a call to my digital phone while I was taking that
walk. I made all the arrangements for covering the technology
survey without talking to a single person _ I did it all by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   And, somewhere along the line that day, I did what I do best. I
discovered the obvious. The future I used to write about really has
arrived. That's a big deal to me because one of the big complaints
in my business _ writing about technology _ is that a lot of what
we cover and a lot of what we speculate about never quite seems to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   I realized on that day that while things might not happen with
the speed and drama of a comet flashing across the sky, a lot of
things that would have been geewhiz topics for a feature story when
I started in this business have become a reality. For instance,
I've watched cellular phones go from an exotic business tool for a
few to a tiny and affordable service that has become part of our
routine daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all this technology is nifty and convenient, but something
more important is going on here beyond the ability to order a pizza
while you drive home or send e-mail across the world in a flash.
Maybe like me, you may need to stop and think for a while to see
the importance behind that.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with e-mail. It's become routine _ not just for
wired folks like me, but for my friend, too, the wife of a village
police chief who works in a New Age bookstore. No one in her family
has ever been to America. I've never been to Frotheim, but we talk
and learn and our world grows smaller and easier to understand.
</P>
<P>
   I know from her that Germany is changing: Women are running for
office and getting elected. She learns from me about how life is in
Atlanta, and I do my best to answer her questions, such as the last
one: Is America really a land of opportunity? We've profited from
the conversation in ways that are equally important and hard to
explain.
</P>
<P>
   And that tiny digital phone in my pocket has come a long way.
When I got my first cellular phone, it was more of an electronic
lifesaver than a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The air time was expensive, and the batteries had the life span
of a butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   But now the phone stays in my shirt pocket, and when there are
things that are important to my life, like friends with sick cats,
I can be there.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of becoming an electronic leash, the phone allows me
to take a walk without worrying that I can't be there if a friend
needs me.
</P>
<P>
   In the past (and I'm dang near famous as a worrier), I would
have sat by the telephone worried that my friend would need to
talk. Instead, I was able to go about my normal routine and not let
a friend down.
</P>
<P>
   We _ me included _ spend a lot of time talking about how cold
technology is. But when used right, it can become a way to swim in
waters that are becoming increasingly swift and deep.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
