<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAC REPORT: Software developers finally bite on burgeoning Apple
market
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year about this time, Apple Computer trumpets that
thousands of new titles have been released for the Mac. If it were
true, this claim rarely translated into visible titles in stores or
catalogs, which continued to offer the same shrinking list of new
Mac software.
</P>
<P>
   But this year it's finally different. Once again, Apple Computer
announced some 3,000-plus new titles for the Mac and, by golly, it
is true.
</P>
<P>
   It seems developers are finally convinced that Apple Computer's
share of the market, driven upward by the success of its iMac and
PowerBook computers, will continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to what Phil Steinmeyer, PopTop Software's CEO and
lead designer of ``Railroad Tycoon II,'' said online recently.
``The Mac is a fast-growing gaming platform, and there are legions
of loyal gamers.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a Windows developer? But it's true. Not only are
developers championing the Mac again, they are releasing titles.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the number of new titles for the Mac is almost
overwhelming. Take a look at games, a category in which most
developers released only for Windows just last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now some of the biggest developers are announcing new titles
daily for the Mac. Among the games coming to the Mac are ``SimCity
3000,'' ``Civilization: Call to Power,'' ``Quake III,'' ``Falcon
4.0'' and Electronic Arts' football simulation ``Madden 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something here for just about everybody.
</P>
<P>
   While games are important, it's not the only genre of Mac
software experiencing a revival. New titles for desktop publishing,
Web publishing and graphic programs are also hitting the market.
One example is Canvas 6.0 by Miami-based developer Deneba Software.
</P>
<P>
   Even more surprising, there's a trickle of new business
productivity software for the Mac. This is the category in which
Apple Computer has always been weakest.
</P>
<P>
   The trend began last year when Microsoft released a new version
of Office 98, which includes Word, Excel, Outlook and PowerPoint.
Since then, smaller players have released new software or announced
coming releases.
</P>
<P>
   For example, BrainForest has released a powerful outliner that
works on both the Mac and the PalmPilot. And Nisus Software
reportedly is nearing release of a big new upgrade for its
acclaimed Nisus Writer word processor.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, if Apple keeps on a roll, these new titles could
just be the beginning of a growing roster of new software for the
Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
