<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POWER USER: Boot up before buying PC from `screwdriver' shop
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jerry Yandel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember that $750 PC I wrote about not too long ago? Now it's
less than $500. You just have to know where to find them.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of ``screwdriver'' shops all over metro
Atlanta. They build systems on the fly, cranking out mini-towers in
the back while taking orders in the front.
</P>
<P>
   They use generic OEM (original equipment manufacturer) parts
that come in shiny, plain, static-resistant packaging with scant
documentation. And, in general, purchases come with a warranty for
one year, parts and labor.
</P>
<P>
   The incredibly low prices are the result of bulk ordering
hardware and selling hundreds of systems a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it all by volume. The volume makes up for having no
margin,'' said a manager of one of these retailers, who compared
his store to a Waffle House for computers. These shops range from
strip-mall stores with nice display cases to a couple of tiny rooms
with some PCs on folding tables hidden in an office park.
</P>
<P>
   The most important part of buying from one of these stores is to
be a smart buyer and a savvy consumer. I know, because I wasn't. I
bought two systems and a monitor for about $1,000 from the retailer
advertising the absolute lowest prices. I had purchased from them
before without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, the systems were reading 32 megabytes of RAM
as 28 MB, and one of the hard drives was only showing up as 2
gigabytes instead of the 6.4 for which I had paid. Other than that,
they ran fine.
</P>
<P>
   (Here's the kind of sub-$500 system we're talking about: a
speedy little 300-MHz AMD gamer with 32 MB of RAM, a 4-gig hard
drive, Windows 98 and all the trimmings _ 8 MB AGP video, 56k bps
modem, 16-bit sound card, 2 USB ports, 40X CD-ROM, speakers,
keyboard and mouse. Total: $480 before tax.)
</P>
<P>
   My ordeal took a week and a half and three round trips from
Stockbridge to Jimmy Carter Boulevard _ about 300 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The fun began when I faxed in my order Friday evening. Saturday
morning, I got a phone call telling me my systems would be ready at
2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When I buy a computer _ whether for me or someone else _ I get
all giddy, like a kid who spots the Scream Machine sticking over
the treetops on his way to Six Flags. So you can imagine my
disappointment when I made the one-way, 50-mile drive only to be
told that they were plumb out of CPUs and new ones were due
Tuesday. OK, fine. The price is right. I can wait.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, I called to confirm my order, and I went back Wednesday
morning. Only one machine was ready, because they only had one
4-gigabyte hard drive _ but I could get a 6-gig for another $20.
Fine, here's a check. I drove around back, and they loaded up my
stuff on a dolly. When I got home, I found the RAM and hard drive
discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
   I could have saved myself a trip _ and this is an important step
for anyone buying from a screwdriver shop _ by asking them to boot
up the system.
</P>
<P>
   A few quick clicks _ right-click the hard drive to see its
properties and check the size, right-click ``my computer'' to get
its properties and see the amount of RAM _ would have uncovered the
discrepancies I found later. Instead, I happily rushed out. ... And
I found myself heading back to Gwinnett County a week later to get
some of the promised tech support.
</P>
<P>
   The tech support I got was a Phillips head screwdriver and a
load of attitude from the guy behind the counter.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't even take the cover off to look at the hard drive or
check that the SDRAM was in the motherboard slot completely. (I
once solved a similar RAM problem by properly seating a SIMM in its
slot. It took 30 seconds.)
</P>
<P>
   I could have checked the machines' innards at home, but a piece
of tape on the cover warned that its removal voided the warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Hah! I ended up voiding the warranty all over the counter
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing they would do was give me a new drive and SDRAM,
but I would have to take out the hard drive and replace it myself.
</P>
<P>
   So, I did that. Then I took my toys and went home.
</P>
<P>
   I have not fired up the system again. And, I guess, if it is
still reading the drive and RAM incorrectly, it will be up to me to
find out why. (Another thing: Only buy from stores that give you
CD-ROM copies of Windows. Those will come in mighty handy if fixing
the systems involves reinstalling the OS.)
</P>
<P>
   In the future, I probably won't use that outfit again. Several
of their competitors' prices are only $20 to $30 higher. But that's
no guarantee that their customer service is any more reality-based.
</P>
<P>
   Whomever I use, I won't leave the store without booting up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
