<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECH MEDIA: Summer movies roll with sites, games
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of new movies are coming out this summer, and most of them
have supporting Web sites. The June issue of Yahoo! Internet Life
features a list of all these commercial Hollywood sites. Plus, it
lists some other noncommercial sites maintained by fans. You'll
find sites listed for ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' ``Austin Powers'' and ``South Park,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence of various media technologies has turned the
high-tech economy on its head in the past several years. Read how
this phenomenon has affected industries from telephone service to
the Internet in a new book called ``Killer App.'' Written by Larry
Downes and Chunka Mui, the book examines why some new high-tech
products have succeeded and others failed. The book is published by
Harvard Business School Publishing and retails for $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   You've seen ``The Phantom Menace.'' Now you can check out the
software. Yes, no sooner than the movie was released, along came a
computer CD game based on the story line. One reason for the speed
of the release is that the same company, LucasArts, was responsible
for the game and the movie. Named after the movie, the game lets
players take on roles from the film. You can play Obi-Wan Kenobi,
Qui-Gon Jinn, Queen Amidala or Captain Panaka. The game, which
contains animated violence, is published only for PCs running
Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the best spring in years for Mac gamers. All of a
sudden, developers are releasing lots of popular Windows titles for
the Mac platform. Among those titles are the air combat game
``Falcon 4.0,'' ``RailRoad Tycoon II'' and ``Quake III.''
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   It's the season for lawn care, and the Internet is a great place
to find information and help. Start at Lawnworld.com, a good
compendium site loaded with text-based information. You can trust
the information, which was developed and compiled by the
agriculture department at Ohio State University. The site is
located at home.att.net
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)dwis497002/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
