<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    B-movie nominations sought Web site honors classic B-movies
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider it a strike back against the Force, a way to make your
voice heard amid the noise surrounding the summer blockbuster
movies.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at B-Movie Theater, the ones behind www.b-movie.com,
are looking for nominations to the B-Movie Hall of Fame. B-movies
are the quirky middle children of film, celluloid afterthoughts
that were not squeaky enough to get the grease afforded big-budget
films.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame defines a B-movie as a movie, either
independent or studio, where the entertainment and/or artistic
value transcends the perceived limitations of its low budget.
Movies like ``The Leopard Man,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   B-movie fans can nominate their favorite movies and actors from
the nomination page, www.b-movie.com.hof
</P>
<P>
   /hof.html. Voting ends July 30. No more than 10 nominations per
category will be counted, so B-movie zealots won't be able to stuff
the virtual box voting for ``Death Race 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 inductees will be announced in August during the first
B-Movie Film Festival in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 1,000 actors and films were nominated. Actors from
the first Hall of Fame class, the Babe Ruths and Ty Cobbs of their
industry, include Jeanne Carmen, the Bowery Boys, Ronald Reagan and
Nancy Davis (Reagan) and Michael Herz.
</P>
<P>
   B-Movie Theater is owned and run by Salt City Home Video, a
seller of independent film and videos in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Web, women and sports
</P>
<P>
   A survey by NPD Online Research found that 36 percent of women
who go online check out sports news while there. Of those, 46
percent get more sports news on the Web than they did six months
ago, and 23 percent said the Web was their primary source of sports
news.
</P>
<P>
   The sites, www.espn.com, www.abcsports.com and www.nfl.com, were
the most popular Web sports sites visited by women, according to
the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic sports survey, conducted in February, included
3,127 people. Of those, 1,595 were female. The survey found that
women who use the Web for sports news tend to be between the ages
of 25 and 44, with an average household income of $64,000. Female
Internet sports fans tend to be married (68 percent) and
college-educated (64 percent).
</P>
<P>
   NPD Online Research is based in Port Washington, N.Y. Its parent
company, NPD Group, is the founder of Media Metrix, a company that
estimates traffic on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Use your thumb
</P>
<P>
   Passwords can be cracked. People use a familiar word for the
password that lets them log on to their computer systems. Sometimes
it's the name of their cat or the name of the town in which they
were born or the street where they live.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that the people who try to break into
computer systems use software that can try every word in the
English language in a matter of hours. That's why computer security
experts recommend making your password a combination of words and
numbers, like Scruffy99.
</P>
<P>
   But if that's too complicated and you would rather spend a few
dollars, there's something interesting on the market.
</P>
<P>
   U.are.U is a $149 device that you can program to recognize your
fingerprint. A user puts his finger on the sensor, from any
direction, and the device reads it.
</P>
<P>
   The device works on Windows 95 and Windows 98 and requires 16
megabytes of RAM and a Pentium-class processor. To set it up, scan
your fingerprint four times. The program creates a mathematical
code from your fingerprint's features. The code is then encrypted.
The system is designed to store and recognize more than one
fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
   PC Magazine, in a February review, said the device was not ``as
fussy as some.''
</P>
<P>
   The deluxe package sells for $199. The plus package is $149. A
$1,000 software development kit is required to integrate the system
into local-business applications, such as medical file management
and badge access.
</P>
<P>
   U.are.U was developed by Digital Persona of Redwood City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The device is on sale at computer retailers and online at
www.digitalpersona.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
