u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGISLATURE-RDP-TEXAS     05-30 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-RDP-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LEGISLATION TO RAISE SPEED LIMIT TO 80 MPH HITS POTHOLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legislation to raise speed limits to 80 mph on
some Texas interstates and 75 mph on certain other highways
apparently was running out of gas late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although slightly different versions of the bill won easy
approval in both the House and the Senate in recent weeks, the
House sponsor said that enough concerns had been raised about the
measure that he probably wouldn't move for final passage.
</P>
<P>
   One safety concern was a related bill, which lawmakers sent
Saturday to Gov. George W. Bush, that will allow large trucks to
legally travel as fast as autos, even 80 mph if both bills became
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some questions about the 80 mile an hour speed
limit,'' said Rep. Pete Gallego, D-Alpine, the House sponsor.
``And, frankly, I think a lot of the concerns are because of
misunderstandings on the part of different people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallego said some people feared 80 mph speed limits in urban
areas, although the bill applies only to rural highways.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Madla, D-San Antonio, said some senators were
concerned about allowing large trucks to legally drive 80 on some
interstates.
</P>
<P>
   Gallego's and Madla's bill, House Bill 3328, would raise the
speed limit from 70 to 75 mph on highways where the higher limit
was warranted by a Texas Department of Transportation speed study.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have raised the legal limit to 80 mph on
east-west interstates in counties with fewer than 25,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Gallego said he wanted to raise the speed limit in his area of
the state, sparsely populated West Texas, where it can take hours
at today's legal speeds to get from one town to another.
</P>
<P>
   But the 80 mph provision also would have affected a 110-mile
stretch of I-10 between Houston and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Bills had to win final approval before midnight Sunday. The
Legislature will conclude its five-month session Monday, but the
last day is reserved for technical changes to bills.
</P>
<P>
   Gallego said the speed limit issue could be studied further
between now and the next regular session in 2001. ``I'm not
uncomfortable letting it go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The related bill, HB 676, which was sent Saturday to Bush, would
allow trucks to legally travel the same speed as cars, instead of
their current highway restriction of 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Some safety experts believe it is actually safer when all
vehicles are traveling the same speed.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Legislators sent Bush SB 365, which would allow the state to
monitor some repeat sex offenders after their release from prison.
Convicts determined to be sexual ``predators'' would be required to
wear electronic tracking devices and attend treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawmakers completed action on HB 2611 to require candidates
and political committees that spend more than $20,000 a year to
file their campaign finance reports electronically.
</P>
<P>
   _ Legislators approved SB 560, which would cap basic phone rates
for six years and lower the cost of in-state long distance calls.
But the measure would allow Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. to
increase the cost of other services, such as Caller ID and call
forwarding.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Senate approved and sent to the governor HB 713, a new
scholarship program for students who maintain a 2.0 grade point
average or better in their first year of college. The measure
includes a special provision that would provide a free college
education for former prisoner of war Stephen Gonzales of
Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   _ Senators also sent to Bush SB 138, which would prevent
government from infringing on the free exercise of religion. The
measure was prompted by a recent dispute between the city of Boerne
and a church's attempt to expand its building.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
