<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PACERS SHARE STOICISM OF THEIR COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ No bands, no cheering crowds met the Indiana
Pacers at the airport here when they returned home after winning
the opening-round playoff series in Milwaukee two weeks ago. There
were no bands, no cheering crowds to hail the Pacers after they won
their second-round playoff series, the Eastern Conference
semifinals, in Philadelphia last week.
</P>
<P>
   The team returned home quietly, if not stealthily. There was a
reason for this. The Pacers carefully orchestrated no orchestra
regarding the arrival of the team. No announcement was made about
it. By orders of the head coach, Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won anything yet,'' Bird explained. ``We'll
celebrate a championship. Nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   And they still haven't won anything _ particularly in the
Eastern Conference finals, where the Knicks won the opening game
Sunday night in Market Square Arena, 93-90.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the Knicks' center, said going into the
four-of-seven-game series, ``This is war!'' but Bird, who became
coach of the Pacers last season, only said: ``I came here to win a
championship. This team has been to the conference finals before,
but has never advanced. I came here to advance.''
</P>
<P>
   And so there had been no chest-thumping or crowing after the
team swept Milwaukee in three games and Philadelphia in four.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is one Pacer in particular who now mirrors the
seeming stoicism of the coach, it is Mark Jackson, as unlikely as
that may have seemed before this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jackson, now in his 12th season in the NBA, who has been
known for his celebratory and wacky gyrations after scoring a
basket, let alone after winning a game. He'd spread his arms after
sinking a drive shot and come back upcourt with arms spread as if
he were an airplane. He switched to a shimmy after scoring a hoop,
and it was hard to tell whether he was exhibiting himself as a fan
dancer or a blender.
</P>
<P>
   Bird watched this last season with only partly disguised
disdain. Then the Pacers lost to the Bulls in seven games in the
conference finals. Before this season began, Bird, according to a
source with the Pacers, ``told him to cut it out.'' Showboating,
Bird said, did not advance the cause. Bird had won three
championships as the player with the Boston Celtics, and was in the
finals twice more. He speaks evenly, and his candor is both
understood and appreciated by the players. ``He's been there,''
Jackson has said. ``He knows.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, no Red Baron, no Tina Turner takeoffs for Jackson.
Instead, he has had one of the best seasons of his career. ``His
floor leadership killed us,'' Larry Brown, coach of the 76ers, said
after the series last week. Jackson's ratio of assists to turnovers
was one of the best in the league during the regular season and has
continued into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And he has, except for an occasional look of triumph _ it just
seemed to bubble up. But Bird remains the unruffled, consistently
cool, expressionless professional.
</P>
<P>
   When Reggie Miller hit a 3-point shot with four-tenths of a
second to go in Game 3 of the Pacer-Bulls series last year to put
the Pacers ahead, 107-105, Bird's face was as straight as a string
as the Bulls called time out. ``He knew,'' Miller said, ``that
there was still time left on the clock, and that Michael Jordan was
in the game. Nothing was for sure.'' Indeed, Jordan's last-second
shot rimmed out to give the Pacers the victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacer players are now comporting themselves with the
attitude reflected by their coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that if Larry Bird were in a car accident,
you wouldn't need paramedics to give him a blood transfusion,''
said the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who attended the Bulls-Pacers series
last year. ``That's because he has ice water in his veins.''
</P>
<P>
   We remember, for example, when the Pistons went ahead by a point
in the last seconds of a playoff game in Boston and Dennis Rodman
and others were jumping around and celebrating the victory, until
Isiah Thomas tossed the ball inbound and Bird intercepted it and
swiftly passed to Dennis Johnson for the winning basket.
</P>
<P>
   There is a maturity in Bird that was evident even in his first
season in the NBA. ``I've always been that way,'' Bird said. ``I've
always liked hanging out with older guys. Right now, some of my
best friends are in their 60s. I just seem to be more comfortable
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many others in basketball, who have never had to work at
anything else in their lives, Bird worked on a garbage truck one
year at home. This was after he quit Indiana University and the
oppressive Bobby Knight after one month on campus following his
high school graduation. Bird returned French Lick, Ind., to sort
out his life, and got the job which, he said, taught him as a
teen-ager a great deal about life's realities as well as working
with men.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise, then, that the Pacers have performed like the
best kinds of garbage collectors: thorough, prideful and not
heading for beers until the last alley is cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   And right now, if there is to be any kind of sweep, it would be
by the Knicks, who lead the series by 1-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
