<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-GENEALOGY01-COX     05-30 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-GENEALOGY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRACING YOUR FAMILY'S HISTORY: Find out this summer where your
roots begin
 &HT;    By Ted Anthony
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was summertime, way back in 1982, and I was bored. Trapped in
the void between middle school and a brand-new high school, I had
little to do and a lot of time to do it. My answer was a summer
project _ my family history.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen years later, it's still a big part of my life. Why?
Because it's fun, it takes you to interesting places and it helps
you understand where you came from. It's like spending time with
fascinating relatives who aren't asking you to mow the lawn or do
the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   When I started, I already had some raw materials _ many families
do. My dad had stored in the closet of his study a bunch of old
papers. Some were written by my grandfather, whom I never knew.
Others were typed on manual typewriters and transcribed from even
older records.
</P>
<P>
   These records took me all the way back to the first Anthony in
America, Manoel Antonio, an 18th century merchant seaman who was
said to be Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   I was off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, I became kind of obsessed. I charted old family
relationships in notebooks, writing down in penciled block letters
the names I came across _ such as Freelove and Philander, Adelaide
and Royal, Sophronia and Aaron Isaac. I thought about the people
who came before me, what their lives were like and what was
important to them. It even got me interested in history _ over the
summer!
</P>
<P>
   But where do you go from there? It's easy. Try a few of these
ideas and create a summer project for yourself:
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk to your relatives, especially the older ones, and tape
record the interviews. This may not seem like ``family history'' to
you now, but if you ever have children or grandchildren, they'll be
happy you did this. Imagine hearing your great-great-grandmother's
voice on tape!
</P>
<P>
   _ What's more, you'd be surprised at what you'll learn. Most
everyone has a family story or two that they love to tell. Through
them you'll find a gateway to the past _ not only to your family's
past but to how people lived in ages different from our own. Take
notes, too; even though that sounds like a school thing to do,
it'll give you a written record of what you learned.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you can't interview relatives in person, ask them to answer
questionnaires. Mail a few out, and tell them what you want to
know: when they were born, what their parents' and grandparents'
names were, where they lived as children. Ask them to describe a
day in their lives when they were your age. You'll find some
interesting differences _ and some surprising similarities.
</P>
<P>
   _ If your family has been in the Atlanta area for more than a
generation or two, go to the public library (yikes, another
school-like thing to do). Ask for the local history section and
start digging.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when I was a kid, I went to our public library in
Pittsburgh to do family research. ``You're not going to find
anything there,'' my father insisted. I marched into the stacks and
dug up a history of Cuyahoga County, Ohio. It included a two-page
biography of my great-great-grandfather, a respected farmer named
Edward Mason Anthony, for whom I'm named.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have access to the Internet, try searching on Yahoo!
under the terms ``genealogy'' or ``family history.'' Those will
lead you to hundreds of sites that will help you on your way. With
the amount of stuff that's on the Web today, you might even find a
new relative or two to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask your parents to take you to the places where your family
came from. If you visit the Washington Monument or Kitty Hawk or
Stone Mountain, why not go to the towns where your own family made
history as well? When you get there, look up your name in the phone
book and see what you find. And again _ write everything down.
Years from now, you'll be glad you did.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say history is bone-dry. To them I say this: My
ancestors were ship captains, immigrants, farmers, storekeepers,
fighters for religious freedom and more. They were all part of
American history, which makes me part of it too. I'm connected to
the past _ personally. I've visited some fascinating places in my
search. And by understanding where I came from, I'm closer to my
family, and I understand better who I am.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that doesn't sound at all bone-dry to me.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   TRACING YOUR FAMILY'S HISTORYTRACING YOUR FAMILY'S HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   For more tips on how to track your family's roots, check out
``The Family Tree Detective: Cracking the Case of Your Family's
Story,'' (Owl Books, $9.95). It teaches you about finding dominant
genes, gives you interview tips and tells you what's in a name.
</P>
<P>
   Manoel Antonio (c. 1740-1792) was the father of . . .
</P>
<P>
   John Anthony (1764-1826), who was the father of . . .
</P>
<P>
   James Shearman Anthony (1794-1845), who was the father of . . .
</P>
<P>
   Edward Mason Anthony (1826-1891), who was the father of . . .
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Mason Anthony (1858-1911), who was the father of . . .
</P>
<P>
   Edward Mason Anthony Sr. (1894-1954), who was the father of . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Mason Anthony Jr. (1922- ), who is the father of . . .
</P>
<P>
   Edward Mason Anthony IV, or Ted Anthony, which is me.
</P>
<P>
   CUTLINE FOR ILLUSTRATION: Beginning his search at age 14, Ted
Anthony set out to find his forefathers. He tracked the Anthony
family line back seven generations. Here's who he found: Manoel
Antonio (c. 1740-1792) was the father of John Anthony (1764-1826),
who was the father of James Shearman Anthony (1794-1845), who was
the father of Edward Mason Anthony (1826-1891), who was the father
of Hubert Mason Anthony (1859-1911), who was the father of Edward
Mason Anthony Sr. (1894-1954), who was the father of Edward Mason
Anthony Jr. (born 1922), who is the father of Edward Mason Anthony
IV, or Ted Anthony (born 1968), who is the writer of today's NFK
article on family trees.
</P>
<P>
   WRITE US: News for Kids, P.O. Box 4689,
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, GA 30302
</P>
<P>
   FAX: 404-526-5509
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
