<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Avalanche pushes Stars to the brink 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DALLAS _ Stars fans were expecting Renoir. They got Ren and
Stimpy. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing the biggest game since the franchise moved to Texas six
years ago, the Stars bumbled their way to a 7-5 loss to the
Colorado Avalanche yesterday in Game 5 of the Western Conference
finals before the 45th consecutive sellout crowd at Reunion Arena. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Ed Belfour had his worst game of the playoffs, and
defenseman Shawn Chambers had possibly the worst game of his
career. The Stars as a whole put together one of their most
confusing efforts of the season at a time when they most needed
consistency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In all, it made for a baffling afternoon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they got was what we gave them,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``We just made far too many mistakes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By doing so, the Stars now have put themselves on the brink of
elimination. They will travel to Denver for tomorrow night's Game 6
trailing the best-of-seven series three games to two. The Stars,
who once held a 2-1 lead in this series and all the momentum, must
win the remaining two games if they hope to advance to the Stanley
Cup Finals for the third time in franchise history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said. ``It's time to pull up our shorts; there's no doubt
about that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars looked as if they were skating with their shorts down
for much of the game. Chambers twice made bad decisions on key
goals, Belfour allowed big shots to squirt through from the
perimeter for the first time in the series and Matvichuk lost a
personal battle with Avalanche center Peter Forsberg, who had vowed
to avenge what he perceived to be a dirty hit by Matvichuk in Game
4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And with all that, the score still was tied at 5-5 with 9:03
remaining in the game thanks to Pat Verbeek's gritty goal-scoring
effort. Verbeek muscled in his second goal of the playoffs on a
backhanded wraparound that cleanly beat Avalanche goalie Patrick
Roy and tied the score. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But only 2:19 later, Chambers, who had been benched for earlier
mistakes, finished off a tough night when he returned to the ice
for a rare third-period shift. After Avalanche center Joe Sakic
came up with a strong play to work high in the slot, Chambers left
Avalanche rookie Chris Drury alone in front of Belfour in hopes of
getting to Sakic, who fired a shot right past Chambers. Sergei
Zubov, Chambers' defensive partner, wasn't able to get to Drury
before the Avalanche rookie swiped a rebound past Belfour for the
game-winner at 13:16 of the third period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drury, who came up with the game-winning goal in overtime of
Game 4, has four game-winning goals in the playoffs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg added an empty-net goal for the Avalanche, who finally
cracked a Stars defense that had held them to 10 goals in the four
previous games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some tired mistakes,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``The physical and emotional side of this series is taking
its toll on people. Some of our slower people today really
struggled.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took advantage of uneven special-teams play for two
power-play goals and one shorthanded goal. But the Avalanche took
advantage of five-on-five situations as lines were juggled and
defensive pairings were mixed to compensate for the special-teams
play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Avalanche, which was missing top-end players
Theo Fleury (flu) and Milan Hejduk (broken collarbone), thrived in
the helter-skelter environment, and the Stars, masters of
discipline, looked totally out of place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We played their game; we fell into exactly the game they
wanted to play, and we couldn't come out of it because we couldn't
get the lead,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``There's no way we can let that
happen again. We didn't give ourselves a chance to win this game
because we just made far too many mistakes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Stars will have to find a way to fix those mistakes by
tomorrow night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to decide what we're going to do with our season in
the next 48 hours,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``We're
still in this, and it's still up to us what's going to happen. We
have to find a way to fix this before the next game.'' &QL; 
\Ntagtop: Mike Heika, (817) 390-7760. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
