<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY OF STARS' DEFENSE IS QUITE STOOGE-LIKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Instead of the three stars of the game yesterday at
Reunion Arena, we're taking nominations for the Three Stooges of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Any three Stars defensemen, feel free to step forward.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of the most important day in franchise history,
or at least since the Stars arrived in Dallas from Minnesota six
years ago, the Stars completely forgot _ in the famous words of one
Darrell Royal _ who brung them to the dance in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   They allowed themselves to be suckered into a shootout with the
gunslinging Colorado Avalanche and _ no suprise here _ were
riddled, 7-5, in a game that was both immensely entertaining and
excruciatingly painful for the 45th consecutive sellout crowd at
Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning loss puts the Stars on a precipice they hoped
they'd never see during a playoff run that they were sure would
take them all the way to the Stanley Cup Finals: On the cusp of
elimination in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars must win first in Denver tomorrow night, then again
Friday night back at Reunion, or their season will be over.
</P>
<P>
   If stupid is as stupid does, as Forrest Gump so eloquently
reminded us a while back, then the Stars went moronic at the most
inopportune time. The one thing they simply could not do against
star-laden Colorado was allow the Avalanche to turn Reunion into a
shooting gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a run-and-gun game,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher
conceded. ``I don't know how it happened, but we fell into it, and
that's not our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Duuuhhh!
</P>
<P>
   This was the absolute worst time for the Stars to abandon their
defense-first style of play, the philosophy that had won them the
Presidents' Trophy the past two seasons as the NHL's best
regular-season team. Not this on a day when goalie Ed Belfour was
giving up goals like Rangers starting pitchers cough up runs.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he was facing a fusillade of odd-man rushes, but ``The
Eagle'' has made those same saves throughout the playoffs and _
sorry, Eddie _ we're spoiled. We've come to expect them every time
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw tired people on the ice for both teams,'' said an
obviously upset Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, who blamed the quick
turnaround from Game 4 and declined to comment on Belfour's
performance. ``It was pretty obvious who those players were. The
physical and emotional side of this series is taking its toll on
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had some people in trouble, and we had some people in
trouble. From a goal standpoint, people saw a pretty exciting
hockey game, and from an effort standpoint, a very exciting hockey
game. But we also saw a lot of uncharacteristic mistakes, a lot of
tired mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to pick on one player, because he wasn't alone out there,
but Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers was an awful minus-4 for the
game. He was on the ice, either standing or prone, for four of
Colorado's seven goals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, so was the faceoff circle, and both moved at about
the same pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I was out there, it's like I would make a bad move,
and it went in our net,'' Chambers admitted. ``We had too many
breakdowns, and it cost us. Every time we did that, they scored.''
</P>
<P>
   It is particularly disturbing that the Stars lost the way they
did because, if Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Joe Nieuwendyk are the
heart of the team, their core of six defensemen _ Hatcher, Craig
Ludwig, Richard Matvichuk, Darryl Sydor, Sergei Zubov and Chambers
_ have been the backbone.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that prides itself on its defense, thrives on
winning the 2-1 and 3-2 games, on taking a one-goal lead and
smothering teams to death. Yesterday, the Stars' defense twice blew
one-goal leads and gallantly fought back from a 5-3 deficit to tie
the score. Then, just two shifts later, they let they the Avalanche
score on yet another odd-man rush with about 6 1/2 minutes left to
take the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our slower people really struggled,'' Hitchcock said.
``It took us out of sync. When your legs are gone, your hands
follow, and you saw some weak puck play and some weak decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their sixth \Rand game-winning\S goal was really disappointing
because we made three mistakes. It was really a two-on-two, then
our defenseman Zubov got run off, then it was really a poor
decision \Rby Chambers, who left Avalanche rookie Chris Drury
uncovered\S at the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche's final goal was a Peter Forsberg chip shot into
an empty net, but by that time, it didn't look all that much
different than the first six.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hurts,'' admitted Nieuwendyk, who scored his ninth
goal of the playoffs. ``We are a tight-checking team, and we got
away from that. That's the way \Rthey\S prepare to play. We bit
into it and it cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost them dearly.
</P>
<P>
   They are in a place they never wanted to be this playoff summer,
and they have no one to blame but their Curly, Larry and Moe
selves.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Stars fan, that's not even a bit funny.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
