<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: BIG BUDGET EARNS BIG BENEFIT FOR DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Buck Showalter wouldn't say it. ``We're going to find
out how good we are,'' said the manager whose team had just
completed a three-game sweep of the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley wouldn't say it. ``We're just going to go out there
and play hard every day and just try to win that game at hand,''
said the outfielder, who collected four hits and drove in five runs
with two home runs in the first three innings of the 10-1 victory
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Randy Johnson was willing to say it. ``It's reassuring to
know this team can contend,'' said the pitcher, who in his first
game against the Mets allowed five hits and struck out 10 in eight
innings. ``It's reassuring to know that we can compete with the
best teams and maybe we're opening some eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, some eyes have opened gapingly wide because the Arizona
Diamondbacks, the two-year-old Diamondbacks, have a
two-and-a-half-game lead in the National League West. If the NL
teams were ranked together, Arizona (30-21) would be tied in second
place with Houston (29-20), both a half-game behind Atlanta
(30-20).
</P>
<P>
   As all of the Diamondbacks, including Johnson, were quick to
point out, the season is only two months old. The marathon has four
more months to run. But Rupert Murdoch's Dodgers, who were
virtually conceded the NL West title before the season began, don't
have a 30-21 record. The Mets, those wild-card wannabes, don't have
a 30-21 record.
</P>
<P>
   But here are the Diamondbacks, the product of Jerry Colangelo's
pocketbook, among the league's elite, creating a lost weekend for
the Mets, who last year won five of nine games with the expansion
team but this season have lost five of six.
</P>
<P>
   If the Los Angeles Dodgers should stop meandering through the
season and take command of the division or if the eventual return
of Barry Bonds injects new life into the San Francisco Giants, the
Diamondbacks could find themselves competing with the Mets for the
wild-card spot. If that should happen, the upstart Diamondbacks
have left the Mets with much to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he saw as the significance of beating the Mets,
Johnson said: ``It's important because the New York Mets have a
very good team, and they're going to be in the wild cards. It's
important to know that we can go and compete with some of the
bigger market teams, the L.A.'s, the New York Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   Note that Johnson, whom the Diamondbacks lured last November
with a four-year, $52.4 million contract, referred to
``bigger-market teams.'' Market size has nothing to do with it.
Revenue and the willingness to spend that revenue are more to the
point. The Diamondbacks have more revenue than most teams and a
greater willingness to spend it than most teams.
</P>
<P>
   That is neither a laudatory nor a critical commentary on
Colangelo's operation of the team. A longtime owner in the National
Basketball Association, Colangelo quickly identified how the
Diamondbacks could compete sooner rather than later and wasted no
time acting on that desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into spring training,'' Johnson, the prized recruit,
said, ``the talk was how good our starting rotation was. The
offense got overshadowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at that offense now. The Diamondbacks are first in the
league in hitting, runs scored, runs driven in, hits, home runs,
total bases and slugging percentage. As if Johnson needed it, they
gave him three runs before he threw his first pitch at Shea
Stadium, then quickly added four more in the next two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to be on a team that's competing for first
place,'' the long-haired left-hander said, but quickly added: ``I
don't want to look that far down the road. I don't want to predict
anything. Just go out and continue doing the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he didn't know how good his team was. Asked if
the league should take the Diamondbacks seriously, he said: ``Not
necessarily. I'm as curious as the fans are to find out how good we
are. We're going to find out. I have a lot of trust in the people
we brought in here. I think about it constantly, but I don't want
to spend a lot of time worrying about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he at least say that the Diamondbacks are a wild-card
contender? ``No,'' he said. ``We're going to be as good as we can
be. I'm looking forward to finding out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets hadn't been eager to find out first-hand how good
Johnson was. But Melvin Mora didn't mind. But then, Mora was
playing in his first major-league game after having spent
eight-plus seasons in a variety of minor league outposts and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' said the shortstop, who hit three fly balls in
three attempts against Johnson. ``A lot of people maybe thought I
wasn't going to touch the ball, but I did. I had three good swings.
I'll get him next time. He's just another pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   And Einstein was merely another scientist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
