<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOVAKIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOVAKS CHOOSE PRO-EUROPE DEMOCRAT AS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia _ Rudolf Schuster, the candidate of the
governing four-party coalition and the popular mayor of the eastern
town of Kosice, defeated former Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar to
become the first elected president of Slovakia, according to
results announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, 65, is one of the few former Communists to have made a
successful transition to democratic politics. His victory _ with 57
percent of the vote _ in a runoff election held on Saturday
confirmed that Slovaks have turned their backs on Meciar, whose six
years as prime minister saw his country become ever more isolated
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster's victory indicated that Slovakia will continue the
course of integration with Europe that has been pursued since
Meciar lost parliamentary elections in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider this result a victory of democracy,'' Prime
Minister Mikulas Dzurinda said of Schuster's victory. ``The outcome
of this election confirms Slovakia's pro-European orientation and
sends a very important signal abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Slovakia was formed, along with the neighboring Czech Republic,
from the peaceful split of Czechoslovakia on Jan. 1, 1993. The
first president of Slovakia, Michal Kovac, was once an ally of
Meciar but increasingly turned against him. When Kovac's five-year
term expired in March 1998, a deadlock in Parliament left the
legislature unable to agree on a successor.
</P>
<P>
   After the parliamentary elections in September, the Constitution
was changed to allow direct election of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Slovak leaders hope that their country will join the Czechs,
Poles and Hungarians among the group of postcommunist countries
seeking swift entry into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slovakia will continue to make its way to the European
Union,'' Schuster said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was defeated, the election results suggest that
Meciar still remains a powerful player on the Slovak political
scene. His years in power were marked by what many Slovaks regarded
as cronyism and by increasing international isolation, but he is an
ebullient campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even younger Slovaks who said they felt uneasy about
Schuster's Communist past explained that they had voted for him
because they did not want a return to the days of Meciar. Frantisek
Palko, 24, said after voting in Bratislava, the capital, on
Saturday that he had chosen Schuster only because ``it is better
than if Vladimir Meciar won.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuster was a member of the Communist Party from 1964 until
1990, and he served as the last Communist speaker of the Slovak
Parliament after the ``Velvet Revolution'' of 1989 ushered in the
demise of Communist rule, which formally ended when democrats won
free elections in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
