u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1STLD     05-30 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES SAY THEY WERE HELD AT SITE THAT WAS BOMBED
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: Adds ``NOT'' to 1st clause of 8th graph.) (Exclusive)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ They had no choice but to spend the night
outside a warehouse off the highway in Korisa, Haxhere Palushi said
Sunday. There were 700 Albanian refugees like her, and Serb
soldiers herded them all inside the building's iron outer gates,
promising they would be allowed to leave Kosovo the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, one soldier clicked the gate shut with a
padlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``One young guy said, `Why did they lock us in? Something is
happening,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, just before midnight on May 13, NATO planes
again bombed the village, in southern Kosovo, killing what Serb
officials and survivors say was more than 80 Albanian refugees.
Mrs. Palushi sat in a field all night watching her 4-year-old
daughter, Diana, bleed from shrapnel wounds in her left leg and
then, at dawn, die.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Korisa killed perhaps more Albanian civilians than
any other in the two-month NATO air campaign, which has been
criticized for its fatal mistakes. At the time, Serb authorities,
claiming that the refugees had merely stopped at Korisa for the
night, said the incident showed why NATO should stop the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But three Albanian survivors _ women interviewed here Sunday for
some of the few eyewitness accounts of the bombing _ said they had
no doubt they were put there intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used us as human shields,'' Mrs. Palushi said. ``It was
all planned.''
</P>
<P>
   While the accounts could not be independently confirmed, they
appeared to give weight to similar allegations by the Pentagon and
NATO that Serb forces have placed civilians near sites, like
bridges or military installations, that could be vulnerable to
attack.
</P>
<P>
   There is still no way to tell from these accounts how widely or
systematically such a strategy might be used. Nor are they likely
to quiet critics who say that NATO targeting procedures are not
adequate on a battlefield where civilians are mixed with military
targets.
</P>
<P>
   But these accounts suggest that in Korisa, at least, the
refugees had been calculatingly placed in harm's way, if not to
deter a NATO attack then to create the kind of civilian casualties
that the Serbs hope could erode support for the air campaign. NATO
officials said the planes specifically targeted the building among
other military sites in the town without knowing that civilians
were there.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Palushi described the bombing in one of the refugee camps
here, at the door-flap of a tent that now sleeps 19 people, 10 of
whom survived the attack. The survivors arrived in Albania on
Saturday, and many of them still show signs of their wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Palushi's older son, Driton, 10, pulled up his shirt to
show a scar that runs from his navel to his sternum, from an
operation to remove a piece of shrapnel that pierced his back and
wedged near one lung. His cousin, Genci Ahmetaj, 4, still has a
bandage on his right foot covering his own shrapnel wound.
</P>
<P>
   Purple scars mark the face of Genci's mother, Zyrafete, 30, and,
no doubt, there are emotional wounds as well.
</P>
<P>
   The night of the attack, Mrs. Ahmetaj said she was sleeping
under the tractor wagon that sheltered her two children, along with
six other children and two adults. Huge explosions erupted. Tents
caught fire. Bits of the tractors blasted through the compound.
Children were shrieking, including hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what was happening,'' she said. ``It was like I
was crazy. I saw my mother and I touched her but she was dead. My
father, blood was all over his face.''
</P>
<P>
   She heard the voice of her 10-year-old son, Agon, from inside
the wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was screaming, `Look what they did to my legs,''' she
said. ``He started screaming, `Mommy, my legs! Why don't you come
get me?' He was only 10 years old. I could only take the little
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go back and get him,'' she said. ``But the other
people wouldn't let me go back and take my son. The Serbs were
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know I left him,'' she said. ``He was there, and he was
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she heard later that Agon died at 7 a.m., next to an
old man who had found him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying, `Give me some water,''' Mrs. Ahmetaj said.
</P>
<P>
   She wept. ``I am worried that no one could give him water.''
</P>
<P>
   She and others said that Serb forces opened fire on the refugees
as they fled from the burning compound. Those who escaped made
their way to Prizren after the attack, where some received
treatment for wounds. Saturday, they were bused out of Kosovo by
the Serbs, apparently the first batch of survivors from the Korisa
attack to get to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   They were among thousands of Albanian refugees fleeing the
burning houses and looting by Serb policemen and paramilitary
soldiers near the city of Prizren. Mrs. Ahmetaj's sister, Sahadete
Ahmetaj, 26, said hundreds of refugees had been living in the hills
near Korisa for two months, waiting to go to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Weary, on May 13, after some in the group approached Serb police
officers, the refugees were promised that they could leave safely
the next day. They took some 700 people to a field for an hour,
then moved them to a warehouse surrounded on three-sides by a
chest-high concrete wall and a fence with an iron door. There they
took everyone's name and birth date, Mrs. Ahmetaj said, saying they
could move on the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But they had to spend that night outside at the courtyard of the
warehouse, she said. The Serb soldiers did not indicate that they
were being arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we could only stay in that place,'' Mrs. Ahmetaj
said. ``We were not allowed to go anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   The police officers then locked the refugees in and left the
compound, the survivors said.
</P>
<P>
   Just before midnight, four American F-16s dropped what officials
said later was one 500-pound laser-guided bomb and seven other
bombs. The women said that 84 refugees were killed, many of them
burned beyond recognition. A NATO official, who spoke on the
condition anonymity, said that despite reports that all the police
had left, some police guards appeared to be among the dead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebel group
fighting the Yugoslav army in Kosovo, said Sunday that the general
area around the warehouse was used to store tanks and ammunition,
though they had no information about that particular building. The
survivors said it appeared to be empty. The NATO official said
intelligence reports before the bombing identified it as a command
post, though he said it might have been vacated before the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Ahmetaj sisters said they did not blame NATO for the attack,
even if it was NATO bombs that killed their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are guilty,'' said Sahadete Ahmetaj. ``NATO didn't
know they attacked us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Palushi, whose daughter was killed, said she did not blame
NATO either, though she said she exploded in anger when she took
her son to a hospital in Prizren and a Serb doctor told her: ``You
wanted NATO to help you. Look what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very upset, I was very nervous,'' she said. ``I said, `I
didn't want NATO. I don't want you. I don't want the KLA. I only
want peace.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     05-30 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, EWING BURIES MILLER AND THE PACERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For years, Patrick Ewing has seen the waifish
Reggie Miller jackknife around screens, pop free for devastating
shots and then go dancing on the New York Knicks' misery, boldly
spinning and twirling on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is not so light on his feet, not so electric in his
methods. But in his own lumbering way, Ewing slipped into Miller's
role Sunday and gave the Knicks a first push toward reaching their
ultimate goal. Displaying the kind of cool that has been questioned
over the years, Ewing scored six points in the final two minutes of
the game, including four consecutive free throws, to help the
Knicks steal Game 1 of the Eastern Conference finals from the
Indiana Pacers, 93-90, before a crestfallen crowd at Market Square
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, his misses have been well chronicled, and his every
make has been often overlooked,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``He
was jumping out on Reggie Miller on a sore Achilles' that most
wouldn't play on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing jumped out on Miller with 13 seconds left in the game and
the Knicks ahead on two Ewing free throws, 90-88. Miller came
whip-snapping around a screen, sprang out beyond the three-point
line and saw Allan Houston coming late to his left and Ewing come
charging to his right. Still, there was a sliver of light and a
chance to release the shot. But Miller's 3-point attempt, which
would have given the Pacers a lead, bounded off the right side of
the rim and fell into the arms of Chris Childs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick has seen that play 200 times,'' said Miller, who led
the Pacers with 19 points. ``He knew it was coming. It was a good
hedge on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   With 12.4 seconds left, Childs was fouled and made both free
throws, giving the Knicks a 92-88 lead. It wasn't over, though.
Antonio Davis came up with an uncontested dunk, and then the Pacers
quickly fouled Childs. This time, he hit just one of two free
throws with 6.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   One more moment for Miller to be a hero. But Miller could not
shake free of Houston, and Mark Jackson was left to throw up a
desperate shot that came up short. Ewing caught the miss and hugged
it until the buzzer sounded. What began as a dreadful day for Ewing
_ he was 4-for-13 with 16 points _ ended with him in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Patrick has done, with how hurt he is, it's amazing,''
Houston said. ``You see him wincing in pain, but he still goes out
there and plays.''
</P>
<P>
   After a game dominated by the Knicks' running game, the end
boiled down to a slower-paced finish between two centers who hadn't
been so involved.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was the Pacers' Rik Smits. The Knicks had a 70-63 lead
to start the fourth quarter. After a miserable stretch by Marcus
Camby, which included two fouls and a three-second violation, the
Pacers pulled to 72-69 on a driving layup by Jalen Rose. Camby came
right back and bulled inside of Sam Perkins to get to the
free-throw line and hit two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers went to Smits, who had missed seven of his first
eight shots. Playing with five fouls, Smits delivered six points in
a two-minute stretch to give the Pacers an 87-82 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing came back with a finger roll. After Smits fouled out with
1 minute 33 seconds left, the Knicks put the ball in Ewing's hands.
He spun through the lane on two consecutive possessions and drew a
foul on both. He came up with four straight free throws to give the
Knicks a 90-88 lead with 29.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was a game of spurts,'' Ewing said. ``We came up and
they came back. We kept our poise and made the plays down the
stretch. A lot of people have doubted us. But we just keep on doing
what we have to do to stay alive. We stepped up our game. Reggie
has killed us so many times, I can't remember. So we started
trapping him. If someone was going to beat us, it was going to be
someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Knicks tested the wheels on their transition game
as quickly as possible, which meant the instant Latrell Sprewell
stepped onto the court. When the Knicks were at their best, they
were taking almost every Pacer miss and turning it into an easy
basket. That style helped them battle back each time the Pacers
looked on the brink of taking over the momentum of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' transition game left them with a 44-40 halftime lead
and helped them come back from a three-point deficit in the third
quarter to grab a 70-63 edge entering into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's aggressiveness was contagious. Larry Johnson and
Houston were all caught up in what he brought onto the floor.
Thirty seconds after he entered the game with 4:47 left in the
first quarter, Sprewell picked off a pass by Jackson and took it
all the way for a fast-break layin to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was on fire whether he was getting out on the break or
penetrating and kicking the ball out to Houston for a
three-pointer. Sprewell, guiding a 12-1 run, led the Knicks to a
nine-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers slowed down the pace. Suddenly, in the half-court
game, Rose was irritating Sprewell and making him miss. Slowly, the
Pacers chipped away to hold the Knicks without a field goal for
nearly six minutes beginning in the final minute of the first
quarter. Meanwhile, the Pacers' second unit became the aggressors.
Antonio Davis got to the line in between runners by Rose over
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers grabbed back the lead, 26-25, with 7:50 left in the
half. The Knicks came right back, though, using their veterans.
Johnson filled the lane on one fast break and popped outside for a
three-pointer on another.
</P>
<P>
   Although Miller was definitely working his way around Houston,
who seemed caught up on too many screens, and Jackson was effective
in posting up Ward, the Knicks were able to counter with 18
fast-break points to the Pacers' five in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers opened up the third quarter using a variety pack
including a basket by Smits, a dunk by Dale Davis and a
three-pointer by Chris Mullin in transition to go on a 13-6 run and
take a 53-50 lead. With an aggressive Kurt Thomas, who flailed at
Smits at the end of one possession, grabbing key rebounds, the
Knicks came back and took the lead 59-57 on a face-up jumper from
Houston over Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell took over. He came up with two runners on the break and
ended the third quarter with a runner that drew a foul on Rose with
four-tenths of a second left to give the Knicks a 70-63 lead after
the third. After the Knicks gave that lead away and trailed by five
points, Ewing came out of nowhere to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it bad,'' Ewing said. ``And when you want it bad,
you step up and try to do the best you can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
