<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICK-VETERANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: A NEW KNICKS' TEAM RELIES ON VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In the week leading up to the Eastern Conference
finals, Reggie Miller and Mark Jackson tried to impress upon their
teammates how different the Knicks were from the team they had
faced on the last Sunday of the regular season; how these Knicks
were different from any Knicks team they had ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting the rout at Market Square Arena on May 2, the two
veterans prodded the Indiana Pacers into tossing aside whatever
preconceived notions they had about Patrick Ewing's decrepit
half-court style and told them to focus on the fuel-injected
vehicle the Knicks had become over the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Latrell Sprewell,'' Miller said of the Knicks'
sixth man. ``He's getting out there and running the break now,
getting points in transition. Their running game is starting to
click through him, and we have to be aware of that. And Marcus
Camby is a great athlete with all kinds of wingspan. The guys
coming off their bench present major problems for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. The Pacers worried about the new guys and
forgot about the old Knicks, the catch-and-shoot veterans who
calmly moved the ball around the perimeter in the final minutes:
Ewing, Allan Houston, Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   For in the crucible of Game 1 Sunday, when every possession in
the fourth quarter meant so much and Sprewell's shot selection left
a lot to be desired, Ewing led the Knicks back from a 5-point
deficit in the final 2 minutes 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won, 93-90, because Ewing rebounded, Houston and
Johnson hit several big shots to keep Indiana at bay, and the
Knicks made almost all their free throws. For one game, the style
of Sprewell and Camby gave in to the substance of Ewing and the
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   What symmetry. Ewing's 36-year-old, battered body sat in a
cramped, 30-year-old locker room Sunday, going through the usual
post-game routine of soaking his left leg in a bucket of ice water.
A member of the news media mentioned to Ewing that he was going to
have to stop writing about how Ewing always misses half his free
throws; Ewing had made eight in a row, including four in the final
30.6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff was always messing with me about that,'' Ewing said of
Coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``This year, I've been hitting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell finished 6 of 16 from the field, and Camby got into
early foul trouble and was hardly a factor. In a chess match to be
played out over the next two weeks, Jalen Rose left the bench first
after Miller got into foul trouble early. Van Gundy countered with
Sprewell a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   Each suffered through a 3-for-9 first half, though Sprewell
finally found a rhythm in the third quarter. But he was all over
the map, taking ill-advised long jumpers and unable to successfully
back Rose into the post so he could get a decent shot within 12
feet of the basket.
</P>
<P>
   He provided the slashing athleticism to keep the defense honest,
his wild forays sometimes leaving his teammates open on the
perimeter. Two possessions in the final quarter, though, reflected
his day.
</P>
<P>
   He flew by Mark Jackson along the left baseline and scored on a
layup to keep the Knicks in front by 4 points. But on the next
possession, with less than six minutes left and the Knicks still
clinging to a two-point lead, Sprewell forced a 19-footer that
nearly went 21 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He then threw up an airball after a no-call against Derrick
McKey, who grazed Sprewell's elbow enough to change the shot.
</P>
<P>
   This series was supposed to come down to both teams' benches, a
duel featuring Sprewell and Camby vs. Rose and Antonio Davis.
Travis Best and Derrick McKey were supposed to play huge roles for
Indiana, and Chris Dudley and Childs were said to be key for the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   And while those players figured in the outcome, you simply
cannot get away from the fact that some people playing now have
been there before, have taken the crucial shots, and they
understand how to get position under the basket when an important
rebound is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Limping and sore, Ewing is still one of those players.
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks were going to pull out Game 1, they would have to
resort to the old guard. Ewing is supposed to recede into the
background and let his teammates win a championship ring for him,
but you sometimes forget how much respect he gets from the
officials in the waning moments of a close game.
</P>
<P>
   Few players can get those calls like Ewing, not that he did not
deserve the calls on the fouls committed against him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets unwarranted criticism in New York,'' Miller said
afterward, impressed that Ewing had played injured. ``He's been the
backbone of the team for so many years. He's always proving the
news media and the fans in New York wrong when it should be the
other way around. He's been there so much for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's definitely a different New York team, a lot
more running and athleticism.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks reverted back to their old-school ways Sunday,
getting the defensive stops they needed and making every possession
count. The more things change, the more they stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, proud and hobbled as ever, was there at the end to decide
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any other body part could hurt him at this
point,'' Van Gundy said. ``There's nothing left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
