<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSINUATION REVISITED IN N.Y. POLICE-BRUTALITY TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the trial in the Abner Louima case opened a
month ago, the lawyer for Officer Justin Volpe suggested that
Louima had suffered severe internal injuries not because of torture
by his client but in a consensual sex act with another man.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive insinuation in an already explosive case was
assailed in front of the courthouse by leaders of groups
representing homosexuals, and it stirred an uproar generally. But
the lawyers for the three other police officers and for the
sergeant also on trial said nothing publicly about the opening
argument by Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg.
</P>
<P>
   That was not surprising: it would have been highly unusual for a
lawyer to publicly undercut the case that a co-defendant's lawyer
was presenting. But when Volpe pleaded guilty in midtrial last
week, a lawyer for one of the four remaining defendants no longer
felt the need for restraint regarding Kornberg's suggestion that
rough sex _ rather than Volpe's ramming a stick into Louima's
rectum _ had torn the victim's rectum and bladder.
</P>
<P>
   John Patten, the lawyer for Sgt. Michael Bellomo, one of the men
on trial, on Wednesday offered a critical assessment of Kornberg's
actions. This was the day after Volpe pleaded guilty to torturing
Louima with the stick in a restroom in the 70th Precinct station
house in Brooklyn and to other charges in the case. While the jury
was not in the courtroom, Patten asked Judge Eugene Nickerson in
U.S. District Court in Brooklyn to declare a mistrial for Bellomo
because of Volpe's guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   Patten first made the expected argument: Volpe's plea hurt his
client's chances of getting a fair trial, because his admission of
guilt could lead the jurors to believe that the other defendants
must also be guilty. But Patten's second argument was not expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an attorney stand before this jury for three
weeks,'' he said, ``opening by saying it was consensual sex and
homosexual behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson interrupted: ``I don't remember him ever saying that.
He implied it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patten agreed, but made clear that he considered this a
distinction without a difference. Kornberg's actions, he went on,
had ``established a certain loss of trust'' between ``that jury and
all of the counsel at this table.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``You can't look people in the eye for three weeks
and tell them one thing and then completely reverse yourself and
then tell them something else without those people coming to some
type of conclusion that we've lied to them. I submit the lack of
trust that could be established by that has overflowed to all
counsel.'' The judge denied the motion for mistrial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because Volpe was out of the case and in jail, Kornberg was not
in the courtroom when Patten spoke. Asked later for comment,
Kornberg, who is known for relishing verbal warfare, was restrained
this time, saying: ``Each lawyer has to do what they feel is best
to protect their client's interests. I'm not surprised the judge
dismissed that motion.''
</P>
<P>
   The four defendants still on trial are Bellomo and Officers
Thomas Wiese, Thomas Bruder and Charles Schwarz. The three officers
are charged with joining Volpe in beating Louima in a police car
between his arrest in a street melee and his torture by Volpe in a
restroom at the station house on Aug. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors, from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn,
said the officers erroneously believed Louima had punched Volpe
during the melee. They said that Schwarz also held Louima down in
the restroom while Volpe used the stick, and accused Bellomo of
trying to cover up the beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   With Volpe and his lawyers, Kornberg and Edwin Schulman, no
longer at the defense table, the remaining four defendants and
their seven lawyers could take advantage of the newly created space
to spread out a bit. Instead, they remain as crowded together as
they have been since the start of the trial, and the three chairs
that Volpe and his lawyers occupied have stayed in place, empty.
</P>
<P>
   And that is how things will remain, two of the defense lawyers
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be as disconnected from Volpe as possible,'' said
Bruder's lawyer, Stuart London.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese's lawyer, Joseph Tacopina, suggested that the empty chairs
would be a perfect prop during the closing arguments, expected this
week, when the lawyers for the remaining defendants argue that the
only guilty person in the case is no longer in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, as the prosecution has vilified them, the
defendants have sat without expression. But last week, there was a
crack in one officer's facade.
</P>
<P>
   The brother of Wiese's fiancee was testifying as a character
witness for him. ``Tommy is a prince among men,'' the witness,
Kevin Reid, said of the officer. ``I love the guy like a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiese removed his eyeglasses. He raised his hand to his eyes and
appeared to be wiping away tears with his fingers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
