<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Short woman gets a kick out of driving tall cars
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BY Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Please do not refer to my condition as
vertically challenged or under-tall. Although it's not politically
correct, it is the ugly truth - I'm SHORT! Eleven-year-olds are
taller than I am, and my son, for yuks and giggles, likes to rest
his arm on top of my head and crack wise about his ``cute little
mama.'' Even tall strangers say dumb stuff like: Seen any good
parades lately?
</P>
<P>
   In these days of super-tall kids (it's all of those vitamins we
poke in their chubby faces), short folks need to take advantage of
every opportunity to gainthe advantage, and I've figured out a way
to hold my own in the transportation department.
</P>
<P>
   I buy tall cars.
</P>
<P>
   For a while last year after a soft drink truck chewed up my '87
Bronco, I thought I might like to have a go at something even
taller - like maybe one of those semi trucks that bounces me around
on the Interstate. I've always thought I'd get a kick out of
driving one of those things, and now that they come with waterbeds
and patios, it's even more tempting.
</P>
<P>
   As I see it, there's only one drawback to my truck driving
career. Backing upcould be a problem, so I've decided not to do
that. Think about it - if I have 12 gears going forward then who
needs to back up? I'll be having all the fun I can have without
reverse as long as I can find nose-in parking places.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Christmas my parents gave me a shiny new maroon
convertible (I was four and the car had push-pedals), I've been
fascinated with things that go Vroom! And over the years I've
learned a lot more about cars than juststeering and paying parking
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, I knew I did not like my parents' 1954 Buick. No
gears to shift. Remember the old Dynaflow transmissions? No
noticeable change of gears. No lurch, No clunk. You just put your
foot in it and waited for inertia to be overcome. I remember
listening to the transmission wind up tighter and tighterand
wondering when the old Roadmaster's vitals were going to come
flying out from under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later I fell in love with an Austin-Healey, a
wicked-looking British sports car. It was sleek, fast, and best of
all, had lots of gears to
</P>
<P>
   shift - as long as the synchromesh was working - which it often
didn't. Once Ispent a lifetime in a Marshall Field's parking lot
waiting for my ``funny car'' mechanic to come and kick something to
make it go.
</P>
<P>
   Just before I drove my first Healey out of the showroom, I
remember asking the dealer what that big hammer in the trunk was
for. He explained it was a resin mallet and was for tightening the
spinners that held the wheels onto the hub. As it turned out, I
never had to pull a wheel but I did use the big hammer - often.
</P>
<P>
   One snowy afternoon in the same parking lot, the Healey wouldn't
start so I went back into the store and called the mechanic. Our
conversation went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Me: It won't go.
</P>
<P>
   Him: What's it doing?
</P>
<P>
   Me: Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Him: Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently this was all the information he needed to walk me
though some highly technical repairs. He told me to open the boot
(trunk), and pound on the accumulator (battery) cable connection
with the mallet. I asked what the battery was doing in the trunk
and he came up with the obvious reply: ``Apparently nothing right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   So there I was in a blizzard, leaning into the ``boot'' and
beating the bejeebers out of my ``accumulator'' when a nice
gentleman offered to help. I
</P>
<P>
   told him all would be fine as soon as I finished thrashing my
battery. He told me I was in the wrong end of the car. I thanked
him and kept pounding.
</P>
<P>
   Before long I gave up sporty cars - not for mechanical reasons
but because I was embarrassing myself. The only way I could get the
clutch to the
</P>
<P>
   firewall to change gears was to slide under the steering wheel
and then I couldn't see
</P>
<P>
   where I was going.
</P>
<P>
   So now I buy tall cars. Today an SUV - tomorrow a big Mack.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
