<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX     05-30 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Tacky' is as 'tacky' does
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Sometimes my clothes don't match. It doesn't
bother me a whole lot, but whenever I suspect I've slipped from
sartorial splendor to ludicrous, a little voice from the past
begins to nag: ``Tacky!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tacky'' is a pejorative southern word noted for its
flexibility of meaning. ``Tacky'' can describe anything from the
paint on the front porch floor to your son's new girlfriend's
tattoo. And no matter how it's used, it's always a ladylike thing
to say.
</P>
<P>
   For example: When I was six I wanted a pair of red sandals. Mama
said red shoes were ``tacky'' and only streetwalkers wore them. I
didn't know what one of those was but I figured it was pretty bad
for Mama to get so bent out of shape about it. No red shoes.
</P>
<P>
   One sleepy Sunday afternoon while I was still in my streetwalker
phase, I was playing store in Mama's shoe closet. On a rack in a
far back corner, I discovered a pair of silver and white satin,
high-heeled shoes that I thought were the most beautiful things I
had ever seen. They looked like Cinderella's own to me, and the
temptation to slip into them and wheel myself around the
neighborhood on my old Roadmaster was overwhelming. Mama caught me
mid-spin and hauled my silly looking self inside for a talk,
insisting I'd made a spectacle
</P>
<P>
   of myself and that it was not appropriate for little girls in
navy blue romper suits and satin high heels to pedal themselves
around the neighborhood. ``Tacky,'' she said. ``Really tacky.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I learned that ``tacky'' in Mama's dialect
covered a broad range of social infractions. Pulling up my dress
and using my petticoat for a handkerchief was seriously tacky, as
was crawling around under the pews inchurch.
</P>
<P>
   When I was nine, I played piano in our elementary school's
orchestra. I loved making music with a bunch of other kids and
found it particularly gratifying when we came out even - you know,
where no one was left playing after the others had finished.
Performing in public was not a problem, unless my mother was in the
audience - which she usually was. ``Psst!?'' I'd hear in a raucous
stage whisper from the first row. ``Sit up straight! Knees
together!? Occasionally, as an abbreviated reminder of my
backsliding ways she'd hiss
</P>
<P>
   that one little word every southern girl dreads: ``Tacky!''
</P>
<P>
   Mama's been gone a long while now, but every time I read the
paper or listen to the news, I can almost hear her comment.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Jones has stopped hanging out in Arkansas hotels, and
during a hiatus between courtrooms has lent her name to a psychic
hot line. ``Paula Jones...Celebrity Psychic Network...Accurate
answers from caring psychic advisors, for life's tough questions,
$3.99 a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Get outta' here.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Buttafuoco (the 38-year-old owner of an auto body shop who
served six months for statutory rape after his 17-year-old
girlfriend shot his wife) is alive and doing well in Los Angeles
where Mrs. Buttafuoco still loves him in spite of the bullet lodged
in her head and he is hosting his own cable talk show and pursuing
an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   Scuzzy living has its own rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Monica goes on Saturday Night Live and for $600 before taxes,
makes jokes about her slatternly romp through the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Class act, dearie.
</P>
<P>
   And let us not overlook Larry Flynt, pornographer extraordinaire
and congressional blackmailer, who recently delivered a lecture in
the hallowed halls of Washington's Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you what folks, if my mama were still here, I could
guarantee she'd be sitting right out there in the front row
harrumphing and muttering, ``Tacky!''
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
