<SLUG> BC-RAC-GIANT-KILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERKENS THE GIANT-KILLER IS FOCUSING ON THE BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ He is a tall, husky, 70-year-old man who
frequently wears a broad-brimmed white hat and a serious look, and
he always rates a respectful salute when he drives through the
stable gate at Belmont Park before dawn. But for a horse trainer
who saddled his first winner nearly 50 years ago and who is known
in New York as ``the Chief'' because of his intensity and success,
Allen Jerkens has a remarkably thin record in Triple Crown racing.
</P>
<P>
   He is 0-for-3 in the Kentucky Derby, he has never run a horse in
the Preakness and he is 0-for-2 in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, Jerkens will run a horse in the 131st Belmont
who did not run in either the Derby or the Preakness, and he will
be approached with wariness and even fear by the trainers of
Charismatic, who needs to win the Belmont to sweep the Triple
Crown, and Silverbulletday, the filly who has won eight races in a
row. To them, Jerkens has long since earned his nickname, the Giant
Killer of racing.
</P>
<P>
   The horse is Best of Luck, the 3-year-old son of Broad Brush
owned by Mrs. Allaire duPont. Best of Luck won the Peter Pan Stakes
a week ago as a stepping stone to the Belmont, and in a sense, he
will be New York's defender against the stars from California.
</P>
<P>
   So, is Best of Luck the horse picked by the Giant Killer to
upset the giants of the Triple Crown series? Is he targeted to play
that role for Jerkens the way Onion and Prove Out did when they
upset Secretariat, the way Handsome Boy did when he upset
Buckpasser, the way Beau Purple did when he upset Kelso three
times?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to finish in the money,'' Jerkens said,
sounding like the voice of reason last week at Barn 30 at Belmont
Park. ``You hate to try running in the Triple Crown unless you have
one of the five top choices. If you don't, it doesn't bug you. You
think about it, but you don't want it to interfere with your other
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best of Luck has some sort of chance. It'll be nice if it
happens. You try hard, but you don't shoot yourself if it doesn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like soft soap, and so does Jerkens' indifference to
that Giant Killer stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say Giant Killer about Billy Mott,'' he said.
``Everybody has his moments.''
</P>
<P>
   But didn't Jerkens target Secretariat _ already a Triple Crown
winner _ in 1973 before the Whitney at Saratoga, which was won by
Onion, and before the Woodward at Belmont, which was won by Prove
Out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Jerkens said. ``I thought Secretariat didn't
work well at Saratoga, and my horse did. That's the only way an
inferior horse can beat a superior one. The other time, in the
Woodward, the track was muddy. They probably would have scratched
Secretariat if he wasn't such a star and everything depended on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerkens reflected and came up with several of the tactical edges
that can make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't particularly scout Secretariat,'' he said. ``Horses
like that, when they run a race, the fields are usually very small.
And as great as he was, he wasn't that great in the mud.''
</P>
<P>
   He came up with a few more nuggets from the past. ``We got 16
pounds against Buckpasser,'' he said. ``Against Kelso, we also got
16, although later we beat him at even weights. My horse just went
to the front on the turf, and Kelso didn't like the turf.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is an oddity in the Jerkens record of success: He is
respected as one of the best trainers in the business, yet he seems
to shun the Triple Crown, the highlight series of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has his own aims,'' he said. ``I don't think I'm
changing with age, either. Nutrition, fitness, the things that
count for a horse. You do your best.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1978, Sensitive Prince ran in the Derby, but he was a
front-runner and he didn't break well, and he finished sixth behind
Affirmed and Alydar. In 1992, Devil His Due ran 12th in the Derby.
In the Belmont in 1993, we ran Virginia Rapids, but he was bothered
by a horse who broke down and finished fifth. Last year, Limit Out
ran in the Belmont, but the saddle slipped. I don't know that he
wanted to go a mile and a half anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of Luck will probably get strong support from the racing
public this week because he has a late-running style suited to the
Belmont Stakes and because he is trained by a hometown legend. In
all of his 11 races, Best of Luck has made a closing rush from deep
in the pack under his jockey, Jean-Luc Samyn.
</P>
<P>
   In the Peter Pan, he was ninth after the start and fifth turning
for home, and he scored by one length over Treasure Island. Best of
Luck has won three times and run in the money nine times, and he is
considered fresh and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great if you can win,'' Jerkens said. ``Winning a Grade I
stakes is worth so much in value to the horse. If a horse wins the
Belmont, it would double his value.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if he outruns Silverbulletday, the fast filly, and
Charismatic, the colt standing on the threshold of sweeping the
Triple Crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
