<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEMORIAL-FITZGIBBON-B     05-30 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-FITZGIBBON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAME OF FATHER JOINS SON'S ON VIETNAM MEMORIAL ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For 34 years, the father and son have lain together in
the same plot in a Braintree cemetery, as close in death as they
were in life, both casualties of the same war.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as the nation honors its war dead, the father will
officially join the son on that black granite pantheon of fallen
soldiers, the Vietnam Veterans Memorial wall in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three years after Technical Sergeant Richard B. Fitzgibbon
Jr. was shot to death in Saigon by a fellow Air Force crew member,
his name has finally been sandblasted into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   His family had pleaded with federal officials for years that he
be recognized as a casualty of the war, along with his son, Lance
Corporal Richard B. Fitzgibbon III, who was killed in action in
Vietnam on Sept. 7, 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The Fitzgibbons are the only known father-son honorees on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as Taps is sounded in the nation's capital, about 40
members of the Fitzgibbon family, representing several generations,
will gather at the wall amid bittersweet feelings of sadness and
pride.
</P>
<P>
   Family members are coming from as far away as Florida and
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all thrilled about this,'' said Alice DelRossi of
Stoneham, the sister and aunt of the dead soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   It was DelRossi who 15 years ago started seeking help from
politicians and ``every other place I could think of'' to have her
brother recognized on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Fitzgibbon's widow, Eunice, who lives in Connecticut,
will make the trip for Monday's unveiling. Her son, 23 and
unmarried, died in Vietnam nine years after his father died in
1956.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of the elder Fitzgibbon's name on the wall, along
with the names of 58,219 Americans who were killed or missing in
action in Vietnam, was ultimately achieved through the efforts of
Representative Edward J. Markey.
</P>
<P>
   The Malden congressman persuaded the Department of Defense to
move the date for qualification to be on the memorial from Jan. 1,
1961, to Nov. 1, 1955, when American soldiers first arrived in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   That change made the elder Fitzgibbon the nation's first Vietnam
War casualty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have come out and acknowledged that we were there (in
Vietnam) when the French lowered their flag in April 1955, and we
immediately raised ours,'' DelRossi said. ``Congressman Markey got
a picture from the French embassy showing that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Fitzgibbon was the son of a Malden mail carrier, and
many members of the family live in the 7th District, which Markey
represents. During World War II, Fitzgibbon saw Navy combat on sea
plane tenders in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   DelRossi said the campaign was painful at times for family
members, but she kept on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told my sister-in-law, Eunice, that I was doing
this,'' DelRossi said the other day, ``because I didn't want to
stir up memories and upset her. Sometimes, things seemed so
hopeless, I'd have to sit down and cry.''
</P>
<P>
   But, then, she said, a writer on the South Shore asked her if he
could write about her failed attempts and he did, in a story
titled, ``No Room on the Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   DelRossi said her son, a Vietnam veteran also named Richard,
printed thousands of copies of the story. Every Memorial Day
weekend for 10 years, Richard DelRossi, a Stoneham police officer
who is now 48, drove to Washington and handed them out at the wall
to tourists and mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of the letdowns, Alice DelRossi said the family
decided to go ahead with its quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been a lot of hell in the family,'' she said. ``We
had lost a lot. I couldn't believe it when Congressman Markey's
office began calling us every few weeks and telling us it was going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had done that before and I was worried about giving
Eunice and her family hope. In fairness to the politicians, these
Vietnam veterans had been treated shabbily in so many quarters.
There were no parades, no yellow ribbons, and our government never
stood forward and told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is left for the Fitzgibbon family to wonder what might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   Richard, the father, was 35 when he was slain by an unstable
fellow crew man, Sergeant Edward C. Clarke, who also wounded
another soldier before falling from a balcony to his death.
</P>
<P>
   On her own, Eunice Fitzgibbon raised four children, two sons and
two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   When Eunice's son Richard told her he wanted to go to Vietnam,
DelRossi recalled, ``His mother begged him not to. But, I think, in
his heart, he wanted to see the building his buddies had named for
his dad, and hoped he might be able to talk to some of his father's
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Eunice's surviving son, Robert, of Park Lane, Fla., was 5 years
old when his father died.
</P>
<P>
   Robert observed his 49th birthday on May 5, the day his father's
name was etched on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was the best present he could get,'' DelRossi said.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the elder Fitzgibbon was kind and generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``After his death, a member of his company wrote his wife that
when the men went to Hong Kong for a break, Dick always used to
come back with the same package,'' she said. ``Back in Saigon, they
found out what it was when they saw him giving out candy and gum to
little street urchins.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the close-knit family gathered at a luncheon in
Virginia hosted by Admiral William Crowe, former chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, who praised the Fitzgibbons for their
patriotic service.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after their long goodbye, they hope to find the peace of
mind that has eluded them for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll believe it when I put my hand on my brother's name,''
Alice DelRossi said. ``Now, I know what they mean by closure. This
is really a beautiful day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
