<HEADER>
A6877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STEWART31-COX     05-30 1828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STEWART31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LET'S DRIVE TWO: It's long day at the tracks for Tony Stewart as
he does double duty as a driver
 &HT;    EDs: A write thru will move around midnight EDT
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indianapolis and Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   When Larry Curry, who co-owns Tony Stewart's Indy Racing League
team, left an Indianapolis restaurant about 11:30 p.m. Saturday, he
had a voice message from Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I called him back, he said, `What are you doing up this
late?''' Curry said. ``I looked at the phone and said, `What are
you doing? I don't have to drive 1,100 miles Sunday.'''
</P>
<P>
   By 3:30 p.m. Sunday, Stewart already had logged 196 laps and 490
miles, and he still faced the prospect of doing it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the 1997 Indy Racing League champion, finished ninth in
the Indianapolis 500, four laps behind winner Kenny Brack, who took
the victory after leader Robby Gordon ran out of fuel with one lap
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 28, of Columbus, Ind., finished ninth in the first half
of his attempt at an unprecedented doubleheader. Stewart was trying
to become the first driver to complete all 1,100 miles in the Indy
500 and the Coca-Cola 600 NASCAR race at Lowe's Motor Speedway in
Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Current Winston Cup driver John Andretti tried the feat in 1994.
He finished 10th in the Indy 500, then crashed in the NASCAR race
before the finish. Robby Gordon was to try it in 1997, but the Indy
500 was postponed two days because of inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   After crossing the finish line in Indianapolis on Sunday,
Stewart boarded an airplane and flew to Concord, where he ran in
Sunday night's Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, I'm not as disappointed as I thought I would
be,'' Stewart said of his finish in the Indy 500. ``The guys worked
really hard and built me a great car.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a former sprint-car and midget champion, is a Winston
Cup rookie driver for Joe Gibbs Racing. In his first year in the
No. 20 Pontiac, Stewart was seventh in points, 304 behind leader
Dale Jarrett, entering Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who spent two years driving in the open-wheel series
before jumping to NASCAR's Busch Grand National division last year,
formed his own IRL team this year to run in the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   During the month of May, Stewart faced a daunting schedule. He
made 14 trips between Charlotte and Indianapolis, logging 5,208
miles. His logistical nightmare Sunday included three airplanes,
two helicopters, eight golf carts, four cars and one Navigator
transporter to move Stewart and his support team of 51 people
between the two tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't bothered me because we understood from day 1 that
the main priority was Winston Cup,'' Curry said. ``It was a
challenge, but I think we made the most of his time (in
Indianapolis).''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a closer look at Stewart's long day behind the wheel,
which started around 9:30 a.m. and wasn't expected to end until
close to midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   1:01 a.m. _ Gates open at Indianapolis Motor Speedway for crew
members and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   5:15 a.m. _ Stewart's crew members arrive at IMS to install
tethering system to left rear tire. The Indy Racing League
announced this week that the safety device, two small cables
attached to the butterfly suspension of the wheels, would be
required.
</P>
<P>
   6:15 a.m. _ Curry, co-owner of Tristar Motorsports and Stewart's
crew chief, arrives at IMS.
</P>
<P>
   8:45 a.m. _ Stewart's No. 22 Dallara/Aurora Indy car leaves
garage No. 15 for pre-race inspection.
</P>
<P>
   8:49 a.m. _ Mechanic Bill Harmon steers Stewart's car onto
Gasoline Alley for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   8:53 a.m. _ Stewart's car is seventh in line for pre-race
inspection. Stewart's orange car is dominated by stickers of its
primary sponsor, Home Depot. Among the familiar sponsors, though,
is one very unfamiliar name: Lee Kissick, CPA. Kissick is Curry's
brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   9:03 a.m. _ Car rolls into inspection. Forteen inspectors
measure the car's height, width from tire to tire and weight. Six
of Stewart's crew members watch intensely as the car is closely
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   9:10 a.m. _ Car passes inspection and is pulled to pit road by a
riding lawn mower.
</P>
<P>
   9:15 a.m. _ Car stops at pit stall No. 26, between the cars of
Steve Knapp and Roberto Moreno. Stewart's car is nine stalls to the
left of the start/finish line. ``I think we've got a good shot at
winning it,'' said Case Leeuwenberg, of Wilmington, N.C., one of
Stewart's seven mechanics. I really do. We've got a good car. He's
got to be patient, but you can't be to cautious because you'll get
lapped here.''
</P>
<P>
   9:30 a.m. _ Stewart wakes up in his motorhome parked in the
infield of IMS. He doesn't eat breakfast, but later has cereal and
fruit in garage area. ``We call it `Tony time,''' Curry said.
``He'll show up 10 minutes before the race and climb in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   9:49 p.m. _ Stewart's crew practices pit stops on pit road. The
first pit stop is its best at 7.56 seconds, but the drill gun on
the right-rear tire sticks. The second stop is 8.6 seconds, and the
third is 7.69.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m. _ Every car is given a six-minute engine warm-up on pit
road, and then the cars are refueled.
</P>
<P>
   10:17 a.m. _ Stewart is examined by Dr. Henry Bock, director of
medical affairs for the speedway and IRL. Stewart's blood pressure,
heart rate and weight are taken. He weighs in at 155 pounds. ``He's
in good spirits,'' said Krista Dwyer, Stewart's fiance. ``We got up
a little earlier than we normally do, but we didn't really do
anything different.'' Stewart is engaged to be married May 6 in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   10:24 a.m. _ Stewart arrives at his garage, wearing blue jeans
and a Home Depot shirt. He meets with Curry and other team members.
</P>
<P>
   11:25 a.m. _ Stewart makes way to pit road for driver
introductions.
</P>
<P>
   11:45 a.m. _ According to Firestone Tire engineers, air
temperature is 85 degrees, but temperature on track is 111 degrees.
``My job is just driving the race car,'' Stewart said. ``We don't
have to worry about the one variable we couldn't do anything about
today, and that was the weather. It's great in Indy, and it's
supposed to be great in Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   11:51 a.m. _ Indianapolis Motor Speedway chairman Mari Hulman
George gives ``Gentleman, start your engines'' command. All 33 cars
on grid are fired and running immediately after command.
</P>
<P>
   11:52 a.m. _ Cars roll from grid for first parade lap.
</P>
<P>
   12:01 p.m. _ Green flag falls and pole-sitter Arie Luyendyk
takes lead in turn one. For fifth consecutive year, field came to
the line for the start without a full stable of cars as Jack
Miller's No. 17 car and Scott Sharp's No. 2 car failed to take the
green because of mechanical problems. Stewart starts on the outside
of the eighth row, 24th overall.
</P>
<P>
   12:07 p.m. _ First caution of the race comes after Eliseo
Salazar crashes in turn two of the ninth lap. Stewart climbed four
spots to 20th in the first eight laps, trailing leader Luyendyk by
18.288 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   12:26 p.m. _ Stewart passes Roberto Guerrero, Steve Knapp, Buddy
Lazier and Robbie Buhl to move into 17th, about 14 seconds behind
Luyendyk.
</P>
<P>
   12:33 p.m. _ Leaders begin to take first green-flag pit stops on
lap 31. Kenny Brack takes four tires and fuel on lap 31, and Billy
Boat, Luyendyk, Gordon and Greg Ray follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   12:35 p.m. _ Stewart gets his first big break of the race when
he remains on the track while most of the leaders makes pit stops.
The move pays off, as Hideshi Matsuda apparently runs out of gas
and stalls in the short chute between turns 3 and 4 on lap 35. On
lap 37 under caution, Stewart's crew changes four tires and refuels
in 16 seconds. The crew also makes a slight adjustment to the
chassis. Stewart climbs from 17th to fifth after the restart on lap
39.
</P>
<P>
   12:46 p.m. _ Ray takes lead from Luyendyk on lap 45. Stewart is
fifth behind Ray, Luyendyk, Sam Schmidt and Brack. Stewart moves to
fourth when Schmidt crashes 17 laps later.
</P>
<P>
   1:03 p.m. _ Stewart makes second pit stop on lap 64. He get four
new tires and fuel, and the crew changes the height of the ``wicker
bill,'' attempting to get more downforce. The longer pit stop costs
Stewart two track positions and he falls to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   1:31 p.m. _ Stewart makes third pit stop on lap 95. The crew
again changes the ``wicker bill'' and tire pressure because
Stewart's complaining that the car is ``too tight.'' Stewart comes
out of the pit stops in 10th place. But his car is later damaged by
a mistake in the pits. While working on the Dallara Oldsmobile
Aurora, the crew released the jack
</P>
<P>
   too soon and slightly damaged the car. ``After that, you're in a
survival mode,'' Curry said. ``You just want to get the car home.
I'm disappointed in the fact we made that mistake. We would have
been the fourth or fifth or sixth car.''
</P>
<P>
   3:17 p.m. _After crossing the finish line at Indy, Stewart
sprints to his hauler, changed into a red T-shirt and blue jeans.
He then returned to his garage to say goodbye to his crew. From
there, Stewart was whisked away in a golf cart to a helicopter,
waiting on the infield near the third turn for a three-minute ride
to the Indianapolis Airport.
</P>
<P>
   3:25 p.m. _ Stewart arrives at the airport, where Home Depot,
his sponsor, has its Falcon VIP jet waiting for the 50-minute
flight to Concord. Aboard the plane, Stewart changed into his
NASCAR racing suit, ate a Power Bar and sipped Powerade and water.
He complained of a blister on his right hand from the steering
wheel and another blister on his right knee from the steering
column. And he even admitted he was a bit tired. ``That's to be
expected after a 500-mile race,'' Stewart said. ``I'm really
excited, though. I thought I'd feel a lot more fatigued. I think
after an hour's sleep, I'll be fine.'' With that, Stewart caught a
short nap in the back of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   4:15 p.m. _ Mandatory drivers' meeting at Lowe's begins _
without Stewart. That means Stewart, who qualified 27th for the
race, will have to start the Coca-Cola 600 at the rear of the
field.
</P>
<P>
   4:48 p.m. _ Stewart's entourage arrives at the speedway in a
Navigator limousine. After reaching the infield of the track,
Lowe's officials force them to remove the Home Depot decals from
their vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   5:50 p.m. _ Stewart arrives at Lowe's in Winston Cup driver
Rusty Wallace's Bell 407 helicopter. The six-seat helicopter lands
on the TBS logo just past the start-finish line. Stewart jumps in a
Chevy Camaro for driver introductions.
</P>
<P>
   5:57 p.m. _ Stewart climbs into his No. 20 Pontiac after a brief
conversation with Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   6:08 p.m. _ Speedway Motorsports Inc. president Bruton Smith,
who owns the Lowe's facility, delivers the ``Gentleman, start your
engines'' command.
</P>
<P>
   6:12 p.m. _ The 43-car field rolls off the grid.
</P>
<P>
   6:15 p.m. _ The green flag falls and Stewart faces 600 more
miles and 1,600 left-hand turns.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
