<HEADLINE>
NATO SAYS SOME MOVEMENT DETECTED IN MILOSEVIC POSITION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO officials hinted Sunday they were more
optimistic about Slobodan Milosevic's willingness to reach a peace
deal, although an official envoy to the Balkans warned the
situation was ``not a normal negotiating process,'' even as NATO
warplanes bombed a crowded bridge in Central Serbia, killing 11.
</P>
<P>
   Several cars plunged into the Velika Morava River after three
missiles struck the bridge used by shoppers to visit a market near
the town of Krusevac, the official Tanjug news agency reported. The
attack wounded at least 30 people.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, last week reportedly accepted
the broad outlines of a peace agreement drawn up by the G-8, the
world's top seven industrialized nations and Russia. But it was not
until Sunday that NATO officials interpreted Milosevic's statement
about the plan as a sign of progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has begun to move from a position of almost total defiance
of the international community when we started'' airstrikes ``on
March 24 to at least now saying that he accepts the key demands of
the G8, which embody NATO's five conditions,'' NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The remark _ coupled with a similar one by NATO's supreme
commander, General Wesley K. Clark, signaled a shift in allied
rhetoric, after a week in which Milosevic's statement was met in
the United States with skepticism, warnings, and promises that the
air campaign would not cease without an agreement fully acceptable
to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sunday, Martti Ahtisaari, the Finnish president who is
serving as the European Union's special envoy to Kosovo, remained
skeptical about Milosevic's intentions, and cautioned that the
central NATO demands, including withdrawal of Serb troops and
acceptance of an international peacekeeping force, must still be
met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just accepting the G8 principles does not give us the clarity
to proceed further,'' Ahtisaari said. ``We need a clear
understanding from the Yugoslav leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari, who is scheduled to travel to Belgrade this week with
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, also dismissed concerns that the
job of negotiating a peace deal has been complicated by the
decision last week by the International War Crimes Tribunal to
indict Milosevic and other Yugoslav leaders for war crimes. These
are not, he said, normal negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go to Belgrade I will explain the offer the international
community is prepared to make, and the chances the Yugoslav people
have for peace,'' Ahtisaari said. ``That's entirely different from
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews and news conferences Sunday, both Shea and
Clark said it appeared Milosevic was shifting toward a diplomatic
solution, even if only to avoid a continuation of the airstrikes.
Clark, noting ``a very significant change in the tone of
pronouncements coming from Belgrade,'' said the developments were a
sign the airstrikes are producing the intended results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the bombing that is impelling the diplomacy,''
Clark said in an interview on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   --A NATO missile attack in Kosovo hit near a convoy of
journalists Sunday, killing a local driver and wounding two
European reporters and a French philosopher, the Serb-run Media
Center in Pristina said.
</P>
<P>
   Wounded were a reporter for the Times of London, Eve-Ann
Prentice, an unidentified reporter from the Italian Corriere della
Sera newspaper, and a French philosopher, Daniel Schiffer, who has
been advocating the Serbian cause. The slain driver was identified
as Nebojsa Radojevic, 28.
</P>
<P>
   --United Nations war crimes prosecutor Louise Arbour said she
has been urged to indict NATO for war crimes connected to the
airstrikes against Yugoslavia. While NATO cannot be indicted as a
whole, she said its leadership could theoretically be charged on
allegations ``that the targeting was inappropriate, that some of
the targets had no military significance, or that if they did they
were disproportionate to the anticipated civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is, certainly, a debate out there that is being brought
to our attention,'' Arbour said on NBC's Meet the Press. ``Now,
where we would take it, if anywhere, is not a matter that I'm
prepared to discuss publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   --NATO pilots depicted the countryside inside Kosovo as eerily
empty and scorched, according to spokesman Jamie Shea, who spoke to
several of them over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``One told me how at night, flying over Kosovo, he could see
lots of red dots representing houses and villages that were
burning,'' Shea said. ``Another spoke to me of the deserted
landscape in which virtually nothing moved. The roads were empty.
No farmers, no activity in the fields. As if the population, like
troglodytes, had gone into hiding in caves and deserted houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 600,000 ethnic Albanians are believed to be dislocated
within Kosovo..
</P>
<P>
   --The 24 Apache helicopters that have not been deployed since
being dispatched to Albania in early April ``will be used at a time
and a place of our choosing,'' Clark said. The helicopters were
brought in to target Serb paramilitary forces at close range. So
far, the US combat helicopters have flown only training missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at the Apaches,'' Clark said. ``They are
trained and ready and I'm convinced that at the right time, they'll
come into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
