<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BRIDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 PEOPLE KILLED AS NATO MISSILES HIT BRIDGE NEAR BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Eleven people were killed Sunday when NATO missiles
struck a bridge south of the Yugoslav capital, plunging people and
cars into a river below, Yugoslav authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Government-controlled media said that between 30 and 40 other
people were reported missing, and that the death toll could rise.
At least 30 people were being treated in nearby hospitals,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses in the town of Varvarin said they had heard two NATO
warplanes humming high overhead when the first bomb struck shortly
before 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two missiles hit first. People rushed to help those trapped.
Four minutes later, another two hit,'' said Slavoljub Blagojevic,
manager of a nearby sports center. ``Thousands of people were on
and around the bridge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Western journalists who were taken to the scene by Yugoslav
officials said there were body parts and mutilated bodies scattered
near the bridge, most of which had fallen some 30 feet down into
the VelikaMorava River.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters saw eight bodies, including that of a decapitated
priest, in a local morgue and were told a ninth victim, a girl, had
died on the way to hospital in nearby Krusevac.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was a market day in the town of Varvarin, some 90 miles
south of Belgrade, and witnesses say the bridge was full of cars
and pedestrians when the first bomb hit.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge was one of the few still linking southern Serbia with
the province of Kosovo, as NATO attempts to cut the supply lines
Serb forces use to send food, ammunition and reinforcements to
Kosovo. The explosion also cut power and phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said it was too early to
say whether the bridge had been downed by NATO bombs. He
acknowledged that NATO considered bridges military targets, but
insisted NATO did not deliberately target civilians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO appeared to escalate its air attacks Sunday, launching
bombs in and around Belgrade at 9 a.m., the first time NATO had
struck the capital on a Sunday morning. With new planes just
arrived at new air bases in Hungary and Bulgaria, NATO has said it
will launch 24-hour attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reports of killing civilians, NATO supreme commander
General Wesley K. Clark Sunday vowed to increase the intensity of
the attacks in Serbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
