<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MISSED SHOT AND A SOAP OPERA IN GAME ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Eds: Rewrites entirely.) (ms) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ If New York Knick fans remember their history,
then they could have been excused if they had covered their eyes
when Reggie Miller took a pass from Mark Jackson and got set to
seal their doom again. ``Reggie has killed us so many times with
the big 3's,'' Patrick Ewing said after the game, recalling this
moment.
</P>
<P>
   All the agony that Miller, the Pacers' guard, has perpetrated
against the Knicks in playoffs over the years seemed to reappear
before their eyes Sunday night, when the Knicks were ahead by 90-88
with 29 seconds left in this opener of the Eastern Conference
finals in Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Reggie loves this stuff. He lives to make other teams' lives
miserable, especially the Knicks. His eyes are nearly aglitter as
he looks toward the basket, ball in his spindly hands.
</P>
<P>
   So Miller _ thin as a strand of linguine, with the mind-set of
the gunslingers in the Wild West movies he so admired as a boy _
was ready to bang home the game-winner once again. Duck, Knicks
fans!
</P>
<P>
   But Allan Houston and Patrick Ewing flew toward him with arms
extended toward the rafters. ``It was a good look,'' Miller said
later. ``By my standards, it was still a good look.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball went up and fell to the basket _ and bounced off the
rim! Reggie missed! Chris Childs recovered the ball and Dale Davis
fouled him.
</P>
<P>
   Childs made both free throws and, as it turned out, put the game
out of reach (though the Pacers had a desperation 3-pointer by
Jackson at the buzzer that fell short). And the Knicks, with a
93-90 victory, continued this most improbable of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Organizational turmoil to them was like spinach to Popeye. The
general manager was dismissed when they were 21-21 with eight games
remaining and a playoff berth in doubt, and they manage to do it.
They are the eighth-seeded team in the conference and knock off
Miami, the top-seeded team. In the next round, they treat the Hawks
the way they might treat a bunch of guys in a pickup game at the Y,
and sweep the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the team president tells the world that he did not
interview a possible replacement for the Knicks' coach. Then he
tells the world he did. The team president's faulty memory was like
fuel to an Apollo space launch.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it seem to matter that their spectacular new player
this season, Latrell Sprewell, grumbles that he wants to play more.
He nonetheless helps them win, as he did Sunday, scoring 16 points,
though it was not one of his best efforts.
</P>
<P>
   It also did not seem to matter that their aging and hobbling
spectacular old player, Patrick Ewing, should be spending his days
and nights in an infirmary rather than in the low post. But there
he was, hitting clutch shots to keep the Knicks from falling
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when they got behind and could have thrown in
the towel,'' Miller said, ``but they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' defense was strong, and when Antonio Davis and Dale
Davis slammed thunderous dunks, igniting the sellout crowd of
16,575, the Knicks weren't cowed. And then Childs stepped to the
line after the Miller miss, with the Knicks bench on its feet, and
Rick Brunson, the substitute guard, couldn't look. He pulled his
jersey over his head. The moans of the crowd told him the shots
were good. And then the bench players hugged each other as the
clock ran out for the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Indiana is such a good team,'' Houston said, ``that you
can't exhale. It was just one game.''
</P>
<P>
   And Larry Bird, who looks so cool on the bench that one is wont
to congratulate his embalmer, said, ``They beat us today. It's not
the end of the world. We have to fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   The stoicism is part of the Bird motif. When, for example, the
Pacers returned home after winning the opening-round playoff series
in Milwaukee two weeks ago, and followed with the second-round
sweep of Philadelphia, there was no crowd to greet the team. No
announcement was made about its arrival. By orders of the head
coach, Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won anything yet,'' Bird explained. ``We'll
celebrate a championship. Nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson had a propensity to shimmy and shake after making a
good play. ``Cut it out,'' Bird said. ``Celebrate when we've won a
championship.'' Now they go back to work, figuring out matchups and
strategy for Game 2 here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike numerous others in basketball who have never had to work
at anything else in their lives, Bird labored on a garbage truck
one year at home. This was after he quit Indiana University and the
oppressive Bobby Knight after one month on campus following his
high school graduation. Bird returned home to French Lick, Ind., to
sort out his life, and got the job, which, he said, taught him as a
teen-ager a great deal about life's realities as well as working
with men.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise, then, that the Pacers have performed like the
best kinds of garbage collectors: thorough, prideful, and not
heading for beers until the last alley is cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   This is something the implausible Knicks, the seemingly
imperturbable Knicks, must yet keep in their mind's eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
