</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON TAKES CONTROL OF THE SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In Game 1 of the Western Conference finals on
Saturday, it looked as if David Robinson were still the principal
player in the San Antonio Spurs' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting jumpers, driving to the basket and receiving passes
on the low block, the swift 7-foot-1-inch center took more shots
than any of his teammates, including his esteemed partner in the
post, Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unusual but welcome position for Robinson to be in.
All season long, the one-time NBA Most Valuable Player deferred to
Duncan offensively, allowing the second-year forward to become an
MVP candidate in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Trail Blazers' quick traps making it tough on
Duncan, and Portland's all but immobile center, Arvydas Sabonis,
guarding Robinson, the Spurs are wisely refocusing their attention
on the Admiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it fun,'' said Robinson, who scored 21 points in San
Antonio's 80-76 victory. ``It's nice this series to be freed up to
add a little offense to the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in San Antonio when Robinson, the MVP in 1995,
was the offense, leading the Spurs in scoring in eight of his first
nine seasons and leading the league in 1994 with a 29.8-point
average.
</P>
<P>
   When Duncan arrived last season with all of his gifts, no one
expected him to supplant Robinson as the team's main feature. But
when San Antonio's season ended in the conference semifinals,
despite the high scoring averages of both Robinson (21.6 points)
and Duncan (21.1 points), it became clear that the offense could go
through only one post player. So in pursuit of that elusive
championship, Robinson turned the offense over to Duncan, willingly
becoming a second option for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, coming from a position where you shoot a lot and
get the chance to do whatever you want,'' Robinson, 33, admitted
Sunday, after the team prepared for Game 2 on Monday. ``Last year
was more of an example of us going back and forth and switching up
the offensive responsibilities. But this year, Tim's really been
the focus and he's done a phenomenal job with it. He's our go-to
guy and I'm glad to be here for support.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how Robinson became the Spurs' second option.
While Robinson says it was coach Gregg Popovich's idea, Popovich
insists there was no official role reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a misconception that we just changed and made Tim
the first option,'' Popovich said. ``David gets an awful lot of
touches on the court. It basically depends a lot on mismatches and
who's guarding who out there. If Tim's got a defender on him that
we think is giving him trouble, we're going to go to David a lot
more than we go to Tim. And at the end of games, we've gone to
David as much as we've gone to Tim.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Popovich's denials, the Spurs, at least offensively,
have clearly become Duncan's team. Robinson averaged a career-low
15.8 points this season, nearly six points fewer than Duncan, and
attempted just 10.8 shots a game, six fewer than Duncan. Saturday's
victory over Portland was just the ninth time this year that
Robinson has shot the ball more than Duncan. Entering this season,
Robinson had averaged 25.1 points and 16.9 shots a game.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich, pointing out that Duncan averages almost eight more
minutes a game than Robinson does, says the difference is due to
playing time. But last year, averaging six more minutes, Duncan
(15.7 shots) averaged just one more shot than Robinson (14.6) .
</P>
<P>
   While some observers attribute Robinson's scoring drop to the
back and knee injuries he has suffered in the past, Robinson says
it is because he is taking fewer shots. His production in other
categories _ 10 rebounds, 2.4 blocks a game, a team-best 50.9
percent shooting _ support his claim that he can still score more
than 20 points a game on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what your role is, whether you're the MVP guy or
whether you're somebody that's supporting him, you've got to do
your job,'' Robinson said. ``At some point, you have to get past
all of that ego stuff and decide that you just want to win
basketball games, and this year, I'm just happy that we're winning
basketball games. I couldn't care less who gets all of the
headlines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
