u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-A     05-30 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL'S SUIT SAYS MICROSOFT BARRED ACCESS TO CRUCIAL DATA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add art note; no other changes.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the trial in the government's antitrust case against
Microsoft Corp. resumes Tuesday in Washington, evidence in a
separate trial set to open this week in Connecticut seems to offer
tantalizing support for an assertion that the company's rivals have
made for years _ that Microsoft wields its industry-standard
Windows operating system as a club to control the software
business.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the Connecticut case is an issue that has been raised
peripherally by several government witnesses in the Washington case
_ how Microsoft controls its competitors' understanding of
application program interfaces, or APIs.
</P>
<P>
   APIs are the paths into and out of the operating system that
programmers must follow for their software _ spreadsheets, Internet
browsers, picture editing and so on _ to run efficiently. Rivals
have long said that Microsoft gives them only rudimentary maps of
the Windows APIs, making it impossible to compete with the designs
of Microsoft's own applications programmers, who enjoy a detailed
road map of Windows, complete with little backroads and alleys that
can be used as shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft dismisses such contentions as whining by competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But in an internal e-mail memo to several senior Microsoft
executives on Feb. 28, 1996, Mark Ryland, a company manager,
observed matter-of-factly, ``Microsoft learned long ago that to
control the APIs is to control the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   That memo is among thousands of internal Microsoft documents
filed in U.S. District Court in Bridgeport, Conn., as part of a
private antitrust suit scheduled to go to trial on Wednesday. Among
other things, they show a spirited debate inside Microsoft over how
much of its software should run ``cross-platform'' _ that is, on
competing operating systems like Unix, the platform for many large
corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the e-mail offers vivid glimpses of Microsoft's
winner-take-all style of competition. In one internal memo, a
Microsoft manager discusses a proposal to enable some of its data
base technology to work on Unix. This was a topic previously raised
with data base companies like Sybase Inc. and Oracle Corp., which
compete with Microsoft in data base software but also develop
products that run on Windows as well as on Unix.
</P>
<P>
   On April 19, 1996, James Allchin, a Microsoft senior vice
president, wrote: ``Please give me one good reason why we should
even consider this. (Hint: any good answer needs to include making
more money and helping kill Unix, Sybase or Oracle.)''
</P>
<P>
   The suit in Connecticut is not directly related to the
government's sweeping antitrust case. But the justice department
and the 19 states suing Microsoft are eagerly awaiting the evidence
in the Connecticut case because it focuses squarely on the issue of
technology access.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, Bristol Technology Inc., a small software maker
in Danbury, Conn., charges that Microsoft illegally cut off its
access to Windows technology after three years of cooperation and
says that Microsoft had a ``duty to deal'' with it.
</P>
<P>
   The government's more traditional antitrust suit charges that
Microsoft used its Windows monopoly to stifle competition from
Internet software. The Justice Department left the issue of
technology access to be addressed in the remedy phase of the trial
if it wins, and it is a crucial subject in continuing settlement
talks with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   One justice department official observed, ``I think we should
put a sign up in the war room here, `It's the APIs, stupid''' _ a
play on the slogan in President Clinton's 1992 campaign stressing
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says that reading too much into a few e-mail messages
is unfair. The company, its lawyers note, is unapologetically
filled with highly competitive people with a passion for the
software business _ a passion reflected in their e-mail. ``And a
lot of the e-mail that Bristol has filed as evidence has nothing to
do with this case,'' said Steve Aeschbacher, a senior corporate
lawyer for Microsoft. ``There are discussions about cross-platform
strategies all the time within Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bristol is not going to win its antitrust suit against
Microsoft merely with piles of inflammatory e-mail that raise
important industry issues. It must produce convincing evidence that
Microsoft violated the antitrust laws, and legal experts say that
is a stiff challenge.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-N     05-30 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: challenge. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bristol has assembled a legal team led by two veteran antitrust
experts known for defending the International Business Machines
Corp., Patrick Lynch, a partner at O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, and Anthony
L. Clapes, a former IBM assistant general counse. But legal
experts say that ``duty-to-deal'' cases are hard to win outside
industries with traditions of regulation, like telecommunications,
or businesses involving natural assets, like ski slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts are very reluctant to say that dominant firms have
a duty to deal, because that takes you down a regulatory path,''
William Kovacic, a professor at the George Washington University
Law School, said. ``It also reduces incentives to innovate if a
dominant firm is forced to share its hard-won assets _ like
intellectual property in the software business _ with other
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol charges that Microsoft used it as a tool in a cynical
campaign to gain a foothold in the market for heavy-duty corporate
computing and then tried to shift those customers over to using
Microsoft's most advanced operating system, Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Windows NT has gradually improved over the years, but after it
was first shipped in 1992, it struggled to compete against Unix in
the market for big corporate systems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's main advantage was the popularity of the many
software applications _ an estimated 100,000 _ written to run on
Windows. For example, a scientist using a powerful Unix work
station for research might want to use Microsoft Word to write
memos or an Excel spreadsheet for doing budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol developed a product that solved that problem. Its Wind/U
software enabled programs written for Windows to run on Unix work
stations, or hub computers called servers, that send data to
workers' desktop machines. That opened mainstream corporate
business to the legions of Windows software developers.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bristol's translation software to work, the company
needed access to Microsoft's technology. In 1994, Bristol signed a
three-year contract with Microsoft giving Bristol virtually open
access to all Windows APIs. Lifted by its partnership with
Microsoft, Bristol thrived. In 1997, Inc. magazine ranked Bristol
140th among the 500 fastest-growing companies in the nation, with a
payroll of 70 people and estimated revenue of $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that was the high point for Bristol. It began negotiating
with Microsoft on a contract for access to the newer versions of
Microsoft's operating-system technology. After the two sides failed
to reach an agreement, Bristol sued last August contending that
Microsoft's offer _ a fourfold increase in price and much-reduced
access to Windows technology _ was an ``apple core,'' as a
Microsoft e-mail message described it.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bristol, the changed terms were no mystery. Windows
NT has made real strides in the corporate market against Unix.
Cripple the cross-platform software provided by Bristol, and many
customers that have become dependent on Windows applications thanks
to Bristol's software would move from Unix to Windows.
``Microsoft's dealings with Bristol are a classic
bait-and-switch,'' Lynch, Bristol's lead trial lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft replies that Bristol has no legal grounds for its case
and has embarked on litigation as a business tactic. It points out
that the 1994 contract covered access only to Windows NT 3.0,
Windows 3.1 and Windows 95, and it contained no language about
future versions of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   True, says Keith Blackwell, the president of Bristol. But he
points to the many public statements Microsoft made about its
commitment to the cross-platform program, called the Windows
Interface Source Environment, or WISE. One document posted on the
Web in 1995 stated, ``Microsoft is committed to providing WISE
licensees'' _ like Bristol _ ``with future versions of Windows
family source code.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell said, ``Microsoft repeatedly and publicly made all
these representations that the WISE program was a safe way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies also had conflicts with Microsoft over access to
Windows technology, including AT&AMP;T, the inventor of Unix, which
eventually settled a contract suit seeking access to Windows NT 5.0
programming code.
</P>
<P>
   But a Bristol rival, Mainsoft Inc., did reach an agreement with
Microsoft last year. And Bristol, according to Microsoft, rejected
the same contract terms that Mainsoft found acceptable. The
negotiations with Microsoft were lengthy and difficult, William
McCarthy, Mainsoft's vice president for business development, said.
``But there's nothing we can't do that we want to do under the new
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol's duty-to-deal case falls apart because ``Microsoft has
not refused to deal with Bristol _ it was offered the same terms as
Mainsoft,'' its lawyer, Aeschbacher, said. ``Just because someone
is not happy with the terms of a deal they are offered, that is not
an antitrust case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol replies that Mainsoft was struggling and willing to take
whatever Microsoft offered to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   An internal e-mail message certainly suggests, at least, that
Microsoft found Mainsoft easier to deal with. On May 18, 1998, Dan
Neault, a WISE program manager, wrote: ``Mainsoft is in our pocket.
Bristol is rattling sabres hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol contends that the offer Mainsoft accepted is a hobbled
version of the original cross-platform promise of the WISE program,
and thus Microsoft has used its market power to undermine
competition.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Microsoft will seek to portray Bristol as a company
bent on litigation, trying to win a huge financial judgment against
a deep-pocketed defendant.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, 1998, a month before negotiations finally broke off,
Bristol received a ``strategic communications game plan'' from
Fleishman-Hillard, a New York public relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   The document, entitled ``David vs. Goliath,'' recommended:
``Position David as a reluctant, yet courageous plaintiff defending
its small, successful and growing entrepreneurial company and
Goliath as a predatory, deep-pocketed, unethical behemoth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol says it would have been foolish to take on Microsoft
without some preparation. And it insists that if anyone was
negotiating in bad faith, it was Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message titled ``Co-opting Unix,'' Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman, listed as part of the company's strategy,
``Picking Mainsoft as our partner for Windows APIs on Unix and
revving up their activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates wrote the message on Sept. 28, 1997, about 11 months
before negotiations between Microsoft and Bristol ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
