<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EMISSIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HE'LL SIGN BILL ENCOURAGING PLANTS TO CUT EMISSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legislation to encourage aging industrial plants
to comply with modern air pollution standards won final legislative
approval Sunday night, and Gov. George W. Bush said he's looking
forward to signing it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 766 by Sen. James ``Buster'' Brown, R-Lake Jackson,
calls on plants built before 1971 to voluntarily begin upgrading
equipment to reduce the amount of contaminants released into the
air. Plants that don't begin cutting emissions would have to pay
fees to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff worked with members of the House and the Senate to
come up with a bill that encourages plants that are grandfathered
to meet standards,'' Bush told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The ``grandfathered'' plants have been exempt from clean air
standards enacted after they were built.
</P>
<P>
   The emissions bill was among more than 100 pieces of legislation
sent to the governor's desk Sunday night. Under Legislature rules,
all bills had to be passed before midnight. The 76th Legislative
session ends Monday, but rules for the final day limit lawmakers to
making technical changes in bills.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bills sent to Bush were the final piece of an
anti-gang initiative, a college scholarship program for low-income
students, a bill adding safeguards to religious expression, and a
measure to boost the amount of lottery prize payouts.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups weren't pleased with the emissions bill,
but said the version that passed is better than some of the earlier
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush wants it both ways. He wants credit for cleaning up the
air, but he stood in the way of attempts to make sure the air got
cleaner,'' said Peter Altman, director of the Sustainable Energy
and Economic Development Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The bill to establish the so-called Hope Scholarship bill, which
would set aside $100 million for financial aid for low-income
students, won bipartisan support as it passed the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 713 by Rep. Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, and Sen. Rodney
Ellis, D-Houston, would provide tuition and fees to qualifying high
school students who have completed college preparatory courses and
maintain grade point averages of 2.0 or better during their first
year of college.
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains funding to provide scholarships for an
estimated 20,000 students during the upcoming two-year budget
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation requiring candidates for state office to file their
lists of campaign contributors and expenditures on a computer disk
so the information can be posted on the Internet also was sent to
the governor without dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Under House Bill 2611 by Rep. Sherri Greenberg, D-Austin, and
Sen. Mike Moncrief, D-Fort Worth, candidates would still be
required to file paper campaign and expense reports.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prohibit candidates from planting phony names on
their lists to determine whether someone misuses the information.
The electronic reporting requirement would apply only to candidates
with Internet access and those who plan to raise more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 8 by Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, would allow the
state to establish a database that tracks gang membership and
activity statewide. Several other bills aimed at combating illegal
gang activity have already been sent to Bush's desk.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Lottery will begin putting a larger chunk of its take
into the prize pool if the governor signs House Bill 844 by Rep.
Ron Wilson, D-Houston. The bill essentially reverses a move the
Legislature made two years ago that reduced the payout from about
57 cents for each dollar taken in to about 52 cents.
</P>
<P>
   If the new measure becomes law, the payout will be set at 57
cents per $1 beginning in September. If the Texas Lottery seeks to
raise the payout higher than 57 cents after September 2000, it
would have to lower its $40 million advertising budget by $1
million for each cent added. .MDBO/.MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
