<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-1200(2TAKE     05-30 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS BOOST FROM 76TH TEXAS LEGISLATURE'S WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was supposed to be about the money.
</P>
<P>
   But the last regularly scheduled gathering of Texas lawmakers
this century might be remembered as much for what it did to the
political fortunes of George W. Bush as how it dispensed with a
record government surplus.
</P>
<P>
   For five months, the 76th Texas Legislature has operated in the
shadow of the Republican governor's budding presidential campaign,
the watchful eye of the national media never far away.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, when the final gavel falls, the score card will be
filled _ just in time for Bush's first campaign trip two weeks
hence to Iowa and New Hampshire, the traditional first tests for
presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Several political observers said Bush will come out a winner
simply because he will take credit for large tax cuts, a huge boost
in education spending, and popular new abortion restrictions _ all
while avoiding any apparent disasters.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there were a few surprise developments that
could provide campaign fodder for Bush opponents.
</P>
<P>
   A bitter partisan fight over hate-crimes legislation wasn't on
anyone's radar screen when the session began. Before it ended,
Bush's unwillingness to take a clear position on that and other
hot-button political issues was thrust into the national spotlight
_ and probably into the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is clearly not very ready for many of the questions that
will be aimed his way,'' said Larry Sabato, a political scientist
at the University of Virginia. ``Once he starts campaigning, he can
only duck and dodge and weave for so long. It's already getting
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Dangers may also be lurking in Bush's record on guns, an issue
that is shifting in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he'll sign a bill shielding gun manufacturers from
lawsuits by cities, a top priority of the National Rifle
Association. Although popular in Texas, the measure could be
controversial elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also made a few confusing twists on requiring
background checks of those who purchase weapons at gun shows before
he settled on the idea that it's a federal problem, not a state
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually has a very pro-gun record that could haunt him,''
Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bush did not get everything he wanted from the
Legislature, either in tax cuts or education. Despite his rare
personal appearance on the Senate floor as the chamber was poised
to consider legislation providing state-backed vouchers for
students to attend private schools, the bill never came up for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry we didn't get a voucher bill,'' Bush said Sunday.
``I think they are needed ... to give people different options,
particularly if their children are going to failed schools.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `INTIMIDATED' BY BUSH
</P>
<P>
   But much of the governor's agenda survived _ even flourished _
despite predictions that partisan politics or a lack of money would
derail his tax cut package and education proposals.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settles Monday, the Legislature is expected to
have approved about $1.7 billion in tax cuts, less than the $2.6
billion Bush wanted but more than earlier plans provided.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also won approval of his top education reform proposal _
aimed at ending social promotion, or the practice of advancing
unprepared students through the public school system.
</P>
<P>
   And the governor saw passage of the toughest anti-abortion bill
that was politically viable: legislation requiring that parents be
notified when their minor children seek abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people, when they take an objective look, will say
this was a good session,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were moments when partisan tensions flared, the
irony for some critics is the extent to which Bush can thank
Democrats for his legislative successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some in the (Democratic) leadership that are
intimidated by his high numbers and are of the opinion that, if we
give him everything we'll do better at the polls than if we fight
him,'' said Rep. Kevin Bailey, D-Houston, an unabashed liberal and
a consistent Bush critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some excellent things this session for our constituency
_ the teacher pay raises, the improvements in funding for things
like kindergarten,'' Bailey said. ``We still, I think, could have
done better ... and should not have just laid down and allowed him
to run over us.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING VS. TAX CUTS
</P>
<P>
   The impact of Bush's popularity on state lawmakers was on
display at a recent meeting of the House Committee on Public
Education, which inherited Bush's top two agenda items: education
revisions and property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Dick Lavine, giving one of his standard lectures about
the relative merits of those two items, urged the panel to forget
the tax cuts and spend all the money on teacher salaries, better
school buildings and more training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of us really disagree with that,'' responded
Rep. Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, the committee's chairman. ``But none
of us got 80 percent of the vote ... statewide.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's reference to Bush was only a tad exaggerated: Bush won
re-election in 1998 with 69 percent of the vote, not 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about his comment, Sadler said he meant that ``some
deference should be made to those that run on a statewide basis and
win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Bush) ran a campaign on certain issues and he was
overwhelmingly elected,'' Sadler said. ``I don't think you can
ignore that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats say that Bush simply jumped out in front of a
parade that was already under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's campaigning on what the Democratic priorities were in
this Legislature,'' Democratic consultant Ed Martin said. ``If he
gets to take credit for that, it's really an injustice to the
people who led this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   READING THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Although there was plenty of give and take between Democrats and
Republicans on the tax cut and social promotion issues, Bush could
not have hoped for a better outcome on the abortion front.
</P>
<P>
   Under the parental notification bill that he plans to sign, only
a judge can bypass the law and allow an abortion to take place
without a parent being notified, precisely the language Bush
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democrats narrowly control the House, the
Democratic-sponsored bill, which would have allowed minors to
notify non-parent family members instead of just a parent, never
made it off the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Even the chairman of the committee that produced the various
versions of the legislation, Rep. Steve Wolens, D-Dallas, expressed
regret that only a judicial ``bypass'' was in the final version.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst place to go take this situation to is a judge who's
not going to care _ and I think all judges are not going to care,''
Wolens said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Democratic bill allowing other family members to
be involved didn't make it, Wolens said that it was all about
deadlines. Under procedural rules, and due to negotiation delays,
he said, it would probably have died for lack of time.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats said the explanation can be found in public
opinion polls and political math. Surveys show that Texans strongly
support parental notification laws, particularly those people who
live and vote in rural districts where many Democrats are
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can read the polls just like the Republicans can,'' said
one operative close to Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the House narrowly rejected an attempt to amend the
GOP bill by adding more exemptions, despite a rare intervention by
Democratic House Speaker Pete Laney, whose vote for additional
bypasses was his only one this session.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome left Rep. Patty Gray, D-Galveston, author of the
Democratic alternative, bitter. She said that some of her
colleagues voted their conscience, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few others who I think succumbed to the pressure
from the (anti-abortion) groups, on how they would report the
vote,'' she said. ``I'm saddened by it, because I don't think
that's what's in people's hearts here, and unfortunately their
hearts didn't match their backbones on this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO VS. TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush is sure to include a long list of accomplishments
from the 76th Legislature on his resume, political scientist Allan
Saxe of the University of Texas at Arlington said it probably won't
be at the front and center of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the possibility that U.S. ground troops could go into
Kosovo, and in light of increased tensions with China, Saxe said
national defense issues will probably overshadow anything that
happened in Texas during the past 140 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will obviously talk about a major tax cut. It will
resonate,'' Saxe said. ``But I think the debate in the Republican
primaries is going to be over foreign policy. ... I think national
defense is going to be a bigger issue than anybody would have
imagined a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
