<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YARNALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D. ROBERT YARNALL JR., 74, RETIRED MANUFACTURER 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   D. Robert Yarnall Jr., who helped build a local Pennsylvania
manufacturing company into a multinational corporation, died on May
27 at the Unitarian Universalist House nursing home in the
Germantown section of Philadelphia. He was 74 and had lived most of
his life in the West Mount Airy section of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from a stroke, his brother, James B.
Yarnall, said.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall started in business in 1950, when he joined the company
co-founded by his father, then known as Yarnall Waring Co., a small
manufacturer of specialty valves for power plants. The company,
based in suburban Philadelphia, eventually changed its name to
Yarway Corp. By 1962, Yarnall, then 37, had been elected president,
and in 1977 he assumed the position of chairman.
</P>
<P>
   While working in that job, Yarnall founded the Envirite Corp. as
an environmental services subsidiary of Yarway. In 1984 the
subsidiary was spun off, and Yarnall remained as a chairman of both
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   By 1986, Yarway had operations in seven countries and its sales
had greatly increased. That year the company merged with Keystone
International, a large maker of industrial valves, and Yarway
stepped down as chairman. He continued as chairman of Envirite
until 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall was born in 1925 in Germantown and attended the
Germantown Friends School. He graduated from Cornell University in
1948 and worked in Europe with the American Friends Service
Committee before beginning his career in business. He was named to
the boards of an assortment of companies and nonprofit groups,
including Quaker Chemical Corp. and the World Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall is survived by his wife, Anne Gates Yarnall; a brother,
James B. Yarnall; a sister, Nan Yarnall; three daughters from his
marriage to the late Rie Yarnall; seven grandchildren and two
step-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
