<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHLETICS-DISPUTE-KAN     05-30 3141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETICS-DISPUTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT OF GIRLS' ATHLETIC ASSOCIATION RAISES
QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL and MIKE McGRAW  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Financial
questions and a staunch refusal to open the books have ignited a
battle for control of a local institution that has fostered
generations of softball and basketball players. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dispute centers on Jack Spahr, 64, executive director and
longtime president of the board of the Johnson County Girls'
Athletic Association, a tax-exempt group that collects almost $1
million a year, nearly half in sports fees from thousands of
Johnson County, Kan., girls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though some parents said they were happy, many have complained
for years about the nonprofit's fund-raisers, rising fees and a
reluctance by the board of directors _ particularly Spahr _ to
share financial information. One fed-up basketball coach broke away
from the association, taking 250 girls with him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr and his supporters defended the job he has done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack is one hell of an asset and always has been,'' said board
member Burl Denton of Merriam, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months, The Kansas City Star interviewed
dozens of people about the association's operations and examined
financial and real estate documents. The newspaper found: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --A concentration of power. As president of the board and the
paid executive director, Spahr serves as his own boss at the
group's sports complex; he and the board ignore their own bylaws
and force out those who question their actions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Questions about money. Spahr and the board refuse to explain
financial discrepancies or to release financial records, as
required by association rules. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Deepening debt. Spahr and the board borrowed about $3 million
for a gym after spending funds parents paid toward the project on
other expenses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A former Internal Revenue Service employee who sponsors a
Johnson County Girls' softball team recently asked Spahr to open
the books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything's on the up and up,'' said Malcolm Ayer, whose
IRS experience included overseeing nonprofits, then Spahr should
open the books to the press and the public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a public charity just like United Way,'' Ayer said he
told Spahr, Denton and the association's lawyer. ``You have a
higher standard to uphold. You need to ... see that whatever
questions there are be answered and be answered honestly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And they didn't agree with that position.'' &QL; 
Consolidation of power &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson County Girls' Athletic Association is the largest
sponsor of softball and basketball programs for girls ages 5 to 18
in the Kansas City area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The group was incorporated in Kansas in 1960 and today serves
about 3,000 girls in softball and 1,500 in basketball. A volleyball
program will be added soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The association's home base is 12 lighted ball diamonds in
Shawnee, Kan., in the Valley of Champions, the site this weekend
for the Memorial Day Tournament. Also at the complex is a
58,000-square-foot gymnasium slated to open in June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many parents look forward to the new gym and are happy with the
complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with it as a kid and now my kids play ... ,'' said
Lisa Ryan of Overland Park. ``JCGAA is a topnotch facility. It
really is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr, a retired printing salesman, got involved in the
association the way many people do _ his daughters played softball
there. Soon he was on the board of directors, a board made up
mainly of parents of current and former players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s Spahr was pushing for changes: higher fees for
the girls, mandatory fund-raisers and the elimination of
double-headers, which he said did not earn the association enough
money, said Denny Mealman, a payroll department manager and former
member of the board of governors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The board of governors was a volunteer group of parents and
coaches who organized the softball and basketball leagues for the
board of directors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Pat Kearn, an accountant whose daughter played
softball, raised questions about the association's finances. Even
then, she said, ``many parents were questioning the constant
increase in expenses.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On July 20 that year, Kearn sent the association a petition
signed by 71 parents asking for a ``public accounting to date of
all the funds received and distributed by the JCGAA for the 1990
softball season.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr responded the same way he has to some others who have
requested such information: with silence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people were upset by the changes being initiated by
Spahr and the board, said Bill Whinery, former chairman of the
governors board. ``It seemed the association was taking more
interest in the association for the association's sake, and not for
the players' sake.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The board of governors, called for in the bylaws, dissolved in
1990, the year the association moved to the new and bigger complex
in Shawnee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mealman quit in frustration; Marcia Pruitt and Taylor McCann
said the board asked them to leave. Whinery said he bowed out
because his daughter had ended her playing days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr acknowledged the bylaws should have been changed to
reflect the elimination of the board of governors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the board was discarded ``because it wasn't working. We
knew we were going to have to phase them out because they had new
ideas every two years. The whole board was behind phasing them out
and did it slow enough to where it didn't make everybody mad.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Pruitt, who works as an office manager, said that she felt
hurt when Spahr told her that her volunteer services organizing the
leagues were no longer needed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The governors, she said, ``were kind of like forced out. Nobody
had any say. He (Spahr) was just like a one-man show.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr replaced Pruitt with a paid employee: his daughter, Deb
Schmidt. Schmidt, who declined to divulge her salary, said she
believed she was hired by the board of directors, not by her
father. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, the board of directors hired Spahr as the
association's first executive director, in essence making Spahr his
own supervisor. His salary the first year was $40,000. For the last
three years, he has been paid $48,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr said his hiring was approved by the association's lawyer
and accountant. But having the head of the board of directors as a
paid staff member is a no-no, says an 80-year-old charity watchdog
group. The National Charities Information Bureau suggests
guidelines for charities and rates national groups on whether they
abide by them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The paid executive directors of two other metropolitan area
youth sports groups, the 3&AMP;2 Baseball Club of Johnson County and
the Wyandotte County (Kan.) Sports Association, are not voting
members of their boards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Spahr called fewer board meetings, former
directors and employees said. When the board did meet, no minutes
were taken, Spahr said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was fine with board member Buford Winn of Boonville, Mo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel we have had a bond and trust there,'' he said.
``We just felt that everything was right, and we felt it wasn't
necessary.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson County Girls' bylaws allow board members to serve as
long as they want unless they are removed by a board vote. Spahr
has served at least 20 years, 11 as president. Winn has been on the
board at least 16 years, and Denton at least nine years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Toeneboehn, a Shawnee resident whose daughter played
softball, was the newest member, with 16 months of service. But
Toeneboehn, who had voiced concerns about several issues, said he
was removed from the board in April in a secret meeting of the
three remaining board members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Questions about money &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Spahr's allies defend his bookkeeping practices and other
actions, he has antagonized many people over the years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In January, longtime treasurer Pat Vielhauer resigned from the
board. In her resignation letter, Vielhauer complained that she
couldn't get answers from Spahr about finances, the gym project or
other matters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Many decisions have been made without board approval or
knowledge of such action being taken,'' wrote Vielhauer. ``Since we
are a nonprofit organization I feel we need to make sure any
actions taken follow the guidelines for a nonprofit
organization.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vielhauer, who was paid about $27,000 a year in her position as
secretary-treasurer, declined to comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missy Phillips, who was fired last June as the association's
director of operations, said Spahr often did not provide her the
information she needed to keep accurate books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much questioned the entire checking account. I'd find
myself saying, `Where is check No. 298?' I could not keep accurate
books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know how much money I was starting with or finishing
with,'' said Phillips, who said she was fired because of false
rumors that she was not doing her job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former facilities manager Jody Gill said he left in 1996 because
he couldn't get answers from Spahr about annual or long-term
budgets. Gill said he felt uncomfortable operating without
financial guidelines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr has brushed aside questions about the association's
operations and finances since he became the central figure in
charge, those around him said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This despite the association's bylaws, filed with the IRS in
1966, that say ``all books and records of the corporation may be
inspected by any member, or his agent or attorney for any proper
purpose at any reasonable time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his only interview with The Star about this story, Spahr
agreed to further interviews and said he would open the
association's books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told you that you can see the books. You can go to the
accountant. I would call the accountant and arrange it,'' Spahr
said. He even offered to share his personal banking records. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a few days later, Spahr said through the association's
attorney, Tom Kowalski, that he had no time for another interview
and that he would not share financial records. In a letter a few
days later, Kowalski told The Star that Spahr, Denton and Winn had
unanimously denied the newspaper's request to see financial
records. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski then asked for a letter explaining the issues that the
newspaper was looking into. Spahr, Denton and Winn did not respond
to the questions raised in the letter, or to further requests from
The Star for comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The backbone of philanthropy is the public trust and
accountability,'' said Dan Langan, spokesman for the National
Charities Information Bureau. ``It is really up to the organization
to allay any doubts that the public has.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The association has released only the 990s, the federal tax
forms for nonprofits, that are public record under IRS
regulations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relying on the 990 tax forms makes it difficult to track the
group's finances, because its expenses vary widely from year to
year. For example, the group told the IRS it spent $213 for
miscellaneous expenses in its 1993 fiscal year and $107,066 in
1996. Insurance cost $14,836 in 1995, about a third of the reported
$41,350 from two years earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 990, which covers most of calendar year 1998, was not
available, but an accountant's report indicated the association's
expenses exceeded revenue by nearly $64,000. Expenditures also
topped revenues by about $6,000 in 1995. The group recorded a
surplus of nearly $110,000 in 1996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The association's accountants, Bridges &AMP; Co. CPAs, said the
group's most recent financial statements were not audited. A
January letter from the firm, obtained by The Star, said the
association ``elected to omit substantially all of the disclosures
and the statement of cash flows required by generally accepted
accounting principles.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certified public accountant Wayne Bridges said the letter means
``we took the stuff they gave us and put it in the form of
financial statements.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The charity watchdog group urges nonprofits to prepare detailed
annual budgets and release audited financial statements. The Olathe
(Kan.) Girls Softball Association and Wyandotte County Sports
Association said they do audits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County Girls' is not required to audit its finances,
though, and the 3&AMP;2 Baseball Club and North Kansas City (Mo.) Area
Baseball said they do not do audits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith Sherinsky, a technical expert at the American Institute
of Certified Public Accountants, said the level of review used by
Johnson County Girls' Athletic Association provides no fiscal
assurances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another money issue involves numbers from last summer's national
18 and under American Fastpitch Association tournament held at the
complex. Spahr told board members and The Star that he collected
$11,238.07 in gate revenues for the six-day tournament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Toeneboehn, who was Spahr's tournament director at the time,
estimated attendance could have been as high as 2,000 a day. He
said the stands were full, even during the middle of the night when
teams played make-up games because of rain. Admission fees should
have been $30,000 or higher, he said. Others agreed, including Ed
Serdar, an American Fastpitch regional director in Illinois who has
been a host for similar tournaments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr would not discuss questions about the gate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deepening debt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is in the building of the gymnasium that the issues of
consolidation of power and money come together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr told reporters in March the gym would cost $2.6 million to
$3.5 million. It will feature four basketball or eight volleyball
courts, a game room, concession stand, sports shop and a large
second-floor office suite for Spahr and his staff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The association has been raising money for the gym and other
improvements for years. Girls paid higher fees and took part in
fund-raisers. A February 1997 association newsletter reported that
girls raised about $56,000 selling trash bags. With the money paid
by parents who did not want to sell bags, nearly $82,000 went into
the building and improvement fund. The association decided to end
fund-raisers last year, Spahr said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1993, the board announced a ``one-time'' building
fee for basketball players. The fee, which some remember as at
least $30, brought the total basketball fee for that year to about
$80. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next year, when the fee remained at $80, parent Linda
Bridges said she complained. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When they topped out over $100 a child _ and I had three
(children playing) _ I just said I can't do this any more,'' said
Linda Bridges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, after fees hit $140 a player, basketball coach
Steve Singer took his team out of the Johnson County Girls'
program. He started a new league and charges about $70 a girl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson County Girls' fee is ``a huge amount of money in
comparison to what leagues normally cost,'' Singer said. ``The cost
is just way out of line.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Bridges said she asked association employees how much of
her fee was going to the new gym, because she wanted to use that
portion as a charitable deduction on her tax return. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end when I was really raising questions, they said all
of the fees are fees and not donations,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How much money the association raised for the gym through higher
fees and fund-raisers is unclear. And unbeknownst to parents who
thought they were paying into the building fund, Spahr told The
Star he spent the money on other improvements at the complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year when it came time to build the gym, the association
borrowed $3.5 million to cover its cost and a previous $500,000
debt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denton, a board member and an experienced contractor, said he
told Spahr to get bids for the gym project. And Denton said Spahr
later told him that he did so. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Spahr, in his interview with The Star, said he did not get
bids. Instead, he interviewed several companies and picked one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I canvassed a lot of the people; I looked around,'' Spahr
said. ``I'm not saying I couldn't have got it done cheaper, but you
know, nobody ever takes the lowest bid.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr chose the Johnson County firm of Strickland Construction,
and Eric Hughes, a Strickland spokesman, said: ``It is not uncommon
for nonprofit or private businesses to negotiate with only one
contractor on a design/build project.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Skip Hutton, president of the Builders' Association of
Missouri, said most private organizations either get bids or
negotiated contracts, or at least negotiate a builder's profit
margin before construction begins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hutton said he didn't know about the Johnson County Girls'
project, but in his experience as a board member of the nonprofit
United Way: ``If it is any kind of sizable project, there would be
a fiduciary responsibility to spend the money wisely, and you would
want to get some bids.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While IRS rules do not require nonprofits to seek bids on such
projects, a failure to do so makes it harder for officials to prove
they have spent the charity's money wisely, said several experts on
nonprofits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is no bidding it is very bad for an exempt
organization, especially on a project of this scope,'' said Fran
Hill, a University of Miami law professor who is an expert on
nonprofits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Owens, director of the Exempt Organizations Division of
the Internal Revenue Service, would not comment specifically on
Johnson County Girls' Athletic Association but said: ``A bidding
procedure certainly is the classic way of determining the best
price for a particular job.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr said he expected the gym to be self-supporting, with
programs in the building bringing in enough to cover the expected
$28,000 in monthly loan payments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Jack Waters, executive vice president of Exchange National
Bank in Shawnee, which loaned the association the money for the
gym, expressed confidence in its viability. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spahr said the board approved all decisions he made on the gym,
that he and the board were prudent with association funds and that
the building was carefully planned all along the way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said some unanticipated costs _ a $250,000 maple wood floor,
a $100,000 fire wall, $142,000 drop-down baskets and $110,000 water
lines _ increased the price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our board of directors knew of this,'' Spahr said. ``The board
agreed to everything, you know, the same way with the financing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the makeup of the board could change soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ayer, the team sponsor, and lawyer Barry Martin said Spahr
contacted them and a third person in recent days and asked them to
serve on an expanded board of directors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ayer said Spahr also agreed to resign from the board while
staying on as executive director. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, Ayer said Spahr had once before agreed to resign from
the board but had changed his mind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
