<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD-BUYOUT-KAN &LR;      05-30 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-BUYOUT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYOUT OF FLOODED PROPERTIES CUTS FINANCIAL RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ Dan and Mary Puhr
returned from a family reunion one day last July and discovered
that a downpour had left their Independence, Mo., yard, three
vehicles and basement in 4 feet of water. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than four months later, it happened again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the Puhrs will turn their house keys over to
Independence as part of a federal buyout program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, spending more than $100 million in federal money, has
used the program more than any other state to get people out of
flood plains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to put our names on the top of the list,'' Puhr
said. ``When we got hit twice in four months, that was a bit much
to take.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 80 property owners in Missouri affected by last year's
floods are selling out, adding to a statewide total of more 4,200
since flooding in 1993. Add in relocations of houses or elevating
them above potential floodwaters, and the total rises to more than
5,200. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's twice as many as the next-highest state, Illinois. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, almost 1,100 properties have been bought out, moved
or elevated since 1993, including many in Johnson and Wyandotte
counties. Only three states had more buyouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency has touted Missouri as a
model of flood-plain management. In the long run, buying somebody
out is cheaper for taxpayers than repeatedly paying federal flood
insurance claims. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very big push on to eliminate repetitive losses,''
said Bob Shea, who oversees the program for the federal agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, exposed to hundreds of miles of the Mississippi and
Missouri rivers, is more prone to flooding than most states.
``Missouri seized very early on the buyout program,'' Shea said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary buyout program was announced in Kansas City, Mo.,
by President Clinton in late 1993 and became a pet project of Gov.
Mel Carnahan's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State officials have spent more than $100 million in 59
communities swamped in the 1993 and 1995 floods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest is to get people out of harm's way,'' said Buck
Katt, assistant director of the Missouri Emergency Management
Agency. ``People's lives have been disrupted too many times.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gene Krase, deputy director for the Kansas Division of Emergency
Services, said buyouts from the 1993 flood greatly eliminated the
need for federal disaster assistance after the 1995 floods,
especially in northeast Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the '95 flood would have triggered another disaster
(declaration) had it not been for the buyout programs,'' Krase
said. ``It absolutely pays.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is happy with the buyouts. Some homeowners say
appraisals are too low. In Alexandria in northeast Missouri, many
of the 40 people who sold in 1993 also had to get federal loans so
they could afford to move. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them wish they hadn't sold, but (the Federal
Emergency Management Agency) came in here with a handful of
money,'' Mayor Bob Davis said. ``It sounded good until they had to
make those $400 or $500 monthly loan payments.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katt said he could understand that, but ``if that's a bigger
burden than being in an area that floods frequently, they should
stay in the area that floods frequently. It depends on your
priority.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another complaint of some property owners is that if they sell
after having collected on a flood-insurance claim, the amount of
the claim is deducted from the purchase price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to help myself by having flood insurance, but I
felt they were condemning me for having it,'' said Carl Davis,
half-brother of the mayor's. ``I paid premiums for 20 years. The
people who didn't have insurance came out ahead.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katt said up to five years in premiums were reimbursed to
homeowners who took the buyouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his family moved from Alexandria after the 1993 flood,
but he kept the property. Davis' old home site is an empty lot, as
are three dozen lots the city acquired. Most are vacant, with some
being used as public gardens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad what they did _ buying property and turning
it into a ghost town,'' Carl Davis said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local governments own the bought-out properties but are not
allowed to build permanent structures on them. Some are converted
to parks and athletic fields. The city has to maintain the land,
which no longer generates tax revenue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Carrollton, Mo., about 70 miles east of Kansas City, the city
is buying about seven homes, including the 100-year-old, white
four-room house that Anna Martin is selling reluctantly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a nice patio, a nice garage, and an acre and a half
that looks like a golf course,'' said Martin, who lived there with
her parents in the late 1940s and moved back 10 years ago. ``It was
always Grandma's house.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin said she and her husband decided to sell the house
because they didn't have flood insurance and because fixing it
would cost too much. The price won't be enough to get them into
their next home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It aggravates me we didn't get enough to relocate without
going into debt,'' Martin said. ``I kept thinking someone would
come along with a better idea, but they didn't.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the Federal Emergency Management Agency knows that
selling is difficult, even if voluntary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very emotional issue,'' Shea said. ``It's hard for them
to deal with.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homes in flood plains don't sell for much because of their
location and, sometimes, their condition. Katt said the average
price paid in Missouri is $24,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But most people are elated to sell, Katt said. Last year, about
60 people who sold their homes in Cape Girardeau, Mo., in 1993 had
a five-year reunion and fish fry to look back and celebrate, Katt
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You never saw so many people with big smiles on their faces,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An avid supporter of the program is the National Wildlife
Federation, which published a nearly 200-page report last year
called ``Higher Ground.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The point of the study was to show how buyouts can reduce
repetitive-loss claims. Land in 300 communities that were top
candidates for buyouts represents less than 1 percent of federally
insured property nationwide, but makes up almost 50 percent of
repetitive-loss claims, the federation found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With buyouts, you really have a situation that helps people,
is fiscally responsible and benefits the environment,'' said Ben
McNitt, the federation's spokesman. Vacated land can stimulate
habitat for birds and other wildlife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The study said that about 100,000 pieces of property _ almost
five times what has been bought since 1993 _ would make sense for
buyouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a long way to go with this,'' McNitt said. ``We
have just begun to see the possible benefits.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
