<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-CONVENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VFW PLANS ACTIVITIES FOR 100TH ANNIVERSARY CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Thousands of
brown military overseas caps, along with the blue dresses worn by
members of the VFW's Ladies Auxiliary, will make vivid veterans'
pride in their numbers and their legacy this summer. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Aug. 14 through 20 at Bartle Hall, the Veterans of Foreign
Wars will hold its 100th anniversary convention in Kansas City,
where the organization has had its headquarters since 1930. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want, I guess, to brag on ourselves,'' said Thomas Pouliot
of Helena, Mont., the VFW's current commander-in-chief. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VFW national conventions are never small. Last year's event in
San Antonio drew 30,000 people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the 100th anniversary gathering will include attractions
that suggest a determined effort to reach beyond the veterans
community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Convention plans currently include an air show at Downtown
Airport, a Kauffman Stadium appearance by singer Kenny Rogers and a
John Philip Sousa concert with the Kansas City Symphony at the
Liberty Memorial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not events we normally have at our convention,''
said Pouliot. ``We are inviting the community to participate in
more ways than in the past.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The VFW also is reminding area residents of its presence on West
34th Street, near Broadway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our headquarters have been here since 1930, and we want the
public here in Kansas City to take part in this convention,'' said
Vern Pall, a Kansas City VFW spokesman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has been invited to address the convention's
opening sessions on Aug. 16. However, it has not been confirmed
that he will attend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The veterans' arrival will recall for the larger Kansas City
community the role that American service personnel have played in
the past century's conflicts, Pall added. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been called the `American Century,' '' Pall said.
``Looking at it from the veterans' point of view, they have been
part of this century's greatest moments.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The convention also will focus attention on veterans concerns as
well as maintaining the veteran community's status in Washington
and elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mere arithmetic makes that a challenge./ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1975 there were 28.2 million veterans in the United States.
Today there are perhaps 25 million. About half the total VFW
membership of almost 2 million is made up of the World War II
generation. Those veterans are dying at the rate of approximately
1,000 a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the VFW membership commands respect on Capitol Hill.
Fortune magazine recently listed the VFW among the top 25 most
powerful membership organizations in the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Veterans were not always so esteemed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Spanish-American War of 1898 galvanized the country
and made heroes of Theodore Roosevelt and Commodore George Dewey,
the public soon forgot how the rigors of jungle fighting devastated
many veterans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are wrecks for life,'' said the chief surgeon of
the American armed forces. ``Others are candidates for a premature
grave and hundreds will require most careful attention and
treatment before they regain the vigor they lost in Cuba.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The VFW traces its beginnings to 1899, when veterans of action
in Cuba and the Philippines began meeting to form organizations
that would represent them in their quest for pensions and medical
care. At the time, the government provided little of either, even
for those disabled or suffering from tropical diseases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first such group formed in Columbus, Ohio, in September
1899. In 1914 that group consolidated with several others, taking
the VFW name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The organization's first lobbyist was appointed in 1919. During
the 1920s the VFW proved influential in the creation of the U.S.
Veterans Bureau, later to become the Department of Veterans
Affairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1920s the VFW helped Congress pass various acts
that established or increased benefits for Spanish-American War and
World War I veterans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last national VFW convention in Kansas City was in 1931. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry Truman, then Jackson County presiding judge, served as
general chairman. Resolutions approved at the 1931 gathering
included a call for better pensions for widows and orphans of World
War I veterans, as well as adequate hospitalization for all
disabled veterans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time there will be similar priorities, such as the medical
health-care budget for the Department of Veterans Affairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the government has come to a crossroads,'' Pouliot
said. ``If there are no additional moneys given this year to our VA
hospitals, medical care and services will begin to be curtailed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The possible use of ground troops by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization in Kosovo also will be discussed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At last year's convention, the VFW membership passed a
resolution opposing the use of ground troops in Kosovo. Since then
the start of NATO air strikes against the government of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic has altered the debate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The VFW's national council of administration recently passed a
resolution stating the VFW believed NATO should use all means
necessary to bring the Yugoslavia action to a successful
conclusion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That would include the ground forces if the NATO military
directors so choose,'' said Pouliot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the resolution will still be on the table in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the body of our organization will review and discuss
this,'' said Pouliot. ``We are a pragmatic organization. Sometimes
we look at an issue and come up with a different decision.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the convention will include discussion of ensuring that
the VFW and its approximately 9,900 posts in the United States and
overseas remain meaningful in their respective communities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Currently VFW members operate food banks, visit senior citizens
and organize essay contests for local students. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that to be relevant in the 21st century, community
service needs to remain an extremely important element,'' said Bill
Smith, the VFW's Washington director for communications and public
affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
