<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK AHEAD: MORE STRENGTH IN MAY'S LABOR MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   Another strong employment report is
forecast when May's labor market statistics are revealed Friday,
but the news isn't expected to be rosy enough to raise fears of a
Federal Reserve reaction. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The consensus anticipates a gain of 200,000-225,000 jobs for the
economy and a 0.1 percent decline in the unemployment rate, to 4.2
percent. Some analysts predict the jobless rate will remain
unchanged, but that's the worst-case forecast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets and institutions will be closed in observance
of the Memorial Day holiday. &QL; 
Tuesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The April reading of the Index of Leading Economic Indicators
isn't expected to show much of an increase, but if it does eke out
a gain it will be the seventh straight monthly rise. The index,
which is designed to predict economic activity three to nine months
hence, has been signaling at least moderate growth through the rest
of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- The index of the National Association of Purchasing
Management is forecast to have made a respectable gain in May,
rising to 53.5, from April's 52.8 level. The index measures
activity in the manufacturing sector, with any reading above 50
reflecting growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Construction spending is forecast to have edged up in April
by 0.2 percent, but the growth trend shows signs of slowing.
Building outlays surged 2 percent in February, but only 0.5 percent
in March. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outlook is mixed for new home sales in April. A consensus of
leading economists surveyed by Thomson Global Markets anticipates a
slight drop in the annual rate, to 900,000. The Merrill Lynch
economic research staff, however, predicts a gain of nearly 2
percent, to an annual rate of 925,000. &QL; 
Thursday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another gain is forecast for factory orders during April, but
not as strong as March. After orders for manufactured goods plunged
1.8 percent in February, the series rebounded with a 2 percent
surge. Most forecasts estimate April's rise at 0.4 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- May sales figures are expected to be reported by major retail
chains. &QL; 
Friday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The employment report's data on the average workweek and average
hourly earnings aren't expected to show much change. The workweek
is likely to have remained the same as the previous month, at 35.5
hours, while hourly earnings are predicted to have edged up 0.2
percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eye on the economy
</P>
<P>
   -- Monday: Memorial Day holiday
</P>
<P>
   -- Tuesday: Another gain for leading indicators
</P>
<P>
   -- Wednesday: Whither new home sales?
</P>
<P>
   -- Thursday: Factory orders rising
</P>
<P>
   -- Friday: Labor market still strong
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
