<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: LONDON THEATER OUTDOORS; GETTING SURREAL; POLISH
TREASURE TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Mass., N.Y. Ill.)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shakespeare in the park, London style, gets off to its official
start this week when the New Shakespeare Co. raises the figurative
curtain on ``The Merry Wives of Windsor'' Tuesday and ``Twelfth
Night'' on Friday at the Open Air Theater in Regent's Park. The
comedies will play in repertory until the season ends on Sept. 4.
Beginning with previews on July 20, they will be joined by ``A
Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum'' and on Aug. 3 by a
children's show, ``The Last Fattybottypuss in the World,'' a
matinee attraction that begins in the park and ends in the London
Zoo. Information: 011- 44-171-486-2431.
</P>
<P>
   Another Look
</P>
<P>
   Surrealist art will fill the Frank Lloyd Wright Rotunda and
several adjoining galleries of the Guggenheim Museum when an
exhibition assembled from two of the most important private
collections of these works opens on Friday for a run through Sept.
12. Trumpeted as the first major New York show of Surrealist art in
30 years, ``Surrealism: Two Private Eyes, the Nesuhi Ertegun and
Daniel Filipacchi Collections'' includes some 700 paintings,
photographs, sculptures, works on paper, books and manuscripts by
artists like Giorgio de Chirico, Salvador Dali, Max Ernst, Frida
Kahlo, Rene Magritte, Joan Miro and Man Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Another Direction
</P>
<P>
   A David Mamet world premiere with a difference beckons playgoers
to the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass., beginning on
Friday. The play is ``Boston Marriage.'' What's unusual about this
new work by the author of ``American Buffalo,'' ``Speed-the-Plow''
and ``Oleanna'' is that it is set at the turn of the century, and
it features an all-female cast. The plot deals with two women and
the revelation of the secrets of their relationship. The stars are
Rebecca Pidgeon (Mamet's wife), Felicity Huffman and Mary McCann.
Directed by Mamet, ``Boston Marriage'' will play through June 27 at
the Hasty Pudding Theater. Information: (617) 547-8300.
</P>
<P>
   Flights of Fancy
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 150 works of art, many of them grand, exotic objects that
have never previously left their homeland, have been assembled from
34 museums, churches and public institutions throughout Poland for
an exhibition opening on Saturday at the Art Institute of Chicago.
Running through Sept. 6, ``Land of the Winged Horsemen: Art in
Poland 1572-1764'' is billed as the first show of national
treasures of Poland's Baroque era to tour the United States. The
objects include a crown and throne of Polish kings; paintings of
royalty and nobility; liturgical objects, and the hussar armor,
with leopard skins and feathers, that inspired the show's title.
The feathers worn by the Husaria, a heavy cavalry regiment,
produced a fearsome rushing sound as it rode into battle.
Information: (312) 443-3600.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
