<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE AMERICAN WAY OF CLASS, A GAME OF SELF-DELUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb.)  (jw) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was pointed out to me recently that the old existential
profundity ``Hell is other people,'' which we used to intone with
such dark fervor, really does better when seen as the basic
principle of comedy or, let's say, comedy at its most aggressive.
Rephrase Jean-Paul Sartre, and you get Dorothy Parker greeting new
visitors with the words ``What fresh hell is this?'' and dubbing
herself and her peers a ladies' auxiliary of the damned.
</P>
<P>
   That Parker tone, with its ironclad brightness, is absolutely
essential to American comedy. Our culture, from the political to
the familial, loves to insist on its cheery, true-hearted
simplicity. And the more this is claimed, the more likely it is
that we have crossed over into the lethally simplistic.
</P>
<P>
   No current movie gets all of this better than ``Election,'' and
no recent movie gets it better than ``Citizen Ruth.'' Both were
written by Alexander Payne and Jim Taylor; both were directed by
Payne, and both are set in the Midwest, the nesting place for a
style that can join the benign and the banal, the open-hearted and
the closed-minded, with head-spinning precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' is about social, sexual and generational power
struggles in an Omaha, Neb., high school (the mostly white George
Washington Carver High, named, with a wonderfully pointless sense
of civic duty, for the Negro scientist who discovered so many uses
for the peanut).
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizen Ruth'' is about how an intensely moral issue _ is one
for or against abortion? _ turns into a bidding war for a female
body, complete with illegal cash contributions and transcendentally
bogus speech making.
</P>
<P>
   Both movies have a crisp, almost claustrophobic look (``Stop
shoving these people, their clothes and their houses in my face,''
you want to say), stay-in-step pacing (as if the camera was helping
to impose conformity on us) and dialogue that hits all the
necessary stops between beatitude and platitude.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the thing about ``Election,'' which, unlike ``Citizen
Ruth,'' is quite a box-office success. Right now, while adults have
good reason to brood over the furies and miseries of adolescence
and the dangers of this or that high school, ``Election'' makes
perfectly clear that adolescence and high school are not just rites
of passage.
</P>
<P>
   In their own crude, scary or (if you're lucky) glittering way,
they prefigure and embody adult life: the power struggles between
teacher and student, framed by the past in the form of parent and
child and by the future in the form of boss and worker; the
alliances and the ruptures; the passionate friendships and
betrayals; the ceaseless negotiating of class and style
distinctions (ethnic and racial ones, too, if they happen to be
available); the seesaw between hormonal imperatives and inhibition;
the perils of unconventional sexual choices. You will probably grow
up to be better at these things. You're certainly not ever going to
be free of them.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the ``Election'' war is Jim McAllister (played by
Matthew Broderick, the perfect emblem of boyishness going rancid).
Jim teaches history, current events and civics and is genially smug
about his desire to impart a real sense of morals and ethics to his
students. On the other side is the bullishly perky Tracy Flick
(Reese Witherspoon). Her calculation and drive enrage him and he is
determined to thwart her election to the Student Council
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Jim has just the kind of smugness that allows a person to be
treacherous and cowardly without thinking ill of himself. (You had
a good reason, you tell yourself, especially if you don't examine
your motives closely.) And as for Tracy, that perkiness has long
been a foolproof cover, especially in the Midwest and the South,
for an ambition that would otherwise look mannishly ruthless and
single-minded.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy has a stage mother _ all the world's a stage in her case _
who regularly writes letters to women like Elizabeth Dole, asking
for advice on how her daughter can be successful in a man's world.
</P>
<P>
   This is all very smart. And so is the Payne-Taylor team's
forthrightness about class.
</P>
<P>
   How do its presumptions and resentments play out? Who can afford
not to think about it? And who has to think about little else?
</P>
<P>
   Tracy is the lower-middle-class daughter of a divorced mother;
her election opponents, Paul and Tammy, are the children of a
cement company owner and his deferential wife (though once Tammy
decides to run for the presidency too, Paul manages to remind her
that she is adopted). Jim McAllister is in the middle, playing one
side against the other. The difference between more privilege and
less often comes down to believing that you are acting decently
when you're not, and pretending that you are acting decently when
you know you're not.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 ``Citizen Ruth'' is starker and meaner about class: as
Ruth Stoops, Laura Dern is an anti-heroine out of Brecht. (``First
feed the face/And then talk right and wrong'' sang the beggars in
``The Threepenny Opera.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ruth is a homeless drug addict (she favors spray paint
inhalation) who has had four children (two were adopted, two went
to her brother) and 16 arrests. She gets taken up in jail by an
anti-abortion group, and while they are busy preparing to make her
a test case in a court battle, she gets spirited away by
abortion-rights advocates who want the same thing. Ruth wants an
abortion, in fact, but when the anti-abortionists offer her money,
she decides to get what she can from whoever will pay, then light
out for the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Men play important roles in both movies, but it is the women who
drive the stories. Not just Tracy, but Tammy, too, the naive young
lesbian who learns to lie and manipulate in her own best interests.
And not just Ruth, but the women around her in both camps,
determined to shape whatever sorry little bits of destiny she may
have.
</P>
<P>
   When D.H. Lawrence described the American character as hard,
isolate, stoic and a killer, he was talking about men, but he might
as well have been describing Tracy Flick. And when we think of the
wild-child outsider who survives by becoming a trickster and con
man, we think of Huck Finn. Well, his descendant is Citizen Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, there is no real territory to light out for
these days. ``That's what's great about America,'' Jim McAllister
says earnestly at one point. ``You can always start over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure you can. But you're stuck with the same old self, ready to
reach out and mess everything up the next time, and the time after
that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
