<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS SEEK MORE MONEY FOR VETERANS' HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 200 people gathered Sunday in front of the
Department of Veterans Affairs Medical Center in Manhattan to
protest what they called the steady erosion of health-care services
for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The Memorial Day weekend rally was one of about 150 that took
place at medical centers across the United States, organized by
Disabled American Veterans, a national advocacy group, said Albion
Giordano, a supervisor of the organization's New York regional
office.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano said the budget for fiscal year 2000 proposed by
President Clinton falls $3 billion short of what is required to
``meet the health-care needs of all veterans.'' The president's
proposal calls for $17.3 billion for health care for veterans,
Giordano's group said.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano said the Department of Veterans Affairs' budget has
stayed at the same level for four years, while the population it
serves has been aging and requiring more services. In recent years,
the agency has been consolidating its hospitals and cutting the
number of its beds.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-Long Island, spoke briefly at the rally.
Lazio said that his mother is a veteran and that his wife,
Patricia, had worked as a nurse practitioner in two hospitals for
veterans in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staff reductions and unnecessary hospital closings are the
problems that are most troubling,'' he said. ``The president's
budget is totally inadequate to meet the minimal needs of
veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Some veterans said they were concerned that the agency's
hospitals seemed understaffed. Others complained of difficulty
getting appointments and getting to see specialists, and a fear
that hospitals would be consolidated or closed.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Shera, 42, a Navy veteran who served on Grenada, said he
was injured while on duty and is partly paralyzed. He said he was
concerned that the agency might close the Veterans Administration
hospital in Castle Point, near his home in Gardiner, which would
force him to travel farther to get care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're dangling this ax of doom over our heads, and I'm tired
of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's simply not enough nursing care to go around,'' said
Paul Tobin, of the Eastern Paralyzed Veterans Association, based in
Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
