<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS BILL THAT BOOSTS TEACHER PAY, CUTS TAXES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT and R.A. DYER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After months of arguing over how to spend the
biggest surplus in state history, the Texas Legislature gave final
approval Sunday night to landmark legislation that will raise
teacher pay, cut taxes and provide a huge boost in education
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush applauded the sweeping legislation, which he
said accomplishes the priorities he laid out on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a message to the people of Texas,'' Bush said. ``I
said, `Let's pay the teachers more money, and let's substantially
cut taxes.' I think this bill will do both.''
</P>
<P>
   The $3.9 billion legislation, Senate Bill 4, provides about $2
billion to boost teacher salaries across the board by $3,000 a
year, and directs $1.3 billion for local school property tax cuts
averaging 6 cents per $100 of property value.
</P>
<P>
   It also attempts to end the practice of social promotion, or
advancing academically unprepared schoolchildren from one grade to
the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one of the most significant school finance
bills we've seen in this state,'' said Rep. Paul Sadler,
D-Henderson, one of the chief architects of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said the bill represents a ``heartfelt thank you'' to
Texas teachers, and will set up the most equitable funding system
ever for the public school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will a have a long-lasting impact on our
children,'' Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   The property tax cuts included in the bill vary among school
districts, depending on such factors as a district's property tax
wealth and debt load. In general terms, the legislation funnels to
districts additional state money and then requires them to make a
corresponding reduction in property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also limits the discretion of local districts to
raise property taxes. It requires a public vote on increases of 3
cents or more per $100 property value this year, and a public vote
for increases of 6 cents or more next year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes provisions to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spend an estimated $173 million over two years for remedial
classes to help end social promotion. The bill will also require
students to pass the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills (TAAS) in
the third, fifth and eighth grades in order to advance, though a
local board could overrule the decision to hold a child back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide $125 million over two years to fund grants for
enhanced pre-kindergarten, kindergarten and Head Start programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Funnel $85 million over two years to school districts to help
ninth-graders at risk of dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   After coming to a logjam and nearly forcing a special session of
the Legislature, House and Senate negotiators finally agreed to the
plan late Saturday. Although the final deal draws elements from
both the House and Senate versions of the school finance
legislation, it most closely resembles the bill adopted by the
Democrat-controlled House.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, chairman of the House Committee on Public Education,
refused to yield to Senate demands to use more of the money for tax
relief, saying that the original Senate proposal would have hurt
school districts without providing substantially more tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the negotiations were salvaged by the use of an
extra $100 million _ much of it to be generated by newly passed
lottery legislation _ which allowed negotiators to agree on a
school finance bill containing provisions of the original House and
Senate plans.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery bill would let the lottery commission, rather than
the Legislature, set payout rates. Texas Comptroller Carol Keeton
Rylander said the bill should bring more than $60 million in
additional education money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that we were able to reach an agreement and get our
work done without a special session,'' said Rep. Kent Grusendorf,
R-Arlington, the only Republican among the House negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents the largest increase in education spending in
the history of the state of Texas. And we'll get some tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
