<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      05-30 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday this spring my friends Steve, Rich, Kathy and I
decided to go bicycling from midtown to Riverdale. Kathy, who is
from Sarasota, Fla., has been in New York only for six months, and
she and Rich are marrying in June.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped at the Morris-Jumel Mansion at West 160th Street and
were outside the gates peering in when the curator came out and
asked if we would like to look around. We said we were on our way
cycling, but she said we would be her free admissions of the day,
so inside we went for a very pleasant tour.
</P>
<P>
   We were continuing up Broadway when we passed a couple of
bagpipers, members of the Emerald Society. Since Rich and Kathy
were looking for bagpipers to play at their wedding, we approached
them. They were off-duty police officers and said they'd be happy
to play, but they didn't have a pen to write down their phone
number. One of the officers took a bullet out of his revolver and
used the lead tip to jot down the number.
</P>
<P>
   We next rode across the Broadway bridge and on our way through
Riverdale passed Wave Hill. We rested near the entrance when a
couple of the guards asked if we would like to go inside. Not
really, we said, but the guards said that admission was free until
noon and that they would watch our bikes. So off we went for
another nice tour.
</P>
<P>
   As we were leaving the Bronx, a community affairs police officer
flagged us down and asked if we wanted to register our bikes in the
police anti-theft program. We declined but appreciated her gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I looked over at Kathy. ``You see,'' I said, ``You didn't
believe us, but we told you New Yorkers were friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LARRY HEROLD
</P>
<P>
   Michael Heim was shopping at Williams-Sonoma on the Upper East
Side when he noticed a fashionably dressed woman awkwardly holding
a stainless-steel colander. Would the colander look all right if
left out on the kitchen counter, she asked the saleswoman. Yes, the
saleswoman said, she thought it would be quite attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The customer then asked what else she might buy that would look
good if left out on the kitchen counter. The saleswoman, obviously
recognizing that she had a customer more concerned with appearance
than utility, happily obliged.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   A man I had never met came to my office seeking an impromptu
meeting with my boss. When I told him that she was out, he asked
whether there was another time that day when he might drop by.
While checking her calendar, I received a personal phone call that
I really couldn't put on hold. I tried to speak as softly as I
could _ it concerned the pain I felt at the recent break-up of a
relationship of five and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   I got off the phone and apologized to the man, who appeared to
have heard some of the conversation. I told him that my boss's
schedule was nearly full, and he said perhaps he'd drop by later.
An hour later he appeared. I smiled and told him my boss hadn't yet
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured,'' he said. ``But it looks like someone is having a
bad day.'' And from behind his back, he brought forth three dozen
yellow roses and put them down in front of me, turned around and
left.
</P>
<P>
   He never returned to call up the favor. He just did it to
brighten a life. And so he did.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANONYMOUS
</P>
<P>
   Recent news stories prompted Susan Thaler to recall an incident
when a friend's daughter was in second grade. The child returned
from school and reported that her teacher, who was black, was
``different from you and me.'' Her mother, hoping to nip any
incipient racism in the bud, explained that all people were created
the same, that no one was different from anyone else. To no avail;
her daughter insisted her teacher was different.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, nearing despair, finally asked why the teacher was
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has eyes in the back of her head,'' her awestruck daughter
whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Fog grounded a U S Airways flight to Richmond, Va., recently and
the passengers in the aircraft at La Guardia were impatiently
waiting for takeoff. After an hour or so, one of the frustrated
passengers announced that she had a few hundred homemade
chocolate-chip cookies she was taking to a nephew's graduation and
proceeded to distribute them to everyone on board. The woman got a
long round of applause and, according to Selma Goldstein, one of
the recipients, the cookies were delicious.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Lydia Page was on a bus recently when a woman of
about 80 tugged at her elbow. ``I don't mean to intrude,'' she said
as she pointed to a store they were passing. Written in bold
letters on the window were PORNOGRAPHY, VIDEOS and one other
descriptive term. ``I know what pornography is, I know what videos
are,'' the woman said. ``But tell me, what do you think they do in
a CD ROOM?''
</P>
<P>
   JUST MAKE A LIST
</P>
<P>
   A week ago I sat me down
</P>
<P>
   And started, with an earnest frown,
</P>
<P>
   To list the things I had to do,
</P>
<P>
   But as I wrote, the memo grew,
</P>
<P>
   For every time I thought of one,
</P>
<P>
   Six jobs occurred that must be done,
</P>
<P>
   Until the list reached such a length
</P>
<P>
   Just reading it sapped all my strength,
</P>
<P>
   And tasks that once seemed small and light
</P>
<P>
   Weighed heavily in black and white,
</P>
<P>
   Till now my head's in such a spin,
</P>
<P>
   I'm too exhausted to begin.
</P>
<P>
   _ PHYLLIS ROSENTEUR
</P>
<P>
   The driver on the uptown Broadway bus spotted a man entering
from the rear door. Jane Seskin reports that he didn't get angry.
``Sir,'' he said politely. ``Is there any reason you are coming
through the back? Have you forgotten there's a very modest service
charge?''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   A young mother and her 8-year-old daughter entered an uncrowded
M train bound for lower Manhattan. A young deaf man sitting next to
the girl was signing to his friend across from him, who was sitting
next to me.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the girl touched the signing man's shoulder and
pointed to her eye, her heart and her mother. The man smiled and
the mother said, ``Oh, I thought it was like this,'' and pointed to
her eye, hugged herself and then pointed to her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The man smiled again, held up his hand with pinky and thumb
pointing up and explained that this also meant, ``I love you.''
They all smiled.
</P>
<P>
   In the subway, with few words, ``I love you'' was expressed
three times among strangers.
</P>
<P>
   _ RACHEL HOTT
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
