<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-INDIANS-480(2TAKE     05-30 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-480(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTO ALOMAR ADDS SKILLS, THRILLS AND VICTORIES TO INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the first Seven Wonders of the World. The Cleveland
Indians have the Eighth, and they are taking him to New York this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Roberto Alomar bunt. Watch him hit a home run. Watch him
steal a base. Most thrilling of all, watch him hurtle through the
air and snare a ground ball or a line drive. You can't watch him
think and teach, but he does those things, too.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar, a second baseman who for 11 years dazzled eyewitnesses
in San Diego, Toronto and Baltimore, has brought his scintillating
act to Cleveland, and he is the primary reason these Indians are
better than the Cleveland teams that won four division
championships and played in two World Series the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   By adding Alomar as a free agent, the Indians completed their
own all-star team: every starter at the eight field positions has
played in the All-Star Game, and the eight players have been named
to All-Star teams a total of 32 times. Lest anyone think their
credentials have faded, they have catapulted the Indians to the
best won-lost record in the major leagues at 32-16 and put them on
course to smash the major league record for runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   With Kenny Lofton, Omar Vizquel and Alomar the first third of
the batting order, the Indians have, in effect, three leadoff
hitters batting before they get to Manny Ramirez, the majors' most
prolific run producer with 60 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   This is the team that will try to knock the Yankees off their
perch as World Series champions and will be at Yankee Stadium
Saturday afternoon to play the Yankees for the first time this
season. Alomar will be the one sprawled in the infield dirt after
making one of his acrobatic snatches of a batted ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie's probably been the reason our team is playing so
well,'' first baseman Jim Thome said last week in Cleveland.
``Obviously by his performance but also his leadership and his
intelligence. You listen to him, he knows what's going on. He knows
what's going to happen when the pitcher's on the mound. He knows
defensively where to play. He's really intelligent when it comes to
baseball. He'll lay a bunt down in a key situation and you look up
and it works out. Call it luck or call it intelligence. I call it
intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Hargrove called the 31-year-old Alomar the ``major
difference'' in this year's version of the Indians, saying he is
one of the few players in the majors who make the players around
him better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie has instincts that are almost flawless,'' Hargrove
said. ``He brings an awareness of the game of baseball to the
people around him that not many players can do. Robbie didn't come
in and scream and holler and strut around and be arrogant and say,
`This is the way it's done.' He dispenses his information in bits
and pieces and he does it at the right time. He's very instinctual
about stuff like that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Alomar at the forefront after a year in which he was
reviled in Baltimore for what some saw as less than an honest
effort, the Indians are romping toward another AL Central title,
leading second-place Kansas City by 8 1/2 games. With the Yankees
shorn of their immortality, the Indians right now are the only sure
thing for a first-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   But their efforts to duplicate the Yankees' remarkable run
through the league last season have suffered a setback. When the
Indians won 29 of their first 39 games, the projectionists pulled
out their calculators and determined that the Indians, if they
maintained that pace, could win 120 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox injected a dose of reality into their season
over the weekend, however, sweeping a three-game series in
Cleveland and leaving the Indians with six losses in their last
nine games. Their .667 winning percentage now projects to 108
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Their recent run production has also been down, but the Indians
still lead the league in scoring by a wide margin. Their 6.8 runs a
game, if maintained, would result in a run total that would eclipse
the major league record of 1,067 held by the 1931 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, though, the Indians refused to look ahead at victory
and run totals. Their focus is first on Hargrove's stated goal of
100 victories and second on duplicating the 1998 Yankees'
impressive approach of playing every game as if it would determine
the outcome of the division race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just looking forward to having a good season and going to
the playoffs,'' Alomar said when asked if he thought the Indians
could match the Yankees' 1998 performance. ``The Yankees have
already done it. You can't compare us with what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four seasons, the Indians have fallen short of the
ultimate goal. They lost the World Series in 1995 and '97 and did
not reach the Series in '96 and '98, years the Yankees won it. The
Indians lost to the Yankees last season in the league playoff
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus was lost a little bit last year,'' Vizquel said.
``We tried to get it back in the playoffs. But it's kind of hard.
Not too many teams can turn it on and off whenever they want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove decided to do something about the focus, hoping to
avoid losing it this season. He set a goal of 100 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '97 and '98,'' he said, ``our stated goal was to get in the
post-season and take our chances. That's kind of how our team
played in '97 and '98. We played just good enough to stay ahead of
everybody and get to the post-season. We were accused of being
lethargic and being on cruise control, so I tried to think of a way
to remedy that. I challenged the guys, and they really embraced the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar's arrival has fueled the players' response to the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know him before he came here,'' said Vizquel, the
shortstop who is Alomar's partner in middle-infield brilliance.
``He's just a really smart player. He knows a little bit about
everything. He can tell you stuff about the other teams that's
important. It's an awesome feeling. You know he's going to do
something every day to make his team win. He just can do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates gave Alomar credit for making noticeable
improvements in some of the players, particularly Ramirez with his
base running. Ramirez, Hargrove said, has worked hard to make
himself a better outfielder, but Alomar has made him a better base
runner, which is one of the remarkable feats of the season. Ramirez
once stole second base, then retreated to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a little more focused,'' Ramirez said of his efforts
on the bases. ``I've been running more aggressive. Robbie's been
helping me. With Robbie's help, I don't make a lot of mistakes.
Robbie says, `Do this, do that.' I'm trying to correct that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar said he has only wanted to help a good player get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day,'' he related, citing an example of his
instruction to Ramirez, ``I was on third and he was on second.
Somebody hit a fly ball to center field. We had one out. The fly
ball to center field was the second out. I tagged and scored, and
he went to third base and they almost got him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the inning, I told him if it's no outs, it's OK if you
do that. But you have to know the guy has a good arm and if you get
thrown out there's three outs and my run doesn't score.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove cited an example of Alomar's own base running that
helps the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does all the little things,'' the manager said Saturday.
``Yesterday is a perfect example. He's stealing second base, Omar
scores on the passed ball and Robbie goes all the way to third
base. Who else would have done that? He just seems to pick the
right time to do what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar's efforts in the field seem to be omnipresent. He
sparkled defensively even in losses to the Red Sox on Friday night
and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning on Saturday, with the Indians ahead, 1-0, on
Alomar's sacrifice fly and a Red Sox runner at first base with one
out, Jose Offerman rapped a grounder between first and second.
Alomar, a seven-time Gold Glove winner, darted to his left, flew
through the air, snatched the ball, spun around and, from his
knees, threw to Vizquel for a forceout at second.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar made two similar flights to his right Friday night. On
one, he snared Trot Nixon's sinking line drive just before it hit
the ground. On the other, he dived in the dirt behind second,
backhanded Offerman's grounder and flipped the ball with his glove
hand to Vizquel, who caught it with his bare hand and in the same
motion fired to first base for what would have been a double play
on anyone but Offerman. ``We've made some good plays, but we
haven't really put on a show like people are expecting,'' Vizquel
had said before the game. That play was a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun watching those two guys because they're so athletic,
so acrobatic, so good at what they do,'' Hargrove said. ``It's fun
watching them in spring training. They take their ground balls and
work on double plays. Then the last five minutes of the session
they start kicking the ball like it's a Hacky Sack and kicking the
ball behind their back. It's amazing how creative they can be and
what they can do with a baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   As a starting pitcher, Dwight Gooden is an appreciative
beneficiary of the Alomar-Vizquel defensive deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become a fan,'' Gooden said. ``You watch it and you want
more. I've never had a sinker, but this year I'm working on a
sinker so I can get some ground balls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
