<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFF-FATIGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OVERTIME, TV AND AIR-CONDITIONING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ You can watch some sporting events on television while
doing other things _ reading newspapers, making phone calls,
preparing meals or cleaning up the house. But other telecasts force
you to push everything aside and pull up a chair to shout and stare
at the screen for three or four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-Colorado series for the Western Conference
championship in the Stanley Cup playoffs is such an event. And what
better place to see it on a sunny Sunday afternoon than in a hotel
room here, with the Yankees and Blue Jays playing about a mile
away, near the sailboats and sunbathers of Lake Ontario?
</P>
<P>
   Just draw the curtains, turn up the air conditioning and tell
the operator to hold the phone calls. It's hockey season, darn it.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Canada, you have a choice. You can watch the Fox
telecast on a Buffalo station to enjoy the insightful commentary of
Mike Emrick and John Davidson. And when Fox's ragged visual
presentation becomes too annoying, you can switch to the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp., which employs producers and directors with a
feel for the rhythm of the game and the proper camera cuts. Too bad
these hotel rooms don't come with two televisions instead of two
beds.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's game, the Avalanche beat the Stars by 7-5 to take a
3-2 lead in the best-of-7-game series. Game 6 is Tuesday night in
Denver. Although Buffalo and Toronto are playing in the Eastern
Conference finals, almost everyone around the NHL agrees that the
Stars-Avalanche match is the true championship, the real World
Series, the match of the two best teams in this spring's
tournament. So why are Buffalo's chances getting better to win the
first cup in Sabres history?
</P>
<P>
   Because Dallas and Colorado are wearing each other out while the
Sabres, leading the Eastern series by 3-1, can clinch their
conference championship by beating the faltering Maple Leafs Monday
night in Air Canada Center. A victory would give Buffalo at least
one more day of rest than the Western winner, four more days if the
Stars win Game 6 and force a Game 7 on Friday night in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Although Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek missed the first two games
with a groin injury, he is back and relatively healthy. So is
Miroslav Satan, the Buffalo sniper who missed a month with a foot
injury. The Sabres emerged from Saturday's easy 5-2 victory with no
new injuries. Should they conclude their series quickly, the Sabres
will be fresh for the championship round, which begins either
Friday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the same for the Western winner, whoever it is,
whenever it is. Sunday's 12-goal shootout was partly the result of
the fatigue felt by both teams after Friday night's 3-2 Colorado
victory in overtime, as bruising a game as any fan could ever wish
to witness. Several players are out with injuries and many are
playing hurt.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, as the two teams exchanged rushes, they looked a
little like Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier throwing punches in the
late rounds of the Thrilla in Manila. Unlike the Sabres, who drive
two hours on a highway for road games, the Avalanche and Stars
travel long distances by air, switching time zones between games.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's rare air can shorten the breath from even the
healthiest athletic lungs. As the calendar moves to June, the
season enters its ninth month, its 10th if you count training camp
and exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   So where does a player like Colorado's Peter Forsberg get his
energy? He scored a goal and set up two others Sunday. He leads all
playoff scorers with 23 points. In Friday's game, he went down
screaming with what looked to be a serious shoulder injury. In
Sunday's game, he was back, crashing into Dallas players.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg is an audacious competitor, the top contender for the
Conn Smythe trophy as most valuable player in the playoffs, a
relentless performer in an enthralling series.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is much to complain about regarding the playoffs in
the 1990s. The tournament should be over by now, not in the third
round after Canada celebrates Victoria Day, as the United States
celebrates Memorial Day. With summer near, the ice is often too
mushy. The best teams should meet in the final round, not the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The American telecasts _ and that includes those on ESPN _ are
sloppy and inattentive to important detail. Inside the arenas,
incessant blasts of canned metal music pollute the aural atmosphere
with a fake frenzy that downs out honest cheering.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? Despite all this, a series like
Colorado-Dallas reminds you of why you learned to love hockey's
excitement and drama in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   And a player like Forsberg demonstrates how the very best
players combine skill, courage, stamina and passion in this most
visceral of team sports. You see a player like this, in a series
like this, and you know that, year after year, no matter how shabby
the presentation, you will keep coming back for more, more, more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
