<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SUMMER-NYT &LR;      05-30 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SUMMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ON SUMMER'S PORCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 31:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dry resonance at night _ the ticking of insects _
is not as authoritative as it will be in another month. The city
has just begun to seep with heat, and has not yet melted at the
crosswalks. Memorial Day is the porch before the house of summer,
and spring is still latent here, still discernible in what blooms
and has not bloomed, in the constellations that have not yet risen
to midsummer's height.
</P>
<P>
   If summer is the flat light on a dead-calm sea, the haze that
enshrouds the horizon after a week without rain, then this is a
time when wind and water are still freshening, still disturbed by
echoes from a more vehement season.
</P>
<P>
   It is always striking how holidays that begin, in effect, as
legislative events embed themselves in our sense of the year's
natural order, as though they marked a celestial event as
distinctive as a solstice. Memorial Day began as a Grand Army
proclamation in 1868 to coordinate the decoration of the graves of
the Union dead, and it was adopted as an official holiday in 1873
by New York, the first state to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the holiday, and the decorating of graves with
flowers, has embraced the dead from all of America's wars, even as
the day itself has, for many Americans, lost its commemorative
quality.
</P>
<P>
   But to anyone who has ever marched in an old-fashioned,
small-town Memorial Day parade, there is no forgetting the peculiar
stir of feelings this day brings. It is a morning parade, and it
makes its way to a cemetery on the edge of town, a place where
cypress grows against the backdrop of clean-shaven lawns and fields
of new-sprung corn.
</P>
<P>
   An odd moment occurs when the parade arrives at the cemetery,
for the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts and the members of the
high-school marching band look on while their elders, evidently
moved though the day is bright and it is not yet noon, honor men _
mostly men _ who barely figure in the minds of the young people
trying to stand at attention. It is always this way, the old
honoring those who died young while the young wait impatiently
nearby, disbelieving in death.
</P>
<P>
   To enter summer with an act of solemnity, however slight,
however quickly dispelled by the long afternoon that follows the
parade, has a certain elemental logic, an emotional fitness.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost an apology for the thoughtless vitality of this
season, a time when the naked exuberance of nature bears the living
away into June and July and forgetfulness. Our job now is to live
out all those summers that were lost to the men and women who died
in wars past, as well as our own summers too. It is no burden to do
so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
