<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STEWART-1STWRITET     05-30 2323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STEWART-1STWRITETHRU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Double duty at the tracks proves too much for Stewart
 &HT;    (EDS: UPDATES STORY to include Stewart's second race of the
day.)
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. and CONCORD, N.C. _ Tony Stewart barely
completed his auto-racing doubleheader on Sunday, leaving Lowe's
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., in an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 28, became the first driver to complete both the
Indianapolis 500 and Coca-Cola 600 NASCAR race in the same day. In
all, he completed 596 laps, 1,090 miles and 2,384 left-hand turns.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was 10 miles short of his goal of 1,100 after enduring
handling problems in the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   By 3:30 p.m. Sunday, Stewart already logged 196 laps and 490
miles, and he still faced the prospect of doing it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the 1997 Indy Racing League champion, finished ninth in
the Indianapolis 500, four laps behind winner Kenny Brack, who took
the victory after leader Robby Gordon ran out of fuel with one lap
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart finished fourth in the Coca-Cola 600, the longest race
on the Winston Cup schedule, behind winner Jeff Burton, Joe Gibbs
Racing teammate Bobby Labonte and Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stewart) was spectacular,'' Martin said. ``He's been that way
all year. It looks like we're all going to be chasing Tony before
too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart completed both races after two other drivers attempted
the feat and failed. Winston Cup driver John Andretti finished 10th
in the Indy 500 in 1994, but then he crashed in the NASCAR race
before the finish. Robby Gordon tried it in 1997, but the Indy 500
was postponed two days because of inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   After crossing the finish line in Indianapolis on Sunday,
Stewart boarded an airplane and flew to Concord, where he ran in
Sunday night's Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a driver, I wanted to win the race,'' Stewart said of the
Indy 500. ``Anything short of winning was a disappointment. We did
everything we could. We fought hard all day. We did the best with
what we had, and we just missed the setup a little bit. ...
Considering all the variables that were against us before we
started this project, and to see how everything has come together,
I'm thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   In Concord, Stewart started in the back of the field because he
missed the drivers' meeting, but he made his way to the front of
the 43-car field quickly. Over the final few laps, Stewart
complained of being ill and was immediately transported to the
infield care center when he finished.
</P>
<P>
   During the month of May, Stewart faced a daunting schedule. He
made 14 trips between Charlotte and Indianapolis, logging 5,208
nautical miles. His logistical nightmare Sunday included three
airplanes, two helicopters, eight golf carts, four cars and one
Navigator transporter to move Stewart and his support team of 51
people between the two tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't bothered me because we understood from day 1 that
the main priority was Winston Cup,'' Curry said. ``It was a
challenge, but I think we made the most of his time (in
Indianapolis).''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a closer look at Stewart's long day behind the wheel,
which started around 9:30 a.m. and didn't end until after 10:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   1:01 a.m. _ Gates open at Indianapolis Motor Speedway for crew
members and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   5:15 a.m. _ Stewart's crew members arrive at IMS to install
tethering system to left rear tire. The Indy Racing League
announced this week that the safety device, two small cables
attached to the butterfly suspension of the wheels, would be
required.
</P>
<P>
   6:15 a.m. _ Curry, co-owner of Tristar Motorsports and Stewart's
crew chief, arrives at IMS.
</P>
<P>
   8:45 a.m. _ Stewart's No. 22 Dallara/Oldsmobile Aurora Indy car
leaves garage No. 15 for pre-race inspection.
</P>
<P>
   8:49 a.m. _ Mechanic Bill Harmon steers Stewart's car onto
Gasoline Alley for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   8:53 a.m. _ Stewart's car is seventh in line for pre-race
inspection. Stewart's orange car is dominated by stickers of its
primary sponsor, Home Depot. Among the familiar sponsors, though,
is one very unfamiliar name: Lee Kissick, CPA. Kissick is Curry's
brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   9:03 a.m. _ Car rolls into inspection. Forteen inspectors
measure the car's height, width from tire to tire and weight. Six
of Stewart's crew members watch intensely as the car is closely
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   9:10 a.m. _ Car passes inspection and is pulled to pit road by a
riding lawn mower.
</P>
<P>
   9:15 a.m. _ Car stops at pit stall No. 26, between the cars of
Steve Knapp and Roberto Moreno. Stewart's car is nine stalls to the
left of the start/finish line. ``I think we've got a good shot at
winning it,'' said Case Leeuwenberg, of Wilmington, N.C., one of
Stewart's seven mechanics. ``I really do. We've got a good car.
He's got to be patient, but you can't be to cautious because you'll
get lapped here.''
</P>
<P>
   9:30 a.m. _ Stewart wakes up in his motorhome parked in the
infield of IMS. He doesn't eat breakfast, but later has cereal and
fruit in garage area. ``We call it `Tony time,''' Curry said.
``He'll show up 10 minutes before the race and climb in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   9:49 p.m. _ Stewart's crew practices pit stops on pit road. The
first pit stop is its best at 7.56 seconds, but the drill gun on
the right-rear tire sticks. The second stop is 8.6 seconds, and the
third is 7.69.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m. _ Every car is given a six-minute engine warm-up on pit
road, and then the cars are refueled.
</P>
<P>
   10:17 a.m. _ Stewart is examined by Dr. Henry Bock, director of
medical affairs for the speedway and IRL. Stewart's blood pressure,
heart rate and weight are taken. He weighs in at 155 pounds. ``He's
in good spirits,'' said Krista Dwyer, Stewart's fiance. ``We got up
a little earlier than we normally do, but we didn't really do
anything different.'' Stewart is engaged to be married May 6 in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   10:24 a.m. _ Stewart arrives at his garage, wearing blue jeans
and a Home Depot shirt. He meets with Curry and other team members.
</P>
<P>
   11:25 a.m. _ Stewart makes way to pit road for driver
introductions. ``This is the most relaxed I've ever been going into
a 500-mile race,'' Stewart says. ``I woke up this morning and
didn't have a single butterfly. I went through the drivers intros
and didn't have a single butterfly then, either. I have a good
feeling about today.''
</P>
<P>
   11:45 a.m. _ According to Firestone Tire engineers, air
temperature is 85 degrees, but temperature on the track is 111
degrees. ``My job is just driving the race car,'' Stewart says.
``We don't have to worry about the one variable we couldn't do
anything about today, and that was the weather. It's great in Indy,
and it's supposed to be great in Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   11:51 a.m. _ Indianapolis Motor Speedway chairman Mari Hulman
George gives ``Gentleman, start your engines'' command. All 33 cars
on grid are fired and running immediately after command.
</P>
<P>
   11:52 a.m. _ Cars roll from grid for first parade lap.
</P>
<P>
   12:01 p.m. _ Green flag falls and pole-sitter Arie Luyendyk
takes lead in turn one. For fifth consecutive year, field came to
the line for the start without a full stable of cars as Jack
Miller's No. 17 car and Scott Sharp's No. 2 car failed to take the
green because of mechanical problems. Stewart starts on the outside
of the eighth row, 24th overall.
</P>
<P>
   12:07 p.m. _ First caution of the race comes after Eliseo
Salazar crashes in turn two of the ninth lap. Stewart climbed four
spots to 20th in the first eight laps, trailing leader Luyendyk by
18.288 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   12:26 p.m. _ Stewart passes Roberto Guerrero, Steve Knapp, Buddy
Lazier and Robbie Buhl to move into 17th, about 14 seconds behind
Luyendyk.
</P>
<P>
   12:33 p.m. _ Leaders begin to take first green-flag pit stops on
lap 31. Kenny Brack takes four tires and fuel on lap 31, and Billy
Boat, Luyendyk, Gordon and Greg Ray follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   12:35 p.m. _ Stewart gets his first big break of the race when
he remains on the track while most of the leaders make pit stops.
The move pays off, as Hideshi Matsuda apparently runs out of gas on
lap 35 and stalls in the short chute between turns 3 and 4. On lap
37 under caution, Stewart's crew changes four tires and refuels in
16 seconds. The crew also makes a slight adjustment to the chassis.
Stewart climbs from 17th to fifth after the restart on lap 39.
</P>
<P>
   12:46 p.m. _ Ray takes lead from Luyendyk on lap 45. Stewart is
fifth behind Ray, Luyendyk, Sam Schmidt and Brack. Stewart moves to
fourth when Schmidt crashes 17 laps later.
</P>
<P>
   1:03 p.m. _ Stewart makes second pit stop on lap 64. He gets
four new tires and fuel, and the crew changes the height of the
``wicker bill,'' attempting to get more downforce. The longer pit
stop costs Stewart two track positions and he falls to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   1:31 p.m. _ Stewart makes third pit stop on lap 95. The crew
again changes the ``wicker bill'' and tire pressure because Stewart
is complaining that the car is ``too tight.'' Stewart comes out of
the pit stops in 10th place. But his car is later damaged by a
mistake in the pits. While working on the Dallara Oldsmobile
Aurora, the crew released the jack
</P>
<P>
   too soon and slightly damaged the car. ``After that, you're in a
survival mode,'' Curry said. ``You just want to get the car home.
I'm disappointed in the fact we made that mistake. We would have
been the fourth or fifth or sixth car.''
</P>
<P>
   3:17 p.m. _ Indy 500 finishes when Brack crosses finish line.
Stewart finishes ninth, four laps behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
   3:19 p.m. _After crossing the finish line at Indy, Stewart
sprints to his motorhome, showers and changes into a red T-shirt
and blue jeans. He then returns to his garage to thank his crew and
Curry. Stewart also is evaluated by Dr. Bock, who says Stewart lost
2 1/2 pounds but doesn't need to take fluids intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   4:02 p.m. _ Stewart is whisked away in a golf cart to a
helicopter, waiting on the infield near the third turn for a
three-minute ride to the Indianapolis Airport.
</P>
<P>
   4:12 p.m. _ Stewart arrives at the airport, where Home Depot,
his sponsor, has its Falcon VIP jet waiting for the 50-minute
flight to Concord. Aboard the plane, Stewart changed into his
NASCAR racing suit, ate a Power Bar and sipped Powerade and water.
He complained of a blister on his right hand from the steering
wheel and another blister on his right knee from the steering
column. And he even admitted he was a bit tired. ``That's to be
expected after a 500-mile race,'' Stewart said. ``I'm really
excited, though. I thought I'd feel a lot more fatigued. I think
after an hour's sleep, I'll be fine.'' With that, Stewart caught a
short nap in the back of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   4:15 p.m. _ Mandatory drivers' meeting at Lowe's begins _
without Stewart. That means Stewart, who qualified 27th for the
race, will have to start the Coca-Cola 600 at the rear of the field
in the 43rd position.
</P>
<P>
   4:21 p.m. _ Stewart's plane leaves ground.
</P>
<P>
   4:48 p.m. _ Stewart's entourage arrives at the speedway in a
Navigator limousine. After reaching the infield of the track,
Lowe's officials force them to remove the Home Depot decals from
their vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   5:37 p.m. _ Stewart's plane reaches gate at Concord Regional
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   5:42 p.m. _ Stewart boards Winston Cup driver Rusty Wallace's
Bell 407 helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   5:50 p.m. _ The six-seat helicopter lands on the TBS logo just
past the start-finish line. Stewart jumps in a Chevy Camaro for
driver introductions.
</P>
<P>
   5:57 p.m. _ Stewart climbs into his No. 20 Pontiac after a brief
conversation with owner Joe Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   6:08 p.m. _ Speedway Motorsports Inc. president Bruton Smith
delivers the ``Gentleman, start your engines'' command.
</P>
<P>
   6:12 p.m. _ The 43-car field rolls off the grid.
</P>
<P>
   6:15 p.m. _ The green flag falls and Stewart faces 600 more
miles and 1,600 left-hand turns.
</P>
<P>
   6:19 p.m. _ Stewart passes three cars in the first two laps.
</P>
<P>
   6:23 p.m. _ Stewart barely avoids a wreck exiting turn 4, where
Rich Bickle and Kyle Petty collide in lap 4.
</P>
<P>
   6:33 p.m. _ Stewart is 33rd after only 10 laps.
</P>
<P>
   6:53 p.m. _ After 61 laps, Stewart climbs to 10th behind the No.
31 Chevy of Mike Skinner and No. 33 Chevy of Ken Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   7:01 p.m. _ Stewart makes his first green-flag pit stop and a
succesful one in only 18.6 seconds on lap 68. He led one lap after
staying on the track longer than the other leaders, and comes off
pit road in ninth place.
</P>
<P>
   7:22 p.m. _ Stewart completes his 100th lap and he's in eighth
place.
</P>
<P>
   7:49 p.m. _ Stewart battles teammate Bobby Labonte, Steve Park,
Jeff Burton and Mark Martin for the lead. He climbs to second
behind Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   9:05 p.m. _ Stewart passes Labonte on lap 295 for his second
lead of the race.
</P>
<P>
   9:15 p.m. _ There are reports from Stewart's pit stall that the
driver is complaining that he's ill. But Stewart continues to run
up front.
</P>
<P>
   9:25 p.m. _ Stewart completes 300th lap, with 100 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   9:27 p.m. _ Stewart passes Burton at the start/finish line of
lap 295 for his third lead.
</P>
<P>
   10:06 p.m. _ Stewart makes final green-flag pit stop with only
26 laps remaining. He takes four tires and his crew manages the
changes in 18.8 seconds. Martin takes only two tires and is out
quickly. Labonte changes four tires and is out in 17.4 seconds,
while Burton needed only 17.3 seconds. Burton is first, followed by
Labonte, Stewart and Martin with 24 laps left.
</P>
<P>
   10:14 p.m. _ Martin passes Stewart for third place with only 13
laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   10:21 p.m. _ Burton beats Labonte to the finish line. Stewart
finishes fourth behind Martin.
</P>
<P>
   10:23 p.m. _ Stewart pulls car next to gas pumps and gets out,
laying next to car.
</P>
<P>
   10:27 p.m. _ Stewart is put on stretcher and loaded into
ambulance. He's taken to infield care center, where he's treated
for dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
