<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: A WAR HERO APPEALS TO THE NONCOMBATANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a theory for a presidential campaign: Take a prominent
Republican senator and war hero, who once underwent enormous
suffering for his country, and voters weary of moral relativism
will leap at the chance to have a chief executive they can really
look up to. Sen. John McCain of Arizona is trying out the scenario
this year, undeterred by the fact that it failed completely for Bob
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, of course, was probably the worst campaigner since John
Quincy Adams or, at least, Michael Dukakis. But his defeat was also
a sign of changing times. A product of the World War II generation,
Dole never seemed to grasp the fact that he was addressing a nation
of noncombatants, most of whom either avoided the draft, were not
eligible, or did not remember that it ever existed. Dole suffered
permanent disability after he was shelled in Italy as a young
draftee, and his campaign carried an implicit, and perhaps
unwelcome, message of guilt _ how could we not elect him, after all
he did for us?
</P>
<P>
   McCain was a 31-year-old Annapolis graduate when he was shot
down over North Vietnam in 1967. He remained a prisoner of war for
more than five years, and he was tortured by his captors, who hung
him from his broken arms. It is an excruciating story to hear, and
the McCain camp offers potential supporters any number of ways to
hear it. But the candidate himself seldom brings it up, and he
makes some effort to point out that he was not a victim. ``I was a
professional,'' he says. ``I wanted to go.'' He seems to understand
how to talk about his war experience to an electorate with a
dwindling population of veterans, and a large number of voters who
might interpret an intense show of emotion as implicit criticism of
their failure to serve. When he mentions his time in the POW camp,
his tone is generally cool and detached. He dismisses the more
effusive tributes with an ironic reference to how little brains it
takes for a pilot to get his plane shot down. He has always shied
away from the bitter side of the Vietnam experience, standing next
to Bill Clinton when the president announced he was granting
Vietnam full diplomatic recognition in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain becomes a serious presidential contender only if
George W. Bush stumbles, and he says that if he wins the
nomination, it will be because of his leadership in the Senate on
issues like campaign finance reform and national defense. He is a
very attractive candidate in a field that is full of automotons and
fire-eaters, although many people who like his forthright manner
may find his conservative voting record hard to swallow. There is
also a man's-man quality to him that could rattle the gender gap.
(A Seattle newspaper recently quoted McCain as calling Leonardo
DiCaprio ``an androgynous wimp.'')
</P>
<P>
   But whether he wins or not, the senator is a bridge candidate, a
symbol of the new way America has begun to think about the
military. After World War II, politics was dominated by veterans,
and politicians who did not serve felt constrained to apologize or
compensate. John Kennedy _ who never stressed that it did not take
much brains to sink a PT boat _ had surrogates remind the voters
that Hubert Humphrey stayed home with a medical exemption. Lyndon
Johnson used his clout as a congressman to get into a fighter plane
over New Guinea so he could tell the public he had been in combat.
Ronald Reagan gradually adopted his film personas and spoke as if
he had spent the war in Europe instead of an Army film unit. As the
Vietnam-era generation assumed power, the political dialogue
continued along the same lines, and candidates argued about Bill
Clinton's draft exemption and Dan Quayle's stint in the Indiana
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of American history, the nation was governed by
lawyers who had never served in the military, and the public
regarded soldiering as a career choice rather than a patriotic
duty. Without much noticing, we have returned to that pattern.
Neither the current secretary of state or secretary of defense had
military experience. Only a third of the members of Congress are
veterans, down from 75 percent in 1971. McCain says the senators
who served in Vietnam feel a special bond, but the bonds do not
have to stretch very far _ there are only six of them.
</P>
<P>
   If this campaign winds up focusing on McCain, we will debate
again the issue of whether military valor translates into
presidential character. If he loses, the subject may never come up
again in our lifetimes. Except for Al Gore, who worked as a
journalist for the Army in Vietnam, the rest of the pack of
presidential candidates is virtually veteran-free. George W. Bush,
Bill Bradley and Steve Forbes, like Dan Quayle, worked off their
draft eligibility as reservists. Younger candidates, like John
Kasich, graduated from college after the draft was abolished in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very rarely do I hear a discussion about Vietnam anymore,''
McCain says, directing the conversation away from the old debate
about how men who fought in the war should feel about the men who
did not. ``I just kind of think it's passe _ it's been a long
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
