A7019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      05-30 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST FOR A GAME, `CURSE OF REGGIE' LIFTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ No Reggie time _ not this time. No 3-point
rainbow to bury the Knicks. This time if Reggie Miller wanted to
put both hands in that taunting choke hold, they would have to grab
his own throat and stay there.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario was familiar, 12.4 seconds left and the Indiana
Pacers down by two points, 90-88. All 16,575 fans at the Market
Square Arena knew where the ball was going; so did the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew you had to prevent Reggie from getting the shot,''
Allan Houston said. Well, they didn't and they did.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who zigzagged with Houston through the lane and off an
Antonio Davis pick, took the pass on the left wing. He turned and
saw something stunning. Houston had stayed close and, like a
mountain on three wobbly wheels, Patrick Ewing lurched at him too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick has seen that play 200 times,'' Miller said of Ewing's
move toward him. ``Injured or not, he knows the game of basketball.
It was a good hedge.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot went up. The ball rimmed out. The breath of the crowd
blew out and the Knicks nailed three free throws in the closing
seconds to win, 93-90. The curse of Reggie Miller had been lifted _
at least momentarily _ so that the Knicks could take a 1-0 lead in
the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ewing said it hurt to hobble so far away from the basket.
But he did it again on Indiana's final play, flashing in front of
Miller, forcing the Pacers to pass the ball to Mark Jackson, who
missed a 3-pointer to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He killed us so many times by hitting big threes,'' Ewing
said. ``We started trapping him. If they were going to beat us,
it's got to be somebody else. You just have to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Miller had no excuses. He finished with 19 points on
7-of-13 shooting. Solid, but no pyrotechnics _ no eight points in
8.9 seconds to win the game as he had done in 1995. No 3-pointer
with 5.1 seconds left to send the game in overtime, which he did
last last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good look at the basket and that's all you can ask,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have thrown in the towel, but they didn't,'' Miller
said of the Knicks. ``It was a good topsy-turvy game.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the theme and tone in the Indiana locker room afterward
was what you would expect from a veteran team that had won seven
straight playoff games. Coach Larry Bird expected his team to be
rusty after a week off and the Pacers were. They got outrun in
transition in the first half by the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes, we gave up a lot of fast-break
points,'' Bird said of the 18 breakaway points the Knicks scored to
take a 44-40 halftime lead. ``We want to play in a half-court
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Dale and Antonio Davis, the Pacers found their legs, and
Rik Smits helped them find the lead with four minutes left in the
game. The Davises combined for 17 points and seven rebounds in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the opportunities to put them away but we just couldn't
finish,'' Dale Davis said. ``This loss hurts but it is a long
series. We will be all right in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits, the big center, scored eight of his 12 points in the
fourth quarter, but fouled out with 1:27 left in the game. His
absence down the stretch allowed the Knicks to pull the noose
tighter around Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had been in there we probably would have run a different
set with a two-man game with myself and Rik,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the Pacers have lost the home-court advantage _ at
least temporarily. They know the sorely need to win the game here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a lot of pressure on us, but we're a veteran team,
there's no panic here,'' said Mark Jackson, who had 11 assists but
only six points and was 1 of 8 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose, who lost his sixth-man duel with Latrell Sprewell,
confessed that the Knicks had won an important game. He had eight
points to Sprewell's 16, but he was hardly downcast about the
Pacers' prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we know there won't be a sweep in this series,'' said
Rose. ``We'll get him here Tuesday and then start all over in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
