<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MEDINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDISH F. MEDINA JR., 58, LAWYER WHO OFTEN AVOIDED TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Standish Forde Medina Jr., a leading trial lawyer who
made a name for himself by resolving disputes so that clients could
avoid trial, died Saturday at Memorial Sloan-Kettering hospital in
Manhattan. Medina, who had residences in Manhattan, Westhampton,
N.Y., and Washington, Conn., was 58.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was leukemia, according to his widow, Kathryn Bach
Medina, division vice president and executive editor at Random
House.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 3 inches tall, with a resonant voice and a playful
wit, Medina, known as Forde to friends, was a striking figure. ``He
was big, enthusiastic and lusty in the most gentlemanly way,'' said
Barbara Paul Robinson, a friend and a partner at Debevoise &AMP;
Plimpton, a 450-member law firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He specialized in the toughest cases in the often arcane world
of securities and class-action law. Euromoney magazine listed him
in 1997 as one of the world's 600 leading litigators. ``He loved
the law,'' said Martin F. Evans, the firm's presiding partner.
``People would come into the office early in the morning and he
would already have analyzed the previous day's proceedings and
prepared detailed to-do lists.''
</P>
<P>
   Among colleagues, Medina was known for bringing order to a
years-long complex of insurance company cases in which
policyholders accused New York Life, Phoenix, Transamerica and
Hancock of unfair sales practices. Medina, representing the
insurance companies, helped design a process that brought automatic
relief for some policyholders and accelerated arbitration for
others, thus avoiding lengthy litigation for all parties.
</P>
<P>
   The law ran in the family. Medina was the grandson of Harold R.
Medina, a federal judge for more than three decades, who was best
known for his handling of the trial of 11 communist leaders in the
1940s. Like his grandfather; uncle, Harold Jr., and father,
Standish, Medina graduated from Princeton University and Columbia
Law School.
</P>
<P>
   While at Columbia, from which Medina graduated magna cum laude
in 1965, he was a Kent Scholar and a member of the law review. He
joined Debevoise &AMP; Plimpton in 1966 and became a partner in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Medina became known as a gregarious guest and
tennis partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very funny with my husband and knew there was something
behind that reserve,'' said Lucinda Franks, the author, who is
married to Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney.
``Forde would always say on the tennis court, `And in this corner,
the Honorable, the Learned, District Attorney Robert Morgenthau,
and over here we have humble Forde Medina, only a lawyer, but he'll
do what he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Medina is survived by his wife of 31 years and their son,
Nathaniel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-99 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990530.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
