   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, May 31. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ Two recent Supreme Court rulings may
spell doom for police ``reality'' shows. A look at what we might
get in their place. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the
``L'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME31 (Phoenix) _ When a Phoenix man was shot in the back at a
party, he believed the shooter wasn't the only one to blame. He
successfully sued the condominium association where it happened,
saying it knew there was a need for added security. Another Phoenix
association now is being sued after its added securitybackfired. If
a gang known for crime routinely hangs out in a common area but a
homeowners association cuts back on security to save money, can it
be sued if there is a crime? Absolutely. Across the Valley of the
Sun, as the Phoenix area is known, and across the country,
community associations are vogue. But when crime happens on their
turf, these groups are becoming targets. ``Courts all across the
country are starting to hold community associations liable,'' says
Beth Mulcahy, a Phoenix attorney who represents more than 150
community associations _ which include planned communities, condo
communities and homeowners associations. By CHRIS FISCUS. Story
will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
